<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A PITCH: CACTUS LEAGUE WANTS EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa. RandyJohnson. Ken Griffey Jr. Garth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful March weather. Booming economy. Major League Baseball
coming off its most thrilling season in many a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cactus League couldn't ask for more, and officials expect to
break attendance records this year.
</P>
<P>
   And _ get ready _ it could get even sweeter with two more teams
possibly on the way.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, the storied Los Angeles Dodgers
and one other team would boost the league to an even dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Cities such as Yuma, former home of the San Diego Padres, and
Marana have expressed interest in hosting a team.
</P>
<P>
   But there are challenges facing Arizona, too.
</P>
<P>
   The car-rental tax that has paid for improvements to Cactus
League facilities won't have any money available for new projects
for at least a decade. Arizona officials worry about Las Vegas,
which hosts some exhibition games each March and has thousands of
new hotel rooms to fill, making a serious pitch for spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   After a challenge from Florida to lure the Chicago Cubs and
other teams to the Grapefruit League in the late 1980s, more than
$160 million has been spent on Cactus League facilities, and
Arizona claims to be king.
</P>
<P>
   ``Top to bottom, we have the best facilities for spring training
bar none,'' said Michael Scully, executive director of the Maricopa
County Sports Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look around the Valley and Tucson, you'll see what he
means.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the turnaround was the `t' word nobody wants to
hear about,'' said Scully, referring to a rental-vehicle tax that
has financed most of the improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.50-per-rental tax in Maricopa County ($3.50 in Pima
County) won't be paying for new facilities any time soon. All of
the expected $5 million or so projected to be generated each year
throughout the next decade is earmarked to pay for existing
facilities, said Chris Baier, sports development director for the
Arizona Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But that won't stop the Cactus League from expanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and the Fort McDowell Yavapai-Apache Indian Tribe
have been discussing terms of a proposed $20 million to $30 million
complex on the reservation that would boast a 12,500-seat stadium
paid for by the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's envisioned that the tribe would pay for the facilities,
but to justify it they need to make sure they get a return,'' Baier
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal officials will only confirm that negotiations continue.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Coons, business development director for the Dodgers, said
the team will also weigh proposals from Vero Beach, Fla., city and
county officials to improve the club's situation there, but he said
talks won't heat up until after spring training. The Dodgers want
their new staff, led by Manager Davey Johnson, to experience a
spring in Vero Beach before pressing ahead with a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Until and if a deal is finalized, it won't be known when a new
stadium here could be completed, but it's unlikely it would be in
time for next spring.
</P>
<P>
   The practice fields could be finished in time for 2000, meaning
the Dodgers would have to work out a deal to share a stadium with
another team for one year. That most likely would be Scottsdale
Stadium, spring home of the San Francisco Giants, although Phoenix
Municipal Stadium, where the Oakland Athletics train, is another
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, the Dodgers could be joined by another team at their
complex in an arrangement similar to Peoria Sports Complex or
Tucson Electric Park, both of which house two teams. Possible teams
mentioned by officials include the Toronto Blue Jays, Houston
Astros, Texas Rangers, Kansas City Royals and even the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league is going to strengthen itself even further over
the next few years,'' Scully said.
</P>
<P>
   Baier calls the Dodger proposition a 50-50 chance, ``but there's
so many things that make more sense about Arizona than Florida for
the Dodgers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny Holman Stadium at Dodgertown holds 6,500 and has limited
revenue potential. Los Angeles is an hour from Phoenix by air, and
the new-look, Fox-owned Dodgers could better market spring training
to hometown fans and sponsors, who are reluctant to make the
cross-country trek to Florida and then face a long drive to
isolated Vero Beach. Another key factor is the convenience of
travel for players, easing player development in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what Florida does, they can't compete with all
that,'' Baier said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers' emotional, 50-year ties to Vero Beach and a
community campaign to keep the team will be weighed heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a large part of Dodger tradition, and we're obviously
tied to that,'' the Dodgers' Coons said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Danadio heads the Keep the Dodgers Committee for the Vero
Beach Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot more than just a team coming for spring
training once a year to Vero Beach,'' Danadio said of the
tradition. ``We feel strongly that with the amount of change going
on in the Dodgers organization, the one thing they have left is
Vero Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   That and the fact that Vero Beach doesn't want to lose an
estimated $30 million a year generated by the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Danadio said the city and county have made a proposal to the
Dodgers to buy the stadium, practice fields and conference center,
and then lease it back to the team for a minimal amount. The
Dodgers would keep the cash purchase price. The Dodgers are the
only major-league team to own its own complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more to lose than anyone else in spring training, so
we have to work a little harder,'' Danadio said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cactus League hopes to have a record attendance
year, but also has plenty to do without dwelling on luring new
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a more exciting time for the Cactus
League,'' said Jerry Geiger, president of the Cactus League
Association. ``We're coming off a terribly exciting, history-making
year for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Geiger and Robert Brinton, who heads the Mesa Visitors and
Convention Bureau, both say the Cactus League has a chance to hit
the 1-million mark in attendance for the first time. Last year's
attendance was about 890,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs pre-sold 119,000 tickets for this spring, while last
year's total attendance during March was 134,000. The team, which
regularly leads the Cactus League in attendance, would have to
average about 11,000 or so the rest of the month to break 1998's
157,000 record attendance. Brinton said it will be close, but
easily better than last year, when poor weather and a less
attractive schedule held attendance down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we were heading into a better season _ thank you,
Sammy,'' Brinton said. ``It's more festive all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   How big is the Cubs' slugger, who last year hit 66 home runs to
finish second to Mark McGwire's record-setting 70?
</P>
<P>
   Thursday in Tucson, the largest crowd ever to see a Cactus
League game in the city _ 11,808 _ turned out at Tucson Electric
Park to see the Cubs and the Arizona Diamondbacks. And Sosa didn't
even show.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams have seen a spike in preseason sales, too. The
Milwaukee Brewers report advance sales up 20 to 30 percent over
last year. And country singer Garth Brooks, back in camp Thursday
after spending five days with his mother, who had a cancerous spot
removed, is attracting bigger crowds to San Diego Padres games.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger said lousy weather at the beginning of last March kept
visitors away, and 60 percent of Cactus League attendance comes
from out of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Brinton estimated that attendance so far is up about 10 percent
across the league.
</P>
<P>
   Scully, the county sports commissioner, said there is a lot of
work to do in marketing the league better. And he said the state
must work to maintain the Cactus League facilities at a high level
without money from the the rental-vehicle tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of excitement with the Dodgers,'' Baier said.
``It makes sense, but there are other challenges on the horizon
when we no longer have that (tax) money.''
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Baier said the Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Bureau had been
trying to woo teams _ including the Dodgers _ to train there.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Powers, a spokesman for the Las Vegas bureau, said its board
had shelved plans to build a spring training complex because it
wouldn't be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   But Powers said private efforts to build facilities could
surface. And Baier said the Dodgers have also talked to private
parties in Las Vegas about a complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, they certainly have the cash in Las Vegas,''
Baier said. ``It's possible they not only have the ability to build
those facilities but to cover all the teams' expenses and give the
teams a share of the revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Baier's worry is that Arizona will become complacent because the
Cactus League is in such good shape now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look into the future, when all these leases begin
expiring in eight to 15 years and the facilities will need
renovation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Arizona cities still want more baseball teams. One city is
Yuma, which nearly landed a minor-league affiliate for the
Diamondbacks and has a long history of baseball, including the
previous spring home of the San Diego Padres and the current spring
home of the Yakult Swallows of Japan's Central League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yuma is still very interested in having a team,'' Baier said.
``I view it as something that would be a goal. They have rabid
fans, and a facility in place. All it would take is renovations.''
</P>
<P>
   And Marana, which early on talked to the Dodgers, is definitely
interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to have four teams in Tucson, wouldn't it?''
Baier asked.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. A new decade is about to begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
