<HEADLINE>
NOBODY CAN FIND THE BASKET, EXCEPT DUKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ It was the region that couldn't shoot straight
Friday in a brutal afternoon of substandard basketball at the East
Regional of the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament. None of the four teams competing shot better than 40
percent and one, Wisconsin, scored only 32 points. Then top-seeded
Duke showed up Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils rolled over Florida A&AMP;M, 99-58. In the first 10
minutes of the game, they showed why they are the tournament
favorite, matching Wisconsin's final point total. Duke went deep on
the bench to play the walk-ons well before the first-half buzzer
sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The overmatched Rattlers (12-19), from the Mid-Eastern Athletic
Conference, played gallantly to stay within 4 points in the opening
four minutes. But then the Blue Devils (33-1) exploded for 23
straight points on their way to a 59-20 halftime lead behind 65.5
percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Duke obviously did not need Trajan Langdon, the fifth-year
senior and leading scorer, who has not played since spraining his
left foot in the quarterfinals of last week's Atlantic Coast
Conference tournament. Nor did the Blue Devils need Elton Brand,
who played just 19 minutes but led four Blue Devils in double
figures with 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   Taymon Domzalski, Duke's little-used big man at 6 feet 10
inches, added 13 points. Duke shot 61.8 percent from the field and
66.7 percent from the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously had more talent than them and should have won,''
said Duke Coach Mike Krzyzewski. ``But they're a great story _ to
go 0-10 and 1-13 and then make the NCAA tournament. What a story!''
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers won their last five games to earn their first
tournament berth. ``It was a dream that we played against probably
the best college team ever assembled,'' said Kevin George, a senior
from Queens. ``It was an honor to be on the same court with them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SOUTHWEST MISSOURI STATE 43, WISCONSIN 32
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The 12th-seeded Bears, coached by Steve Alford, upset the
fifth-seeded Badgers in a game filled with missed shots.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin (22-10) was 12 of 47 from the field (25.5 percent),
including six minutes without scoring in the second half, to insure
its place in the record book. The Badgers scored the fewest points
in an NCAA tournament game since the advent of the shot clock in
1986 and the fewest in any NCAA tournament game since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the Bears will play Tennessee, which defeated
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dick Bennett of Wisconsin knew his team entered the
tournament struggling to score. It had been bounced from the Big
Ten tournament by Michigan State after a 10-minute stretch without
a basket. But he said he felt helpless Friday as he watched the
Badgers, who were 2 of 16 from behind the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They locked onto our cuts, and inside we weren't physical
enough,'' said Bennett, whose team runs a deliberate, cut-and-shoot
offense.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE 62, DELAWARE 52
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Tennessee's victory over Delaware was also numbing to watch.
After the number of air balls reached double digits and the
turnovers slowed the game to shuffleboard pace, the Tennessee
Volunteers decided that if somebody had to win this game, it might
as well be them. They did it in pitiful fashion, beating the Blue
Hens in one of the most poorly played games in NCAA tournament
history.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams were a combined 38 for 118 from the field, lost
the ball 33 times and looked like recreation league teams as they
stepped out of bounds, fought their teammates for rebounds and
missed layups. The fourth-seeded Volunteers (21-8) shot 29.8
percent; the 13th-seeded Blue Hens (25-6) shot 32.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the second half, the lights inside the Charlotte
Coliseum were brightened, prompting Tennessee guard Brandon Wharton
to joke afterward, ``It was probably a horrible game to watch so
they had to put the spotlight on the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Hens had a 6-point lead with 7 minutes 31 seconds to go
in the first half, but the Volunteers mounted a 16-7 run to take a
25-22 lead into the locker room. Delaware, despite 23 points from
forward Mike Pegues, pulled within 3 points with 11 minutes left in
the game, then watched the Vols score 13 of the next 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware was held to its lowest point total of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
