<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-BULL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS JUST ABOUT HIT AN ALL-TIME FRANCHISE LOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Knicks had been able to camouflage their character
flaws, hide their casual attitude and cardboard pride. They had
been able to keep their dark secret to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's out. The stripped-down Chicago Bulls revealed the
soul-less underbelly of a Knicks franchise Friday night that barely
displayed any pride and effort in a 76-63 defeat at the United
Center that brushed against the team's all-time lows.
</P>
<P>
   Only a meaningless lay-in by Marcus Camby with 22.9 seconds left
prevented the Knicks from tying the team's all-time low for points
in a game _ 61, set on March 22, 1992, in a game against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   And before garbage time set in the fourth quarter, the Knicks,
who had just 33 points after three quarters, were clearly on the
verge of sinking beneath the league's all-time low offensive mark
for a regular-season game. That figure, 55 points, was set by
Indiana a year ago in a game against San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks did manage to set a franchise low for points
with 22 in the first half, and tied another team mark by scoring
just 5 points in the second quarter (the previous 5 came in a game
against Portland two years ago). By the miserable end, the Knicks
(11-9) had turned the ball over 23 times and shot just 31 percent
and their 19 field goals had also tied an all-time NBA low.
</P>
<P>
   Stars like Allan Houston, Larry Johnson and Latrell Sprewell
were of no help. The Bulls (6-14) led by as many as 32 in the third
quarter as the Knicks staggered to their sixth loss in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   This was not about missing the injured Patrick Ewing. This was
deeper than that. After all, this was not exactly the championship
Bulls of old they were facing. And this was not the third night of
three consecutive nights in this crammed season, either. This was a
simple back-to-back game against a shell of a championship team.
</P>
<P>
   And the Knicks simply failed to show up. Even worse, they did
not seem to care. They were blank-faced as they absorbed this
near-historic humiliation. They did not pound their fists or yell
at the skies or scream at each other. Without the slightest
emotion, the Knicks just surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   There were times when Coach Jeff Van Gundy just stood on the
sideline, hands on hips, with a look of disgust flooding his tired
face. He was motionless, stunned. Not to this unthinkable degree,
but Van Gundy had almost predicted this kind of mental collapse
before the game. He had been worried about the team's attitude,
about the casual way they accepted losing just as long as they
still kept their heads about .500.
</P>
<P>
   `'We're stuck in a little mediocrity,'' said Van Gundy. `'I want
the six guys who have been here before to pull us out of it. I just
have the feeling that we're too accepting of mediocrity.''
</P>
<P>
   But mediocrity did not begin to describe the lifeless approach
the Knicks had as they spent four quarters setting, or nearly
setting, all sorts of all-time lows. It was almost surreal. As
quick as a blunder, the Knicks were down, 20-2, in the first
quarter before they scrambled to pull within 29-17. And to think,
the real unraveling was only about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   In the franchise-tying 5-point second quarter, the Knicks missed
their last nine shots before the break, made just one of 13 field
goals and turned the ball over seven times. By the end of their
franchise-low 22-point first half _ the likes of which had not been
seen since the Knicks title team of 1973 scored just 26 against the
Bulls at Chicago Stadium on Feb. 23, 1973 _ the team had turned the
ball over 15 times and hit just 7 of 27 shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, the league's lowest scoring team, were making a
mockery of the Knicks' celebrated defense. Toni Kukoc, who had been
10 for 41 in the two previous meetings with the Knicks this season,
finished the first half 6 for 9 and 4 for 4 from 3-point range. His
20 first-half points were collected as he popped free of Johnson,
Sprewell, Camby and any other plodding Knick that Van Gundy wanted
to throw at him.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls didn't have to be great. They didn't have to have
Michael Jordan. All they needed was to capitalize on the
half-hearted Knicks to build a lead that bulged at 25 points during
the second quarter. There was little Van Gundy could do. Timeouts
didn't help, pulling Kurt Thomas or Chris Dudley or Houston or
Johnson didn't help, either.
</P>
<P>
   This spinout was beyond his control. Every player he had come to
rely on without Ewing was letting the team down. In the first half,
Johnson was 1 for 5, Houston was 1 for 6 and Sprewell was 2 for 9.
It was Sprewell who scored all 5 points in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' second quarter made the first one something to brag
about, even though it was nearly as miserable. At the start, Kukoc
lost Johnson to hit two consecutive 3-pointers in concert with a
Bulls team that was feeling dizzy with their lead. The Bulls hit
their first six shots of the game at the same time the Knicks were
committing five turnovers in the first four minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing to be said that the scoreboard didn't already
indicate.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ward, who had ice on his sore right shoulder before the
game, took a spill in the opening minute. He played 5 minutes,
turned the ball over once and then left the game with a bruised
right shoulder and did not return.
</P>
</TEXT>
