<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SECRETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICE SECRETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 21 years Laura Shaw worked as an insurance claims processor
for New England Financial, leading what looked to co-workers like a
quiet life on a modest salary. No one would have pegged her as a
candidate for the 20-count indictment handed up by a federal grand
jury March 2 or as the mastermind behind a computer scam that
allegedly siphoned $3.3 million from her company.
</P>
<P>
   She apparently did it for the love of horses _ not bets at the
track, but the buying and training of American saddlebreds for
show. Colleagues at New England Financial knew of her hobby from
the horse photographs on her desk but had no idea how deep this
passion went or that it might have led her down the twisted path of
what now seems to have been a double life.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's story makes a person wonder about the illusions of the
office and whether one can ever really know the man or woman in the
next cubicle. We think we know these co-workers of many years,
chit-chat with them at lunch, and even share confidences under the
umbrella of a corporate camaraderie that makes them seem pretty
much like us, give or take a few personality quirks.
</P>
<P>
   But how many Walter Mitty fantasies percolate behind a pair of
bifocals seemingly intent on the latest policy memo? How many of
those fantasies inch into reality as the placid accountant tries to
write a spy novel during lunch hours or the married-with-family
president calls his tootsie?
</P>
<P>
   When word of criminal behavior surfaces in these incubators of
conformity, the incongruity is almost paralyzing, for such
aberrations seem impossible amid the rules, security, and attention
to detail that weave the cocoon of company life.
</P>
<P>
   The press arrives and asks: Who was this renegade disguised as a
bureaucrat? Did anyone suspect? If the crime is a violent one, then
surely there must have been signs. But co-workers can often recall
nothing more than the pleasant smile of a prompt and courteous
employee.
</P>
<P>
   Thoreau once observed that people lead lives of quiet
desperation _ probably because they're invisible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
