</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-RETREAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE IMPROVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be hard to imagine a more pressing time for members of
the US House of Representatives to promote civility among their
peers. The impeachment of President Clinton strained already frayed
relations between Democrats and Republicans and exacerbated raw
divisons within the Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   So a House retreat planned in Hershey, Penn., starting next
Friday deserves applause. Whether it has a hope of success is
another matter.
</P>
<P>
   A similar retreat was held two years ago. Less than a month
later two House leaders _ Republican whip Tom DeLay and Democrat
David Obey _ were involved in a shoving-and-cussing incident on the
House floor that embarrassed all of Congress. Highly partisan
wrangling on legislative issues and then the impeachment drama
added to an unusually rancorous session.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Thomas Sawyer, an Ohio Democrat and one of the
retreat's organizers, says optimistically that even the DeLay-Obey
dust-up had positive consequences, because many members rushed to
restore order. Another organizer, Illinois Republican Ray LaHood,
says most Democrats and Republicans agree that bipartisanship is
needed on at least a few issues to prove that the House is not
stuck in endless acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   So the organizers have invited Nobel Peace Prize laureate John
Hume to set an example. The theory is that members who come to know
one another as three-dimensional people rather than one-dimensional
issue positions will be able to make the compromises bipartisanship
requires.
</P>
<P>
   Two problems remain. One is that some congressmen are in fact
one-dimensional, at least in their politics. And another was noted
by organizer Amo Houghton, a New York Republican: While about half
the House will attend, the absentees will include many of those
``who need it the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, credit is due those determined to see that the retreat's
success is measured not simply in keeping physical assaults to a
minimum but in achieving bipartisan progress. That would merit
another peace prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
