<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TARGETING THE TOBACCO FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 40 state attorneys general sued the tobacco industry to
recover Medicaid costs associated with smoking-related illnesses,
the federal government declined an invitation to join. When the
historic $386 billion tobacco settlement arrived in Congress for
ratification in 1996, lawmakers dithered, delayed, and disgraced
the bill by loading it with unrelated giveaways, then killed it on
the grounds that it was too expensive. The federal government,
including the Clinton administration, does not deserve its claim on
the $246 billion the states negotiated later with the cigarette
companies, even though Washington picks up about 57 cents of every
Medicaid dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the states are not bound to use the money as
the AGs intended _ to fund programs aimed at reducing smoking,
especially among young people, so the escalating cycle of disease
can be broken. Some have plans for the money that include highway
and prison projects not even tangentially related to the public
health. In Massachusetts, Governor &UR;  &LR; Paul Cellucci has proposed
using the state's initial share of the settlement _ $361 million _
for AIDS initiatives, insurance coverage, and other laudable
purposes, but with none of the money going to the state's highly
successful tobacco control program.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Martin Meehan, a leader in the congressional
fight against big tobacco, has proposed legislation that would
require all states to devote at least 25 percent of the settlement
cash to antismoking programs as a condition for Washington waiving
its claim. The Senate recently adopted language waiving the claim
without any conditions, which leaves the door open to mischief.
</P>
<P>
   Although some in Washington have excellent ideas for using the
settlement money, including better enforcement by the Food and Drug
Administration and a national advertising campaign, those should be
funded through general revenues. Meehan's proposal is an
appropriate compromise between squandering an opportunity to reduce
smoking and dictating how the states should spend the cash they
worked so hard to earn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
