<HEADER>
A8963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-GERMANY-BOS     03-13 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GERMANY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER IN COMMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oskar Lafontaine, the German finance minister, did not deserve
the label ``most dangerous man in Europe'' (bestowed by a London
tabloid), but his resignation lifts a burden from Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder. Six months after he first took office, Schroeder
has gained unquestioned control of the German government.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine is described as a Keynesian for believing that an
increase in consumer demand is necessary to revive the German
economy. John Maynard Keynes, the late British economist, was
prescribing remedies for the Great Depression. He would no doubt be
concerned about the 11 percent German unemployment rate today, but
he might also have noted that mandatory social service
contributions add 42 percent to already high German wages. Foreign
companies rarely invest there, preferring Ireland or Britain for
lower taxes and fewer regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The European financial establishment disliked Lafontaine so much
that a cut in interest rates, one of his better ideas, was unlikely
as long as he was in office. He was especially feared because as
chairman of the Social Democratic Party, his power base extended
beyond the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder has consolidated his power by becoming party chairman,
and he replaced Lafontaine with a technocrat. For the rest of his
term, economic policy will be the chancellor's ultimate
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder has gained great popularity by saying little about his
economic views. He seems to be a disciple of Tony Blair, the
British prime minister, who is trying to chart a middle way between
dogmatic socialism and untrammeled capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Blair has one great advantage over his German counterpart.
Margaret Thatcher, as inflexible in her own way as Lafontaine, did
much to cut away obsolete regulations and subsidies in the '80s to
prepare Britain for international economic competition. Schroeder
faces the formidable task of finding a distinctly German approach
that revamps the economy while preserving programs that protect the
vulnerable from the cruelties of capitalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 0033EST &QL; 
