<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-RAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAP CLAPTRAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the fight against domestic violence, the lyrics of rap songs
can be a slippery enemy but one that deserves to be exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Cloaked in free speech rights, some songs slash at women. The
white rapper Eminem is one example. He has earned respect and a
recording contract from the black rap community. He might have
something to say about being white in a black world. But his new
release, ``The Slim Shady LP,'' includes the lowdown on a father
hiding mom's body in the trunk and not quite admitting this to his
child. This prompted Timothy White, editor in chief of Billboard
magazine, to write a column criticizing Eminem for taking a
``leadership role in making money by exploiting the world's
misery.''
</P>
<P>
   But calling one song ``delightfully mean-spirited,'' critic
Brian McCollum of the Detroit Free Press says the CD is part of an
entertainment tradition, ``the wink-and-nod allure of horror film
violence.'' Others rightly argue that rap is an art that braves
some of life's darkest corners.
</P>
<P>
   Those who condemn rap's attacks on women risk sounding racist or
like the prudes who wanted Elvis's swiveling hips kept off
television. Eminem and other performers' robust use of free speech
deserves an equal and opposing reaction. It's too long a leap to
say that lyrics will make listeners act violently. But it's
essential to ask what daily decay comes from fans mouthing lines
about drugging and raping a girl or assaulting a television star.
</P>
<P>
   Portrayed as making a lot of money, rap singers have dangerous
clout, argues Kate Cloud of Respond Inc., a nonprofit organization
in Boston that serves battered women and children. Respond benefits
from sales of a CD that includes the work of local musicians.
</P>
<P>
   This presents a challenge to other artists: Pick worthy
adversaries. Rap has the raw power to expose violence instead of
glorifying it, to show the child who sees his mother's murder, to
dissect what turns people against those they know.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a right _ which must be vigilantly defended _ to
trot out tired, brutal cliches. The world is hungry for artists who
can do more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
