<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8965 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  (ForreleaseSunday March14 1999) &LR;  03-13 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, March 14, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans take water for granted. They expend enormous
quantities of it to wash their cars, sprinkle their lawns, and
irrigate their fields. Only when passing through Death Valley or
some other arid sector of the Southwest might the average
water-spoiled American be inclined to imagine fresh water as a
disappearing natural resource, an economic threat, or a cause of
war.
</P>
<P>
   But in many parts of the world these are the perils of water
scarcity. For people in the Middle East, for people living near the
Nile or in the Fertile Crescent formed by the Tigris and Euphrates,
for the 1.2 billion people of China, the need for fresh water
presages conflict and crisis in the coming century.
</P>
<P>
   The former secretary general of the United Nations, Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, predicted when he was Egypt's foreign minister that
``the next war in our region will be over the waters of the Nile,
not politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's situation as a country dependent on the good will of its
riparian neighbors is a classic example of the dangers that finite
supplies of fresh water present. Egyptians have always been
sustained by the waters of the Nile _ but there are nine countries
upstream of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959 Egypt and Sudan signed the Nile Treaty, which has served
fairly well as a basis for the equitable sharing of Nile waters.
But as Ethiopia begins to divert water from the Nile for a
burgeoning population, the two countries risk coming into conflict
over a resource as indispensable as air.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the bitter disputes to be unknotted in final-status
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority, none
promises to be more difficult than the quarrel over water rights. A
recent international study establishing the facts and parameters of
the water problem in the land between Jordan's eastern border and
the Mediterranean coast of Israel warned that even with competent
management of water resources, ``the area's inhabitants will almost
assuredly live under conditions of significant water stress in the
near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, routinely denied permission to dig wells in the
West Bank, aspire to gain control over the West Bank aquifer, which
Israel can hardly do without. On the Israeli side there is
trepidation that once the West Bank is ceded to the Palestinians,
improvident water management might doom both peoples to the
irreparable loss of the pristine water in their sole aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mideast as elsewhere, the perils of scarce water are
compounded by a blatant contradiction. Although freshwater sources
often extend or flow across borders, there is no international or
supranational legal framework like the Law of the Sea to guide the
apportioning of water rights. Each conflict over water must be
addressed in an ad hoc way through binational or regional
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   There is a further contradiction in the legal principles
governing the water laws that do exist. On the one hand, a given
country may assume it has a right to do whatever it wishes with all
the water in its territory, even if that water flows to it across a
border. On the other hand, one country's right to dam up or divert
its water implies that it has a right to reduce the amount of water
flowing to a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   A dramatic illustration of the dangers inherent in conflicts
over water rights can be seen in Turkey's elaborate and expensive
damming of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers. The 22 dams and 19
hydroelectric plants being built on the two rivers are in the
southeast, the Kurdish region of Turkey. The enormous value
Turkey's $32 billion dam project is expected to have in the next
century has a lot to do with Ankara's zealous repression of almost
all Kurdish political activity.
</P>
<P>
   And damming the Tigris and Euphrates has provoked tensions in
relations with Turkey's neighbors Syria and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Since there are no affordable technological fixes for the
world's looming water crisis _ desalination being too costly for
poor countries and transportation of water remaining impractical _
the realistic palliatives for the foreseeable future must be
conservation, cooperation among states, and population control.
None of these remedies will be easy to administer, but the world
has no choice in the matter. There is no life without water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
