<HEADER>
A8966 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  (ForreleaseSunday March14 1999) &LR;  03-13 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING POLITICS WITH REAL SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, March 14, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the Gulf of Tonkin resolution, which Lyndon Johnson
used as an ersatz authorization for America's undeclared war in
Vietnam, the legislative and executive branches have feuded over
their respective roles in taking the always grave decision to place
US troops in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   This week that quarrel reached a boiling point. The most telling
sign that Congress is abandoning a tradition that partisanship
should cease at the water's edge was the premature House vote on
the Clinton administration's plan to include 4,000 US soldiers
among 28,000 NATO peacekeepers who will go to Kosovo in the event
that the Serb and Albanian sides sign a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The administration properly implored the House not to take its
nonbinding vote until after the belligerents signed onto the peace
agreement. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright warned that the
House's ill-timed consideration of the issue could abort precarious
negotiations that are at a crucial stage and ``be taken by both
sides as a green light to resume fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The same brief was reinforced at House hearings by former Senate
majority leader Bob Dole and Jeane Kirkpatrick, Ronald Reagan's
ambassador to the United Nations. Both said it is very much in
America's interest to put out the Kosovo fire before it flares up
into a regional conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 219 to 191 Thursday to authorize the deployment
of US troops, irresponsibly refusing to wait for a peace accord to
be signed.
</P>
<P>
   Congress certainly has a right to demand consultation in
decisions that can result in American casualties. It was in the
name of that right that Barney Frank became the only liberal
Democrat to vote for a resolution against sending troops to Kosovo.
The resolution, proposed by Republican Tillie Fowler of Florida,
was defeated, but any legislator who remembered the Gulf of Tonkin
deception could be excused for supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the only conceivable reason for holding the House vote
this week, when it might imperil the Kosovo peace negotiations, was
intemperate partisanship. The Republican leadership should not
allow itself to be blinded in this way again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 0038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
