<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8967 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  (ForreleaseSunday March14 1999) &LR;  03-13 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-INDIARED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING (INDIA) RED 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, March 14, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crayola should keep ``indian red'' in the box and spell it with
a capital I. The color, introduced in 1958 and printed in lowercase
because the crayon manufacturer heard that children have trouble
reading capital letters, is being renamed because of teacher
complaints that it ``confuses'' children who think it refers to the
skin pigment of Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It has nothing to do with Native Americans _ the reddish brown
tint is named for a pigment found in soil around India and used to
make fine oil paints. A simple explanation and pointer to a map
would clear up any confusion, just as a quick grammar lesson would
explain that proper nouns begin with capital letters. There would
also be room for a lesson in respect for human beings of all ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   But a chance at education suffers because of hypersensitivity to
the possibility that someone might be offended, however mistakenly,
and because adults feel they must dilute fascinating concepts that
students might find too difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the fate of Crayola's ``prussian blue'' (again spelled
incorrectly), eliminated in 1958 because of complaints that
children couldn't relate to Prussia, which was no longer on the
map.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Empire isn't on the map, either, but good teaching
always makes it relevant. The same is true of ancient Greece.
Likewise, many a young mind might have been prompted to find out
about the former German state and its rigid military life while
musing over a crayon named for the uniforms worn by Prussian
soldiers. The replacement name, ``midnight blue,'' has probably
never sent a child to the encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   Crayola did make the right move when it changed ``flesh'' to
``peach'' in 1962, acknowledging that skin comes in many hues. But
bending to misplaced pressure for the wrong reasons cheapens the
stand for a valid cause.
</P>
<P>
   The job of anyone connected with the education of children
should be to teach them to think. Eliminating ``indian red''
teaches them to duck the truth and take the easy way out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
