A8968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-BRUINS-NY     03-13 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-BRUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' PLAYOFF PUSH UPENDED BY THE BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John MacLean sounded as if he were describing a fireworks
display.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just boom, boom,'' MacLean said. ``It's just bang, bang,
bang.''
</P>
<P>
   MacLean, a Rangers right wing, accounted for some of the
pyrotechnics Friday night at Madison Square Garden when he scored
twice to give the Rangers two of their three one-goal leads in the
third period against the Boston Bruins. But Anson Carter of the
Bruins answered with the final two rocket bursts, 19 seconds apart
with less than three minutes remaining, to give the Bruins a 5-4
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The result was significant in the Eastern Conference playoff
race because it left the Rangers 4 points behind the eighth-place
Bruins for the final post-season berth. The Rangers are in 10th
place, 1 point behind Florida, and with 16 games to go in the
regular season, the Rangers have played one more game than both
Boston and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Both goalies _ Mike Richter of the Rangers and Byron Dafoe of
the Bruins _ played well for two periods, but both wore down under
the barrage of the shooting gallery. The game was tied at 1-1 at
the second intermission, then exploded with seven goals in a third
period that the old-time hockey coaches used to call
rambly-scrambly and loosey-goosey.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers finished with 44 shots and the Bruins with 38.
Carter's winning goal, which was unassisted, came at 17 minutes 32
seconds of the third period after several Rangers, including
Richter, had trouble handling the puck in their end.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a little sloppy down low,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, watching from the other end, thought his team was lucky
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, we got away with one,'' he said. ``The way we were
playing, we didn't deserve to win that game. That's a 4-point game.
It's a pretty devastating loss for the Rangers. I don't know what
that does for their psyche going into the stretch run.''
</P>
<P>
   That run continues Sunday on Long Island against the Islanders.
Richter, who has played in the last 10 games, said his team would
refocus, although he added: ``It's not like you deceive yourself
and say it doesn't matter that we lost.'' He stressed that the team
still has 16 games remaining to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Heinze also scored two goals for the Bruins and Jason
Allison got the other, the only power-play goal of the night.
MacLean's two goals give him 25 with the Rangers. Adam Graves, who
has 32 for the season and a new contract on the way, got one of the
other Ranger goals, with another scored by Mike Knuble. Petr Nedved
had 2 assists and 11 shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   John Muckler, the Rangers' coach, spoke soothing words
afterward, saying, ``Oh, I guess it's a breakdown, it's bad luck,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a different tone than he displayed in the first period,
when his team fell behind by 1-0 and almost by 2-0 until a Boston
goal was disallowed after a video review showed a man in the
crease.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Muckler called a timeout to scold his players on
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a little bit rattled and we just tried to calm
everybody down,'' Muckler said. The coach said the game was ``a
learning experience'' for some of the Rangers, particularly their
young players. Manny Malhotra, the rookie center, set up Knuble's
goal and put four shots on net. But he was on the ice for the
winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not from a lack of trying,'' Muckler said of the defeat,
referring to the team in general. ``We did some not-very-good
things in behind the blue line, there's no question about that. But
those things are going to happen. You can't dwell on it. We lost,
we're four points behind, and we're going to Long Island. We've got
to get over it. We're not out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   His players seemed calm enough afterward, some even upbeat.
Brian Leetch, the captain, said: ``It was some hockey game.
Obviously, it was disappointing for us at the end, but it was an
exciting game to play in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got two of their veteran defensemen back from
injuries. Ulf Samuelsson had missed two games with a concussion,
and Peter Popovic had not played in a month because of blood in his
right eye. The Rangers also used Mike Maneluk, a forward acquired
from Chicago on waivers on March 4. Maneluk had dressed for one
game, last Sunday in Boston, but did not play.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   RICK CURRAN, agent for ADAM GRAVES, said it would be ``just a
matter of days'' before the Rangers announce a new multiyear
contract for the veteran left wing. Graves, who has 32 goals this
season, will be 31 this summer. Without a contract, he could become
an unrestricted free agent. He makes $3 million this season and
stands to earn more on his next deal. ``Things are almost done,''
Curran said. ``I'm optimistic.'' Graves said after the game
``Hopefully, it will get done.'' He said he was more focused these
days on hockey and his newborn daughter, MONTANA, and her older
sister, MADISON. ... Other Rangers who could become unrestricted
free agents this summer are the defensemen BRIAN LEETCH and ULF
SAMUELSSON. Although Leetch's agent has discussed a new pact with
the General Manager NEIL SMITH, there has been no indication of
momentum from either side. Samuelsson said recently that he had had
no negotiations. The trade deadline is March 23. . . . Still
injured for the Rangers are forward TODD HARVEY and defenseman JEFF
BEUKEBOOM. Harvey has a broken right thumb and Beukeboom is
recovering from a concussion. Harvey will be back in about two
weeks. Beukeboom's return is indefinite. . .. Out of uniform Friday
night were defensemen STAN NECKAR and RICH BRENNAN.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
