<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PRIVACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEEPING THROUGH WINDOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, March 15, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does it take a law _ that is, pesky government intervention _ to
protect consumers who use the Internet? The issue flared recently
when Richard Smith, president of a Cambridge, Mass., software
company, made a troubling, Big Brother discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Smith found that Microsoft's Windows 98 on some computer systems
_ mostly networked computers and not home PCs _ generates
identification numbers. Without customers' consent, these numbers
were transmitted to Microsoft and could in theory have been used as
tracking devices.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bug, Microsoft said of the problem, and it is being
cleared up. The numbers were meant only to provide information to
speed up phone calls made by customers seeking product support.
</P>
<P>
   But on-line privacy is more than a one-glitch issue. In another
case, US Representative Edward Markey of Massachusetts charged in a
letter to the Intel Corp. that its Pentium III chips could violate
consumers' privacy by creating a way to track their Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Self-regulate, says the Online Privacy Alliance, a
coalition of more than 80 corporations and associations, including
Microsoft and Intel. The alliance suggests that Web page sponsors
post their privacy policies and earn a privacy seal of approval
from independent organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Disclosure should help. But there still ought to be a law _ a
legal standard that protects consumers without strangling industry.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act
last year, protecting those who are 12 years old or younger. This
year Markey is drafting legislation to cover adults. Three
provisions _ summed up as knowledge, notice, and no _ would give
consumers knowledge about what information is collected about them;
notice of how the information would be used; and the ability to say
no to the taking of their information. In Europe, a Markey aide
says, privacy rules are stricter because of awareness that data as
basic as someone's religion could be used harmfully.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation died in the last two Congresses. That's a
shame. Whether on the street or the Internet, people are entitled
to privacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
