<SLUG> BC-BBA-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS, GONZALEZ'S AGENTS TO TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Texas Rangers will receive their
first indication Saturday of how difficult it will be to keep Juan
Gonzalez in a Texas uniform beyond the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers president Tom Schieffer plans to begin discussions with
Gonzalez's representatives, Jim Bronner and Fernando Cuza,
regarding a contract extension for the two-time American League
most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Two issues likely will be addressed when the parties convene:
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's existing contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' commitment toward retaining their right fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we want Juan to play for us, but I don't think this
is just a real big deal (Saturday)'' Schieffer said. ``Juan is
under a long-term contract now. Obviously, we've been able to work
out a long-term contract with him in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both sides know each other a lot better now than they
did five years ago, so I don't think there's going to be any
particular problem working something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez declined to discuss the matter and said he remains
committed solely to ``staying focused on baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's existing contract will pay him $8.5 million this
season and $7.5 million the next should the Rangers exercise their
option for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Gonzalez well below the game's best-paid position
player. That distinction belongs to first baseman Mo Vaughn, who
received a six-year contract worth $80 million ($13.33 million per
year) this winter from the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   To what lengths will the Rangers be willing to go?
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez could command more than Vaughn received and threaten
the level attained by pitcher Kevin Brown, who became the game's
best-paid player after signing a seven-year contract worth $105
million _ or $15 million annually _ with the Los Angeles Dodgers
this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the sort of guy who has to have a dollar more than
somebody else,'' Schieffer said of Gonzalez. ``He makes a lot of
money, but I really don't think money is the motivating factor for
Juan. I don't think he really measures his self-worth by how much
money he makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to be well-compensated. He wants to be compensated as
well as someone else in his position, as well he should be. I don't
have any problem with that, but he traditionally has not been very
difficult to deal with on salary matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Players Association encourages its marquee members to test
the market through free agency and thereby establish new salary
levels. Gonzalez and Seattle center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. could
become free agents after the 2000 season, and some major-league
officials speculate that one or both could command a contract worth
as much as $20 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone is going to put pressure on Juan
Gonzalez,'' Schieffer said. ``Juan Gonzalez has shown a pretty good
ability to take care of his own business. I think he's going to do
what he feels is in his best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado right fielder Larry Walker, whom Bronner also
represents, recently signed a six-year contract extension worth $75
million. Walker perhaps hurt his chances of earning more by taking
an active role during the negotiations against Bronner's advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just do it,'' Walker said before signing. ``There's
certain money on the table, and I'm fine with it.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Rafael Palmeiro, who this winter signed a
five-year contract worth $45 million, likely accepted less to
return to the Rangers and also accepted $1 million per year
deferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may decide he wants to wait a year,'' Schieffer said of
Gonzalez. ``We may decide we want to wait a year. The nice thing
about it is we've basically got two years to come up with
something, but I really don't expect this to be a difficult
negotiation at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, no one should expect a swift resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wouldn't expect any final agreement to come out of
(Saturday),'' Schieffer said. ``It's just the beginning of the
process.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
