<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS GO BIG TO CONTROL BOARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Leave it to the NBA's resident iron man to explain why
the Mavericks are suddenly attacking the backboards with a
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a conscious effort to go out and do our jobs,''
forward A.C. Green said of a 49-37 rebounding advantage over the
Orlando Magic on Thursday. ``We've been so lackadaisical in trying
to let the game come to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We challenged ourselves, as being men and as being
professionals, to really come and play as hard and as strong as you
possibly could. We've been extremely passive on defense, and the
energy hasn't been there.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly wasn't the case against Orlando, as the
Mavericks' front line of Green, Gary Trent and Shawn Bradley
dominated the glass. Green collected 13 points and 11 rebounds,
Trent had 21 points and 10 boards and Bradley added 10 points and
10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The front line epitomized the hard-hat effort Dallas (7-14)
hopes to take against the Vancouver Grizzlies (4-16) at 7 p.m.
Saturday at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coaches said an aggressive attitude by the front line
makes the rebounding pendulum swing Dallas' way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think part of the success with rebounding comes with A.C. at
the (small forward) spot, so we should outrebound most teams,''
Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson said. ``But I think more
than anything it's just become the focus of our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we've rebounded well we've seemed to come up with
wins. The guys understand what kind of priority it is and they're
taking it to task.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' big lineup of the 7-foot-6 Bradley, the 6-9 Green
and the 6-8 Trent came after 6-7 Cedric Ceballos, the starting
small forward, fractured both wrists.
</P>
<P>
   Trent, Green and Bradley focus on rebounding, an aspect of the
game that keeps teams in games when their jump shots desert them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've been committed every night to rebounding, it's
just some nights you can get there and some nights you can't,''
Trent said. ``Every night everybody wants to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just some nights you're maybe not mentally focused into
attacking the glass like you are at times. But the more consistency
you have with it, the more success you have with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who averages 3.57 blocks while shooting .527 from the
floor, likes the front-liners' cerebral approach: They go into
games knowing that no rebounds equals no victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see us go out and attack the basket like we
did'' Thursday, Bradley said. ``If we keep doing that, I think
everything's going to be all right with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Green, who will play his 1,000th consecutive game
Saturday, has been the ringleader on the boards, attacking early
and often. Green collected eight rebounds against Orlando in the
first half, and his spirited play has been infectious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been a guy like A.C. starting the rebounding
surge, and then Gary picking up on it, and then Shawn,'' Nelson
said. ``It's like anything else _ if it's successful, guys become
accustomed to doing it and it catches on like wildfire, and that's
what's been going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your offense is not clicking, you've got to find
different ways to generate offense. For us, it has been our
defensive and offensive rebounding that has paved the way.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
