<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST WIN BRINGS STAR TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The team that launched a thousand monologues had
the last laugh on Thursday night by defeating the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Los Angeles Clippers demonstrated you don't have
to have a great team to be good sports. After spending a couple of
hours in preparation for tonight's game with Portland at the Sports
Arena, the players and coaches boarded a bus. Destination: Burbank
and a taping of ``The Tonight Show'' at NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Leno, who has taken more shots at the Clippers this season
than Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant combined, decided to salute
the team's first victory of 1999 by having coach Chris Ford and the
players as guests on his show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad we've got the win,'' Ford said of the hoopla.
``I just stay focused on one game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   And that next game tonight brings a formidable foe in the Trail
Blazers, who have a 15-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   Told you so: Thursday's victory by Detroit Mercy over UCLA in
the opening round of the NCAA Tournament came as no surprise to
Clippers forward Maurice Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you it would happen,'' said Taylor, cousin of Titans
point guard Rashard Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's coach is Perry Watson, a former Michigan assistant who
was given much of the credit for bringing Taylor to the Wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   Lights, camera, `Kandi': Friday's practice was under the
scrutiny of TNT, which sent a film crew to record footage of rookie
center Michael Olowokandi. The cable network has chosen Olowokandi,
the league's top draft pick, as the subject of an upcoming ``day in
the life'' feature, which actually will require two days of
filming.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two games of Olowokandi's life, he has combined for
three points.
</P>
<P>
   Just shoe it: One of the week's highlights was provided by
forward Tyrone Nesby and the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal in Tuesday's
Lakers-Clippers game at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby, an acrobatic and undrafted 6-foot-6 rookie from Nevada
Las Vegas, attempted to dunk on the 7-1, 318-pound O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The heroic effort resulted in a hard foul by O'Neal that was
judged flagrant. Moments before the tipoff of Wednesday's rematch
at the Forum, Nesby and O'Neal chatted about their collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was sorry he messed me up,'' Nesby said. ``I told
him it was cool, but that I wouldn't mind him hookin' me up with
some shoes. He said he could do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
