<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-UCLAMEN-LADN     03-13 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-UCLAMEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' PROBLEMS PERSIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Remove the inconsistencies and the injuries, the
youthful enthusiasm and the endless mistakes, and UCLA's 1998-99
journey went as scripted Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   With nine freshmen and sophomores in prominent roles, the Bruins
were picked fourth in the Pacific-10. They finished third.
</P>
<P>
   In the Associated Press and USA Today/ESPN preseason rankings,
they were slotted 12th and 13th, respectively. In the final
regular-season polls, they finished 12th and 13th, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers figured them for 18-21 wins. They had 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty similar to what I thought,'' UCLA coach Steve
Lavin said. ``I thought maybe we could win the first-round game and
lose the second, or get to the Sweet 16. Across the board, I
figured we'd be third or fourth in the conference and get 20 wins,
which we were able to do. But it would have been nice to go at
least a round further.''
</P>
<P>
   But final judgment will not come for a year or two, when the
freshmen and sophomores are juniors and seniors. If the Bruins
continue to improve _ if they win the Pac-10 title and make a Final
Four run _ this season will stand as a bridge to future success.
</P>
<P>
   If they do not _ if they wallow in the 20-win range and struggle
to survive the tournament's early rounds _ then this season is the
best Lavin can do.
</P>
<P>
   There are three components to coaching: recruiting, motivating
and teaching. Lavin has shown he can sign elite players and get
them to play hard. But his ability (and his staff's ability) to
teach the game, plot strategy and develop talent remains unproven.
</P>
<P>
   There is no replacement for experience and no substitute for
health. The Bruins lacked both this year. If Baron Davis and Dan
Gadzuric had been healthy all season, UCLA may have won another
game or two and received a No. 4 seed instead of a 5, and that
could have made the difference between a first-round exit and a
Sweet 16 finish.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems cut much deeper than injuries and inexperience,
and they begin in practice.
</P>
<P>
   A typical UCLA practice emphasizes conditioning, scrimmaging and
transition drills _ lots of transition drills _ on the premise that
you practice like you play. No doubt, it's effective. The Bruins
are well conditioned and devastating on the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   But several NBA scouts who watched UCLA practice in November and
December dinged the workouts on three counts: lack of teaching,
inattention to detail (uncorrected mistakes), and poor skill
development. The season proved them right.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA won 22 games because it had more talent that its
opposition. Based on Lavin's recruiting, that trend will continue
indefinitely. However, the Bruins will not beat the elite _
Stanford, Maryland, Kentucky, Duke _ until teaching and skill work
receive greater priority in the daily routine.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Davis, a mega-talent who would thrive under any
circumstances, which players improved from Nov. 1 to March 11?
Guard Ray Young and walk-on forward Sean Farnham are probably the
only ones.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Jerome Moiso did not improve. If anything, he got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Barnes, Ryan Bailey and Travis Reed never developed
consistency or confidence in Lavin's chaotic substitution pattern.
</P>
<P>
   JaRon Rush never found his 3-point stroke and never stopped
shooting _ especially early in possessions, before the offense was
set and rebounders positioned. He became the poster boy for
impatience.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Watson was as careless with the ball in the final game (six
turnovers) as he was in the first (five turnovers). Davis is
expected to depart for the NBA, placing the ball in Watson's hands
next season. Unless he gains discipline _ and unless his mistakes
are corrected in practice _ fans in the front row had better seek
cover.
</P>
<P>
   And what of injured center Gadzuric, who is expected to recover
from knee surgery by early summer. Currently, Gadzuric has one
low-post move: With his back to the basket, he turns over his left
shoulder and shoots a soft jumper. Will he diversify? Will he
develop a hook? Will he learn to pass out of the post?
</P>
<P>
   Playing pickup games each day in the men's gym won't cut it for
Gadzuric or anyone. The Bruins must devote themselves to the
loneliness of summer skill work.
</P>
<P>
   There's more, of course. The Bruins never learned to shoot free
throws. They never learned to play sound defense without fouling.
They never developed a consistent half-court offense with screens
and ball rotation and a sense for time and score. Davis often
masked the deficiencies with tremendous playmaking, but when he was
on the bench (foul trouble) the offense disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair to judge Lavin on one season with injuries and a
young team. As Arizona and North Carolina proved, the tournament is
a dangerous place for freshmen and sophomores. But if the problems
are not resolved by next March, the future won't look so bright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
