<SLUG> BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMNSPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLY ROCKS WASHINGTON'S WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Sometime last night, Wally Szczerbiak had to have
gone to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Washington Huskies might have had a chance to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought . . . nah.
</P>
<P>
   Awake or asleep, the man can't be spelled, checked or stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But you know what? Not for 43 points worth.
</P>
<P>
   Not when his team scores 59. Not when it's the first round of
the NCAA basketball tournament. Not when his teammates are guys who
wouldn't be in the Huskies' league if it was the Pac-30.
</P>
<P>
   Either Szczerbiak is better than Lew Alcindor, Bill Walton, Gary
Payton, Jason Kidd, Clint Richardson, Sidney Wicks, Sean Elliott
and all the other hoop greats who have put up lesser numbers
against Washington, or the Huskies didn't have much of a clue
Friday in their Midwest Region opener when they allowed themselves
to be posterized into tourney immortality.
</P>
<P>
   While the form chart says a No. 7 seed losing to a No. 10 seed
is only a mild upset, it was plain that Washington had physical
talent superior to tiny, albeit intrepid, Miami of Ohio. What they
didn't have was a better game plan, nor the ability or willingness
to adjust when things went amiss.
</P>
<P>
   So the UW season ended on a 59-58 thud that reverberated around
the mostly empty Superdome, as hollow a place Friday as the Husky
soul.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, Bob Bender was outcoached by his RedHawks counterpart,
Charlie Coles. While Miami came up with a plan to shut down
Washington's strength, Todd MacCulloch, the Huskies were helpless
to faze Szczerbiak even a little. Washington might as well have
tried to catch an eagle with a wheelbarrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He punished us for every breakdown, mentally and physically,''
said a crestfallen Bender, who flopped in the first round this year
as he soared last year _ a one-point decision that came down to the
final defensive stop.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Huskies beat Xavier 69-68 when Deon Luton's
jumper with 11 seconds remaining held up through a final defensive
denial. This time, Washington didn't even get off a game-winning
shot attempt, despite a timeout to set up the final 23 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In the final moments, just as they did the last 30 minutes of
the game, the Huskies didn't look to MacCulloch down low. In
defiance of all known laws of physics, as well as the laws of
basketball that say a 6-6 guy checking a 7-0 guy is dead meat,
MacCulloch (The Bigger Easy) took exactly two more shots in the
second half than the Space Needle, finishing with 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to know what was worse _ the offensive failure with
MacCulloch or the defensive failure on Szczerbiak. What is clear is
that the Huskies should be embarrassed on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   Last time a big Washington sports contest had a similar feel was
December's Oahu Bowl against Air Force, in which the physically
imposing Husky football team was whipped by some determined little
meanies who had bigger hearts and better clues.
</P>
<P>
   But give Bender some credit _ unlike former football coach Jim
Lambright, he didn't blame the scout team.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is no one in the college hoops nation capable of
imitating Szczerbiak, nicknamed World before Friday, owner of it
today. As MacCulloch summarized it, ``He's the strongest guy we've
played who can shoot the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   For Seattle hoops followers used to seeing pathetic shooting
because they watch a lot of NBA games, Szczerbiak was a revelation.
A sculpted 6-8, 240-pound senior, he began almost every move facing
the basket, instead of posting underneath. Playing with the zeal of
a man denied his proper vowels, he beat every Husky defender off
the drive, overpowered each inside, and shot over the zone.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most surprising thing was how surprised he was that
Washington failed to prepare a special defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of possessions, we ran set plays, and I got
as open as I've been all year,'' he said. ``In the (Mid-America
Conference), they're always hedging on screens, chasing me around,
bodying me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday when the World turned, he usually found Husky forward
Greg Clark, alone. He didn't do a bad job, but Szczerbiak is an NBA
lottery pick who demands a double-team.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies rarely ran at him a second player, although a 2-3
zone was deployed in the second half with modest success. Bender
said afterwards that the Huskies haven't used or practiced exotic
defenses such as a box-and-one or a diamond-and-two, but that may
change.
</P>
<P>
   A little late, no?
</P>
<P>
   Even more amazing than Szczerbiak's 21 first-half points were
his 22 in the second, demonstrating Washington was unable or
unwilling to force the game into the hands of other RedHawks. At
least Szczerbiak's foes in the MAC held him to an average of 23.6
points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your league is always toughest on you, because they know you
so well,'' said Coles, whose recovery from a courtside heart attack
13 months ago has made him an endearing tourney story. ``When you
get out of the league, the talent is better and they trust their
great player on our great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Washington nor any other team in the tourney has a match
for Szczerbiak. But opponents can have an alternate strategy,
because the remaining RedHawks in Friday's freakish affair combined
for 19 shots, 14 less than Szczerbiak alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a day and a half,'' said a smiling Coles, looking ahead
to Sunday's match against No. 2 seed Utah, ``to teach these other
guys to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender and his returning Huskies will have spring, summer and
fall in which to be better prepared to face the World, or any like
him.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
