<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SZCZERBIAK GOES FOR 43, UW GOES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Despite being harassed and hounded, Wally
Szczerbiak found enough freedom to terminate Washington's season
Friday in a crushing development on the bayou.
</P>
<P>
   The senior forward scored 43 points to lead Miami of Ohio to a
59-58 victory, knocking down one jumper after another and
flattening Washington in the process, ousting the Huskies from the
NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak hit his career-high during a Midwest Region
first-round game at the Superdome. With 28 points, UW's Donald
Watts matched his.
</P>
<P>
   But the Husky guard was somehow ordinary in comparison, an
obscure figure who tried to rescue his team. Szczerbiak would not
allow any such heroics by anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   He dominated and frustrated the Huskies in a memorable
performance, functioning in an offense designed solely for him,
making 18 of 33 shots and a permanent impression on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player, as good as people said he is,'' Husky
coach Bob Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best shooters I've ever seen,'' said Thalo
Green, one of Szczerbiak's pursuers. ``He's like Reggie Miller. As
soon as he sees daylight, he's firing it up and it's going down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies did too, and the thump could be heard back in
Seattle. Daylight for Szczerbiak meant darkness for Washington. A
potential game against Utah on Sunday turned into a flight home
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room amid the evident disappointment, the Huskies
rationalized and philosophized. Maybe they could have been more
efficient getting the ball to Todd MacCulloch. Maybe they could
have come up with a better defensive plan for Szczerbiak.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies played reasonably well. They did not lose as
much as the RedHawks won. And that happened because of one dramatic
effort by Szczerbiak. In his final collegiate game, Watts realized
as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I could get the ball and take us to the win,''
Watts said. ``But there was another guy on the other team that felt
the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak felt it and stroked it, shooting the ball with
remarkable accuracy in effortless fashion. In this city, he was the
big easy, displaying Dan Majerle range and Dan Marino release. The
Huskies discovered that Szczerbiak is tough to spell, stop and
describe, a unique player who is tough and sleek. He is an NBA
lottery pick who enhanced his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed every time I drove, there weren't two or three guys
ready to help,'' Szczerbiak said. ``I had been used to getting a
lot more double-teams in the MAC Conference. I've got to credit my
guys with getting me open. I didn't really have to force too much
or go one-on-one too much.''
</P>
<P>
   He was consistent throughout, burning Washington from tipoff to
the final horn, scoring 21 points in the first half, 22 in the
second, hitting the first basket and the last.
</P>
<P>
   Yet because of Watts' play, the Huskies were still in position
to win when they called a timeout with 18.3 seconds to play. Watts
got them to this point, completing his career in the way that he
pictured, except for the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling what was to come, Watts finished the first half with a
fast-breaking slam, pulling Washington within 29-26.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, he put the Huskies in front 43-37 during a
spectacular four-minute stretch, scoring 12 straight points for
Washington. It was highlighted by a four-point play, Watts getting
fouled after drilling a three. At that point, Watts hoped the lead
would grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had gotten up by 8, 9 or 10 (points), Mr. Szczerbiak
might have felt a hand around his throat, feeling like: `I have to
make this shot,''' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mr. Szczerbiak never tightened up. He nailed two
straight jumpers, continuing an assault that would put Miami in
front again. The Huskies were not choking Dawgs, either, Watts and
Deon Luton keeping them close, setting up the final possession.
</P>
<P>
   Bender wanted Watts to get the ball on the left wing and dribble
toward the middle off a Luton screen. A Watts shot was the first
option. A pass to MacCulloch in the post was the second option.
Luton was the third.
</P>
<P>
   All went as planned until Watts was stripped with five seconds
remaining, the ball popping into Greg Clark's hands. Knowing his
team's season and the clock were about to expire, Clark attempted
to shoot from the right side, only to be snuffed by Szczerbiak, who
grabbed the ball and dribbled toward a midcourt celebration.
</P>
<P>
   It was Miami madness.
</P>
<P>
   The box score seemed to show that Szczerbiak had little support.
Only two other teammates, Damon Frierson (12) and John Estick (4),
scored. Collecting 43 of his team's total of 59, Szczerbiak
accounted for 73 percent of the points.
</P>
<P>
   But Miami coach Charlie Coles said: ``It's not going to sound
right, but this was a team effort. The screening was the best I've
seen all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The RedHawks' offense uses a variety of multiple screens
designed to unleash Szczerbiak. Defenders get lost in the maze.
</P>
<P>
   ``They use so many screens to get one player open,'' said Clark,
who dogged Szczerbiak throughout. ``You're working your butt off
and it gets to you after awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration factor was apparent at the other end of the
floor. Although MacCulloch had a 6-inch size advantage on his
pestering defenders, he rarely used it. MacCulloch was either not
in good position or open to receive a pass, the consequences being
that the Huskies' meal ticket went hungry.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch experienced two inexplicable stretches: for 30
minutes, the last 11 minutes of the first half and last 19 minutes
of the game, he did not get a shot off. The Husky senior center was
4-for-6, limited to 11 points by Estick, Mike Ensminger and other
helping teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really packing it in inside,'' MacCulloch said.
``They threw two and three guys at me. They tried very hard to keep
me outside of where I like to get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Szczerbiak: ``Our assistant coach, James Woodford, drew a
box on the floor in practice and said, `There is no way that
MacCulloch gets the ball in here. Even if he gets the ball out of
the box, we still double- and triple-team him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year MacCulloch bludgeoned smaller teams Xavier and
Richmond as the Huskies reached the Sweet 16 of this tournament.
This year they were eliminated in the first round on a day that was
as long as their faces.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, Washington returns home after a
one-point loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very happy time,'' MacCulloch said. ``This team
fell short of what it is capable of, but we'll never have another
chance to prove it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
