<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA QUIETLY LURKING AS WEBER PLAYS CINDERELLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Maybe some people never heard of Weber State. Maybe
the new darlings of this NCAA tournament, who sliced and diced
their way through North Carolina on Thursday night and earned their
role as this year's Valparaiso, aren't on too many people's radar.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden, Utah _ home of the Cinderella Weber State Wildcats _ is
not a basketball hotbed too many people get to over the course of a
normal lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   But Billy Donovan, coach of the University of Florida men's
basketball team, isn't one of those guys.
</P>
<P>
   One of basketball's ultimate overachievers, Donovan once had a
long tryout with the Jazz, getting a sampling of Utah's outposts
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when we were going through exhibition season, we
went through Ogden, Logan and we played over at BYU and at Weber
State, so I'm certainly familiar with the place,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Donovan, his tour of Utah was short-lived. The
too-small, too-slow but still undeniable point guard never did make
the Jazz back in 1987, when Utah made him the 68th pick of the NBA
draft right after Donovan led Rick Pitino's Providence to the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still bitter they cut me,'' Donovan said Friday. ``I think
they made a poor decision. And I think I could have done a much
better job than John Stockton did.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a quintessential New York wise-cracker smile broke
across Donovan's boyish face. He had just zinged off a typical
Donovan ``gotcha,'' and he had accomplished it with just the right
mix of moxie, charm and unrelenting determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's straightforward. He isn't a coach who tells you what you
want to hear,'' Gator senior Greg Stolt said. ``But he tells you
what you need to hear if you want to be a better basketball
player.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why, despite the overwhelming sentiment that says any
good college basketball fan must root for the darlings of Weber
State in Saturday's second-round NCAA tournament game, there is
still room to quibble that Donovan and his Gators are also worthy
of, at the very least, more than cursory dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the Gators' fault that Weber State and NCAA insta-star
Harold ``The Show'' Arceneaux will have the support of the KeyArena
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we shouldn't be the Cinderella of this
tournament,'' Donovan lobbied. ``This is only the fifth time
Florida has been in the tournament. Weber State's been in 12
times.''
</P>
<P>
   With such salesmanship techniques, you can now understand why
fellow coaches such as South Carolina's Eddie Fogler and Kansas'
Roy Williams have gotten real panicky over Donovan. He is beating
them to key recruits and they loathe him for it.
</P>
<P>
   In the three seasons at Florida, Donovan has tenaciously
competed for the very same McDonald's All-Americans who previously
never would have given the Gators as much as a second look. Now,
Donovan is stocking the roster with players who he hopes put
Florida on the basketball map, year in and year out.
</P>
<P>
   That will be quite a change.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to Florida, but the last time the Gators made a dent
in NCAA tournament, they were a sleeper that made it all the way to
the 1994 Final Four and put a fair share of diehard hoops fans to
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Gators? College basketball? It used to be the only time the
hoops team would draw a crowd is if football coach Steve Spurrier
was in the house.
</P>
<P>
   This season, though, something unbelievable occurred in
Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 150 Gator basketball fans camped outside the arena
the night before Florida played Kentucky in an SEC showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, the 33-year-old wunder-coach out of Pitino's
Providence-New York Knicks-Kentucky crucible, thanked the fans by
buying them boxes of pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Florida now also has something called the Rowdy Reptiles. This
is a fan group whose rabid allegiance belongs to the basketball
team _ one that is seeded No. 6 in the West and looking to knock
off Arceneaux and those other Weber darlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arceneaux can put a show on. That's why he gets his
nickname,'' Donovan said. ``I've been very impressed with him as a
basketball player. He's got a great feel how to play. He's got
great tempo, range, he can put it down and create his own shot. He
can put it down at the free-throw line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can put a guy on him and say, `OK, guard
him.' He just has too many ways to score because he can use
screens, he can go one-on-one and he can post up.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Carolina was too big, too slow and too green for the
crafty Wildcats, the Gators will present an entirely different
look.
</P>
<P>
   An unabashed Pitino disciple, Donovan is completely committed to
the full-court press. And now that Donovan has brought in freshman
sensations such as Mike Miller and Teddy Dupay, the Gators finally
have the horses to run the floor for 40 exhausting minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very demanding style of play for your coaching staff
and your players,'' Donovan said. ``When you see that style on TV,
it's obviously a very entertaining, but I don't think people truly
understand the type of shape you need to be in play 40 minutes of
that type of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the darlings of Weber State are going to get a taste
of ``Billy Ball.'' It is distilled directly from the Final Four
squads Donovan played a part in at Providence and Kentucky, where
he was Pitino's assistant for six years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Billy Ball'' is the kind of thing that, much to the
chagrin of everyone rooting for Weber State, could probably break a
Cinderella's glass slipper.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
