<HEADLINE>
LITTLE GONZAGA GUNNING FOR GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Gonzaga not only wants to beat Stanford on Saturday
and become a Sweet 16 team, but mimic the Cardinal basketball
program.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities already are obvious to Bulldogs coach Dan
Monson.
</P>
<P>
   ``University-wise, there is not much difference,'' he said
Friday. ``Gonzaga and Stanford are both very small schools with
good academic traditions and play with a lot of the similar type
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a disparity in talent, it might show up at KeyArena
in the second round of the NCAA tournament sub-regional. The highly
ranked Cardinal, the only Pac-10 team remaining, takes on the
Bullogs, the only West Coast Conference team invited.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's opener, surprising Weber State plays Florida.
</P>
<P>
   From a local standpoint, the first game is the most anticipated:
Little Gonzaga of the WCC against high-profile Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between a Stanford kid (and a Gonzaga player)
is they get kids who are a little more ready-made than us,'' Monson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford gets players ready to step in and be stars. Gonzaga
develops stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a good program to model after, and maybe I am trying
to kid myself to take my program and model (it) after theirs,''
Monson said. ``But I think it's the right way to do it. They have a
good system with good kids and I have a lot of respect for how they
get it done there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford and Gonzaga programs are chugging along on a
parallel path.
</P>
<P>
   Both have been 20-game plus winners for several years now and
elite teams in their respective leagues. Both are league champions
this season.
</P>
<P>
   And here they are, in the same place, wanting to go to the same
place _ the West Regionals in Phoenix next week.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, the Bulldogs don't have an inferiority complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our matchup advantage is our offense,'' said Richie
Frahm, one of the most accurate long-range shooters in college.
``If we execute and play well as a team, get all of the guys shots,
then I think that's our advantage. As far as personnel-wise, I
think we match up perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might be a little thicker down low, but our guys are
going to be aggressive and overcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   Seniors Mark Madsen and Tim Young anchor a Cardinal front line
that outrebounded Alcorn State, 45-23, Thursday. It is up Gonzaga
senior center Jeremy Eaton (6-foot-11) and sophomore forward Casey
Calvary (6-foot-8) to handle most of the Gonzaga board work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say they are a lot more mobile than we are,'' Madsen
said. ``They go outside more than we do and shoot more jumpers. Tim
and I, the majority of our moves are made close to the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever team controls the boards has the best chance of
reaching the West Regionals in Phoenix next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanford rebounds well and so do we,'' Monson said. ``They had
16 offensive rebounds (against Alcorn State) and we can't afford to
let them stand under the basket and keep taking shots until they
make one.''
</P>
<P>
   Blocking out and long-range shooting accuracy tops Gonzaga's
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are an excellent 3-point shooting team and it obviously
is something we will have to defend,'' Cardinal coach Mike
Montgomery said. ``I hope we can defend the three as well as we
have on most occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Seniors Arthur Lee and Kris Weems probably will be responsible
for keeping guard Matt Santangelo and Frahm from catching fire from
the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gonzaga is definitely a good 3-point shooting team,'' Lee
said, ``but we have seen a lot of them throughout the course of the
season. We just have to do what we have been all year long, which
is have someone in their face throughout the game and don't let
them get open looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that is easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldog philosophy was established long before now and few
teams have been able to stop them on the way to becoming the
winningest team in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball fans around the country don't know much about
Gonzaga, but the Cardinal is well aware of the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard about them a lot this year, being on the West
Coast,'' Madsen said. ``We were in the area when they came down and
beat Santa Clara by 30 or 40 points. We're definitely familiar with
the fact that they are good and have a lot of different attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as respecting them, it is easier to respect them, given
the fact we have seen them more this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating Stanford would make Gonzaga a Sweet 16 team and elevate
the basketball program to another level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, every win you get in the NCAA tournament is
unbelievable exposure,'' Monson said. ``It's great for your school,
your alumni. The win (Thursday against Minnesota) probably was the
biggest win in our program because we have gone into unchartered
waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are out to sea a little farther. If we win that would
be even more uncharted waters and we want to go all the way to
ocean. We want to test all the waters out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
