r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PAYNE-SPI &LR;      03-13 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PAYNE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARROQUETTE'S NEW SERIES PAINFUL AT TIMES; `RESCUE' CAN'T BE
SAVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to watch John Larroquette. That elastic ability in
front of the camera is often better than a second serving of
profiteroles. From his Emmy-winning dramatic turn last season on
``The Practice,'' to his multi-Emmy tour de force as Dan Fielding
in ``Night Court'' to his understated comedic brilliance on ``The
John Larroquette Show,'' the tall actor from New Orleans is
something to behold.
</P>
<P>
   But watching him in ``Payne'' is painful. The timing is still
there, the comic flourishes perfectly expansive, the booming voice
still booming when it needs to be, but Larroquette's new comedy for
CBS may have to be an acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   Based on John Cleese's farcical ``Fawlty Towers'' of a
generation ago, ``Payne'' has Larroquette playing Royal Payne, the
contemptuous and contemptible proprietor of Whispering Pines, a
small hotel on the California coast. JoBeth Williams plays his
wife, Constance Payne, in the role that Prunella Scales created
opposite Cleese.
</P>
<P>
   Williams may unwittingly be part of the problem. She told
critics a couple of months ago that she senses an easy chemistry
when working with Larroquette, but it's not apparent in the three
episodes provided for review. While the lines might be funny, even
inspired, they seem forced and uncomfortably stilted as delivered
by the two stars.
</P>
<P>
   Such stiltage _ or is it stilton? _ might have worked in a
British farce like ``Fawlty Towers.'' But it seems cheesy in an
American sitcom. Besides, U.S. audiences are more likely to compare
``Payne'' with ``Newhart,'' which ran for eight seasons on CBS,
four of them in Nielsen's Top 20.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Bob Newhart's Dick Loudon was kind and gentle where
Larroquette's Royal Payne is mean and cranky, but as hotel-themed
comedies go, they're very much alike, complete with the oddball
supporting characters. Bottom line: ``Newhart'' was funnier, and
it's still available on Nickelodeon's Nick at Nite.
</P>
<P>
   In its well-modulated rush to probe the hearts and minds of Los
Angeles paramedics, ``Rescue 77'' takes the viewer on an emotional
roller coaster that runs the gamut from medium to moderate ,
stopping ever so briefly at somewhat restrained.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because paramedics have to be cool and sober under
all sorts of trying conditions. Or maybe it's the acting. Or the
writing. Or maybe the cameras were rolling during a full-dress
run-through and producer/director Eric Laneuville, who cut his
teeth in the hallowed halls of ``St. Elsewhere,'' figured it was
good enough for an Aaron Spelling production.
</P>
<P>
   A Spelling production obviously means the men are chiseled and
the women are also. But for an action/adventure series with an
impressive pedigree _ its creator is former firefighter and
``Backdraft'' alumnus Gregory Widen _ ``Rescue 77'' is surprisingly
unexciting, even as our heroes are dangling from a helicopter as
they try to rescue a pilot from a smashed airplane on an L.A.
hillside.
</P>
<P>
   The principal players in this WB drama _ Marjorie Monaghan,
Victor Browne, Christian Kane and Richard Roundtree _ never
progress beyond stick figures on the storyboard, even as Widen
tries to mix a little pathos in with the pacing.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from some Sarah McLachlan music halfway through Monday
night's premiere, ``Rescue 77'' has a weaker pulse than ``Hyperion
Bay,'' the series it's temporarily replacing. And instead of
real-life situations, we get fake-life monologues like this, when
Browne's character, Michael Bell, gives Monaghan's character,
Kathleen Bell, a heart-to-heart after a tough day: ``You have to
get up now,'' he says, ``walk back to the rig, make some dark joke
about it that no one else will understand, and go on. Or not.''
</P>
<P>
   As a viewer, I choose ``not.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne. Half-hour comedy series about a couple running a hotel on
the California coast. Starring John Larroquette and JoBeth
Williams. Premieres Monday night on CBS, with another episode
Wednesday. Moves to its regular Wednesday time slot March 24 at 8
p.m. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Rescue 77. Hour-long drama series about paramedics in Los
Angeles. Starring Marjorie Monaghan, Victor Browne, Christian Kane
and Richard Roundtree. Premieres Monday night on The WB. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330 or send e-mail to
tvguy &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
