r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CA-PROP10-LADN     03-13 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-PROP10-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA SHOULD UTILIZE PROVEN PROGRAM MODELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Dr. Kerby T. Alvy, a clinical child psychologist, is the author of
``Parent Training Today: A Social Necessity'' and the founder and
director of the 25-year-old Center for the Improvement of Child
Caring in Los Angeles. Alvy can be reached at ciccflash.net,
www.ciccparenting.org or (800) 325-2422.) 
BY KERBY T. ALVY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The most exciting feature of Proposition 10 is its
goal of helping every child in California to begin life in a
nurturing and supportive home.
</P>
<P>
   The architects, managers and leaders of homes are parents, and
they deserve and need the best information and training to carry
out their critically important roles.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 10 recognizes this by including parenting education
as one of the services that can and should be underwritten by the
hundreds of millions of dollars that are now available statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the driving force behind Proposition 10, Rob Reiner, a
caring and concerned parent, rightfully states that parenting
education is the core service.
</P>
<P>
   It behooves the state and county commissions that will decide
exactly how the funds will be used to keep the centrality of
parenting education clearly in mind.
</P>
<P>
   It is also equally as important that they do not reinvent the
programmatic wheel when it comes to parenting education. Many
excellent, research-proven parenting programs already exist.
</P>
<P>
   These carefully crafted programs were developed by a variety of
knowledgeable organizations in different parts of the country and
through a variety of research and demonstration projects, many
supported by public tax dollars. The best programs have been
recognized as national models for helping parents become more
effective and for preventing a wide range of social and health
problems that stem from uniformed and ineffective parenting, such
as child abuse, drug abuse, juvenile delinquency and school
failure.
</P>
<P>
   These programs provide the basic child development information
that all parents need in order to have realistic expectations about
what infants and young children can and cannot do. They teach a
series of parenting strategies and skills for creating rich,
supportive and safe physical and social surroundings for children.
They orient parents how to relate to these little people with the
proper mix of warmth, responsiveness and nonviolent guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these programs are designed for parents of children who
are particularly challenging, either because of temperament and
behavior or because of health problems. A few of the programs also
address the importance of cultural values and traditions in child
rearing. They help parents instill a sense of cultural pride right
from the beginning, including programs that were originally
developed here in California like the ``Effective Black Parenting''
and ``Los Ninos Bien Educados'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   These programs can be taught through a variety of formats and
through several different mediums. They can be taught as classes or
seminars, which are led by instructors who have received
professional training. They can be taught on a one-to-one basis
through home visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Their teaching can also be conveyed through video-based and
CD-ROM versions that do not require instructors or through the
radio, television and the Internet. It is also now possible to
teach the course over the phone through teleconferencing
technology. The most enduring results, however, seem to come from
in-person classes and seminars. It is wise to have all formats
available in all communities.
</P>
<P>
   The state and county commissions are in complementary positions
to ensure that all communities are provided equal access to the
full spectrum of top programs and service delivery formats.
</P>
<P>
   One of the primary missions of the state commission is to
provide technical assistance, professional training and public
education, which supports the community services that the county
commissions decide to underwrite with their lion's share of the
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The state commission could create a state-of-the-art
clearinghouse of parenting and parent training program information
and research that would help form decisions about community
services having to do with parenting. They could initiate a
parenting instructor training academy to prepare cadres of
qualified persons from local schools and agencies to deliver the
best programs. They could also conduct a statewide public education
campaign about the value of parenting education, which could be
patterned after the Effective Parenting Campaign that the Center
for the Improvement of Child Caring is currently running in several
Southern California counties.
</P>
<P>
   With these supports, the county commissions would be able to
carry out the parent education mandates of Proposition 10 with a
solid base of knowledge and professional assistance. Then the
public would be assured that the parenting services that are made
available in each county are of the highest quality.
</P>
<P>
   As these high-quality services become widely available in every
community in the state, more and more of California's children will
receive the most meaningful gift that comes with the passage of
Proposition 10: the gift of effective parenting.
</P>
<P>
   It is a gift that keeps giving, since effectively parented
children pass on the basics of a caring and humane society.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
