<HEADLINE>
KINGS, ROBINSON SEARCHING FOR ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rob Blake's speech to his teammates was only the
first meeting the Los Angeles Kings held Thursday. In the second,
the Kings' captain and his alternates, Luc Robitaille and Doug
Bodger, approached the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, coach Larry Robinson disclosed that among other things,
the players suggested Robinson stick with the lineup that recorded
a 4-2 victory Tuesday night over the Detroit Red Wings. Robinson
added that he will follow the advice when the Kings (24-36-5) face
the Vancouver Canucks at 7 tonight at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is we've had so much inconsistency that I've been
trying to find a spark somewhere, or find a combination somewhere
that's going to work,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   And as a result, Robinson has spent much of the season
tinkering, a tendency he said he will refrain from tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players, that was the biggest thing that they came to me
and said was, `Let's work on this reward system. If the team is
playing well and the guys are playing well, why mix it up?' ''
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I was doing that only to try to take the personnel
I felt that we had and put it together the best way I knew how to
go against the team that we were playing. They feel if they stick
with the same guys, they'll be able to beat any team, so we'll try
it.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, with 17 games remaining and a seven-point gap
between his team and a Western Conference playoff berth, Robinson
is open to suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an employer,'' he said. ``You've got to listen to
your employees. They're the ones that are doing the work for you.
If they feel this is one of the things that's going to help them
play better and win hockey games, then, hey, nothing that we do is
etched in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to stick with the status quo will mean another
unwanted night off for defenseman Steve Duchesne, who was a healthy
scratch Tuesday and won't play tonight unless Robinson has a sudden
change of heart. Duchesne, in the first season of a three-year,
$11.25-million contract, has struggled most of the season,
producing just 23 points while posting a minus-6 defensive rating.
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne made it clear Friday that he is disappointed with his
present situation, but he also stressed that he willingly accepts
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come to L.A. to do poorly,'' said Duchesne, who
played for St. Louis last season. ``I feel a little bit like I let
my teammates down. It's not for lack of trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about a comment this week by Robinson that he hasn't
adequately been ``paying the price'' to make plays - a reference to
Duchesne's reputation for skirting physical contact - Duchesne
said, ``I don't want to say anything, so let's just put it that
way, OK. I don't want to cause any trouble. ... I'd like to tell
you probably a lot more. I want to be positive. I don't want to
cause any trouble with the coaching staff or myself. I want my
teammates to play well, think about hockey and win. I'll be there
to support them.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said some of Duchesne's difficulties might stem from
the high expectations held for him when the Kings signed him as a
free agent last summer. Primary was the expectation that he would
spark the Kings' power play, which instead has been among the worst
in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``And sometimes you can take a player,'' Robinson added, ``and
he looks good in a certain organization, and then he gets out of
that organization and somehow, he doesn't blend with the style
you're playing or the people that you're playing with. Good hockey
players are the ones who should be able to adjust. I think he's
capable of adjusting. I think he just hasn't made that adjustment
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still a great skater. He still sees the ice well. He can
do all those things. He's just got to put it together, stop trying
to be something that you're not. He's a good hockey player. He's
just got to get out there and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he will get his next opportunity, though, remains to be
seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
