<HEADLINE>
LIFELESS TEXAS FALLS TO PURDUE
</HEADLINE>
 REGION-TEXAS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Somewhere, Tom Penders might be laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about the former Texas coach. When his teams
got into the NCAA Tournament, they won _ seven of eight first-round
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns were the not-ready-for-tournament-time players
Friday night and lost a most winnable NCAA East Region game to
Purdue, 58-54.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers, who lost four of their last five games, in
essence won on forward Cameron Stephens' 19-foot jumper with less
than five seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' answer? So typical of the night's performance, Gabe
Muoneke threw a half-court pass that Kris Clack caught off-balance,
tumbling out of bounds with it while 4.1 seconds remained.
</P>
<P>
   On the inbounds pass, Ivan Wagner quickly fouled Purdue's Tony
Mayfield, who had the assist on Stephens' bucket. Mayfield sank
both free throws to seal the Boilermakers' victory.
</P>
<P>
   Texas (19-13) had time, however, to throw away one more pass
before falling for the third time in its last four games after
streaking to the Big 12 regular-season championship.
</P>
<P>
   One might have expected Texas coach Rick Barnes at some point to
throw his coat, kick a chair, to do something to bring life into a
lifeless team.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes never ignited _ and neither did the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Texas joined the ranks of the NCAA Tournament's unlucky sevens,
becoming the fourth seventh seed to lose to a No. 10 in the
tournament's first two days. Luck, however, had little to do with
Texas' loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns committed 22 turnovers and for most of the night
ignored Chris Mihm inside, although the 7-foot sophomore scored 21
points and pulled down 14 rebounds. Muoneke, with 12, was the only
other UT player to score in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Down one point at the half, Texas started the second half
playing the way it had most of the season, but soon reverted to its
dismal, inconsistent first-half performance and never led by more
than two. Purdue couldn't establish any consistency, either, and
the teams traded the lead six times heading into the last four
minutes with the Boilermakers up, 50-49.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clay made a 3-pointer that tied the score at 54-54 with
24.8 seconds to play. Purdue executed down the stretch. Texas
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Texas trailed at the half, 30-29. But they likely would have
been further back had they not been playing the only team in the
field of 64 with a losing conference record.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue, 7-9 in the Big Ten, outhustled, outjumped and outplayed
the Longhorns, although emotional leader Brian Cardinal spent the
last 10 minutes of the half on the bench with two fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Gene Keady could afford to let Cardinal sit because the
Longhorns were flat-footed and acted as if they had never played
together before. Wagner started bad and never got better. Muoneke
and Clay hit rare 3-pointers for Texas' first six points, but
Wagner threw the ball away twice in between.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue led 18-11 at the midway point, before Cardinal picked up
his second foul. Yet, Texas couldn't _ or refused _ to take
advantage by going inside to Mihm, although he was guarded by 6-7
Greg McQuay or 6-10 freshman John Allison.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas did throw inside, it was usually on a bounce pass and
usually resulted in a scramble that prevented Mihm from getting off
a shot. Fortunately, he got to the line, where eight of his 10
points came during the half. His only bucket was on a follow shot
that tied the game at 27-27 with 3:40 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns outscored the Boilermakers 12-1 to come from 20-13
down to a 25-20 lead. Mihm had four field goals and Clack a
3-pointer from the right corner during the run. Texas couldn't keep
it going, however and McQuay put Purdue up with a follow slam with
37.4 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Texas called a time out five seconds later, but the best they
could do was to set up Chico Vazquez for a missed 3-pointer from
deep in the right corner _ the 15th miss of 23 attempts in the
half. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
