<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS CLINCH PLAYOFF BERTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Dallas Stars won the battle of streaks Friday
night, dominating the hottest team in hockey and clinching a
playoff berth in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In crunching the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, 4-0, the Stars went
streak crazy. Among the notables:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars ran their undefeated streak against the Ducks to
10-0-1 in their past 11 games at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars stopped the Ducks' eight-game unbeaten streak
(7-0-1), which was the hottest in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Stars ran their unbeaten streak in their alternate ``green
star'' jersey to 14-0-5. In fact, they have not lost since
introducing the third sweater last season.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nieuwendyk had two goals to stretch his consecutive
game-scoring streak to nine games.
</P>
<P>
   And the Stars stopped Teemu Selanne's point-scoring streak at 17
_ one short of the losingest in the NHL this season (18 games by
Eric Lindros of the Flyers).
</P>
<P>
   In winning their third consecutive game before the 29th
consecutive sellout crowd of 16,928 at Reunion Arena, and
stretching their home-winning streak to five games, the Stars moved
to 42-12-10 _ going 30 games above .500 for the first time in
franchise history. They clinched a playoff berth at the earliest
date in franchise history. Since the Calgary Flames, who sit ninth
in the Western Conference, lost Friday night, they can garner no
more than 92 points. The Stars have 94.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very strong, very methodical,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``We didn't want to give them anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In a game filled with plenty of pushing and shoving and a few
fights, Ed Belfour recorded 27 saves to notch his 44th career
shutout _ two behind Patrick Roy of the Colorado Avalanche for the
lead among active NHL goalies. He was helped out by a defense
featuring sterling performances by Derian Hatcher, Sergei Zubov,
Richard Matvichuk, Shawn Chambers, Craig Ludwig and Sergey Gusev.
In addition, the Stars forwards wore down the Ducks and kept
Anaheim's scoring chances to the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie was good, but the whole defense was good,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, whose line was given the assignment of checking Selanne
and Paul Kariya _ two of top-five scorers in the NHL _ led off the
scoring with his 29th goal of the season. Jamie Langenbrunner set
up the goal with hard work behind the net and Modano was left wide
open for an easy slam dunk at the 5:09 mark of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hrkac then gave the Stars a needed cushion when he scored
at the 10:23 mark of the second period off a strong setup from Mike
Keane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever scored first was going to have the advantage,''
Hitchcock said. ``When we scored first, they had to take some
chances and that created some open ice for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk cashed in on that open ice for two goals in the third
period _ his 19th and 20th on the season and his eighth in the past
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   With Nieuwendyk playing healthy after battling soreness in his
knees for much of the season, the Stars have two lines clicking at
the same time. In addition to Nieuwendyk's streak, Modano has five
goals in the past five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best players were our best players,'' Hitchcock said.
``When that happens, we're in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars prepare for a three-game road trip in which they play
the Philadelphia Flyers on Sunday, the Pittsburgh Penguins on
Tuesday and the Washington Capitals on Wednesday. They return to
Reunion Arena on Friday to face the red-hot Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fun time of the year,'' Modano said. ``These are
the good challenges.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
