<SLUG> BC--BKC-LONGHORNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDUE SLIPS PAST LETHARGIC TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You expected Texas coach Rick Barnes at some point to
throw his coat, kick a chair, do something to get some life into a
lifeless team.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes never ignited _ and neither did the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Texas thus dropped a winnable first-round NCAA Tournament East
Region game to Purdue on Friday night, 58-54, to join the ranks of
the NCAA Tournament's unlucky sevens. The Longhorns were the fourth
seventh seed to lose to a No. 10 in the tournament's first two
days. Luck, however, had little to do with Texas' loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns committed 22 turnovers and for most of the night
ignored Chris Mihm inside, even though the 7-foot sophomore scored
21 points and pulled down 14 rebounds. Gabe Muoneke, with 12, was
the only other UT player in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``A disappointing way to end the season,'' Mihm said. ``I wish
we could have kept the momentum we had going. We did sort of
tighten up and that's uncharacteristic of us all year. I don't know
what to say. It's an NCAA Tournament and it's one and done.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also couldn't explain his team's play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some guys do some things they haven't done in a long
time,'' he said. ``I could sit here and say maybe it was nerves,
but again, I don't know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're a better basketball team than we were tonight.
But that's the problem in this tournament. If you're not playing
good basketball at this time of year, you're done. So much of it
gets down to situational play, and if you can't handle situations,
you go home. There's a lot we didn't do. But the biggest thing is
we just turned it over.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas won seven of eight first-round games under former coach
Tom Penders, but Friday night the Longhorns were the
not-ready-for-tournament-time players.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers, who lost four of their last five games, in
essence won on forward Cameron Stephens' 19-foot jumper with less
than five seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little piece of the shot,'' Mihm said. ``But it went
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' answer? Typical of the night's performance, Muoneke threw
a half-court pass that Kris Clack caught off-balance, and tumbled
out of bounds with 4.1 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Wagner on the inbound pass quickly fouled Purdue's Tony
Mayfield, who had the assist on Stephens' bucket. Mayfield sank
both free throws to seal the Boilermakers' victory.
</P>
<P>
   Texas (19-13) had time, however, to throw away one more pass.
</P>
<P>
   Down one at the half, Texas started the second half playing the
way it had most of the season, but soon reverted to its dismal,
inconsistent, flat-footed first-half performance and never led by
more than two. Purdue couldn't establish any consistency, either,
and the teams traded the lead six times heading into the last four
minutes with the Boilermakers up, 50-49.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner scored on a drive for a 51-50 lead. But Jaraan Cornell,
who led with 18, scored four consecutive points on a 15-foot jumper
and two free throws sandwiched around a UT turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clay made a 3-pointer that tied the score at 54 with 24.8
seconds to play. Purdue then executed down the stretch. Texas
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of my players, the way they fought back from
playing poorly and got it together the past 10 or 12 days,'' Purdue
coach Gene Keady said. ``Tonight was one of those games that could
have gone either way.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's Brian Cardinal (14 points) claimed that Muoneke punched
him twice in a spill six minutes into the half. Muoneke said they
traded elbows and repeated replays appeared to back Muoneke's
version. Barnes said he would take a look and deal with the
incident if it was as Cardinal claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt he did a couple of things that were unnecessary,''
Muoneke said. ``The referee came up to me and said don't worry
about it, just stay out of the way. So he knew what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He elbowed me twice. ... so if he wants to vocalize what
really went wrong, go ask him. He knows what he did. And I'm not
going to take that from anybody. I didn't punch him. I did the same
thing he did to me _ plain and simple.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
