<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, March 13.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO (Independence, Mo.) _ Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic Friday became the first former members of the old Soviet
bloc to join NATO, expanding the Western military alliance to 19
members. At a ceremony in the hometown of the late U.S. President
Harry Truman, the foreign ministers of the three new members signed
formal documents of accession and gave them to U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, who told the ministers: ``You are truly
allies, you are truly home.'' By Jane Perlez. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-ASSESS (Independence, Mo.) _ News Analysis: A feeling of
deliverance from an implacably cruel fate suffused the little
auditorium at th Harry S. Truman Library in Independence, Mo.,
where the ceremony took place. It took place here, of course,
because it was Truman, with his secretary of state, Dean Acheson,
who called NATO into existence to meet the Soviet threat after
World War II. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-AVIATOR-ITALY (Rome) _ Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema
warned Friday that Italy may want to make some changes to the NATO
alliance. D'Alema, like the rest of Italy, was outraged by the
acquittal of the U.S. pilot who flew into a ski lift cable in
Northern Italy last year, killing 20 people. Under NATO rules, the
United States had jurisdiction over the case. By Alessandra Stanley
</P>
<P>
   ALGERIA-TRAIN (Oran, Algeria) _ In the 1990s, life in Algeria
has been disfigured by massacres of entire villages, bombings in
restaurants and cafes and killings of artists, journalists and
others judged to have offended Islamic mores. But few experiences
have been as unnerving as riding Train 1001. On its seven-hour run
from Algiers to Oran, the country's second-largest city, it has
been attacked at least 25 times, usually with land mines. Now Train
1001 has become a new kind of symbol, of an Algeria working its way
back from the brink. After years of running half-empty, the train
is full again and runs safely for months at a time. By John F.
Burns. With photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Kosovo Liberation Army leaders
decided Friday to accept a European-sponsored peace plan and
directed the leader of the ethnic Albanian delegation to sign the
accord ahead of peace talks that are planned to resume on Monday in
Paris. By Carlotta Gall. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRADES-SHORTAGE (Chicago) _ Faced with a shortage of
tradesworkers to meet the voracious demand for new construction in
the United States, desperate builders and eager unions have kicked
off aggressive campaigns to court new workers, attracting women and
members of racial minorities to the traditional bastion of white
men, a world where a coveted union card was handed from father to
son. By Dirk Johnson. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FBI-INFORMER (Boston) _ It began in 1995 as a simple
racketeering indictment whose defendants included two reputed mob
leaders long infamous in Irish-dominated South Boston: James
(Whitey) Bulger and Stephen (The Rifleman) Flemmi. By now, however,
the case has become what many call one of the most embarrassing
messes for the Federal Bureau of Investigation in years. And it has
called into question one of the oldest practices in law enforcement
and one of the most troublesome: the use of confidential informers
to fight organized crime. By Carey Goldberg. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ASSESS (Washington) _ As they seek their way after
impeachment, congressional Republicans these last few weeks have
gone on the offensive against President Clinton on national
security and foreign policy, while taking stands on Social Security
and education that will allow them to make some claim to those
domestic concerns. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RUMORS (Washington) _ In the suspicion-rich aftermath of
Paula Jones, Monica Lewinsky, impeachment, and the rest of it, a
strange and ghoulish vigil has undeniably taken hold here. It's a
marital death watch, perhaps arising less from any smoke signals
that the Clintons are sending out than from Washington insiders'
presumptions about what they would do were they in Mrs. Clinton's
pumps. By Frank Bruni. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OIL-TALKS (Undated) _ A group of major oil producers announced
Friday that they had agreed to cut oil production by 2 million
barrels a day, a move that sent depressed crude oil prices upward.
Some analysts said that if the cuts are implemented as planned by
April 1 they could lead to a steady recovery of crude oil prices,
which would lead to an increase in the price of gasoline. But
others said that even if the supply cuts stick, the increase at the
pump would be modest at first _ about 5 cents a gallon. By Agis
Salpukas. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-INFLATION _ The oil price surge this year, which got another
boost Friday with a new agreement on cutting production, is
beginning to sting consumers. But despite the oil price increase,
economists are not predicting a new surge in inflation across the
board. Rather, they are merely saying that the decline in inflation
will be over if the oil-price rises stick. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS-TRUST (New York) _ Federal authorities probing
corruption at Bankers Trust New York Corp. are focusing their
investigation around the activities of B.J. Kingdon, who formerly
ran one of the bank's largest businesses and sat on its 12-member
operating committee, according to lawyers and Bankers Trust
employees involved in the investigation. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   REDSKINS-SALE (Undated) _ Two months ago, when Howard Milstein
and his partners agreed to buy the Washington Redskins, it looked
as if nothing could stand in the way of their dream of acquiring a
National Football League team. But Milstein has faced an
unexpectedly rocky road. And if the league's finance committee
rejects the deal, Milstein and his partners will lose not only the
team, but a $30 million nonrefundable deposit. By Richard Sandomir.
With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DUPONT-PIONEER (Undated) _ Pioneer Hi-Bred International, the
world's largest producer of seed corn, and DuPont Co. announced
Friday that they were discussing a possible combination, raising
the prospect of a bidding war in the agriculture industry. By David
J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PHILOSOPHY (Moscow) _ For 70 years, Russian philosophy
was Marxism-Leninism. It was more than a dusty schoolroom
requirement; it was the national religion, the source of the
state's political authority and legitimacy. But the collapse of the
USSR has brought freedom to the study of philosophy. This freedom
has pitched Russian philosophy both backward and forward. What
philosophical school is most popular now? ``What day is it?'' a
philosopher responded with a laugh. By Patricia Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   GASS-PROFILE (St. Louis) _ A profile of the novelist William
Gass, 74, one of the most respected writers never to write a best
seller, who has led a spirited attack on the traditional American
novel, denouncing plot as less important than form and language. By
Dee Wedemeyer. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MATH-BOOKS (Princeton, N.J.) _ On the boom in sales of popular
books about mathematics. By Paul Lewis. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Baltimore) _ It is the year 2002, and violence has
erupted again in Northern Ireland. The U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service decides to target for deportation all
resident aliens who have endorsed or contributed to Noraid, an
American support group for the Irish Republican Army. By Anthony
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKC-EAST (Charlotte, N.C.) _ It was the region that couldn't
shoot straight Friday in a brutal afternoon of substandard
basketball at the East Regional of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament. None of the four teams competing shot
better than 40 percent and one, Wisconsin, scored only 32 points.
Then top-seeded Duke showed up Friday night. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-MIDWEST-II (New Orleans) _ Chagrined by his losing
performance in the Mid-American Conference tournament final, Miami
of Ohio's Wally Szczerbiak came into the Midwest Regional looking
to get the sour taste out of his mouth. He did so by keeping the
basketball in his own hands. The senior forward scored a
career-high 43 points in the Red Hawks' 59-58 victory over
Washington Friday in the Superdome. By Charlie Nobles.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-WEST (Denver) _ After the Connecticut basketball players
practiced at McNichols Arena Friday, the two most talked about
people were Jim Calhoun and Kenny Thomas. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SCANDAL (Undated) _ The International Olympic Committee on
Friday censured the most powerful delegate implicated in the Salt
Lake City bribery scandal, but stopped short of recommending his
expulsion. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN (Orlando) _ Sports of The Times column: What a
week for the NCAA: First the organization's test standards were
thrown out, then March Madness starts with an academic scandal in
Minnesota. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-HOLYFIELD-LENNOX (New York) _ The hype is over: Evander
Holyfield and Lennox Lewis will fight for the heavyweight
championship on Saturday night at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OBITUARIES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-MENUHIN (Undated) _ Violinist Yehudi Menuhin, whose
astonishing youthful virtuosity grew into one of the great musical
talents of the 20th century, died Friday. He was 82. By Allan
Kozinn. With photos.
</P>
