<HEADLINE>
CSUN'S DREAM SEASON HITS THE WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT COLLINS, Colo. _ They almost pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge women's basketball team, picked by no
one to even stay with Colorado State for even a half, put a scare
into the Rams before losing 71-59 Friday night in an NCAA Women's
Tournament first-round game at Moby Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The 15th-seeded Matadors (21-8), down by one at the half, held
on to a lead for most of the second half but unraveled in a
four-minute stretch late in the game when the second-seeded Rams
went on a 19-0 point run.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Cronin's two free throws gave Colorado State a 57-55 lead
with 3:50 left. At that point, it seemed like the Rams, who were
playing in the NCAA Tournament for the second consecutive season,
were a little too much for CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   Jacque Johnson made a steal for the Rams just 10 seconds later,
and Cronin finished on the other end with an 8-footer to make it
59-55.
</P>
<P>
   Cronin wasn't finished. She nailed a 3-pointer with 2:20 left to
extend Colorado State's lead to 62-55.
</P>
<P>
   Edniesha Curry, the Matadors' emotional leader and best player,
picked up her third foul with 16:21 left. She didn't return until
the 10:39 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors picked up the pace without Curry. A steal and layup
with Jamilah Jones gave CSUN a 43-37 lead with 13:19 left. The lead
was 45-38 when Curry came back.
</P>
<P>
   The lead reached seven again, 53-46, with 6{ minutes left on
Vivica Lof's 18-footer.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan Colorado State crowd _ at an estimated 8,500, by
far the largest CSUN has played in front of this season _ was in
shock. The fans sat hushed through most of the first half as the
Matadors stayed ahead of the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN exploited the Rams' zone defense for four 3-pointers in the
first 20 minutes, including two by Lof, a 6-3 reserve center.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State, which was playing at home for the first time
since Feb. 20, was just 11 of 32 from the field (34 percent) in the
first half. The Rams, who didn't lead until Hammon made two free
throws with 3:33 minutes left that made it 25-24, missed 10 of 12
3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors stayed within a point (29-28) of the Rams at
halftime despite committing 14 turnovers and having the same amount
of rebounds, 19, as smaller Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, the second-leading scorer in the Big Sky, attempted _ and
made _ only one basket in the first half: a long 3-pointer that
gave CSUN a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who led by as many as seven points in the game's
first 17 minutes, benefited from a shaky start by Hammon, who
missed her first shot _ a layup _ and turned the ball over on the
next Rams possession.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State missed 12 of its first 15 shots. Hammon was 3 of
10 in the first half. The poor shooting was reminiscent of the
Rams' the 24 percent (14 of 58) effort in a 65-49 loss to SMU in
the WAC Tournament final.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State 72, UC Santa Barbara 70: Carly Deer
scored on a layup with 11 seconds left and the Bears (24-6) held on
to end the Gauchos' school-record 21-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Deer's basket came eight seconds after Erin Buescher gave UCSB
(26-4) a 70-69 lead.
</P>
<P>
   SMS sophomore guard Jackie Stiles, the nation's leading scorer
at 25.9 points per game and the Missouri Valley Conference MVP, was
held to 18 by the 10th-seeded Gauchos. Buescher scored a game-high
27 on 10-of-18 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   UCSB, which took an 11-0 lead before the Bears roared back with
a 14-2 run, played without former Simi Valley High standout Tawnee
Cooper, a junior guard.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper suffered a broken left leg and partially torn ACL five
weeks ago. At the time of the injury, she was third on the team in
scoring (12.3).
</P>
</TEXT>
