<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-HOUSTON-1STLE     03-13 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-HOUSTON-1ST </SLUG>
 LEDE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NFL
</P>
<P>
   McNair vows sellouts &QL; 
if Houston gets NFL team &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN WILLIAMS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ Houston businessman Bob McNair on Friday guaranteed
sellouts at every home game for five years should he get an NFL
expansion football team, a pledge that would prevent local
television blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual promise is aimed at gaining an upper hand over Los
Angeles, which has more than a 3-1 edge in the number of TV
households and is considered a better place for the league to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   However, network officials have said they would prefer that the
NFL be in a town that can guarantee sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm that confident we will succeed,'' McNair said. ``We're
telling television that you're not going to suffer blackouts in
Houston. That should be a big challenge to Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Two groups in Los Angeles are competing for a team. Hollywood
dealmaker Michael Ovitz wants to build a new stadium in suburban
Carson atop a waste dump. Real estate developer Ed Roski and
billionaire Eli Broad want to remodel the L.A. Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   An official for Roski declined comment on McNair's pledge, other
than to say, ``Oh, my god.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials, preparing to gather in Phoenix on Sunday for a
meeting to decide which city will get an expansion team, declined
comment.
</P>
<P>
   One NFL official said the league would expect Houston to sell
out every home game during the first five years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, making such a pledge is very uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he would devise a system to give to charity any
tickets not sold by the deadline for a blackout. Under NFL rules, a
game is not televised within 75 miles if not a sellout 72 hours
before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said giving the tickets to charity would cost him 34
percent of their face value, the percentage of gate receipts a home
team must pledge to the visiting team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could come at a cost to the team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Challenging Los Angeles' TV advantage has been a major goal of
McNair in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, he distributed a report to team owners
showing that while Los Angeles has a larger base of viewers who
watch NFL games, having a home team in that city does not produce a
large gain over having a new team in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Using network records for the 1993 and 1994 seasons, the
incremental gain of a Los Angeles Raiders game over the base was
only about 28,000 more than the incremental gain of a Houston
Oilers' game.
</P>
<P>
   Both cities lost their NFL franchises in 1995, with Los Angeles
also losing the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix this week, Denver Broncos owner Pat Bowlen told
Bloomberg News Service that many owners prefer Los Angeles because
of its TV market.
</P>
<P>
   But Bowlen, a member of the expansion and television committees,
said he doesn't believe ``Los Angeles is the no-brainer people are
making it out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any confidence that a stadium agreement is going
to get done by either Los Angeles group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Los Angeles cannot solidify a stadium financing plan that
allows for play in 2002, Bowlen said he will throw his support to
Houston, where public financing, stadium design and ownership have
been decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the stadium isn't ready, there's nothing wrong with giving
Houston the expansion team, negotiating our own stadium agreement
in Los Angeles and later relocating a team there,'' Bowlen said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Texas' two U.S. senators and the region's seven House
members have sent NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue a letter asking
that he hold to his word.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three years ago, Tagliabue stood in Houston's City Hall
and said the city would likely get another football team if it put
together a state-of-the-art stadium deal.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the group _ led by Republican Sens. Phil Gramm and
Kay Bailey Hutchison _ implored the league to give Houston the 32nd
franchise over Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The letter reminded Tagliabue of his comments May 29, 1996,
after meeting with Gramm, then-Mayor Bob Lanier, Harris County
Judge Robert Eckels and others in wake of the Oilers' departure for
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said he saw no reason why Houston could not have
another team within six years if a stadium financing plan were in
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly should be the objective,'' Tagliabue said.
``I've seen some suggestions that talk about 2002 or beyond, and I
think if we get to work and make this a priority, which is what we
committed to today, it can be done sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter said Houston's proposed $310 million,
retractable-roof stadium ``meets all the requirements set by you.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was also signed by U.S. Reps. Bill Archer, R-Houston;
Nick Lampson, D-Beaumont; Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land; Gene Green,
D-Houston; Kevin Brady, R-The Woodlands; Sheila Jackson Lee,
D-Houston; and Ken Bentsen, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional officials from California have not made a similar
lobbying effort on behalf of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Houston football market is tremendous, and NFL consultants
predict great fan interest in a franchise,'' the Texas letter said.
</P>
