<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 03:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9017 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-CSUN-COLORADOSTAT     03-13 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CSUN-COLORADOSTATE-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO STATE ENDS CSUN'S SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT COLLINS, Colo. _ It was a little after midnight here when
the dream dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge women's basketball team, given little
or no chance to beat heavily favored Colorado State, gave the Rams
a scare before losing 71-59 in the first round of the NCAA Women's
Tournament on Friday night at Moby Arena.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (21-8) saw its seven-game winning streak broken in its
first appearance in the tournament. Until the final five minutes,
the 15th-seeded Matadors looked like they would earn a
``SportsCenter'' highlight.
</P>
<P>
   With 5 minutes, 48 seconds left, CSUN led 55-48.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't tell until the last five minutes who was the No.
4 team in the country,'' CSUN guard Tina Greer said.
</P>
<P>
   But the glass slipper did not fit. It was the classic case of a
team with tournament experience, playing in front of a sellout
crowd of 8,741, doing what it had to do to advance. The
second-seeded Rams (31-2) went on a 19-0 run in a crucial five
minute stretch that made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN coach Frozena Jerro said she was getting the feeling of an
upset just prior to the Rams' onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was getting to that point,'' she said. ``I couldn't let it
sink in too soon. I felt if we could hold on for a couple more
minutes, we would have a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State relied on its two standout seniors _ Becky Hammon
and Katie Cronin _ to pull out the Rams' 20th-consecutive home win.
Even though they combined to make just eight of 25 shots, the combo
of Hammon and Cronin was responsible for the Rams' final 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every huddle, it was like `We are not losing this,''' said
Hammon, an All-American who finished with a game-high 27. ``I'd
rather have a momentum shift in the last two minutes than in the
first 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Edniesha Curry, the Matadors' emotional leader and best player,
picked up her third foul with 16:21 left. She didn't return until
the 10:39 mark.
</P>
<P>
   But the Matadors extended the lead without Curry. A steal and
layup by Jamilah Jones gave CSUN a 43-37 lead with 13:19 left. The
lead was 45-38 when Curry came back.
</P>
<P>
   The lead reached seven again, 53-46, with 6{ minutes left on
Vivica Lof's 18-footer.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan Colorado State crowd _ by far the largest CSUN has
played in front of this season _ was in shock. The fans sat hushed
through most of the first half as the Matadors stayed ahead of the
Rams.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN exploited the Rams' zone defense for four 3-pointers in the
first 20 minutes, including two by Lof, a 6-3 reserve center who
scored a team-high 12. The Rams, who were playing at home for the
first time since Feb. 20, were just 11 of 32 from the field (34
percent) in the first half. They didn't lead until Hammon made a
pair of free throws with 3:33 left that made it 25-24, missed 10 of
12 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors stayed within a point (29-28) of the Rams at
halftime despite committing 14 turnovers and having the same number
of rebounds, 19, as the smaller Rams. For the game, CSUN
outrebounded Colorado State 41-37.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, the second-leading scorer in the Big Sky, attempted _ and
made _ only one basket in the first half: a long 3-pointer that
gave CSUN a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who led by as many as seven points in the game's
first 17 minutes, benefited from a shaky start by Hammon, who
missed her first shot _ a layup _ and turned the ball over on the
next Rams possession.
</P>
<P>
   CSU missed 12 of its first 15 shots. Hammon was 3 of 10 in the
first half. The poor shooting was reminiscent of the Rams' the 24
percent (14 of 58) effort in a 65-49 loss to SMU in the WAC
Tournament final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
