<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9032 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-CORRUPTION-REVI     03-13 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-CORRUPTION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING OUT HOW MUCH THE BOSS REALLY MAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all the railing of unions about income
inequality, some labor leaders don't seem to take the issue too
seriously when it hits close to home.
</P>
<P>
   Take Gus Bevona, the longtime president of a New York City
janitors' local who made $531,529 in 1997. That's 17 times what his
union's members earned on average. Or take Frank Wsol, head of a
teamsters local in Chicago, who was paid $473,069.
</P>
<P>
   These salaries may be small compared to what Bill Gates or
Michael Eisner make, but they are surprisingly high in a field
where people become leaders, at least in theory, because they are
more interested in raising their members' incomes than in raising
their own.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason some union leaders have been able to jack up
their salaries is that it is often hard for members to find out
what their leaders are paid. Many times, union leaders have their
salaries increased at sparsely attended board meetings, and
afterward they do little to broadcast the news, knowing it would
hurt their re-election chances. Until recently, often the only way
union members could find out how much their leaders earned was to
go or write to an office of the U.S. Department of Labor to ask to
see a bare-bones financial report that every parent union and local
must file annually.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, union members _ or members of the public _ wanting
to know how much a labor leader earned must request a form known as
an LM-2 for that leader's union. But there are complications that
make this process as hard as doing a jigsaw puzzle. It is often
necessary to track down an array of forms to get the whole picture.
A union official may be paid separately as president of a local,
president of a citywide joint council and board member of the
parent union.
</P>
<P>
   For example, to figure out Bevona's salary, union members must
go first to the Labor Department's Office of Labor-Management
Standards in lower Manhattan. There, they must ask for the LM-2
form for Local 32B-32J of the Service Employees International
Union, Bevona's local, which represents 55,000 janitors and
doormen. The report shows the local paid him $365,401 in 1997 _ the
most recent year for which a report was filed.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be wrong to stop there. Bevona also served as
president of a related local, Local 32B-32J-144, representing
22,000 home health-care aides who assist the elderly and disabled.
The LM-2 for that local reveals that Bevona received an additional
$86,128. That raised his income to $451,529.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most intrepid union members might stop their search
right there, but Bevona was also a board member of the
Washington-based parent union. To determine how much he earned for
that post, it is necessary to ask the Labor Department's main
office in Washington for the parent union's LM-2. That form shows
that Bevona received an additional $80,000 for being on that board.
Voila, his 1997 income totaled $531,529.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department has recently made it easier to obtain LM-2
forms by requesting them through the Internet at
(www.dol.gov/dol/esa/public/regs/compliance/olms/rrlo/ordern.htm).
</P>
<P>
   Bevona's unusual salary and the marble-lined penthouse apartment
he had built atop union headquarters were among the reasons his
parent union pressured him to take early retirement in February.
</P>
<P>
   Upset that so many teamster leaders belong to what it calls the
$100,000 club, a dissident group called Teamsters for a Democratic
Union has begun collecting LM-2 forms for every teamster local. The
group has published what it found. Thus it became known that Wsol
received $428,745 from Local 710 in 1997 as well as $44,324 for his
work as vice president of Teamsters Joint Council 25 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to have an organization that makes a point of getting
these documents,'' said Ken Paff, national coordinator of Teamsters
for a Democratic Union. ``Ever since the 1980s when we really began
publicizing the members of the $100,000 club, the number of
teamster leaders earning that much has declined steadily.''
</P>
<P>
   But even LM-2 forms tell only a little of the story. When Bevona
retired, he stunned members by walking away with $1.5 million _
$850,000 in a lump sum severance payment and $650,000 in unused
vacation time. There was no mention of those accrued liabilities in
the LM-2 forms filed by Bevona's local, even in the lines where the
union was asked to list liabilities. And members who wanted to
learn details about Bevona's penthouse could learn nothing from the
financial reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``When unions file these forms with the government, they should
be required to list information like how large a pension a union
leader is due and how much vacation time they are owed,'' said
Herman Benson, founder of the Association for Union Democracy, a
Brooklyn-based nonprofit watchdog group. ``That way members would
know if something outrageous is developing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many union members complain that most unions representing
government employees are exempt from the requirement to file LM-2
forms. Benson's group and many union members are lobbying for
legislation that would require such disclosure by government
employee unions.
</P>
<P>
   Some disgruntled union members also want the AFL-CIO to publish
guidelines on how much union leaders should earn. It makes no
sense, they say, for Wsol to earn more than twice as much as
AFL-CIO president John Sweeney or for Bevona to earn five times as
much as Dennis Rivera, president of a New York hospital workers'
union with more than double the membership of Bevona's local
</P>
<P>
   ``These guidelines,'' Benson said, ``would be a real moral boost
for the labor movement and might save it a lot of embarrassment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
