A9033 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOB-TITLES-REVIEW-NYT     03-13 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-TITLES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASE HOLD FOR THE DEPUTY DEPUTY. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration may have reinvented the
federal work force by cutting nearly 400,000 lower-level jobs, but
it has also reinforced an already top-heavy bureaucracy with more
layers of lavishly titled officials in the upper ranks of the
government, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the study, by Paul Light of the Brookings Institution,
concluded that the administration has created as many new job
titles among the government's higher tiers in the last six years as
the seven prior administrations did over 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the newer positions include deputy to the deputy
secretary, principal assistant deputy undersecretary and associate
principal deputy assistant secretary. Any given department may have
only one of the new positions, but experience suggests that they
will spread.
</P>
<P>
   Titles that have already spread like kudzu through the agencies
since 1960 include deputy assistant secretaries (484), associate
assistant secretaries (148), assistant assistant secretaries (220)
and deputy assistant assistant secretaries (82).
</P>
<P>
   And a handful of officials hold titles like associate deputy
assistant secretary, chief of staff to the associate assistant
secretary, chief of staff to the assistant assistant secretary and
principal deputy to the deputy assistant secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive growth of such jobs may help the self-esteem of
some officials and their bosses, but it has also contributed to
significant paper shuffling and delays in decision making, the
study says.
</P>
<P>
   The titles have been part of a six-year management overhaul by
the White House that has eliminated many of the more important
lower-level jobs and contracted them out to private companies. As a
result, people have found it harder to reach federal employees when
they call or write the government, and top officials have become
more insulated from the needs of the people and the issues that
affect them, the study says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got here two months ago, and I've been saying, I've got
to have a chief of staff,'' Light said. ``That person would be
chief of staff to the senior fellow. But I won't really be somebody
until I have a deputy chief of staff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
