<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 The Week in Review  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't Look Too Far
</P>
<P>
   Those unschooled in the nuances of presidential candidates'
announcements and exploratory committees may picture experts
huddled around a table deliberating whether their candidate should
take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiling his 10-member exploratory panel last week, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush said he was ``grateful they will take time to help
me make this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush exploratory committee has no immediate plans to
meet. What's to explore? The governor himself said he would back
out only if his candidacy were greeted with ``a large thud.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole did not disclose her committee members' names
last week because there aren't any. ``That's a legalism,''
explained Mrs. Dole's senior strategist, Kieran Mahoney.
</P>
<P>
   By registering an exploratory committee with the Federal
Election Commission, contenders can begin collecting money for
travel and early organizational efforts. But it is not required;
candidates could just as easily create full-fledged campaign
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Why do many hopefuls maintain the fiction that they are
exploring when there is little doubt of their intentions? If their
campaigns collapse early, they can make a graceful exit, saying
that _ technically _ they were never in the race. And why announce
in one grand event if you can build the drama?
</P>
<P>
   As one Federal Election Commission official put it, ``A lot of
this is going through the hoops just for the political mileage.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD L. BERKE
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Seuss He's Not
</P>
<P>
   It took only hours for William Ivey, chairman of the National
