<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9038 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-POLS-REVIEW-NYT     03-13 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-POLS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ILLINOIS, IT'S THE POLITICAL LIFE FOR RILEY, GILHOOLEY ET AL. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ There seems to be truth in the adage about the luck of
the Irish, at least when it comes to running for political office.
As sure as the Chicago River runs green for St. Patrick's Day,
politicians with Irish names hold all but a few of the major
offices in Illinois _ from Fitzgerald to Madigan to Devine, a pair
of Ryans, and, of course, another mayor named Daley. The sons and
daughters of Erin also do pretty well elsewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given a choice, people pick Irish,'' said Michael Hout, a
sociologist at the University of California in Berkeley who
conducted a study of how people of mixed backgrounds identify
themselves on census forms. More people identified themselves as
Irish than immigration and natural selection alone would predict,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The background least often chosen was British. ``For all the
Anglophiles at Harvard, there seems to be some antipathy west of
there to be identified as British,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hout suggested that the ``positive cultural markers'' of the
Irish, traits stereotypically associated with that group _
gregariousness, wit, charm and ``the flavor of the underdog'' _
make them appealing to many Americans. Even St. Patrick's Day, a
day set aside to celebrate the Irish, plays a role, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very things that the Irish were once vilified for _ being
boisterous, charmers, social animals, storytellers _ are seen as
wonderful attributes in American society today,'' said Paul Green,
a political-science professor at Governors State University.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars say the euphonious quality of Irish names makes
them songlike. It has become so common for American parents to use
Irish last names like Ryan, Shannon and Kelly for their children's
first names that a Harvard researcher is studying the trend.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Irish love of words seems tailor-made for
politics. President Clinton proclaims ancestral links to Ireland,
as did former Presidents Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan and many
predecessors. John F. Kennedy was the first Irish Catholic elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   Irish-Americans have long been disproportionately represented in
Congress, said Melvin Holli, a political scientist at the
University of Illinois at Chicago, and the author of books about
ethnicity and politics. ``The priesthood, the police force and
politics _ that's the Irish trinity,'' said Holli, referring to the
Irish influence on those institutions.
</P>
<P>
   As an immigrant group that arrived speaking English, the Irish
built political machines in 19th-century Chicago and New York; they
survived by making inroads in municipal government.
</P>
<P>
   Irish names have been on the ballot so long, goes one theory,
that people simply feel comfortable voting in Irish-Americans. It
certainly helped the legendary Mayor Richard J. Daley and his son,
Richard M. Daley.
</P>
<P>
   Elections for judgeships in Chicago have sometimes been called
``the Irish Sweepstakes,'' given the names of the usual victors. In
one campaign for a Cook County judge last year, voters were given a
choice between James Patrick McCarthy and Bonnie Fitzgerald
McGrath, who happened to be Jewish. McCarthy emerged as the victor,
most likely because he was a Democrat, which can still trump the
opposition in most Chicago wards. (Not always. Michael Flanagan, an
unknown Republican, toppled the powerful, though indicted, Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski.)
</P>
<P>
   Today Irish-Americans, according to research gathered by the
Rev. Andrew Greeley, the Roman Catholic priest and novelist, are a
prosperous, privileged ethnic group. It has been a long journey
from the days when the 19th century refugees of the potato famine
endured open ridicule and discrimination. ``Scratch a convict or a
pauper,'' read an editorial in The Chicago Evening Post in 1868,
``and the chances are that you tickle the skin of an Irish
Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the time being the Chicago descendants of those
immigrants seem to have had the last word even though they are
outnumbered by Americans whose ancestors came from Germany, Eastern
Europe, Africa and Mexico. Chicago baseball teams play in stadiums
named for Irishmen: Wrigley Field and Comiskey Park. O'Hare airport
is named for a World War II hero. An Irish-American has been mayor
for all but nine of the past 66 years, including the first Mayor
Daley, whose ``idea of affirmative action was nine Irishmen and a
Swede,'' his press secretary, Frank Sullivan, once said. It is a
different world for his son, who has put together a diverse City
Hall team. Nearly half of black voters supported Daley in his
landslide victory in February.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Alderman Mathias Bauler wrote a ditty that said
while most immigrant groups detested each other, they would all
vote for an Irishman.
</P>
<P>
   Bauler, who was of German descent, did not use his given first
name in Chicago politics: he went by the nickname Paddy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
