<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9041 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIMAGGIO-INTERVIEW-RE     03-13 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMAGGIO-INTERVIEW-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JOE DiMAGGIO: THE SILENT CELEBRITY  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (editors: also see KUBRICK-INTERVIEW-REVIEW. The Times is running
the two pieces together under a single headline, ``The Silent
Celebrity and the Quotable Recluse.'')  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Joe DiMaggio's day, athletes were expected to play, not talk.
Still, the shy Yankee legend, who died last week at 84, did
thousands of interviews over six decades.
</P>
<P>
   He poured his heart out _ well, sort of like Calvin Coolidge
poured his heart out. In one 1994 session, for example, DiMaggio
described the 1936-51 Yankees, which won 10 pennants over his
career, as ``a very fine ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   While his teammate Yogi Berra filled reporters' notebooks, the
following lines prove that DiMag was no Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN SCHWARZ
</P>
<P>
   _ On providing good copy:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember a reporter asking for a quote, and I didn't
know what a quote was. I thought it was some kind of soft drink.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On getting emotional on the field:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't. It wouldn't look right.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On his defensive prowess:
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no trick to catching a ball in the open field, no
matter how far it is hit, as long as it stays in the air long
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On his silent approach:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a ballplayer, not an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On his retirement:
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought I could make my last year a good one. I had a
bad one, instead.''
</P>
<P>
   _ To a rebuffed woman in a nightclub who snapped, ``All right, I
guess I'm not Marilyn Monroe'':
</P>
<P>
   ``No _ I wish you were, but you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On selling newspapers as a boy in San Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``Papers were only 3 cents then, and you kept a penny. Sometimes
people would go along and give you a nickel. That was a 2-cent
tip.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On someday telling his full story:
</P>
<P>
   ``Memoirs? No. No, no, no, no. I don't want to talk about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
