<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOILER-ROOMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEMARKETING RAIDS REVEAL SCAM VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took just a telephone call to sweet-talk Jeff
Daly out of $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   A smooth telemarketer promised the Agua Dulce man up to a 400
percent profit if he invested in a film called ``Operation: Desert
Gold,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he forked over the money, joining the swelling ranks of
people defrauded by Southern California telemarketing schemes,
increasingly based in the San Fernando Valley, authorities say.
They include the one the FBI says Chris Rawlings ran before he was
kidnapped from his home and killed in the crash of his Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their primary existence is to take money from people,'' said
Daly, 50. ``I have no idea how I ended up on their phone lists.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly's case is not unique.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles alone last year, a federal crackdown identified
about 20 telemarketing scams, called boiler rooms because of their
high-pressure selling tactics. They included the one selling
``Operation: Desert Gold,'' federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and local investigators broke up telemarketing
operations in 40 states during the past year, accusing them of
bilking excited investors out of more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many fraudulent telemarketing
operations exist in Los Angeles, but recent raids have turned up
thousands of victims scammed by Valley operations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They include Rawlings' multimillion-dollar telemarketing
operation, which may have led to his death, police said. It was
just a small glimpse at the phony industry.
</P>
<P>
   The operation used several locations from Calabasas to West Los
Angeles and involved at least seven others, who have been indicted
on mail fraud charges tied to an alleged telemarketing scheme.
Altogether with Rawlings, they are accused of bilking investors out
of more than $19 million over several years.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-count indictment charges that Peter Aro, John Dickens,
Timothy Griffeith, Vincent Rabiola, John Watson, Gerald Whiteford
and Michael Wineman operated a scheme to defraud mostly elderly
victims who thought they were investing in unrelated Beatles and
Marvin Gaye recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Telemarketing scammers prey on people looking for quick ways to
make money and seem gullible.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these people are elderly with fading memories,'' said
Herschel Elkins, a senior assistant attorney general with the
state's Consumer Law Section in Los Angeles. ``They are target No.
1.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside nondescript storefronts or offices across L.A.'s San
Fernando Valley, hundreds of low-paid telemarketers follow scripts
and cold-call households fishing for cash.
</P>
<P>
   And the number of victims scammed by area boiler rooms is in the
tens of thousands, which state officials have calculated using
files left behind in vacated office spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vulnerable investors sometimes give away their life savings
over the telephone and they never see a return because scammers
pocket the cash,'' said Lisa A. Gok, assistant regional director of
the Securities and Exchange Commission's office of enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to all be in Orange County, now there's a trend into
the Valley. There's no real explanation for it except that the
migrate from place to place,'' Gok said.
</P>
<P>
   The scams have created such grave mistrust toward legitimate
venture capitalists that independent film producer Bill Lansford,
owner of El Dorado Productions, decided finance his film ``Adios
East Los'' with investments from friends and their contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met face to face with our investors, unlike the
fast-talking Hollywood crooks. They're a small group of weasles,''
he said. ``Our investors understand that we don't lease Rolls
Royces and smoke Cuban cigars, and that gives them a better chance
of making a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   They've even made life difficult for direct-marketing businesses
including Kevin Peterson Publishing in Encino, despite the fact
that they do business-to-business marketing _ not phone
solicitations for cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boiler rooms have created skepticism with potential clients,
and some of them have been burned before,'' Peterson said. ``It
makes it tougher to get new clients because they envision scam
businesses where there's a guy walking around yelling, `Make more
calls.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Operation: Desert Gold,'' the Securities and
Exchange Commission is suing three principals in the venture
capital scheme, which ran between 1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC alleges that David Burnell and J. Eric Rymland, both of
San Francisco, and Daniel Rung of Riverside ran a scheme that
bilked 600 investors out of more than $8 million. ``Operation:
Desert Gold'' was based in San Francisco and Riverside, but they
had a boiler room operating in Van Nuys as well, the SEC alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The case remains in litigation.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
