<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUICIDE RATE OF YOUTHS IS CLIMBING IN IRELAND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Though long stereotyped as a happy land of pious
churchgoers and bibulous dancers of jigs, Ireland is suffering a
sharply rising increase in suicides, particularly among young men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ireland has the fastest-growing rate of youth suicide in the
world, and almost one in four suicides occur among those aged
between 15 and 24,'' said the Catholic Archdiocese of Dublin in a
statement at a recent conference on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   A government task force reported earlier this year that the rate
of suicides of males between 15 and 24 was about 19 per 100,000
people, higher than that in most European countries and apparently
growing. Since 1945, the overall rate of suicide in Ireland has
increased from 2.5 to nearly 14. The rate in England is about 12,
and in Northern Ireland, torn for 30 years by sectarian warfare,
about 11. Since 1987, the number of Irish people who have killed
themselves has doubled, to about 500 a year, and men are
responsible for four of five of those deaths.
</P>
<P>
   These figures are lower than the actual number of suicides
because police in rural areas often report suicides as accidents to
spare the feelings of relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that while alcoholism, depression and other serious
illnesses still are major causes of suicide here, other broader
changes in Irish society may also be contributing.
</P>
<P>
   First is the church's admittedly more benign view of suicide,
which is no longer vehemently condemned from the pulpit in this
overwhelmingly Catholic country. Second, experts say, is the
changing roles of men and women in what remains a male-dominated
society. Ten years ago only one-third of married women held jobs
outside their homes; now the number is approaching the European
Union average of about 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equality for women is a good thing,'' Dr. John Sheehan, a
psychiatrist at the Mater Hospital in Dublin, said in an interview.
``But men now feel unsure of their roles. They fear they may no
longer be the breadwinners.''
</P>
<P>
   John Waters, the author of books on Irish society and a
columnist for The Irish Times, asserts that newspapers and
television programs still avoid reporting and analyzing suicide.
For older Irish men and women, this recalls the debate in the late
1940s over the treatment of suicide in the novel ``The Heart of the
Matter,'' by Graham Greene, the English writer whose work was
discussed here with particular interest because he was a convert to
Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, one character speculates that the suicide, Scobie,
may be pardoned by God and should not be condemned by men. The
suggestion now seems prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Pat O'Donoghue, who has created a special liturgy for
relations of people who commit suicide, noted that the
Vatican-approved Catechism says that suicide is ``against natural
law.'' But it adds: ``By ways known to Him alone, God can provide
the opportunity for salutary repentance. The church prays for
persons who have taken their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The church, O'Donoghue added, has since 1961 permitted suicides
to be buried in consecrated ground after official Masses of
requiem. He acknowledged that the fear of hell that once deterred
suicidal people was disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan, the hospital psychiatrist, agreed. ``A major social
change in Ireland,'' he wrote in a recent article in the Dublin
Archdiocese newsletter, ``has been the decline in religious
practice over the past 20 years. It appears that there is an
inverse relationship between the practice of religion and the rise
in suicide. Young people are no longer frightened of eternal
damnation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Dublin area, where about one-third of the population of
3.6 million lives, about 200 people call the Samaritans, a
volunteer organization, every day, many of them to discuss their
possible suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gallagher, the director of the Samaritans' Dublin office,
said people often call in and start discussing a different problem,
like the death of a relative, before the volunteer carefully raises
the question of suicide. But about one-third of the callers never
speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be their first port of call or their last port of
call,'' he said. ``They want you to know you're going to be the
last person on earth to speak to them. We offer support. We don't
usually know where they go after that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1309EST &QL; 
