<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9080 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-DOLE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-13 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DOLE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Announcing her presidential exploratory
committee here last week, Elizabeth Dole invoked the last
Republican hero, Ronald Reagan. Three days earlier, presenting his
own committee in Austin, Texas Gov. George W. Bush mentioned the
first Republican hero, Abraham Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Neither made even a reference to two of the biggest names in
Republican politics today, who also happen to be their most
prominent supporters: former Sen. Bob Dole and former President
George Bush, respectively. Both were conspicuously absent from the
events. The closest Dole came to appearing with his wife was in one
of seven blown-up photographs that served as the backdrop. (Reagan
got equal billing: There was a photograph of him and Mrs. Dole.)
</P>
<P>
   A Bush or a Dole has appeared on every Republican presidential
ticket since 1976. But by distancing themselves from their famous
family members, the latest Bush and Dole candidates to seek the
White House demonstrate the complications _ the drawbacks as well
as advantages _ of belonging to political dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their individual accomplishments, Mrs. Dole and Bush
would not be such hot tickets _ they are swamping the GOP field in
early polls _ were it not for their pedigrees. Behind the scenes,
they have been eagerly tapping into their families' extended
financial and political networks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the obligatory questions by reporters about his father,
Bush repeated his well-practiced reply after his announcement last
week: ``I inherited half his friends and all his enemies. I'm
working on the other half of his friends _ and trying to peel off a
few of his enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the voters who regard the Bush and Dole names as famous,
others view them as infamous. So the two newest national contenders
are forced to make a purely political calculation: How closely do
they want to be identified with losers? Who can forget that Dole,
the former Senate Republican leader, suffered a humiliating defeat
to President Clinton in 1996? Or that former President Bush was
ousted from office by him in 1992?
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is very straightforward, to try to get all the
benefits of the famous name _ and none of the negatives,'' said
Nelson Warfield, Dole's press secretary in the 1996 campaign. ``The
spotlight would not be nearly as bright for Elizabeth if her last
name were Doyle. But any losing campaign leaves bad memories, so
too much deja Dole can hurt her.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are sensitive to the suggestion that they are
riding on familial coattails. Bush, who earned $14 million from a
minority investment in the Texas Rangers baseball team, is a widely
popular governor in his own right; Mrs. Dole served in five
administrations, twice in the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Both are determined not to be compared with the Kennedys, whose
patriarch, Joseph Kennedy, was perceived as prodding his sons into
politics. Americans ``are a robustly anti-dynastic culture,'' said
Tony Dolan, Reagan's former chief speech writer, who recently met
with the elder Bush in Texas. ``George W. has to make clear that he
doesn't think he has a right to inheritance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole's newly hired pollster, Linda DiVall, distinguished
her candidate from another spouse of a famous politician _ Hillary
Rodham Clinton _ who is toying with running for the U.S. Senate
from New York. ``She is not running because she is the spouse or
out of any sense of entitlement _ or what we see with Hillary
Clinton,'' Ms. DiVall said. ``And there's no attempt to hide him.
But she needs to establish her individual identity.''
</P>
<P>
   In personality alone, the candidates cannot be accused of being
spinoffs of their more celebrated _ in some cases, scorned _ kin.
Mrs. Dole, who has never been elected to office, is a regimented
perfectionist; her husband, a veteran politician, is known for his
looser, seat-of-the-pants approach.
</P>
<P>
   Bristling at contrasts to his father, Bush cited his distinct
upbringing and achievements. ``I went to Sam Houston Elementary
School in Midland, Texas,'' he said last week. ``And he went to
Greenwich Country Day in Connecticut. I married Laura; he married
Barbara. He was never a governor, and, therefore, it's hard to get
an apples-to-apples comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   But comparisons are inevitable, particularly since both
candidates have refused to answer questions about their positions
on crucial national and international matters. That has left their
rivals to fill in the blanks. Naming no names, two familiar
presidential candidates, Lamar Alexander and Steve Forbes, himself
the scion of publishing tycoon Malcolm Forbes, recently sought to
get at the son by condemning the father's promise of a ``kinder and
gentler'' nation.
</P>
<P>
   Voters have been left to assume _ rightly or wrongly _ that Gov.
Bush's and Mrs. Dole's philosophies do not diverge appreciably from
that of former President Bush or Dole. Despite the governor's
popularity in the polls, for example, surveys continue to show that
many Republicans confuse Bush with his father. And in random
interviews at Republican events, participants who favor abortion
rights often remark that Bush's anti-abortion stand was tolerable
because they remembered that his father once was on their side.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of Mrs. Dole and Bush to define themselves has left
Republicans searching for hints. That Richard Darman, President
Bush's budget director, has been nowhere to be seen in his son's
organization has sent a signal that the governor has a more
conservative economic philosophy. Many conservatives blame Darman
for talking the president into the politically fatal tax increase
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   From the opposite perspective, many conservatives groused last
week about Mrs. Dole's hiring of Ms. DiVall because she has worked
for Planned Parenthood and the National Education Association,
which are seen as liberal organizations. (Ms. DiVall says she has
also had many conservatives on her client roster, including Sen.
Phil Gramm of Texas and former House Speaker Newt Gingrich.) In
assembling a staff, Mrs. Dole has pointedly reached beyond her
husband's advisers from 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, one of Bush's top supporters, state Sen. Thurman
Gaskill, said voters should not expect the governor to campaign
alongside his father. Gaskill, who was also a big backer of the
elder Bush, explained, ``Conservatives always had some reservations
with President Bush, and that's who the governor has to appeal to.
He wants to make them feel a little more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their determination to break free, Bush and Mrs. Dole
can take heart that Vice President Al Gore, the current Democratic
front-runner, dare not attack them for their lineage. After Gore
was picked as Clinton's running mate in 1992, his father, former
Sen. Albert Gore Sr., D-Tenn., remarked that his namesake was
destined for the White House, saying, ``He was raised for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
