<HEADER>
A9081 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS-LIFE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-13 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-LIFE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU WANT TO SEE A MARTIAN, LOOK IN THE MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good science often starts with flights of imagination that are
all but unknown publicly. That's because the creative process ends
in scientific reports cast to seem as dry and objective as
possible. All the same, history shows scientists driven by visions
not only wild in their own day, but sometimes still audacious.
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Kepler, who discovered that the planets move in
elliptical paths around the Sun, was motivated by a mystical love
of musical harmonies. Friedrich August Kekule, a founder of organic
chemistry, told of hitting on the ring structure of benzene after a
dream in which a snake curled itself into a loop. Ernest
Rutherford, inspired by the majesty of the solar system, proposed a
model of the atom in which electrons orbit around a central
nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   Today, science is toying quietly with the notion that all
terrestrial life came from Mars _ that we, in effect, are the
Martians.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that billions of years ago, life arose first on the
red planet, probably dotted back then with blue lakes and seas.
Cosmic collisions sent the alien slimes and microbes flying on
rocky debris through space like so many windblown seeds until they
fell to Earth and flourished, in time producing such specimens as
Monica Lewinsky and Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound goofy. But supporting evidence, if sketchy, has
been growing steadily for a decade. So Aliens ``R'' Us is a hot
topic. Scientists even plan to address the issue experimentally as
Mars probes costing many billions of dollars swing into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can tell, nearly everybody believes it's
plausible,'' said Joseph Burns, a planetary scientist at Cornell
University. ``Who knows? Maybe we are the little green men.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rummel, a top NASA biologist who explores the
extraterrestrial life issue, agreed. ``It's a fascinating
question,'' he said, adding that scientists in the next few years
may find that Martians and Earthlings are ``really the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The wilder dreams of science are seldom aired in public. When
they are, the unveiling tends to be done by superstars, not the
rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Sagan, the late astronomer and science author, in his 1994
book, ``Pale Blue Dot'' (Random House), asked gingerly if the
Earthly tree of life could have arisen from Martian seeds, if the
two planets ``regularly exchanged life-forms'' over the ages.
</P>
<P>
   So too, Francis Crick, the co-discoverer of DNA's structure, in
his 1981 book, ``Life Itself'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), broached the
more general idea that primitive life came to Earth from somewhere
in outer space, a notion known as panspermia.
</P>
<P>
   Behind such musings lies a problem of logic that has grown more
unsettling in recent years. The time appears to have been very
short between the end of the lethal bombardment of the young Earth
by all kinds of planetary crud and building blocks (the same blitz
that pockmarked the Moon) and the start of terrestrial life. By
some estimates, the two events were nearly simultaneous, leaving no
time for the slow twists and turns of biologic evolution. So
scientists often look to the heavens for answers.
</P>
<P>
   As a birthplace, Mars seems increasingly apt. Though cold and
dry today, it is thought to have been wetter and warmer long ago. A
growing number of scientists argue that it was far more habitable
than the early Earth, if only because its small size made it less
of a target for cosmic intruders big enough to wipe out all
rudimentary life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being out when the hunters are drunk,'' said Norman
Sleep, a geophysicist at Stanford University who sees Mars as the
cradle of life. ``You're better off being a rabbit than a deer.''
</P>
<P>
   Also wowing Mars fans is the discovery that cosmic smashups of
an ordinary sort have sent hundreds of tons of the distant planet
falling to Earth. Experts estimate that a Mars rock lands as often
as every three days, and that billions have done so over time _
even though only 13 of them have been identified so far.
</P>
<P>
   The rain of debris from Mars was hardest, experts agree, in the
Earth's early days. And the reverse trip was far less likely
because the Sun pulls Earth debris away from Mars and toward
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Burns of Cornell and his colleagues, using big computers to
track likely paths of Mars debris, made news in 1996 by showing
that the trek to Earth through the wilds of outer space could be as
short as a few months. ``We were stunned to see how easily this
material moves around,'' Burns remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists see other tantalizing clues. Some forms of
terrestrial life, they note, can withstand dangerously high levels
of radiation _ the main bar to unprotected life surviving the
rigors of outer space.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, scientists reported that Deinococcus radiodurans, a
microbe often found around nuclear reactors, could easily handle a
dose 3,000 times stronger than what would kill a human. A riddle is
why the microbe's skills evolved, since Earth apparently never
experienced such high levels of radiation. Could it be that it came
from somewhere in space where radiation is much higher?
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, scientists hope to settle the Aliens
``R'' Us question once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Mars probes are already returning stunning photos. NASA hopes to
find Martian life, either fossil or extant, and return samples of
it to Earth by 2008 for detailed analysis.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, scientists say, we may finally find ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four years ago, this wasn't a live issue,'' said
Sleep. ``Now everybody is thinking about the possibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS-LIFE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-13 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-LIFE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU WANT TO SEE A MARTIAN, LOOK IN THE MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good science often starts with flights of imagination that are
all but unknown publicly. That's because the creative process ends
in scientific reports cast to seem as dry and objective as
possible. All the same, history shows scientists driven by visions
not only wild in their own day, but sometimes still audacious.
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Kepler, who discovered that the planets move in
elliptical paths around the Sun, was motivated by a mystical love
of musical harmonies. Friedrich August Kekule, a founder of organic
chemistry, told of hitting on the ring structure of benzene after a
dream in which a snake curled itself into a loop. Ernest
Rutherford, inspired by the majesty of the solar system, proposed a
model of the atom in which electrons orbit around a central
nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   Today, science is toying quietly with the notion that all
terrestrial life came from Mars _ that we, in effect, are the
Martians.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that billions of years ago, life arose first on the
red planet, probably dotted back then with blue lakes and seas.
Cosmic collisions sent the alien slimes and microbes flying on
rocky debris through space like so many windblown seeds until they
fell to Earth and flourished, in time producing such specimens as
Monica Lewinsky and Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound goofy. But supporting evidence, if sketchy, has
been growing steadily for a decade. So Aliens ``R'' Us is a hot
topic. Scientists even plan to address the issue experimentally as
Mars probes costing many billions of dollars swing into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can tell, nearly everybody believes it's
plausible,'' said Joseph Burns, a planetary scientist at Cornell
University. ``Who knows? Maybe we are the little green men.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rummel, a top NASA biologist who explores the
extraterrestrial life issue, agreed. ``It's a fascinating
question,'' he said, adding that scientists in the next few years
may find that Martians and Earthlings are ``really the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The wilder dreams of science are seldom aired in public. When
they are, the unveiling tends to be done by superstars, not the
rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Sagan, the late astronomer and science author, in his 1994
book, ``Pale Blue Dot'' (Random House), asked gingerly if the
Earthly tree of life could have arisen from Martian seeds, if the
two planets ``regularly exchanged life-forms'' over the ages.
</P>
<P>
   So too, Francis Crick, the co-discoverer of DNA's structure, in
his 1981 book, ``Life Itself'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), broached the
more general idea that primitive life came to Earth from somewhere
in outer space, a notion known as panspermia.
</P>
<P>
   Behind such musings lies a problem of logic that has grown more
unsettling in recent years. The time appears to have been very
short between the end of the lethal bombardment of the young Earth
by all kinds of planetary crud and building blocks (the same blitz
that pockmarked the Moon) and the start of terrestrial life. By
some estimates, the two events were nearly simultaneous, leaving no
time for the slow twists and turns of biologic evolution. So
scientists often look to the heavens for answers.
</P>
<P>
   As a birthplace, Mars seems increasingly apt. Though cold and
dry today, it is thought to have been wetter and warmer long ago. A
growing number of scientists argue that it was far more habitable
than the early Earth, if only because its small size made it less
of a target for cosmic intruders big enough to wipe out all
rudimentary life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being out when the hunters are drunk,'' said Norman
Sleep, a geophysicist at Stanford University who sees Mars as the
cradle of life. ``You're better off being a rabbit than a deer.''
</P>
<P>
   Also wowing Mars fans is the discovery that cosmic smashups of
an ordinary sort have sent hundreds of tons of the distant planet
falling to Earth. Experts estimate that a Mars rock lands as often
as every three days, and that billions have done so over time _
even though only 13 of them have been identified so far.
</P>
<P>
   The rain of debris from Mars was hardest, experts agree, in the
Earth's early days. And the reverse trip was far less likely
because the Sun pulls Earth debris away from Mars and toward
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Burns of Cornell and his colleagues, using big computers to
track likely paths of Mars debris, made news in 1996 by showing
that the trek to Earth through the wilds of outer space could be as
short as a few months. ``We were stunned to see how easily this
material moves around,'' Burns remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists see other tantalizing clues. Some forms of
terrestrial life, they note, can withstand dangerously high levels
of radiation _ the main bar to unprotected life surviving the
rigors of outer space.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, scientists reported that Deinococcus radiodurans, a
microbe often found around nuclear reactors, could easily handle a
dose 3,000 times stronger than what would kill a human. A riddle is
why the microbe's skills evolved, since Earth apparently never
experienced such high levels of radiation. Could it be that it came
from somewhere in space where radiation is much higher?
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, scientists hope to settle the Aliens
``R'' Us question once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Mars probes are already returning stunning photos. NASA hopes to
find Martian life, either fossil or extant, and return samples of
it to Earth by 2008 for detailed analysis.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, scientists say, we may finally find ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four years ago, this wasn't a live issue,'' said
Sleep. ``Now everybody is thinking about the possibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
