<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, March 14, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Added to final budget: IRISH-POLS-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scheduled for the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   DOGS-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In cities and towns across the
nation, a chorus of politically influential voices cries out in
unison: Woof! From leash laws to legislation to curb dangerous
animals to regulations limiting the number of dogs per household,
canine questions are the new hot button of local politics. By
Douglas Martin. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ESPIONAGE-DIPLOMACY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Although the Chinese
nuclear spying scandal may have a big impact on U.S. politics, it
is not likely to have a significant effect on U.S. diplomacy with
China. Espionage is largely separate from mainstream foreign
policy, and, after all, all countries spy on each other. By Tim
Weiner. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   IRISH-POLS-REVIEW (Chicago) _ There seems to be truth in the
adage about the luck of the Irish, at least when it comes to
running for political office. As sure as the Chicago River runs
green for St. Patrick's Day, politicians with Irish names hold all
but a few of the major offices in Illinois. And of course, the sons
and daughters of Erin also do pretty well elsewhere in the country.
By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-LIFE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Science is toying quietly with the
notion that life on Earth evolved from microbes that arrived here
from Mars. That may sound goofy. But supporting evidence, if
sketchy, has been growing steadily for a decade. By William Broad.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DOLE-REVIEW (Des Moines) _ For all their individual
accomplishments, Elizabeth Dole and George W. Bush would not be
such hot tickets were it not for their pedigrees. But by distancing
themselves from their famous family members, they demonstrate the
complications _ the drawbacks as well as advantages _ of belonging
to political dynasties. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-HOUSE-PSYCH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some political
psychologists and political scientists recommend the appointment of
a White House shrink on call for presidents, their families and
senior staff members. The presidency is too important a job to be
deprived of easy access to professional psychological support. By
David Wallis.
</P>
<P>
   CADILLAC-RACING-REVIEW (Detroit) _ A look at the off-beat _ and
sometimes off-key _ efforts to build a new, sprier reputation for
Cadillac. The latest: Cadillac is building a race car to compete
next year at Le Mans, the venerable French race in which entrants
try to drive as many times around a track as possible in 24 hours.
By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-CORRUPTION-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the difficulties
at ferreting out corruption among labor union leaders. One reason
that some union leaders have been able to jack up their salaries to
excessive levels is that it is often hard for members to find out
exactly what those salaries are. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   JOB-TITLES-REVIEW (Washington) _ The Clinton administration may
have reinvented the federal work force by cutting nearly 400,000
lower-level jobs, but it has also reinforced an already top-heavy
bureaucracy with more layers of lavishly titled upper-level
officials. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK-INTERVIEW-REVIEW (Undated) _ Excerpts from a 1987
interview with Stanley Kubrick show that the reclusive filmmaker
was a man of colorful quotes.
</P>
<P>
   DIMAGGIO-INTERVIEW-REVIEW (Undated) _ Excerpts from interviews
with Joe DiMaggio indicate that the celebrity baseball hero was not
a man of colorful quotes.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-TRANSITION-REVIEW (Berlin) _ A correspondent's
impressions of Germany as it makes its way between the
contradictory tendencies of caution and risk-taking. It is today a
place in transition that tends to shatter preconceptions. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-REVIEW (Addis Ababa) _ Badme is an obscure town
in the highlands between Ethiopia and Eritrea. But lying on nearby
battlefields are the corpses of 10,000 soldiers who died over the
last month because each nation claims Badme and the surrounding
area as its own. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
