<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9102 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUBURBIA-FENCES-NYT &LR;      03-13 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBURBIA-FENCES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN IN SUBURBIA OVER THE GOOD SIDE AND THE BAD SIDE OF
FENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Fla., Texas)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a good side and a bad side to everything. Especially
fences.
</P>
<P>
   A new range war has broken out, this time on the suburban
frontier. As in days of old, it concerns fences _ specifically,
wooden stockade fences, which are growing in popularity and lend a
touch of Fort Apache to even the most unremarkable ranch home.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a pretty picture. Which is why, in shades of the tense
confrontation between fence-building homesteaders and cattle
ranchers in the movie ``Shane,'' the town board in Haverstraw,
N.Y., adopted a law last week that bars homeowners from installing
stockade fences so that the spiky unfinished side faces the
neighbors and the pretty, polished side faces the house. Outlaws
have 30 days to comply or face a $250 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very upsetting,'' said Denise Werlitz, a 45-year-old
insurance representative and unlikely villain of the dispute that
has come to roost on her fence, whose ``bad side'' faces out. ``I
feel, if I'm buying it, I should be able to see the nicer side of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Florence Jender, who lives down the block and whose own stockade
fence is placed nice-side-out, sees things differently.
``Aesthetically, it's not correct,'' she said curtly. ``For
niceness, and the property values, it should be the correct way.''
</P>
<P>
   Descendants of the fences that protected colonists against
Indians and marauding animals, stockade fences have been
proliferating in Haverstraw, about 35 miles northwest of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The ``offensive side'' of a stockade fence, as Garret Freeman,
the chief code enforcement officer for the town, calls it,
typically consists of horizontal rails and posts that support the
``good side,'' a series of pointed pickets, rounded mechanically to
mimic tree trunks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the earliest stockade fences, which were a fundamental
element of survival, today's rustic fences are usually bought for
privacy and, in Ms. Werlitz's case, to protect her yard from flying
debris from the road. Solid ``privacy fencing'' is flourishing in
high-density areas where ``people want to be the king of their own
little world,'' said Robert B. Shipley, the owner of Anchor Fence
in Rexford, N.Y. He estimates that 15 percent to 20 percent of his
residential sales are the stockade variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can fully appreciate how it could become an emotional
issue about personal rights,'' said Terry Dempsey, executive vice
president of the American Fence Association in Stone Mountain, Ga.,
which promotes ``fence-scaping'' the landscape and whose members
sell about 72,000 miles of fencing a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one tenet we have in America is that we all strive to be
good neighbors,'' he said. ``You wouldn't show exposed studs on the
outside of your house.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown in Haverstraw _ which resulted in the new local law
No. 2, an amendment to the zoning code _ came about because of the
increasing number of complaints about the brazen disregard of fence
etiquette, with at least a dozen offenders. Since the 19th century,
the fence has been viewed not only as a boundary but as a public
amenity. ``Just like we do in our families, the idea has been to
put the better face out in public,'' said Philip Dole, a professor
emeritus of architecture at the University of Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Installing a stockade fence the wrong way has a certain
historical irony. ``When you turn it around,'' said Shipley, ``you
offer your predator a ladder to get over your fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law in Haverstraw, similar to one in West Haverstraw
down the road, stipulates that fence posts be placed on the inside
of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're spite fences, in a sense,'' said Freeman, 56, the code
enforcer, a lifelong Haverstraw resident who cruises the territory
of mostly new, $250,000 to $300,000 Tudors and center-hall
Colonials in a decommissioned police car looking for offending
examples.
</P>
<P>
   His mission echoes the ``fence viewers'' of colonial New
England, who were appointed by towns to survey fences and fine
owners of damaged ones, which threatened the public peace with
unruly cattle. ``Would you want to look at this all the time?'' he
said, stopping at one of several egregious examples. ``It says, `To
hell with you and I don't care.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The number of similar laws appears to be growing, although their
exact number is unrecorded, said Kevin Crawford, the lawyer for the
Association of Towns, which represents 910 communities in the state
of New York. There are regulations on the books in other towns,
including Brecksville, Ohio, a suburb of Cleveland, and Satellite
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year in Altamont, N.Y., a suburb of Albany, the
village board passed a similar law prompted by a renegade stockade
fence in a subdivision. Walter Jensen, the Altamont building
inspector, called the reversed stockade fence ``an inconsiderate
act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People today profess to be kinder and gentler, just like
George Bush talked about,'' he added. ``But they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of Bush territory _ Tyler, Texas _ Larry Barbin,
owner of Barbin Fence Inc., a fence contractor, said that 90
percent of his customers for stockade fencing ask for the smooth
side facing them.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Clemens, the director of building and zoning for Clifton
Park, N.Y., also near Albany, where the majority of new homes are
in subdivisions, says privacy fences are ``a growing problem'' for
communities like his, which, unlike Tyler, are considering fencing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   To some, wrong-way fences, along with unmowed lawns and black
plastic sheeting anchoring a mountain of leaves, are part of what
John R. Stilgoe, a professor of landscape history at the Harvard
Graduate School of Design, called ``a collapsing code of visual
neighborliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Danielsen, director of residential policy for the Urban
Land Institute, a real estate research organization based in
Washington, said that there was a growing trend in middle-class
communities toward ``increasingly trying to exercise control over
their neighbors'' through formal ordinances more commonly
associated with master-planned and gated communities.
</P>
<P>
   Longer working hours, mobility and smaller families have
contributed to neighbors not knowing one another, she said. ``In
the past, they might have had a social relationship,'' she said.
``But today it's become difficult for people to face neighbors to
say something doesn't look pleasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Salkin, director of the Government Law Center at the
Albany Law School, says that for every person who erects a fence
for their children's safety, there is another ``going from the
garage to work, from work to the garage, barricading themselves
against the neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, the code enforcer, said he remembered the Haverstraw of
his youth, when lawns were vast expanses of greenery with no
fences, ``like one big backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   He also misses the days before people looked to code enforcers
to mediate squabbles. ``The kids solve their own problems, and the
parents hold grudges,'' he said. ``I tell them, `I'm not a
counseling agent. You've got to talk to each other.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1432EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
