<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9104 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-ZIMMER-AR     03-13 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-ZIMMER-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HALF CENTURY IN BASEBALL, AND ZIMMER STILL BREATHES IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The Christmas card list of Don and Jean Carol
Zimmer holds steady at about 300 and requires more than a month to
satisfy, for there has always been news to report in their 51 years
in baseball, and she can't help but write long notes.
</P>
<P>
   New friends are made each season. Others are lost in time. Merry
Christmas to Casey Stengel and Ted Williams; have a great New Year
to Jackie Robinson and Derek Jeter; happy holidays, Yogi Berra.
Season's greetings go out to the landlady who kept their boarding
room in 1951, and to George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' owner.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer seems to have known everyone and seen everything in
his half century in the game as a player, coach and manager, and
now, at 68, he is filling in for his close friend Joe Torre, the
Yankees' manager, who learned last week that he had prostate
cancer. No one knows whether it will be for three weeks or three
months, and Zimmer's mission is to maintain the culture Torre has
created.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer has always seized opportunity as a manager and as a
person; carpe diem. As the Yankees' bench coach, he spoke to Torre
in low tones during games, offering advice, and found that Torre
and he almost always agreed. Now he will speak to Torre before
games and follow his own instincts in crucial innings, knowing
Torre would probably take the same course of action.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer was there as a young infielder when the Brooklyn Dodgers
finally beat the Yankees in the World Series, in 1955. He played
with the 1962 Mets, arguably the worst team ever, and was a bench
coach for the 1998 Yankees, perhaps the best team ever.
</P>
<P>
   He played in Cuba before Castro, and with the Washington
Senators after Kennedy. When Carlton Fisk hit his home run to end
Game 6 of the 1975 World Series _ history's fall classic _ Zimmer
followed Fisk to home plate from the third-base coach's box,
jumping and hollering joyfully. When the Yankees finally beat
Boston in a one-game playoff to end the grueling 1978 pennant race,
Zimmer was managing the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer briefly retired before the 1996 season and received a
single Social Security check of about $1,000 _ the only money he
has made outside of baseball. ``I've lived a full life, I'll tell
you that,'' Zimmer said as he sat in the dugout here Friday,
staring forward, his arms rested on a baseball bat, Svengali in a
Yankees cap. ``How can a man have any better?''
</P>
<P>
   He is instantly recognizable to baseball fans and players:
Zimmer is thickly built, short and strong, with a round head and
prominent cheeks and small eyes that appear perfectly circular,
like dimes. When Zimmer is angry, his eyelids peel back and the
white around his eyes is revealed, and you know somebody is in deep
trouble; an umpire suggested Zimmer wasn't telling the truth a
couple of years ago, and, oh boy, the eyelids disappeared
completely.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmer's eyes are soft when he is with friends and trading
barbs. If he has a Charlie Brown head, then he has Snoopy's love of
life: Happiness is playing baseball with friends. He can tell many,
many stories. Joe Girardi, the catcher who has been with Zimmer on
three different teams, including the Yankees, said players look
forward to rain delays, when someone might ask Zimmer about Willie
Mays, or maybe Joe DiMaggio or Casey falling asleep in the dugout,
or breaking curfew or the day the Cubs fired him. Zimmer spills
over with anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Zim would change anything in his life,'' Girardi
said. ``He likes to have fun. He enjoys every minute on the field.
When he sees people who aren't enjoying it, he doesn't
understand.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer was already a major-league manager when Jeter was born,
and the hair that remains on his head is gray, but he mixes easily
with the players; he is fun to be around, and there is no
generation gap.
</P>
<P>
   He and third baseman Scott Brosius are bridge partners in a
season-long game against Girardi and outfielder Paul O'Neill.
Zimmer sits upright in a chair, his feet crossed underneath him,
glasses at the end of his nose, expressionless. Brosius finds
himself desperately trying to understand Zimmer's strategy, his
aggressive play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's intimidating as a partner _ I don't know what I'm doing
anyway, and I'm afraid I'm going to screw up the hand,'' said
Brosius, who teased Zimmer that his batting average probably was
200 points lower after they played because he was so mentally
drained.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to play, he likes to win; he shows emotion out
there,'' O'Neill said. ``He shows emotion in a card game. I like
that in him; I like Joe the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   All the details of Zimmer's lifetime are contained in the
scrapbooks his wife has kept since they were teen-agers, 65
scrapbooks in all. Born and raised in Cincinnati, Zimmer's idol as
a teen-ager was Pee Wee Reese, the star shortstop for the Brooklyn
Dodgers. He signed with the Dodgers and was a shortstop like Reese,
devoted to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He and Carol Jean Bauerle, his high school sweetheart commonly
known to everyone by her nickname Soot, married on the field before
a minor-league game in Elmira, N.Y., in 1951; once the ceremony
ended, Zimmer changed from his suit into his baseball uniform and
played, Soot and family and friends watching from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Hitters didn't bother with helmets when Zimmer began playing,
and he suffered a terrible beaning in 1953, going into a two-week
coma. To relieve swelling on his brain, doctors drilled holes in
his skull _ indentations that can still be seen. (Zimmer legend has
it that he has a metal plate in his head and sets off alarms at
security checkpoints in airports. Not so, said Mrs. Zimmer, adding
that the conventional wisdom is so prevalent that he doesn't bother
correcting it.)
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer learned how to walk and talk and play baseball again,
however, and broke into the majors the next year with the Brooklyn
Dodgers, with Reese guiding him. They remain the best of friends,
and Zimmer was supposed to see him last Wednesday, the day Torre
disclosed his illness to the entire team.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer bounced from Brooklyn to Los Angeles to the Chicago Cubs,
to the Mets and Cincinnati and Washington, playing 12 years in all.
He began managing in the minors in 1967, and in 1972 he took over
the San Diego Padres, in the first of his 13 years as a
major-league manager.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer managed the Red Sox from 1976-80, and in 1978, Boston won
99 games but surrendered a 14-game lead over the Yankees before
losing the one-game playoff on Bucky Dent's three-run homer. Zimmer
speaks of that season with relish, of the joy of going to the park
with so much on the line every day.
</P>
<P>
   He is still booed in Fenway Park for the outcome of that season,
many Red Sox faithful forever maintaining that Zimmer should've
rested his regulars more, should've trusted the maverick
left-hander Bill Lee _ the David Wells of his time _ in a crucial
game against the Yankees. But Zimmer apparently took the booing as
a natural extension of his job. When his grown daughter tearfully
told him that she hated to hear him berated, Zimmer suggested she
stop coming to the park.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer recalled how in 1981, the first year after the Red Sox
fired him and he was hired to manage the Texas Rangers, his team
opened the season in Boston. As Zimmer strolled to home plate to
exchange lineup cards with the new Red Sox manager, Ralph Houk, a
hurricane of boos followed, louder and louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a bad baseball town,'' Zimmer told the home plate
umpire, acting deadly serious. ``Can you believe how they're
treating a respected manager like Ralph Houk?''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer managed the Chicago Cubs until from 1988-91, coached from
1992-95 and then quit the game, intent on spending more time with
his grandchildren. After Steinbrenner hired Torre following the
1995 season, Torre asked Zimmer to coach for him, though the two
men knew each other only professionally, from opposing dugouts.
Once Zimmer and Torre agreed that Zimmer would always be encouraged
to offer opinions, Zimmer agreed to come out of retirement, and
after two weeks with Torre he told his wife that he had made the
right decision, that they would work great together.
</P>
<P>
   Neither realized they would become such good friends, sharing
mornings at a race track, playing golf and eating dinner, always on
the move; Torre once said that the best way to get a young player
in physical condition was to have him follow Zimmer around all day.
Torre constantly called Zimmer in the off-season, playfully
badgering him five times in one week from Maui in December, like
high school pals.
</P>
<P>
   Torre asked Zimmer early last week to take over in his absence.
Zimmer agreed, but he said he wouldn't use Torre's office, or ride
in his seat on the team bus or plane. Those will be left for his
friend. Zimmer nearly broke down Thursday when asked about his
feelings for Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends, that's what baseball has been about,'' said Zimmer,
the man whose name is on 300 Christmas cards every year. Best
wishes, Joe Torre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
