<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, March 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An important winter storm will begin to strengthen over the
southeastern states on Sunday, causing an area of snow, sleet and
rain to spread from the Ohio Valley into the Middle Atlantic
States. A wintry mixture will gradually taper off during the
morning and midday near the Ohio River as low pressure over
Tennessee transfers energy to a storm center in the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, wet snow and sleet will increase in intensity from
the mountains of Virginia and West Virginia to southern
Pennsylvania. Mainly rain will fall near the middle Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, clouds will increase from the northern
Appalachians to the New England coast. Snow will develop across
these areas late on Sunday and Sunday night as winds from the east
increase. The precipitation may mix with sleet and rain near the
coast by early Monday, but heavy snow accumulations are expected in
the interior.
</P>
<P>
   A band of strong thunderstorms will precede a cold front as it
moves across the eastern Carolinas and Florida. Onshore winds will
become gusty near the Carolina coast during the afternoon and
evening. In the wake of the front, breezes from the northwest will
deliver cooler and drier air. A few showers will linger over the
Tennessee and southern Mississippi valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and tranquil conditions will cover a large area from the
Plains into the Rocky Mountains. Meanwhile, a period of rain and
mountain snow will accompany a cold front in northern California.
Farther north, light showers will dissipate as drier air reaches
the northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: March Storms
</P>
<P>
   In much of the East, March storms can be the fiercest of the
winter season. Unlike midwinter tempests, March storms can draw on
the burgeoning warmth and moisture that gathers in the southern
states as spring approaches. Strong thunderstorms often result from
the clash of the sultry air with the remnant chill of winter. Snow
can be particularly heavy where the moisture-laden air is forced to
rise over cold air near the ground. The heat that is released when
the abundant moisture condenses into clouds and precipitation adds
further fuel to the storms, giving rise to widespread high winds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
