<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE'S TIE TO TURKEY TURNS CHILLIER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Relations between Turkey and the European
Union, which have been cool since the union left Turkey off a list
of prospective members more than a year ago, have now turned
frigid.
</P>
<P>
   The principal reason for the change, according to diplomats in
the Turkish capital, is the emotional debate that has erupted over
the imprisoned Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   After Ocalan was forced out of his hideout in Syria in October,
he spent nearly three months in Europe, most of it in Italy. Later
he was caught while living under the protection of Greek diplomats
in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders are outraged by Europe's willingness to harbor
Ocalan and by the refusal of the European Union to denounce him as
a terrorist, as Turkey and the United States have done.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, they have rejected warnings from the European
Union that they must give Ocalan a fair trial, saying they are
capable of doing so without being told. Turkey also has rejected
requests by the union and other foreign organizations to send
observers to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We of course abhor any attempts, no matter from what circles,
to interfere, to intervene in Turkey's internal affairs,'' Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit said at a recent news conference. ``We
couldn't accept it, and we couldn't discuss political matters with
the EU so long as our application for full membership, or at least
our candidacy, is not accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sharply worded statement, the Turkish Foreign Ministry
accused the European Union of hypocrisy for seeking to protect
Ocalan's human rights while failing to condemn Greece for harboring
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not possible to reconcile the silence of the EU about
this criminal collaboration with the principle of rule of law that
it advocates,'' the statement said. ``What is expected from the EU,
above everything, is that it should ask its member which has
shamefully violated international law to account for its behavior.
The credibility of the EU will remain seriously damaged unless it
acts in this way.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, diplomats from the European Union say they are
frustrated by Turkey's refusal to discuss matters that could lead
to an improvement in relations. They say that because Greece is a
member of the union, it is unrealistic for Turkey to expect the
union to issue an explicit condemnation of its actions.
</P>
<P>
   By rejecting political dialogue with the union, those diplomats
say, Turkey is pulling itself away from Europe. Some suspect that
is precisely what Ecevit, who has long been suspicious of Europe's
intentions toward Turkey, wants, and also what anti-Turkish
politicians in Europe want.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Turks say they are willing to talk to us about technical
matters like financing and development projects, but not about
political matters,'' said an ambassador from a European country.
``That doesn't work for us. When we talk to a country, we want to
discuss the full range of our concerns, which in the case of Turkey
means democracy, human rights, the Kurdish issue and, at this
point, the Ocalan trial. Since they refuse to do that, the dialogue
is practically frozen.''
</P>
<P>
   A new representative from Europe, Karen Fogg, took up her post
here in July and has been frustrated by this confrontation. She
previously held a similar post in Romania, which she said was
consumed with a pro-European fervor that sharply contrasts with
what she has found in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the Ocalan affair blew up, there was the possibility for
a slow rebuilding of the relationship, a chance for both sides to
develop some credibility and confidence,'' Ms. Fogg said in an
interview. ``But even for some time before that, we had been seeing
an unbelievable lack of interest. Everything is in a state of
suspended animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a kind of a circular pattern, with each side waiting
for the other to make the first move. They say, `What we need is
some encouragement, some sign that you're taking us seriously as a
candidate.' We say, `Can you show us one centimeter of progress and
stop being rude and act as if you want to be accepted?'
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find so sad here is the lack of enthusiasm,'' she
continued. ``It's quite different from what you see in Eastern
Europe, where people are focused entirely on getting into the EU
and are working on a hundred different fronts to do what they have
to do to get in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
