</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-BASQUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATISTS IN SPAIN RAGE OVER ARRESTS OF 17 BASQUES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID _ The arrest last week of the suspected military chief of
the Basque separatist group ETA, while the guerrillas were
observing a unilateral cease-fire, has provoked a storm of
criticism that the government might be squandering a chance to
negotiate an end to 30 years of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Basque nationalist politicians have called the arrests of 17
suspected guerrillas in France and Spain since Tuesday
``provocation.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of a week that also included some protests and
scattered violence, the peace effort was stalled. No one was
willing to pronounce it dead, however, and few predicted that the
rebels immediately would resume a campaign of shootings or
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The government responded to the criticism by saying that the
weakened guerrillas might now have even more reason to embrace
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our commitment to peace is permanent,'' said Prime Minister
Jose Maria Aznar. ``We have to work at it every day. I wish they
would do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a pro-independence Basque youth organization called
Jarrai urged its members to participate in a ``day of struggle''
that resulted in scattered firebombings and smashed windows. Five
people were injured, five others were arrested in various
disturbances and a Basque town councilwoman from the governing
conservative Popular Party received a package bomb which the police
defused.
</P>
<P>
   The round of arrests was the first crackdown since the ETA began
its cease-fire last September. The rebel leadership, which has made
its views known through communiques sent at night to Basque media,
was noticeably silent after the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Some terrorism experts say that ETA forces could be at very
reduced numbers. ETA, whose initials in Basque stand for Basque
Homeland and Liberty, is believed responsible for about 800 deaths
since 1968. The group is fighting for the independence of the
northern Basque region, home to 2.1 million people.
</P>
<P>
   The interior ministers of Spain and France met in Paris earlier
this month to analyze the rebels' rear guard in France.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of the suspected military leader, Jose Javier
Arizcuren, 40, came on Tuesday, four days after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He was apprehended in Paris just as the Spanish prime minister
arrived for a visit with French President Jacques Chirac and Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin. Aznar thanked them for ``very fruitful
cooperation'' against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Arizcuren is wanted for 10 killings and also for involvement in
a failed assassination plot in 1995 against Spain's king, Juan
Carlos, the Spanish authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Another suspect detained in Paris was Irantzu Gallestegui, 26.
She is wanted in the 1997 killing of Miguel Angel Blanco, a
conservative Basque town councilman. His death prompted about six
million Spaniards to march against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   As the arrests mounted and the police seized a home in southern
France containing more than 660 pounds of materials to make
explosives, the authorities said the rebels appeared to be making
preparations for possible attacks.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no known direct contacts during the cease-fire
between the government and ETA.
</P>
<P>
   The government maintains that the rebels must renounce violence
before peace talks can begin. But even then, a senior government
official said, there are sharp differences over what to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   The government, he said, wants to limit talks to rebel
disarmament and the fate of 461 rebels in Spanish jails and others
in exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have any political negotiations with ETA,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. But the rebels have
said talks would have to include the issue of Basque sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   With such a chasm, Sagrario Moran, a Madrid professor who wrote
a book about the ETA conflict, does not expect any talks until
after the general elections scheduled for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peace process is being used by all the political parties
as a tool, to get votes,'' Ms. Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   The leftist Euskal Herritarrok coalition, which is considered
close to the rebels, surged in Basque regional elections last
October after the cease-fire began, and for the first time became a
real power in the Basque Parliament. The Parliament, which was
established in 1980, is dominated by the moderate Basque
Nationalist Party, which favors independence if achieved
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Next June, the nationalists will battle the Madrid-based Popular
Party and the Socialists for town hall seats in the Basque region.
Along with its own Parliament, the region has taxing power and a
6,000-member police force.
</P>
</TEXT>
