<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-SCHOOLS-ART-2T     03-13 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-SCHOOLS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S NEIGHBORHOOD SCHOOL PLAN REKINDLES DEBATE OVER
DESEGREGATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nearly 25 years ago Jacqueline Johnson boarded a school
bus every school day to travel from her black neighborhood,
Roxbury, to a predominantly white school in another part of the
city, Jamaica Plain.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with three children of her own in Boston public schools
she eagerly hopes the city will end busing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have my child able to walk to school,'' Ms.
Johnson said. ``I think it's important that you have that sense of
community. I'd have more involvement in the school if it's close to
home.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ruth Batson was younger, but no less feisty, she was among
those black parents whose lawsuit resulted in extensive busing of
students. Today when she hears talk about the need to end busing in
favor of improved neighborhood schools, she shakes her head,
wondering if the city is giving up on integration and returning to
a time when black students were short-changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that hurts me the most is so many black people are
saying, `We don't have segregated schools any more. Let's move on.
Let's move on,''' Ms. Batson said.
</P>
<P>
   Race and public schools weigh heavily on Bostonians these days
as the city moves warily away from desegregation efforts that began
explosively in 1974 with a federal court order. Like many other
cities, Boston over the last 25 years has struggled to maintain
some measure of integration by sprinkling the dwindling number of
whites, who make up less than 20 percent of the students, around
the system.
</P>
<P>
   But in January, Mayor Thomas M. Menino announced a new effort to
build more schools in minority neighborhoods over the next six
years as part of a plan to allow more students to attend school
nearer their homes and thus reduce the need for busing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a much different city today than it was then,''
Menino said in an interview, referring to the pre-busing era.
``It's a much more integrated city; more people of color in every
neighborhood. So this is the time in our history when we've got to
make a decision to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   With Boston's 64,000 students performing poorly on standardized
tests and truancy rates there among the highest in the country,
school officials say the priority must be improving the system,
rather than integration.
</P>
<P>
   ``My issue is focusing on how to improve education for all
children in this city and not be distracted or have a lot of energy
and resources going into debates around student assignment,'' said
Thomas W. Payzant, the school superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts are not unique. Similar sentiments are growing
among black and white parents in a number of places, like Prince
Georges County, Md., where blacks constitute a majority of the
public school students.
</P>
<P>
   But such actions are particularly poignant in Boston, where in
response to Judge W. Arthur Garrity's 1974 order to integrate
schools, whites attacked school buses full of black children and
roughed up black bystanders. The trouble led some to label Boston
``the Little Rock of the North.''
</P>
<P>
   As the city inches back toward neighborhood schools, some now
worry that simmering racial antagonism will burst forth again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine came to work for the Boston public schools
two years ago from Milwaukee,'' said James W. Fraser, director of
the Center for Innovation in Urban Education at Northeastern
University here.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of her comments to me a short while after she started
working was that, `As soon as I start tapping the surface, it's
like desegregation happened yesterday. The issues, and the hurts
and the wounds and the feelings about it, are still so fresh.'''
</P>
<P>
   Boston is also an example of the continuing debate among blacks
over education strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Is it better to keep pressing for integration in the face of
schools that do not seem to improve, continued white resistance and
what some view as an increasingly hostile federal judiciary? Or is
it better to accept a possible resegregation of the system and
concentrate on improving schools in black neighborhoods?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not just change the inner-city schools, rather than just
bus our kids?'' Ms. Johnson asked. ``It doesn't make too much sense
to me for my kid to go way across town when they could upgrade the
schools for the children in inner-city areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, a federal appeals court ruled that the city had
complied with desegregation. Two years later, heeding Garrity's
order that they not lapse back into segregation, Boston school
officials allowed parents to choose any school within three large
zones in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a parent received their first choice depended on whether
the child's presence at that school would upset its racial balance
as determined by the demographics of that zone.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents say that the policy, known as ``controlled
choice,'' leads to a mad scramble for the available slots in the
better schools. Elementary schools like the Beethoven School in the
predominantly white neighborhood of West Roxbury consistently have
more applicants than schools that parents feel are inferior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fight among those in the know; those who know how to
work the system,'' said Jacqueline Rivers, a black educator who
served on a task force concerning student assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know how to work the system, you take what you
can get. The middle-class parents whose kids are still in the
system and the knowledgeable parents, that's who the fight is
among.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials say a 1995 study of the system by a management
consultant showed that nearly 80 percent of parents received their
first choice of schools. But the study noted that white parents
were much less likely to get their first choice than minority
parents were.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm a parent, I say I'd like to send my child to a
particular school in South Boston,'' said Councilwoman Peggy
Davis-Mullen, an opponent of busing. ``They look it up and say, `We
have five white seats and 15 minority seats.' If there are more
than five white kids in the school, they say, `We're sorry, we
don't recommend you try that school.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In November, a federal appeals court struck down the admission
program at Boston Latin School, the city's most prestigious public
high school. The court ruled that the policy of trying to reserve
some slots at the school to maintain a racial balance was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Boston Latin ruling, some busing opponents
say the school system's ``controlled choice'' policy is vulnerable
to a similar lawsuit charging it with maintaining an illegal system
of racial quotas in certain schools.
</P>
<P>
   To some black leaders, Boston appears to be moving toward a
system in which the students will be racially separated in schools
that are supposedly equal. They are not sure whether the move is
intended to improve schools or resegregate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not in vogue to have diversity,'' said Leonard Alkins,
president of the Boston Chapter of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People. ``Affirmative action and diversity
are being attacked on all levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some blacks who support the idea of improved neighborhood
schools worry that it might result in a system in which white
neighborhoods with more political power get more resources and
better teachers than minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That continues to be a real concern,'' Ms. Rivers said. ``It's
really going to take a level of vigilance among black and Latino
activists to make sure that our schools are not short-changed.
Menino has been pretty good. But he is a politician and the squeaky
wheel tends to get the oil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1459EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
