<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-TA-MOK-650(2     03-13 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-TA-MOK-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF TOP KHMER ROUGE, ONLY ONE AWAITS JUDGMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ In the end he was alone, the last fighter
left in the brutal three-decade-long Khmer Rouge insurgency. As his
colleagues surrendered and were embraced by the government, the
peasant general Ta Mok remained in the jungle, searching in vain
for a place to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Last week he was captured, apparently through a deal with Thai
military units that had given him sanctuary across the border.
Instead of the embrace that greeted his comrades after their
earlier surrenders, Ta Mok, a battlefield leader with a reputation
for cruelty, was locked inside a prison cell to await trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the harsh politics of Cambodia today, it is possible that Ta
Mok will in the end be the only Khmer Rouge leader called to
account for the deaths of more than a million people between 1975
and 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of the moment suggest that his Khmer Rouge
colleagues could be left free to enjoy a quiet retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Their fate is in the hands of Prime Minister Hun Sen, whose word
is law here. So far, he has resisted calls from abroad _ and from
many Cambodians _ for the arrests of such prominent Khmer Rouge
defectors as Khieu Samphan, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday Cambodia's foreign minister, Hor Nam Hong,
formally rejected a recommendation by the United Nations that a
score of Khmer Rouge leaders, including Ta Mok, be turned over to
an impartial international tribunal. Any trials, he said, would be
held here.
</P>
<P>
   The most hated Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot, died in April. For
the moment at least, it appears that the government hopes Ta Mok
will become his surrogate as the focus for recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ta Mok will be made a sacrificial animal, like the Gang of
Four in China,'' said Lao Mong Hay, a prominent human rights
advocate. ``If that happens, the issue of a Khmer Rouge trial and
the Khmer Rouge massacres and the Cambodian suffering will not have
been solved.''
</P>
<P>
   As much of the world moves toward accountability for past crimes
_ from the tribunals involving Rwanda and Bosnia to President
Clinton's apology this week for American actions in Guatemala _
Cambodia appears to be in full retreat, a diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't work just to say, `Let bygones be bygones,' '' he
said. ``Whether the leadership thinks so or not, it is in their own
country's interest to go through the painful process and confront
their past.''
</P>
<P>
   A radical Maoist movement, the Khmer Rouge caused huge numbers
of deaths when it evacuated Cambodia's cities and enforced brutal
work brigades in which people died from starvation, disease and
overwork. Many other Cambodians were killed in summary executions
and in a wave of internal purges.
</P>
<P>
   After they were driven from power by a Vietnamese invasion, the
Khmer Rouge regrouped as a jungle insurgency, continuing to enforce
Communist rule in areas they controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Ta Mok, 72, may have been an easy scapegoat. A rough-edged
peasant without the foreign education or intellectual pretensions
of other Khmer Rouge leaders, he could be harsh, savage and
capricious in his treatment of subordinates and enemies, according
to a number of accounts.
</P>
<P>
   He became known for his roughshod imposition of communal life in
Communist-controlled areas before 1975 and for his brutality
against his enemies within the movement. He was instrumental in
carrying out purges during the period of Khmer Rouge rule and has
been connected with the tortures of Tuol Sleng prison, where more
than 14,000 people were sent to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1996, when the largest Khmer Rouge-controlled region, in
Western Cambodia, had begun losing its ideological edge and living
a more relaxed capitalist life style, it was Ta Mok who tried to
lead a crackdown, causing the split that was the beginning of the
end for the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When, one year later, it seemed that Pol Pot's bad name was too
heavy a liability for the hard-pressed insurgency, it was Ta Mok
who engineered his ouster and arrest, then took over his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Openly disdaining politics, however, Ta Mok did not develop the
kind of constituency or relationships within and outside the
movement that helped his colleagues negotiate their surrenders.
</P>
<P>
   And those colleagues seemed happy, once they gave up the
struggle, to point their fingers at the man they had left behind
and blame everything on him.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stance that seems to suit Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Since the surrenders of Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea in December
_ followed by their government-sponsored visits to the beach and to
the temples at Angkor _ the prime minister has been carefully
ambiguous about his plans for them. He is keeping his options open,
holding at bay competing pressure groups and foreign interests.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been the most insistent voice abroad in
urging trials. On the other side, China _ the main sponsor of the
Khmer Rouge in past years _ is expected to veto any plan for an
international tribunal that might come before the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Hun Sen has avoided definitive statements,
leaving political analysts here to debate whether his bottom line
ultimately is to punish his longtime Khmer Rouge enemies or to
dodge the uncertainties of full-fledged trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bottom line is, whatever is in Hun Sen's
interest,'' a Western diplomat said. ``So I don't think anything is
written in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Several foreign diplomats and Cambodian analysts agreed that
Hun's basic goals are to avoid instability and renewed fighting, to
maintain personal control of events and to block any revival of
Khmer Rouge power.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister has warned of what he calls a new civil war
if he tries to arrest Khmer Rouge leaders who now live mostly in
remote areas that are controlled by their own troops. Those
soldiers have nominally defected to the government, although this
may in effect be little more than a change in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Hun Sen has chosen not to agree to an
international tribunal, a forum that would reduce his ability to
manage the course of events. Instead, he appears bent on trying Ta
Mok in a Cambodian court, despite the fact that he once admitted
that Cambodia's judiciary is not up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   In a report this month to the United Nations, a team of three
international lawyers said they doubted that the Cambodian legal
system had the expertise or political independence to conduct a
procedure that would be seen as just.
</P>
<P>
   They recommended against a domestically run trial, saying
Cambodia lacked ``three key criteria for a fair and effective
judiciary: a trained cadre of judges, lawyers and investigators;
adequate infrastructure, and a culture of respect for due
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, they said, ``the level of corruption in the
court system and the routine subjection of judicial decisions to
political influence would make it nearly impossible for
prosecutors, investigators and judges to be immune from such
pressure in the course of what would undoubtedly be very
politically charged trials.''
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat said he could already foresee the outcome of
a trial for Ta Mok.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be found guilty, of course,'' the diplomat said. ``I
think that has been decided already. There is no death penalty in
Cambodia, so he will be sentenced to life. Maybe at first he will
go to jail. Then he will move to house arrest in some military
camp. And then five years from now people will say, `What ever
happened to Ta Mok?' and you'll discover that he's living in a nice
villa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
