<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9122 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-NATO-ART-1STLD     03-13 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NATO-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO TRIES TO SMOOTH TIES TO RUSSIA BEFORE 50TH ANNIVERSARY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (repreating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If NATO's diplomats get their way, next month's 50th
birthday party in Washington will be replete with post-Cold War
symbolism, featuring top Russian officials in its large cast to
demonstrate just how well the old enemies now work side by side.
</P>
<P>
   There is just one small problem: Russia has not yet decided if
it wants the part.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin, playing as hard to get as ever, says it might
dispatch a senior representative to the celebration _ but only if a
rupture is avoided over Kosovo and limits are put on the number of
alliance troops that can be rushed during any crisis to Poland, the
Czech Republic or Hungary, who joined NATO on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years after NATO and Russia sealed a much-advertised
cooperation agreement, the two sides are still refighting old
battles over the enlargement of the Western alliance. Despite the
obvious weaknesses of Russia's military machine, its nuclear muscle
and the superpower mentality of its foreign-policy elite seem
destined to ensure that those battles grow no-less rancorous with
time.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to reassure a Russia still unhappy about NATO's
enlargement, NATO has confidentially proposed to limit crisis
deployments to bolster Poland, the Czech Republic or Hungary. The
two divisions that could be dispatched to each of these nations
under the Western plan would be equivalent to a light army corps
with about 460 tanks. The Russians, though, want to limit such
deployments to a division or even less.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian strategy, however, is to undermine NATO
effectiveness,'' said Sergei Karaganov of the Council on Foreign
and Defense Policy, a group of opinion makers with close ties to
the Russian government and military circles. ``We want to have NATO
as weak as possible because we are not part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the NATO-Russian relationship is troubled. NATO and
Russian officials meet regularly in Brussels over security policy,
and the two sides conduct joint peacekeeping patrols in Bosnia. But
the two sides have yet to establish a genuine partnership _ and the
future of the relationship looks anything but rosy.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is not only trying to blunt any military advantage the
alliance derives from now admitting Poland, the Czech Republic and
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Its longer-term strategy is to discourage the alliance from
trying to include the Baltic states _ Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania
_ or other former Soviet-bloc nations by making the process as
diplomatically painful as possible _ an approach Western officials
call the ``root canal'' strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's anxiety over NATO, by and large, is a preoccupation of
its political elite. Virtually nobody in Russia is happy about the
alliance's decision to accept new members. But the issue ranks
relatively low on the average citizen's long litany of worries, a
list dominated by domestic concerns like soaring prices, unpaid
wages and crime.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively modulated response of the public is important
because it makes it unlikely that a rabid nationalist could rise to
power on a surge of anti-NATO resentment, the calamity many critics
of NATO expansion said they expected.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls also show that popular unease over NATO is
along generational lines _ the young are far less worried than
elderly Russians who lived through the Cold War _ and thus may fade
in time.
</P>
<P>
   But if NATO expansion has not changed the face of Russian
domestic politics, it has contributed to the sourness of the West's
diplomatic relations with Russia, already under stress from
disputes over Iraq, the former Yugoslavia and arms control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign policy is always a preoccupation of the elites,'' said
Aleksei Arbatov, a member of Parliament from the liberal Yabloko
party and an acerbic critic of NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the West's diplomacy over the last few years has been
aimed at preventing the bitterness that Russian politicians feel
over NATO's expansion from bubbling over.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to ease Russian worries, NATO negotiated a 1997 accord
with Russia, called the Founding Act, which set the terms of NATO
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that accord, the West indicated it had no plan, need
or intention to permanently station a substantial number of NATO
combat forces on the territory of its new members or to keep
nuclear weapons there. But the West stopped short of making that a
binding, legal commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also established a new NATO-Russian council, a
panel the Western alliance touted as a sign that Moscow was
adjusting itself, however painfully, to the realities of an
expanded NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the accord signaled little more than a temporary truce.
That is hardly surprising, for the debate also reflects Moscow's
deeper resentments over its loss of superpower status and over
American willingness to use its power in Iraq and Yugoslavia in the
face of Russia opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is not Poland, the Czech Republic or Hungary,''
said Toby T. Gati, a former assistant secretary of state in the
Clinton administration. ``The real issue is American power. What
the Russians do not like is that there is one country which has the
capability to act by itself and direct an alliance. NATO expansion
is not the defining issue, though it has left the Russians with a
bad taste.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's decision to expand, for example, is not the main
reason the Russian Parliament has yet to approve the Start II
strategic arms treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to ratify the accord has more to do with the U.S.
decision to bomb Iraq in December _ an attack that took place just
days before the accord was to be taken up by Russia's Parliament _
and President Clinton's surprise move to press ahead with the
testing and development of anti-missile systems.
</P>
<P>
   Even without NATO expansion, it is probably unlikely that Moscow
and Washington would be working in lock step, say, to thwart Iran's
nuclear ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even Russian politicians who support reforms say the move
has taken its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means the further isolation of Russia and has led to a
tendency here to be more critical of the United States,'' said
former Finance Minister Boris Fyodorov, a supporter of capitalist
reforms who is much admired in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been too weak to stymie the alliance's expansion
plans, but it has sought to fight a rear-guard effort. On Kosovo,
the Russians have insisted that no airstrikes be carried out
without the approval of the U.N. Security Council, where they hold
a veto.
</P>
<P>
   And President Boris Yeltsin personally warned the Americans to
keep their hands off Kosovo _ a warning that has psychologically
bolstered the Serbs in their refusal to accept NATO ground troops
in their battle-torn province.
</P>
<P>
   In Vienna, where negotiators from 30 nations are trying to
update the old East-West treaty limiting non-nuclear arms, the
Russians are seeking to blunt NATO by limiting the Western combat
forces that can be dispatched to the territory of its new members.
</P>
<P>
   Having promised not to station any permanent large contingent of
combat forces in Poland, the Czech Republic or Hungary as part of
the Founding Act, NATO says it needs the right to rush as many as
two combat divisions to any or each of those nations if a crisis
breaks out. The proposal for such emergency deployments is based on
a classified assessment of military requirements by NATO military
commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sort of scenario we have in mind is a crisis short of
major aggression against the alliance, where all bets would be
off,'' a senior Western diplomat said. ``Let's say there was a
Serbian threat against Hungary. Then we want to be able to
reinforce. It might be hypothetical today, but it could become very
real if there was a Serbian decision to lash out at the
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Russians have insisted that the ceiling be set at one
division or even a brigade. They have informed NATO that they will
not send a top level representative to the Washington summit talks
if this matter is not worked out or if the two sides are at odds
over Kosovo, American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials say that Russia and NATO may yet come to terms
on the force limits. To make the West's proposal more palatable,
for example, the United States is privately encouraging Poland to
cut 200 more tanks from its arsenal than it had previously planned,
something Western officials say Poland can do by getting rid of old
models in storage.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has also told the Russians that it is willing to relax
limits on the number of Russian armored personnel carriers on its
southern flank, a region that greatly concerns Russia, as it
includes the volatile Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   And a number of senior diplomats, including Foreign Minister
Robin Cook of Britain, have assured Moscow that the alliance will
not use the Washington meeting to issue a new flurry of invitations
to potential NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this will be enough to induce Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov or Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov to make the Washington
trip, as the Clinton administration would like, is still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely to change the basic stance among Russian
foreign-policy specialists toward the alliance. Sergei Rogov, the
director of the U.S.A.-Canada Institute, a research center on
Russian-Western relations, said it was possible the two sides could
learn to work together effectively, but added he was not
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that NATO is enlarging despite our objections and is
claiming the role of the dominant security organization in Europe
is perceived here as a negative,'' Rogov said. ``We are being
marginalized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1507EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
