</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NATO (Moscow) _ Almost two years after NATO and Russia
sealed a much-advertised cooperation agreement, the two sides are
still refighting old battles over the enlargement of the Western
alliance. Despite the obvious weaknesses of Russia's military
machine, its nuclear muscle and the superpower mentality of its
foreign-policy elite seem destined to insure that those battles
grow no-less rancorous with time. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-NATO (Berlin) _ With Poland, the Czech Republic and
Hungary now in NATO, Germany finds itself surrounded by allies for
the first time since it was unified in 1871. And the benefits have
been immediate. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-POWER (United Nations) _ In a world with conflicts raging
from Angola to Kosovo, the United Nations Security Council, the
heart of the world body, finds itself increasingly marginalized. By
Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-TA-MOK (Phnom Penh) _ In the harsh politics of Cambodia
today, it is possible that the peasant general Ta Mok will in the
end be the only Khmer Rouge leader called to account for the deaths
of more than a million people between 1975 and 1979. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-UNTOUCHABLES (Shanker Bigha) _ In one of India's poorest
and most populated states, nearly three decades of massacres have
been aimed at keeping low caste Indians in line. By Celia W.
Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-BANZER (La Paz, Bolivia) _ While Chile's Gen. Augusto
Pinochet awaits his fate in London, another of Latin America's
former dictators, Hugo Banzer of Bolivia, now the country's elected
president, is also coming under scrutiny for his part in a ``dirty
war'' against leftists in the 1970s. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-BASQUES (Madrid) _ The arrest last week of the suspected
military chief of the Basque separatist group ETA, while the
guerrillas were observing a unilateral cease-fire, has provoked a
storm of criticism that the government might be squandering a
chance to negotiate an end to 30 years of violence. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-AIR-LINK (Berlin) _ Can a city claim to be the ``capital
of Europe'' without a direct air link to the United States? By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-SUICIDE (Dublin) _ Young Irish men have one of the
fastest rising rates of suicide in the world. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANT-TEENS (New York) _ Over the last several years, a
small but growing number of teen-agers _ virtually all boys, some
as young as 14 or 15 _ have arrived without their parents, much
like the child immigrants of a century ago. Once here, they become
New York's youngest immigrant workers, their cheap, nimble labor
easily absorbed by the city's thriving service economy. On their
own, they are free as birds, and yet they are trapped in an
underground ruled in large measure by fear _ of the immigration
authorities, child welfare agencies, smugglers, thugs and bosses,
past and potential. And immigration scholars and social workers
wonder if they will ever be able to break free. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   APPEALS-FAIRNESS (Fort Myers, Fla.) _ A crushing load of cases
is reshaping the federal appeals courts, second in importance only
to the U.S. Supreme Court, creating a two-level justice system in
which tens of thousands of appeals get limited review so judges can
focus on those they consider significant. By William Glaberson.
With art.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBIA-FENCES (Undated) _ A new range war has broken out, this
time on the suburban frontier. As in days of old, it concerns
fences _ specifically, wooden stockade fences, which are growing in
popularity and lend a touch of Fort Apache to even the most
unremarkable ranch home. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-RECALLS (Undated) _ Contamination of hot dogs and cold cuts
by a sometimes deadly bacterium _ a germ that is little known by
the public _ has led to an extraordinary series of recalls in
recent months, as well as increased government action to detect the
problem sooner and prevent it. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-SCHOOLS (Boston) _ As Boston inches back toward a new
effort to build more schools in minority neighborhoods, some worry
that simmering racial antagonism will burst forth again. By Steven
A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN-MAFIA (Los Angeles) _ The authorities here have turned
their sights once again on la Eme, known as the Mexican Mafia, one
of California's oldest and still most powerful prison gangs,
charging its members with waging a brutal campaign for control of
Southern California's gangs and drug trade. By Christian
Berthelsen.
</P>
<P>
   UNABOMBER-LINCOLN (Lincoln, Mont.) _ Theodore J. Kaczynski won
national notoriety as the Unabomber, but in this mountain village
nestled in pine forests below the Continental Divide, new detective
work is giving him a new notoriety: as a pioneer for environmental
sabotage. By James Brooke. With art.
</P>
<P>
   ROAD-KILL-BILL (NASHVILLE, Tenn.) _ If only the bill had
contained the word ``deer,'' then perhaps the possum jokes could
have been stopped flat. But no. Instead, the author phrased it this
way: ``Wild animals accidentally killed by a motor vehicle may be
possessed by any person for personal use and consumption.'' In
other words, it would be legal to eat road kill. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   PEACH-EXTRACT (Washington) _ Federal researchers discover that a
fragrant, nontoxic extract of peach pits can replace methyl
bromide, a widely used, toxic pesticide that destroys the earth's
protective ozone layer. U.S. farmers are so dependent on methyl
bromide to fumigate strawberry and tomato fields (among other uses)
that they persuaded Congress last year to delay its phase-out,
which was required by the Clean Air Act and the Montreal Protocol
to protect the ozone layer. Although the peach extract may not
answer all the farmers' needs, its discovery illustrates a new
approach of biological prospecting that is shaping the future of
agriculture, industry and medicine. By John Cushman. With art.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bob Herbert on how two moderate
Republicans _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and the late Supreme Court
Justice Harry Blackmun _ approached the issue of abortion.
</P>
