<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-840&AMP;ADD-     03-13 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW TALKS ON KOSOVO, NATO'S CREDIBILITY IS AT STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With KOSOVO-BOMBING) 
 (DW) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ When peace talks on Kosovo resume here on Monday, not
only the fate of the province's two million people but also the
credibility of European diplomacy and the NATO military alliance
will hang in the balance, European and American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   France and Britain, who are leading the talks, plan to give
Serbian and ethnic Albanian negotiators only two to three days to
accept an international peace plan for autonomy in Kosovo worked
out last month or face the consequences, according to allied
officials.
</P>
<P>
   But allied resolve hangs on final acceptance of the plan by
Albanian military commanders who have been battling with Serbian
forces for independence of the southern Serbian province, where 90
percent of the population is ethnic Albanian. The proposed accord
offers Kosovo autonomy for the next three years, and leaves its
fate after that uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   A key Kosovo Liberation Army negotiator, Hashim Thaci, said
before leaving for Paris Saturday, ``The definitive answer will be
given in Paris.'' Other Albanian delegates have said the answer
will be ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Albanians do sign the deal by Monday, officials say, then
the Serbs will be confronted with a clear NATO ultimatum: Accept
the plan within two or three days, and some 26,000 allied
peacekeepers to enforce it, or risk an allied bombing campaign that
could wipe out much of Serbia's sophisticated air defenses and
other sensitive targets within a week.
</P>
<P>
   But less than 48 hours before the talks were to start, the
Albanians still had not signed, and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic had not budged from rejection of numerous appeals by
European, American and Russian officials to agree to take the
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to focus all the pressure we can on Milosevic, and
that is handicapped without a clear Albanian `yes,' '' a senior
NATO diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators from Yugoslavia, of which Serbia is the dominant
component, agreed to provisions restoring autonomy to Kosovo that
were worked out in last month's talks in Rambouillet outside Paris,
which broke off on Feb. 23. But Milosevic has insisted that 2,000
unarmed civilian observers who have been monitoring an unsuccessful
cease-fire in Kosovo since last October would be enough to
supervise a new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   These observers would have to be evacuated before any bombing
started, allied military commanders say. The official in charge of
the observers, William Walker, told allied officials in Brussels
Saturday that they could be evacuated in 8 to 12 hours, but only if
Serbian forces did not try to prevent them from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's no resolution, and we go in with air strikes, I'm
afraid this will end NATO's relationship with the Russians,'' an
allied official in Brussels said, ``but if we don't go with air
strikes, then NATO loses its credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Milosevic, who as Serbia's leader a decade ago abolished
autonomy for Kosovo, would back down after an initial salvo or
brave a complete phased campaign against his air defense system is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials, starting with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, were taken by surprise by the reluctance of the Albanian
armed rebels to settle for an agreement that would require them to
disband, but ensure an armed international presence for at least
three years to keep Serbian security forces mostly out of the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's personal involvement in the Rambouillet talks is now
regarded by American and European officials as a risky gamble that
backfired.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Solana, the alliance's top civilian leader, was given
authority at the end of January to launch a two-phase bombing
campaign against the Serbs, but only if they were the main obstacle
to ending a year of fighting that has killed an estimated 2,000
people and driven 200,000 others from their homes in the province.
</P>
<P>
   If the Albanians come to the table Monday but will not sign,
European and American officials say, Solana is unlikely to order
the air armada into action. The air power ranged against Serbia
includes American cruise missiles launched from Navy ships in the
Adriatic, hundreds of fighter-bombers based in Italy, and even
B-52s operating from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   If the alliance was paralyzed by Albanian refusal to sign, a
threat already devalued by Milosevic's violation of terms he agreed
to last October would evaporate. But French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine has told allied officials that if the warring parties are
not ready to make peace, international negotiators may have to let
them fight it out.
</P>
<P>
   New fighting in the past week, allied officials say, has created
another 10,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials in Brussels said that they already had moved
10,000 troops, the vanguard of the prospective force, into
neighboring Macedonia. Some 26,000 soldiers could start fanning out
across Kosovo within a week of any agreement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The allies would like to include Russian troops among the
peacekeepers if they do go in. But officials in Brussels said that
Russia was objecting to putting them under NATO command. Plans for
the force would put the peacekeepers under a British general, Sir
Michael Walker, with a French deputy. The entire force would have
14,000 French and British troops and 4,000 Americans, and Walker
would report to NATO's Supreme Allied Commander, Gen. Wesley K.
Clark, an American.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, speaking to French military officials in Paris Saturday,
said, ``We're at a very dangerous position in this situation.''
Serbian forces in Kosovo, he said, were now seven to eight times
more than the level Milosevic had agreed to last October.
</P>
<P>
   With the final outcome of talks uncertain, Vedrine and his
co-chairman, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, have not
announced whether they would be in attendance when the negotiators
reconvene Monday morning in a French government conference center
near the Arc de Triomphe.
</P>
<P>
   The building was the site of talks between the United States and
Vietnam that produced an agreement allowing American withdrawal in
1973. Earlier, when the building was the Hotel Majestic, it was the
German military headquarters for occupied France from 1940 to 1944.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
