<HEADER>
A9144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      03-13 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn.: Minn., Utah, Calif., N.Y., Iowa, N.H., Wyo., Colo., Idaho,
Mont., Ariz., Nev., N.M., Fla.) 
A MIDWEST LAB FOR CAMPAIGN REFORM  PLAN TO PUT ROCKIES ON THE
PRIMARIES MAP NEWEST BALLOT BOX: PERSONAL COMPUTER?  (jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably no state has done more than Minnesota to overhaul its
campaign finance laws. And a major part of the change is the system
the state has set up for holding down campaign giving and spending.
</P>
<P>
   As the federal government does for presidential candidates,
Minnesota helps pay some of the campaign costs of candidates for
state office who agree to limit spending. It partially reimburses
voters who contribute to such candidates. And it allows taxpayers
to check a box on the Minnesota income tax form that authorizes the
state treasurer to send $5 to the party of the taxpayer's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a system we think others should take a look at,'' said
Gary Goldsmith of the Minnesota Campaign Finance and Public
Disclosure Board. ``A typical cap would be $24,000 for a
legislative race, with the state putting up perhaps a third of
that. Our campaigns don't cost the absurd hundreds of thousands of
dollars that you see elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The checkoff box also gives parties a good status check each
spring.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this point, only about 650 taxpayers had checked
the Reform Party box. But so far this year, according to the
Minnesota Department of Revenue and the campaign finance board,
more than 4,600 taxpayers have checked that box, a solid indication
that the political upheaval that swept the Reform candidate Jesse
Ventura into the governor's office last fall has plenty of
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republicans, the checkoffs are up slightly, to 4,800 now
compared with 4,200 a year ago. For the Democratic-Farmer-Labor
Party, they have fallen sharply to 5,600, compared with 8,500 a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic-Farmer-Labor leaders insist their
parties are holding their own and are raising ample money through
other means, like direct mail. In fact, these leaders say the
outlook for public financing of Minnesota elections may not be
quite as bright as state officials say, since the number of
taxpayers filling in a checkoff box has slipped to 8.2 percent from
11.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes more than public money to build a political party,''
said Tony Sutton, executive director of the Minnesota Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   PLAN TO PUT ROCKIES ON THE PRIMARIES MAP
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Rocky Mountain states have watched with envy as
others have taken the lead in nominating presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt, a Republican, is making some headway
in changing that.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out that the region is among the fastest growing in the
country, Leavitt is pressing for a Rocky Mountain primary early in
the primary season, when most of the action now is. He argues that
if all eight Rocky Mountain states hold their primaries on the same
date, the region will rival the nominating influence of California
or New York or another regional group.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Leavitt signed a bill authorizing the state's
major parties to hold primaries next March 10, and once again urged
other Rockies states to follow.
</P>
<P>
   As he sees it, a March 10 Rocky Mountain primary in 2000 would
make the region the ``linchpin'' between two big batches of
primaries that have deliberately been scheduled to follow closely
the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary. The first batch,
set for March 7, includes California and New York; the second, set
for March 14, includes mainly Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven other states that Leavitt wants to hook up with,
Wyoming's Legislature has approved a March 10 primary and similar
bills have a good possibility of passage in Colorado, Idaho and
Montana. Question marks hang over Arizona, Nevada and New Mexico,
where some lawmakers say changing to a common voting date will be
politically disruptive or too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   NEWEST BALLOT BOX: PERSONAL COMPUTER?
</P>
<P>
   Everything else, it seems, is on the Internet. So why not online
voting?
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is looking at the possibility for military
personnel overseas. Florida is pondering the possibilities at home.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes California, home of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The state actually tried computer voting in a recent election,
and next week a study panel of election and technology experts will
take a long look at whether balloting by computer is a way to make
voting easier, thereby slowing, or even reversing, the decline in
turnout in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest questions?
</P>
<P>
   According to the head of the study group, Secretary of State
Bill Jones, security and computer availability loom largest,
especially questions about how to register voters, how to check the
validity of their votes if cast from home or work and how to keep
prying eyes from seeing and identifying votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If security and access can be resolved, then online voting
might be one way to help improve voter participation,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have been talking about experimenting with
computer voting as early as next year. Florida has also been
talking about setting up a test next year.
</P>
<P>
   Many technology experts say a secure computer voting system can
readily be designed. A bigger question, they say, is whether the
public will accept it and whether politicians who prefer to run in
low-turnout elections will go along.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the cyberballoting that California already tried?
</P>
<P>
   When Piedmont, just east of Oakland, held a special election
this month, voters found computerized touch-screens at the polling
places.
</P>
<P>
   They liked them, election officials report. So did the
officials. The tally at the end of the day took just minutes, not
hours as in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1526EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
