<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHILD-DEATHS-NYT &LR;      03-13 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: THIS CLUB HAS A PREREQUISITE _ LOSS OF A CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAUGERTIES, N.Y. _ One night five years ago, when Gabriel Swart
was 21 and a senior at the State University of New York in Buffalo,
he got into a friend's car. The friend was drunk, but only Gabriel
was killed in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Clark was 26 and driving home when she was hit head on by
a driver with a suspended license. She would have been 33 last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel and Angela have been dead for years, but their parents
still meet once a month to talk about their loss, to comfort one
another and the grieving parents of other children lost to car
accidents, to cancer after years of suffering or to an exploding
aneurysm in the brain. Even years later, they join in groups to
mourn together.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, this should not be surprising. Americans are great
joiners, always have been. They join associations based on cars or
the Irish county where some ancestor was born; they join bowling
leagues and neighborhood committees. But what comfort can a group
of strangers offer a parent in the howling agony of a lost son or
daughter? Isn't grief at that level too deep to share beyond the
circle of family and old friends?
</P>
<P>
   For Gabriel's parents, Richard and Nina Swart, and for Angela's,
Ed and Mary Lou Clark, the answer is that those of us who stand
outside the circle of loss are the strangers, and that other bereft
parents are a new kind of family.
</P>
<P>
   In the company of sorrow, the Clarks and the Swarts first
received and then, years later, began to dispense the answers to
the questions each parent who has lost a child asks: When will I
get better? When will I start to live again? Am I going crazy?
</P>
<P>
   The name of their organization is the Compassionate Friends _
``the club nobody wants to be eligible for,'' Swart said with
bitter humor. And far from being a refuge for only a handful, it
has dozens of chapters around the country and all the trappings of
American organizational efficiency: Web sites, videos, brochures,
telephone trees.
</P>
<P>
   The Swarts and the Clarks belong to the Mid-Hudson Valley
Chapter, whose members live in small towns connected by the winding
Catskill roads that have claimed many of their children. Ulster
County has less than half the population of Staten Island in New
York City but recorded the same number of traffic deaths in 1997:
14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going to the Albany meeting for the first time and
seeing 50 people and thinking, `God, there are so many of our
children dying,''' said Mrs. Clark, who runs a housecleaning
service. ``And then when we formed the circle and we each started
telling our stories, I realized how much we all had in common.''
</P>
<P>
   But suppose, these parents were asked, that a rude person who
stood outside the circle of loss were to say, ``Hey, I know it was
terrible but this was years ago _ get over it, focus on the kids
you still have, get on with your life.'' What would they say?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea,'' replied Mrs. Swart, operator of a day-care
center. ``You would not even get close to knowing what it is
like.''
</P>
<P>
   The distance between the bereft and everyone else can be so
great that the Swarts and the Clarks have had to reorder their very
understanding of friendship. ``Some old friends are confused by
what happened and you see them cut across the street to avoid us,''
Swart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We become toxic,'' said his wife. ``But then there are others
who you wouldn't expect too much from, yet who step up and help you
in the most wonderful way,'' Swart added.
</P>
<P>
   So in the comfort of their circle, the Compassionate Friends
discuss coping strategies. Clark, a retired military man, likes
nature and long walks, while his wife is likely to zone out in
front of the television. They talk about what to avoid in the
media: the TV show ``E.R.''; the Robin Williams movie ``What Dreams
May Come,'' for its depiction of suicides damned to hell; anything
in the oeuvre of Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   They discuss the problem of family videos. Some people watch
movies of their lost children over and over, but Clark isn't yet
ready to see Angela on old tapes. Mrs. Swart recently started
taking out old pictures of Gabriel, but Swart doesn't want to look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
