<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOMBINGS-435&AMP;A     03-13 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOMBINGS-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB IN KOSOVO MARKET KILLS 5 AS LEADERS LEAVE FOR PARIS TALKS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also KOSOVO-TALKS) 
(jw) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Serbia _ Three powerful bombs exploded Saturday in
northern Kosovo, tearing into people on a market day, killing at
least five people and wounding dozens just as leaders of the
province's ethnic Albanian majority departed for Paris peace talks
with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The dead included two children. More than 60 people were
injured, some seriously, when two bombs detonated within half an
hour of each other in the town of Podujevo, and another exploded an
hour later in the nearby town of Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs mark an escalation in the conflict in Kosovo, where
the worst city violence to date in a yearlong war has been drive-by
shootings or grenades thrown into cafes. Saturday's bombs, placed
in public places at the busiest time, were apparently designed for
an effect of maximum terror.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours after the explosion in Mitrovica, the bodies of two
women and a 3-year-old child, still lay amid bloody debris of
smashed market stalls, broken eggs, crushed lettuce and spilt
apples and oranges. Blood marked the pavement where people had
dragged the wounded to cars. A 12-inch bomb crater gaped in the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb went off just after 2 p.m. local time, witnesses said.
Agim, an 18-year-old cigarette seller who gave only his first name,
was just 20 paces away, across the road, when the bomb went off.
``I was dazed, at a loss. Then I saw an old man with a wounded leg.
Then I went closer to help and saw that poor woman and her child
next to her. There was another 5-year-old child still moving. I
took him and gave him to a man to take to hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Agim said people ran, screaming and crying, afraid there was
another bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Police cordoned off the area and chalked round spots on the
ground scattered with shrapnel. A foreigner assisting in the
investigation said the bomb seemed to have been placed in a thick
metallic envelope and possibly placed on the ground under a set of
metal weighing scales.
</P>
<P>
   The metallic envelope sent lethal shreds of hot metal into the
crowd, explaining the high level of casualties, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitrovica bomb killed three people and wounded 42, said
Mijat Bojovic, the investigating judge in Mitrovica. Ambulances and
military helicopters marked with a red cross were in operation
between Mitrovica and Pristina, Kosovo's capital, all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In Podujevo, a bomb was placed in a garbage can near the market
and another bomb was hurled at the post office. Two people died and
21 were wounded in those blasts.
</P>
<P>
   No one has claimed responsibility for the bombs and police
declined to speculate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Market sellers and shopkeepers, mostly Albanian, in Mitrovica
were unanimous in their accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else but the Serbs?'' said Faik, a young man working in a
bakery across from Mitrovica market. ``Their target in most cases
is women and children. They have their reasons to kill a bit, scare
us a bit, to make us think of leaving and make us stay at home from
fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Miki Mahajlovic of the Serb Media Center in Pristina blamed the
bombing on ethnic Albanian ``terrorists'' of the Kosovo Liberation
Army who he said wanted to wreck the peace process. ``It is a very
effective method to create fear among the people,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
