<SLUG> BC-POPE-AGCA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN FAVORS MERCY FOR TURK WHO SHOT POPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Vatican has let the Italian government know that it
would favor clemency for Mehmet Ali Agca, the Turkish gunman who
tried to assassinate the pope in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Agca, who is serving a life sentence in an Italian prison in
Ancona, has repeatedly asked the pope and the Italian government
for release or extradition to Turkey. The pope forgave Agca for the
attempt on his life, but the Vatican has always emphasized that any
decision about his sentence is up to the Italian government.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night President Luigi Scalfaro told reporters that
he might agree to allow Agca to return to Turkey. ``Since so many
years have passed,'' he said, ``I don't think it would be a
difficult case.''
</P>
<P>
   Agca has said that if he cannot be freed, he would prefer to go
home to Turkey, where he faces a 10-year sentence for the murder of
a Turkish journalist. In an open letter to the pope last month, he
asked the pope to intervene on his behalf. Scalfaro said Saturday
night he had not received an appeal for clemency from the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Agca's lawyer, Marina Magistrelli, said Saturday night that the
Italian Justice Ministry had been considering Agca's request since
September, and contacted the Vatican through diplomatic channels
later last year, seeking its views. The Vatican, also working
through diplomatic channels, told the Justice Ministry at that time
that it would view such a granting of clemency ``favorably.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Vals said he could not
comment on the status of Agca's case or Italy's judicial process.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning, the holy father stated that he
forgave Agca; he said it for the first time three days after the
attempt when he was in the hospital, and he has repeated it,''
Navarro-Vals said Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
