<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9164 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMUGGLE-NIGHT14-COX     03-13 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLE-NIGHT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX SMUGGLING SERIES: SIDEBAR, A NIGHT WITH BORDER PATROL
 &HT;    (This story is for Saturday-Sunday, March 13-14. Four photos and
four graphics are available with this series. The series includes,
for Saturday-Sunday, SMUGGLE-MAIN, SMUGGLE-PUNISH, SMUGGLE-CASES,
SMUGGLE-NIGHT and, for Monday, SMUGGLE-WORKSITES.)
 &HT;    By Gary Kane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ On this night, the huddled masses are wet
and tired, sitting along the curb fronting the lobby of the Golden
Sands hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Border Patrol convoy of two vans and a patrol car
squeezes into the scene, which is already thick with onlookers and
television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Belotti approaches a cluster of paramedics and asks for a
head count.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this shuts us down for the rest of the night,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Belotti, 33, works the graveyard shift at the Border Patrol
station in Pembroke Pines. He knows that red-tape chore of formally
charging 26 Cubans with illegally entering the country will consume
the rest of his shift _ about six more hours. The station will
virtually shut down while the new arrivals are processed and bused
to Krome Detention Center.
</P>
<P>
   And while Belotti wrestles with paperwork, the Florida coastline
loses its border sentry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, I'm the only Border Patrol agent working this
shift between Corpus Christie, Texas, and Swanton, Vermont,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, two other agents are also assigned to the midnight
shift. But vacations, illness and staggered schedules sometimes
leave the station with just one man.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular night, three agents who went off-duty at
midnight agree to work a double shift to help Belotti. They hunch
over computer screens, filling in electronic forms. They glance now
and then into the sleepy faces of men, women and children to pose
questions and snap Polaroids.
</P>
<P>
   What is your daughter's name?
</P>
<P>
   How were you employed in your hometown?
</P>
<P>
   Whom did you pay to bring you here?
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, a story unfolds. The group, mostly from the city of
Pinar del Rio, left Cuba at about 3 p.m. aboard a 28-foot red and
white fishing boat. Everyone claims to have paid 10,000 Cuban pesos
(about $450) for the trip. A man called ``Pipo'' operated the boat.
The seas were rough. Several people became seasick. When the glow
of hotel lights grew bright, they slipped over the side and Pipo
sped away.
</P>
<P>
   The story is familiar to Belotti, who transferred six months ago
to the Miami sector from a Border Patrol outpost in Nogales, Ariz.
So familiar that he doesn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a lot of staged landings,'' he says. ``I'm
talking about people who wade out into the surf here and then turn
themselves in as illegal aliens when they really came ashore in the
Keys a week ago and already spent time with their families who live
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Staged landings buy time for the smuggler's get-away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people we picked up tonight probably walked along the
beach for a couple of hours before they went up to the hotel and
asked for help,'' he says. Sometimes refugees buy cheap, rickety
boats in Cuba and pay smugglers to tow them to the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   Alien smuggling is growing, Border Patrol agents say. Virtually
no one risks the dangerous crossing on rafts or makeshift boats.
Many of the new arrivals are relatives of Cubans who came to the
United States in 1994 in large numbers. Their smuggling fees, which
can run as high as $8,000, sometimes are paid by family members
already living here, agents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you notice that the mother of one of the women we loaded
into our vans tonight was in the crowd to welcome her?'' Belotti
asks.
</P>
<P>
   Only those Cubans intercepted at sea are turned away. Those who
make landfall are entitled to stay in the country under provisions
of the Cuban Readjustment Act. The Border Patrol deals almost
exclusively with the ones with sand on their shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we do here. We process these people so they can
start their lives in the United States,'' Belotti quips.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't like that in Nogales, he says. Mexicans caught
entering the U.S. were taken back. And during his six years in that
border town, he never encountered crowds of cheering onlookers,
such as this night when shouts of Libertad! greeted the new
arrivals as they climbed aboard the Border Patrol vans.
</P>
<P>
   When he isn't dealing with smuggled aliens, Belotti patrols the
border _ though it seems like a futile exercise. His beat covers
the coast from the Palm Beach-Broward county line down to Key West
and up to Naples on the Gulf. He stops at area marinas and passes
out leaflets warning boaters about the penalties for transporting
aliens. He also keeps an eye out for anything unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch for the guys with 17 life preservers in their boat or
the guys going fishing without any fishing poles,'' he explains.
``We're hoping to deter amateurs from getting into the smuggling
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Amateurs are more likely to spawn a tragedy, he says. Their
inexperience and greed prompt them to overload boats or attempt
treacherous seas. In December, 14 people drowned when a 29-foot
Scarab capsized a few miles from the coast; 21 people were aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Belotti says the station also works Operation Child Care, in
which agents use computer databases to identify migrants arrested
for sex crimes against children. Agents have been rounding them up
for deportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But right now that's on hold because of the influx of Cuban
smugglings,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen agents and supervisors work the Pembroke Pines station
now. When Belotti transferred here, he noticed a plaque commending
the station _ 24 agents were listed.
</P>
<P>
   It's 3:50 a.m. and the sporadic clatter of computer keyboards
stops. Belotti and the three agents working overtime have processed
21 of the illegal migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, sleeping women and children sprawl across the concrete
floor of a windowless holding cell. The cell door is open and a
small floor fan circulates the air. The men occupy an adjacent cell
behind a locked steel door. A light switch outside the cell oddly
controls both the lights and air conditioning inside. The men
choose pitch darkness after their cell turns refrigerator cold.
</P>
<P>
   Belotti heads for the lunchroom to see if anything's left in the
coffee pot.
</P>
<P>
   A computer flickers and a screen saver scrolls: ``The Madness
has to stop. Make Cuba the 51st state.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Kane is a staff writer for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
