A9186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-     03-13 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LUXURY OF DARRYL STRAWBERRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Darryl Strawberry has one hit in six at-bats in
his first two exhibition games, and feels he is slowly regaining
his swing. But there is a thorny issue that eventually must be
hurdled before Strawberry joins the New York Yankees in the regular
season _ an issue that may turn ugly.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the Yankees exercised the $2.5 million option on
Strawberry, they arranged with major-league baseball to keep his
salary from being included in the money subject to luxury tax.
Therefore, the Yankees will be subject to a 33 percent tax on
Strawberry's salary as soon as he's placed on their roster.
</P>
<P>
   When the details of his contract were worked out in January,
they didn't appear to be an obstacle for Strawberry's return. But
in the interim, the Yankees lost two significant arbitration
decisions, $5 million to Derek Jeter and $4.25 million to Mariano
Rivera. Since then, the Yankees have been trying to cut costs in
other ways _ they're exploring possible trades involving reliever
Darren Holmes (two years remaining at $3.25 million), were
conservative in their negotiations with catcher Jorge Posada and
pitcher Ramiro Mendoza, and even reduced the travel time for some
scouts in spring training. George Steinbrenner, the Yankees'
principal owner, is not in a mood to spend money unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's inclusion on the roster is not necessary, for now.
The Yankees have three left fielders in Chad Curtis, Ricky Ledee
and Shane Spencer _ Strawberry probably couldn't play left field
now, anyway, until he rebuilds his leg strength _ and they have a
designated hitter in Chili Davis. Strawberry would be a spare part,
in spite of his strong comeback last season, before he learned of
his colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees may want Strawberry to remain in the minor leagues
and continue his rehabilitation. But Strawberry, who turned 37
Friday, has made it clear he wants to be part of the team on
opening day, and its a goal to him, as he lifts weights and
strengthens his legs. Others in the organization feel Strawberry
won't willingly accept an assignment to the minors for one day
longer than is necessary _ and after exercising the multimillion
option on Strawberry, the Yankees may want him to do what they ask.
</P>
<P>
   Center Field Status
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, assured Curtis that
he is not trying to trade him and currently is not discussing him
as part of any prospective deals. Cashman could change his mind and
swap Curtis and his three-year, $6 million deal at any time, but it
probably isn't likely until the Yankees are confident Ledee could
play center field on a regular basis if Williams is hurt.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Ledee's play in center has been good, with some trouble
spots. In one game against Kansas City, Ledee repeatedly positioned
himself very deep in center, and short fly balls dropped in front
of him. Jose Cardenal, the Yankees' coach responsible for
outfielders, was not there that day. But Cardenal intends to always
be with Ledee now. When Ledee plays center field, Cardenal will
follow him and help position him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can play there,'' Cardenal said. ``He's got the quickness,
and he gets a good jump on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, in any event, is having a strong spring training,
batting .500 and driving the ball to the opposite field, something
he failed to do in the final half of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Report
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre's condition aside, the Yankees' roster generally
remained in good condition, avoiding injuries. But there are some
nagging problems.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte, the left-hander who strained his elbow in an
exhibition game, will likely attempt to play catch Monday. If
Pettitte can rehabilitate his injury without delay, he should be
ready to be part of the Yankees' rotation by the opening week of
the season. Don Zimmer, who has stepped in as manager in Torre's
absence, said of Pettitte, ``Some days he feels good, some days
he's not so good.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of players are suffering from flu symptoms, including
right fielder Paul O'Neill, who was scratched from the starting
lineup in Friday's exhibition game, and Jerome Walton, the
nonroster invitee who has missed three straight games.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Bernie Williams is recovering from a strained quad
muscle, but his injury is not serious. If this were the regular
season, said one club official, Williams would likely play through
the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Preseason Batting Averages: From .500 to .053
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis leads the Yankees with six runs batted in and a .500
batting average. Chili Davis is hitting .429, Jorge Posada .385 and
Scott Brosius .364. On the flip side, Joe Girardi is batting .154
and Paul O'Neill .053. Orlando Hernandez has allowed seven hits in
seven innings, with one walk and nine strikeouts; Mariano Rivera
has not permitted runs in five and two-thirds innings, but he has
been somewhat erratic, with four walks.
</P>
</TEXT>
