<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     03-13 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BRING BACK THE BIG OUTDOOR FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yankee Stadium remains the House That Ruth Built, a
baseball shrine. But once upon a time, boxers lived in that house
too. And it's time boxers returned.
</P>
<P>
   If the Madison Square Garden executives want to be taken
seriously as boxing promoters, they need to bring back boxing's
summer festival, the outdoor heavyweight title fight. Put it in
Yankee Stadium or in the Mets' proposed new ball park after its
planned 2002 opening near where Shea Stadium is now.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, boxing needs the summer stage of a big New York
ball park to create the aura that a big fight deserves, an aura
that a casino-hotel or even the Garden has never quite equaled, not
even in Saturday night's heavyweight unification bout between
Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we had 50,000 to 60,000 seats for Holyfield-Lewis,
we could've sold them,'' said Dave Checketts, the Garden president.
``It was the hottest ticket we've ever had at the Garden in my time
here. If a fight this big came along again, I think we'd have to
look at putting it outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever there was a big summer heavyweight title fight in New
York years ago, it was staged outdoors in Yankee Stadium or in the
old Polo Grounds. From high up there on the slopes of the upper
deck, multitudes peered toward the ring perched near second base,
surrounded by rows of ringside seats.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Louis fought outdoors here 10 times, Ezzard Charles five
times, Rocky Marciano four times.
</P>
<P>
   In the last Stadium show, Muhammad Ali outpointed Ken Norton
over 15 rounds on the chilly night of Sept. 28, 1976. But the
attendance was a disappointing 30,298 in the big Bronx ball park
where more than 70,000 watched Louis demolish Max Schmeling in a
first-round knockout in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden and Top Rank Inc. were the co-promoters of that
Ali-Norton III bout. But nobody has tried to put on a big ball park
fight in New York since then.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy to do. For any fight to fill most of all those
ball park seats, it must be a huge attraction. Even bigger than the
Holyfield-Lewis sellout.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, that next huge attraction simply doesn't exist.
But sooner or later, that huge attraction will surely develop. It
always has.
</P>
<P>
   When it does, and when the site auction begins, the Garden (as
the promoter planning to use, say, Yankee Stadium) would need to
again outbid the Las Vegas casino-hotels that have monopolized the
big title fights over the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor fights create risks. The ring needs a rain canopy. The
stadium's baseball grass needs to be covered. The electronic
equipment needs to be protected.
</P>
<P>
   But if the attraction is compelling enough, the reward is worth
the risks. Four years ago, the promoter Don King's outdoor show
featuring Julio Cesar Chavez in Mexico City drew 120,000, believed
to be the largest attendance in boxing history.
</P>
<P>
   In today's economy, the ticket scale at Yankee Stadium for an
outdoor fight would be at least as high as Saturday night's
Holyfield-Lewis bout that had a top of $1,500 for a ringside seat.
The Stadium could hold at least 55,000 for a big fight.
</P>
<P>
   With tickets priced from $200 ringside to $25 in the upper deck
for Ali-Norton III in the Stadium, then newly reopened, the gate
was about $2.4 million. Ali's purse was $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Stadium's record boxing crowd was 79,000 in 1930 when Max
Schmeling won the heavyweight title from Jack Sharkey on a foul. In
1923, the year the Stadium opened, 58,000 saw lightweight champion
Benny Leonard outpoint Lew Tendler.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 at the now leveled Polo Grounds, 54,487 attended Joe
Louis' 13th-round knockout of Billy Conn. Five years later, with
Louis warning that Conn ``can run, but he can't hide'' before their
rematch at Yankee Stadium after World War II, Louis registered an
eighth-round knockout.
</P>
<P>
   In his three Stadium title fights, Marciano outpointed Ezzard
Charles, knocked out Charles and knocked out Archie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Ingemar Johansson dethroned Floyd Patterson at the Stadium in
1959, then lost to Patterson at the Polo Grounds in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most memorable Stadium scenes involved middleweight
champion Sugar Ray Robinson's attempt to dethrone Joey Maxim as
light-heavyweight champion in 1952. Although far ahead on the three
scorecards, Robinson collapsed from heat prostration and couldn't
come out for the 14th round.
</P>
<P>
   If the Garden wants to enhance its reputation as a boxing
promoter, it needs to think about a big outdoor fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
