<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     03-13 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE LONG ROAD TO THE BIGGEST FIGHT FOR LEWIS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y., N.J., Canada)   (jw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were times, back when they were nomadic
Canadian amateurs barnstorming through Europe, when Egerton Marcus
had Lennox Lewis, and Lewis had Marcus, and everyone else was an
opponent speaking a language they only understood as unfriendly to
them.
</P>
<P>
   They were young men on the rise to Olympic glory, and the only
way to get there was to get up and go, find the fights, overcome
the odds and obstacles of being far from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only way for us to get better because we couldn't
get the fights we needed in Canada,'' Marcus said. ``We went all
over Europe together, and so many nights, he'd be the only one in
the crowd rooting for me, and I'd be the only one rooting for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   They met in their late teens and the long, winding road brought
them to Madison Square Garden Saturday night, Lewis finally face to
face with Evander Holyfield, Marcus in his familiar supporting
role, among a dubious crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who question Lennox's heart,'' said Marcus, a Lewis
sparring partner for this fight, a friend forever, ``they just
don't know him.''
</P>
<P>
   And right there, without really intending to, Marcus enunciated
the mystery and majority appeal of the sold-out heavyweight
championship unification bout. It was the unmistakable notion that,
after 33 fights across a full decade, the boxing public still did
not have any real level of certitude regarding Lewis, the complete
heavyweight package minus the validation of a single night of
unquestioned exceptional achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The case could be made, in fact, that the most notable event of
Lewis' career was the night he avenged his one defeat, when the
took back his World Boxing Council title from Oliver McCall, but
mainly because McCall was seized with emotional turbulence, and
dissolved in a pool of tears. That display of dysfunction, even
more than Mike Tyson's munching on Holyfield's ears, could serve as
a 1990s requiem for the heavyweights, whose standing in the general
sports spectrum has probably sunk lower than at any time in the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The people who say that's because boxing is too crude and
corrupt for America's growing number of latte-loving consumers
haven't looked at the television ratings for professional
wrestling. Or, for that matter, Jerry Springer. Boxing isn't dying
as much as it has cried itself to a state of suspended animation.
There have been more compelling fights in Knicks-Miami playoff
series than there have been in the heavyweight division since Tyson
moved down in class to the criminal justice division.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield could at least proudly say he has been in most of
them, and point to the scars of three epic battles with Riddick
Bowe, in addition to his experiences with the shadow that once was
Tyson. The most famous name in Lennox Lewis' portfolio of opponents
is Phil Jackson (KO, 8) on May 6, 1994, in Atlantic City,
apparently the same night Michael Jordan was gambling between
playoff games with the Knicks. Oh, not that Phil Jackson? Well,
anyway, Lewis, who as a young fighter would go anywhere to fight
anyone, had somehow managed over 10 professional years to not fight
Bowe, Tyson and Holyfield, the only three heavyweights he could
have proved himself against.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys could see how big, strong and quick Lennox is, and
they didn't want to fight him,'' Marcus said. ``They didn't want to
take the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   That has always been the Lewis camp spin, and, of course, the
others claimed Lewis wanted no part of them, that he lacked the
fiber, if not the skills. They said he was better suited to his
beloved rounds of chess.
</P>
<P>
   Egerton Marcus took particular offense at this. He considers
himself a pretty tough guy _ the middleweight silver medalist at
the Seoul Olympics in 1988, when Lewis won the super heavyweight
gold _ and at least the equal of Lewis in chess.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't beat me as much as I beat him,'' Marcus said,
before thinking better and declaring their rivalry a draw.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus grew up in Toronto, Lewis in nearby Kitchener. They
stayed at each other's homes, knew each other's friends. They were
teammates, and rivals. He was often the victim of Lewis' practical
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd do things like put a rock in my luggage, and I'd get
pulled over going through customs at the airport,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   His own promising career, hampered by injuries, took him to
Holyfield's camp as a sparring partner. For this fight, he had been
the Holyfield stand-in, the shorter man, trying to get inside
Lewis' jab, to the body, against the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox is naturally strong, stronger than Evander,'' Marcus
said. ``When he hits you, he moves you.''
</P>
<P>
   All those nights when it was just them, sharing their dreams in
faraway places, Egerton Marcus could see all those lesser fighters
who were moved out of Lewis' way. He came to the Garden Saturday
night to find out, once and for all, if Lewis could punch away the
last remaining obstacle to becoming the undisputed champion of the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
