<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME SERVES AS AN ELIXIR FOR BASEBALL-SAVVY DOMINICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ Omar Minaya stared out the
window of the New York Mets' team bus, taking in the devastation
Hurricane Georges had wrought.
</P>
<P>
   As senior assistant general manager and head of international
scouting for the Mets, this was not Minaya's first visit back to
his homeland since the hurricane hit last September. But its
effects on Minaya _ and the island _ had obviously not worn off by
the time the Mets arrived here Friday morning for a pair of
exhibition games against the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   What was once a plush grove of palm trees lining the way from
the Aeropuerto de las Americas to the capital was now a surrealist
exhibition of uprooted and disfigured palms, fronds bowed and bent,
trunks turned around and upside down. It is now an utterly barren
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this stuff used to be beautiful palm trees,'' Minaya said
softly. ``Now, it's total destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can only think of how I've been coming here so
many years, looking at players, and how this was always such a
beautiful trip. But the first imprint that comes to my mind today
is the thought of how this drive used to be and how it is no
more.''
</P>
<P>
   All Minaya wanted to do was get to Santo Domingo, a vibrant city
of nearly 3 million people, and forget about the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to see the smiles of the people because of
baseball,'' Minaya explained.
</P>
<P>
   The sport is deeply ingrained in the Dominican culture. As the
Mets' team bus pulled into Quesqueya Stadium on Saturday morning, a
flood of children in multi-colored uniforms enveloped the players,
bursting on to the scene from an adjacent field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go with these guys,'' said Paul Wilson, who was
scheduled to pitch for the Mets Saturday. ``I'll bet they have more
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and the Expos could not help enjoying themselves here
on Friday night, as the Mets rallied late for a 6-3 victory.
Merenque blared from the stadium loudspeakers between innings.
Cheerleaders danced on the dugout tops. No one had to tell the
near-capacity crowd when to clap. The fans did it on their own, to
a beat of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``For baseball purists, this is like heaven,'' Minaya said, his
face beaming as he sat seat by the dugout. ``Yes, the music is
loud. But there's no giant screen to tell you to clap now. Here,
you clap if you want to and don't if you don't.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The same goes for dancing or chanting. Baseball here is a
fiesta. And, as Minaya had hoped, it apparently has helped the
people to forget about the devastating storm, or at least to put it
aside for a time. For baseball is a link to the past. Especially
for Minaya, who left his inland town of Valverde Mao, near the
border with Haiti, for New York, when he was 8.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the United States that Minaya first played organized
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some recollections of playing baseball in the Dominican
Republic as a boy, but never on a team,'' Minaya said.
</P>
<P>
   In America, he grew up in the shadow of Shea Stadium and was a
Mets fan ``when they did not play the Giants and the Pirates. ``I
always rooted for Marichal and Clemente,'' Minaya said of the two
greatest Latin players of that erea.
</P>
<P>
   Minaya developed into enough of a ball player himself to be
taken in the 14th round of the 1978 draft by the Oakland A's. But
the young outfielder never made it past Class A ball and spent his
last two seasons as a player in Europe, living in a villa in the
Tuscany region of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, something was always calling Minaya back to his roots.
``Up here, I'm probably American,'' Minaya said, pointing to his
head. ``But I'm Dominican inside. That's my bloodline. And that
never goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Minaya landed a job with the Texas Rangers as an area
scout, working New York, New Jersey and the Dominican Republic,
where he would re-establish his ties back home.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, Minaya would go on to coach Juan Gonzalez and
sign Sammy Sosa as he rose to become the team's director of
scouting. When the Mets hired him, in September 1997, he took on
the added responsibilities of assistant general manager. But Minaya
continues to scout to this day. He was even scheduled to look over
a pitching prospect here Saturday afternoon _ all the while
savoring the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how I picture baseball to be in the 1940s and '50s,''
Minaya said. ``This has an atmosphere to it. It's like reliving the
baseball that I heard of and that I read about. These are not the
greatest clubhouses or fields. But there is a personal attachment
between the fans and the players. You play baseball here for the
love of the game. And that's what I love about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the storm was not forgotten, it had at least receded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1632EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-13 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FIVE POINTS OF LIGHT SAVE GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although bitter and hurt at not having been chosen independent
counsel for the Olympic investigation, I have decided to share my
recommendations with the International Olympic Committee, which
meets this week to whitewash itself.
</P>
<P>
   The following five points, if followed, will return the image of
the Games to something almost worthy of Bud Greenspan's elegiac
documentaries or the grand pronouncements of the senior American
IOC member, Anita DeFrantz. They will save the Games as our
beleaguered planet's only truly international television soap opera
and one of the few events with the power to stop, or at least
interrupt, war, famine, pestilence and politics.
</P>
<P>
   1. Reopen the Pelops probe. For centuries, it has been whispered
that the Olympics began when Pelops bribed King Oenomaus' groom to
loosen the axle on his master's chariot. Pelops won the race and
went on to claim the dead loser's daughter and kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   As a little thank-you to the gods, Pelops founded the all-male
Games. Athletes were naked and no women were allowed to watch. Only
Dionysus knows what really went on. Secret payoffs of olive-oil
franchises to winners were the least of it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's clear that case now. If the Olympics really began with a
fixed race, then blaming the current rings-leader, Juan Antonio
Samaranch, for turning a blind eye to corruption is just plain
unfair. It's the system he inherited. And he's done a darn fine job
of maintaining it.
</P>
<P>
   2. Find the silver chalice, the Maltese Falcon of the Games.
When it was discovered that Jim Thorpe had played minor-league
baseball, thus compromising his amateur status, Olympic officials
took back the two gold medals he had won at the 1912 Stockholm
Games. Everyone knows that.
</P>
<P>
   But they also took back a jewel-encrusted silver chalice in the
shape of a Viking ship presented to him by Czar Nicholas II of
Russia. Officials claimed it was only a ``traveling'' trophy. God
knows what that chalice is worth now.
</P>
<P>
   The only Olympic official who responded to the attempt by Grace
Thorpe to get the chalice for her father's museum was Robert
Helmick, president of the U.S. Olympic Committee. Alas, he soon
stepped down from the presidency amid allegations of conflict of
interest. Helmick thought it might have ``traveled'' to IOC
headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Is the chalice still in the palace? Or was it melted down to
make a lot of rings and brooches for IOC members and their
sweeties? Crack that case and we're on our way to closure.
</P>
<P>
   3. Let's move past the 1936 Holocaust Games. The current
controversy, provoked by the Simon Wiesenthal Center's
dissemination of anti-Semitic letters written by top Olympic
officials as they lobbied the world to give Berlin and the Nazis a
happy news platform, serves no further purpose.
</P>
<P>
   That the future Olympic czar Avery Brundage might have made
gazillions building the German Embassy in Washington if World War
II had not interfered is no longer relevant. This is exactly the
kind of old stuff that turns off younger viewers. People who want
to beat that drum will only drive the Olympics off the networks and
onto the History Channel.
</P>
<P>
   4. Make performance-enhancing products equally available to all.
These include athletic shoes, muscle-compression garments, sports
drinks, psychological and spiritual services, and, of course, such
biochemical aids as liquor (for shooters), steroids, blood-packing
gear, human growth hormone, amphetamines, anti-depressants,
you-name-it-we'll-cook-it.
</P>
<P>
   As long as only the wealthier athletes have access to doctors
who know how to mask and cycle, there can be no true fair play. Why
shouldn't a kayaker from a poor family have the same opportunity as
a blue-blood equestrian or a celebrity runner backed by a
corporation? Random testing should be for IQ and screen appeal
only. Let stupid and ugly athletes go to college, but not to these
Games.
</P>
<P>
   5. Make the Games truly professional. Every athlete who shows up
for the opening-day parade gets at least the minimum fee due an
extra in a television miniseries. The scale rises with screen time,
which means that a luger with a heartbreaking story that keeps us
tuning in for days could make more money than, say, the
latest-model ice doll. Of course, if said ice doll wins a gold
medal, there would be a big bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The money would come from several sources, including the
national organizations and athletic federations that routinely
reward athletes for victories now, from television and from
commercial sponsors. Corporations and politicians would be given
naming privileges.
</P>
<P>
   If for a mere $15 million in expenses and bribes you get the
Salt Lake City Games, how many college scholarships,
hip-replacement operations and Dionysian nights could be offered
needy IOC members in return for, say, the Dole/Viagra Javelin
Throw?
</P>
<P>
   As brilliant as these recommendations may seem to some, they are
not to be construed as part of a last-ditch job application.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics are over as a major social force, and I am moving
on as well.
</P>
<P>
   I have decided to pursue becoming independent counsel for the
investigation into the National Collegiate Athletic Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
