<SLUG> BC-RUN-KENYA-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW YORK EXPORT TO KENYA: STRETCHING LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAPSAIT, Kenya _ Jim Wharton, an exercise physiologist from New
York City, rode in the back of a four-wheel-drive vehicle up a
bumpy mountainside to a shrine of his sport. He passed donkeys. He
passed a man carrying a shaggy sheep. Barefoot boys waved. The air
felt thinner.
</P>
<P>
   A car drove by, and Wharton poked his head out the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do some stretching exercises,'' he called out
with great excitement.
</P>
<P>
   The two men inside, young runners in track suits, smiled
tolerantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe later,'' the driver said and pulled away down the rutted
road.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton, a peppy 57, came to Kenya _ minus his luggage, which
got lost along the way _ because he is an expert on stretching.
Here in the Rift Valley is where some of the world's greatest
runners train, and stretching is not something many of them like
very much.
</P>
<P>
   While Kenyans have long dominated long-distance running,
Wharton, a dedicated runner himself, was invited to three elite
running camps to see if he could help with a problem he says is
relatively recent: As the runners go faster and faster,
consistently running marathons under 2 hours 10 minutes, they are
getting hurt more and more.
</P>
<P>
   But he also came to take a half-awed, half-skeptical look at
exactly what it is that makes Kenya continue to produce such superb
runners, three decades after the nation won its first gold medals
in the 1968 Olympics in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction back in the United States was: could it
really be that much better?'' he asked. ``I mean, we've got
altitude. We've got wonderful places. It's not that you're
suspicious. You're curious. You look at all aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not pause. He may have been raised in West Virginia, but
he is unmistakably a New Yorker now. ``Is there something in the
food?'' he asked. That was just the start of a treatise on running
surfaces, the ``architecture'' of the foot, the lack of
distractions and the cooperative nature of training. ``It's
attitude, not altitude,'' he finally concluded. ``The attitude is
magic.''
</P>
<P>
   His mission for the day was to teach 30 athletes at a running
camp in this atom-sized town in western Kenya _ altitude just over
10,000 feet _ stretching routines that he and his son, Phil, have
been preaching for more than a decade. The basic idea, which they
learned from a retired professor from the University of Illinois,
Aaron Mattes, is that most athletes do it all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than stretching a limb and holding the muscle taut for 20
or 30 seconds, they teach what they call ``active-isolated
stretching.'' Each stretching exercise is aimed at one particular
muscle group, which is then contracted and relaxed 10 or so times
and held in one place no longer than two or three seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Moses Tanui, who won the Boston Marathon in 1996 and 1998, and
runs one of the three camps, has used the technique. So has Joshua
Kimaiyo, 26, a runner and brother of Eric Kimaiyo, who owns the
camp here and has won the Honolulu marathon twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never stretched before,'' Joshua Kimaiyo said. ``We came
home from training and we were too tired.'' That is understandable:
the athletes run an average of 15 miles a day, rarely on flat
surfaces. Kimaiyo's hip started bothering him a year ago and last
fall in Italy he worked with Wharton on a stretching routine. He
said it has worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than injections,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton said, ``There's more, I won't say pressure, but more
challenge, to push the envelope. As they push the envelope, it's
still a human body.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wharton became interested in stretching after Phil, while a
runner at the University of Florida, developed a curvature of the
spine. Nothing helped, including acupuncture and chiropractors,
Wharton said, until they came upon the stretching routines. They
say that the stretching straightened Phil's spine.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton was invited to Kenya by Dr. Gabrielle Rosa, an Italian
doctor and trainer at the three camps, which are sponsored in part
by Fila, a shoe company. Fila was forced to dress Wharton because
his own clothes were lost somewhere between Kenya and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Also lost in the luggage was a set of ropes that Wharton loops
around feet and legs for the stretching routines. So on a recent
morning he went to a hardware store in Eldoret, the main city in
this area and arguably the running center of Kenya, and bought
several dozen yards of rope. He wrapped the frayed ends in red and
green tape, the colors of Kenya's flag. Then he rode the 60 miles
to the camp.
</P>
<P>
   With some prodding, the trainers managed to haul two dozen of
the athletes higher, to a flat spot on a peak with a view of the
green hills and gold plains of the Rift Valley. Wharton lay down
and began pelvic warm-ups. Then it was on to the hamstrings, the
thigh, the lower back. The runners, fumbling with their ropes,
groaned.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Simon Biwott, 28, nonetheless proclaimed it ``very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel after stretching, the body is somehow more healthy
than before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ngolepus, 18, an aspiring marathoner, had similar praise,
though he was a bit more terse. ``My muscles became good,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton, far from home, was more emotional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost lost it,'' he said. ``I am here on a hillside in
Kenya teaching guys who don't even know how to stretch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
