<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-MARBURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARBURY BRINGS AGGRESSIVE MESSAGE TO NETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See MARBURY-HOMETOWN) 
 (bl)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The New Jersey Nets' days of ignoring their coaches'
play calls, squandering double-digit leads late in the game, and
breaking down mentally under the stress and emotion of a
hard-fought contest are over, as far as Stephon Marbury is
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, the audacious point guard from Brooklyn, N.Y., who was
traded to the Nets on Thursday, will not stand for such
dysfunction. He proved as much Friday night when, in street clothes
and on the sideline, he chastised his new teammates as they
surrendered yet another fourth-quarter lead and lost one more game
they should have won.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with conviction and without hesitation, the 22-year-old
Marbury told the Nets to follow Coach John Calipari's game plan and
accept the challenge of holding off the charging Philadelphia
76ers. The fact that he had not played a second, was more than two
years younger than everyone else in the huddle, and perhaps coming
off as a bit abrasive for someone who had joined the team less than
24 hours earlier, never entered his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win, and when you want to win, you don't care,''
said Marbury, who will make his Nets debut in a nationally
televised game Sunday afternoon against the Miami Heat. ``And I
think these guys want to win so they're not looking at it as I'm
jumping down their throats. I think they're looking at it as: `This
guy wants to win and he's going to do whatever it takes to win.
He's going to tell you if something's wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   That inborn leadership that comes to Marbury as naturally as a
behind-the-back dribble is one of the many reasons the Nets gave up
three players and potentially two first-round draft picks to trade
for the former Minnesota Timberwolves star. His quickness, scoring
ability, knack for passing, and poise during intense moments of
competition combine to make him a great player.
</P>
<P>
   But his greatest attribute may be his willingness and courage to
lead. It is certainly the one that the rudderless Nets (3-16) need
most.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Stephon, what you have is a leader, a warrior, a player
who's going to come at you and wants to win in the worst way, a
player who's going to make everybody better,'' Calipari said.
``He'll make my job easier. His mom said, `I see you on TV jumping
around.' And I said: `I won't have to do that anymore. Now, I can
sit and watch a little bit.'''
</P>
<P>
   What Calipari will see will certainly look a lot better than
anything he has witnessed in the past two and a half years. In
Keith Van Horn, Kerry Kittles and Marbury, who practiced with the
Nets for the first time Saturday at Miami University, New Jersey
has perhaps the greatest young nucleus in the National Basketball
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Hoop pundits regarded Marbury and Kevin Garnett, Minnesota's
All-Star forward, as the John Stockton and Karl Malone of the next
generation, but the league's most prolific one-two punch of the
future will now play its home games in the Meadowlands. Marbury and
Van Horn, the 6-foot-10-inch forward averaging more than 22 points
and eight rebounds a game, give the Nets two superstars, two
perennial All-Stars in the making and two players who can't wait to
get on the court together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as excited as can be that he's here,'' Van Horn said
Friday. ``He's what we've been lacking. I was sitting at dinner
with Jayson Williams last night and I told him that it feels like
the biggest weight has been taken off my shoulders, because it's
been hard and difficult for me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Sam Cassell, whom the Nets traded to Milwaukee in the
three-team deal for Marbury, missing 14 games this season with a
sprained right ankle, the burden of carrying the Nets' offense fell
solely on Van Horn's broad shoulders. Without a true point guard to
orchestrate the pick-and-roll, Van Horn has been forced to score
the bulk of his points on dribble-drive isolation plays that left
him drained of energy late in games. Though his scoring has not
suffered, he has been worn down because of the precious few easy
baskets he has made.
</P>
<P>
   With Marbury, one of the league's finest young clutch players,
all of that will end, as the duo should be deadly on the
pick-and-roll. Marbury, who has an outstanding knowledge of the
game and has already offered insightful critiques of many of his
new teammates, said Van Horn's outside shooting ability should
enable them to run a more effective pick-and-roll than he and
Garnett did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see pick-and-roll all day with me and Keith,'' said Marbury,
who will wear No. 33 for the Nets. ``He can shoot the 3, so that
makes him more of a weapon because he has the in-between game and
he has the 3-point game. So the pick-and-roll can be set high or
low. Keith is a player who I think I can help raise to
superstardom.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury also envisions one of the league's finest backcourts in
himself and Kittles. Marbury demanded that Kittles remain a Net for
the trade to go through. Kittles, who has struggled mightily this
season, shooting a career-low 34 percent, expects Marbury to serve
as his perfect pick-me-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to play with him,'' Kittles said. ``With his
ability to break down defenders, penetrate the lane and find the
open man, he should have an immediate impact on my game.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Marbury's aggressive style of verbal leadership, the Nets
were far from offended. Humbled after stumbling to the worst record
in the Eastern Conference, they believe that is just what they
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for a point guard to come in and say those things,''
the veteran swingman Kendall Gill said. ``You can say it as a
forward or a center, but if you're not directing the offense you
don't really have control over it. So it's good for Stephon to say
it because he is the one who will have control over running the
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Nets are Marbury's team.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The details of the draft picks the Nets surrendered in the trade
are as follows: Minnesota has until April 1 to decide between
taking the Nets' 1999 first-round pick unconditionally or only if
the Nets do not receive one of the top three picks. If they take
the pick unconditionally, it is the only Nets draft choice
Minnesota receives in the trade. If it selects the second option
and the Nets have the fourth pick or lower, it also receives the
Nets' first-round pick in 2003. If it selects the second option and
the Nets have one of the first three picks, it receives a
first-round pick in 2000 and 2003 but not in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
