<HEADLINE>
DECISION ON 32ND TEAM NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob McNair wants to own the National Football League's 32nd
team, and wants it in Houston. Eli Broad and Michael Ovitz, who are
leading competing expansion groups in Los Angeles, want the team in
their city.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is expected to make its decision Tuesday. If it's
Houston, McNair would get the team. But if it's Los Angeles, the
league could choose the city, not one of the groups, and hope to
lure other potential owners to an auction. Last year's auction to
sell the Cleveland Browns brought $530 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared to pay the market value, but not above market
value,'' said McNair, who has contacted eight teams about moving to
Houston if he loses to the expansion race to Los Angeles. The ante
could be at least $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL's encouraged me to do this,'' said McNair, who
recently sold the bulk of his power generation company for $1.1
billion. ``And I've got sufficient personal assets to make the NFL
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broad group is looking to gut the Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum and build a new stadium; Ovitz and his investors want to
build in Carson, Calif. They both lag behind Houston in firm
financing to build stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the media markets were the same size, then Los Angeles
would be at a significant disadvantage,'' said Broad, the
billionaire chairman of SunAmerica, an insurance company. ``But Los
Angeles is the second-largest market, and ratings have been down
without a team there.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad and McNair said that even at a steep price, the team could
be a decent investment. ``I don't do philanthropy in business or
sports,'' McNair said. ``We can run it and make money. But there
are better businesses than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Broad: ``If you want immediate returns on investment, you
don't get into football. But five years out, the team values will
go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad disputed the impression that some owners do not want to
return to the Coliseum. `The USC crime rate is down 47 percent in
recent years,'' he said. ``The Coliseum's problem was the Los
Angeles Raiders.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz recently said: ``It's up to the owners to see if they want
to go back to where they've been. What works in Los Angeles is
something new, fresh and exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1643EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
