<SLUG> BC-ST.JOHN'S-INDIANA-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S MAKES IT LOOK EASY IN VICTORY OVER INDIANA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ During a news conference Friday at the South
Regional, a reporter from Indiana asked St. John's coach Mike
Jarvis whether he would use a zone defense against the Hoosiers,
since they do not execute their halfcourt offense as well when not
facing man-to-man defense.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis asked the reporter if he was setting him up by dispensing
bad information or if he would be proven accurate.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the reporter was right, and he had better
make sure Indiana coach Bob Knight never learns his identity.
</P>
<P>
   Using a zone defense for all but the first few minutes of
Saturday's game, St. John's dominated the Hoosiers, eliminating the
easy layups on which they rely and cruising to a shockingly easy
86-61 victory.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's, which was not ranked in any of the polls when the
season began, now advances to the regional semifinals of the NCAA
tournament for the first time since 1991. No matter the result, the
trip assures the Red Storm that this season will be viewed as a
success. St. John's will play the winner of Saturday's second game,
between Maryland and Creighton, on Thursday in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   So easy was the victory over Indiana that even when the Red
Storm endured a momentary swoon midway through the second half, the
lead was still 18 points. With five minutes remaining in the game,
the lead was back up to 23, and with two minutes left the walk-ons
were in, the lead was 30 and point guard Erick Barkley was
embracing everyone on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Only a nitpicker _ and a coach _ would note that the margin of
victory would have been much larger if St. John's had shot its free
throws as successfully as it did everything else. Everything else _
the tight defense, the professional interior passing, the dominance
on the boards _ was practically flawless.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the start did the Red Storm look as if it would have a
struggle. St. John's was down by 12-9 going into the first
television timeout with 15 minutes 36 seconds left in the first
half, the result of three easy layups and an A.J. Guyton 3-pointer.
St. John's came out of the timeout in a zone, and Luke Recker,
Indiana's shooting guard, hit a 3-pointer to make the lead 15-9.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, St. John's went on a 13-0 run _ including
3-pointers by Barkley (seven points, five assists in the first
half), Ron Artest (10 points) and Lavor Postell (10 points) _ to
give St. John's a 22-15 lead. During that run, St. John's missed
four free throws that could have extended the lead, but Indiana got
just one easy layup in the rest of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, which shot better than 60 percent from the field and
took just three 3-pointers against George Washington in the first
round, resorted almost exclusively to jumpers. The Hoosiers tried
11 3-pointers and made just four, and were 12 of 27 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, everyone seemed to be hitting for St. John's. Center
Tyrone Grant, still hampered by an infected cut on his right hand,
made two straight layups _ one on a nice move along the baseline
and another while cutting through the lane, as he took a bullet
pass from Barkley. The St. John's lead was up to 10 points with
5:03 left in the first half when Barkley hit a floater in the lane.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Everything Indiana did, St. John's seemed to do one better.
After Recker, a former Mr. Basketball in Indiana, hit another
3-pointer, Bootsy Thornton responded with one for St. John's.
Indiana's William Gladness lofted a hook over Artest, but Artest
took a foul-line pass from Postell into the lane for a layup. He
followed with a 3-pointer and, on the next possession, stripped
Recker to start a fast break that resulted in a Grant layup.
</P>
<P>
   On the last possession of the half, Artest, who had missed five
3-pointers, passed up two open shots to pass inside to Thornton,
who finished with a layup for a 45-30 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Except for poor free-throw shooting _ St. John's was 9-of-15
from the line in the first half _ the Red Storm played a nearly
perfect first half, shooting 55.6 percent from the field and
hitting 6-of-12 3-pointers. The Red Storm had 12 assists on 15
field goals highlighted by the spectacular interior passing, and
dominated on the boards against the much larger Indiana lineup,
19-11. The aggressive defense resulted in nine steals.
</P>
<P>
   The second half was merely more of the same. Thornton opened the
half with a 3-pointer and, after Gladness hit a layup, Thornton,
who seemed insulted when the announcer called him Bootsy Thompson
in the pre-game introductions, hit a fall-away jumper. Artest
followed with a 3-pointer and the lead was up to 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   After Indiana's Rob Turner committed a foul, he began to walk
dejectedly upcourt with the ball tucked under his arm. Barkley
swooped in and ripped the ball out of Tucker's hands as surely as
St. John's tore this game from Indiana's weak grasp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
