<SLUG> BC-BBO-CONSISTENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES AND YANKEES ARE ROLE MODELS FOR EVERYDAY CONSISTENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ When the Houston Astros gathered for the first
full-squad workout of spring training, their manager told them he
wanted to be just like the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves, someone later asked? Why do you want to be
like the Atlanta Braves? They either do not get to the World
Series, or they lose the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Well, I'd like to be like the Buffalo Bills, too,'''
Larry Dierker said, referring to the team that made four
consecutive Super Bowl appearances without winning. What is this
guy, a loser? Not by any means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just like to be good every single year and have a chance
to get to the World Series,'' Dierker said. ``The playoffs are a
crapshoot. You hope you're hot. If we get into the playoffs enough,
I think we'll eventually go to the World Series. To me, the
playoffs have to be the first goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros reached the playoffs the last two seasons under
Dierker, who emerged from the broadcast booth to become a
championship manager. But in his mind, two years is only a start.
The Braves have made the past seven playoffs, showing a consistency
that makes Dierker and other managers envious.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and the New York Yankees have become role models.
Other teams would like nothing more than to be able to emulate
their style of play, professionalism and success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are going to be critical if you don't advance to the
playoffs or get to the World Series,'' Dierker said, ``I hope
they're that successful in their lives that they do every last
thing right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Phillies are nowhere near even the Astros'
recent status, but they, too, see the Braves as an ideal role
model.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really have a good thing going,'' Terry Francona, the
Phillies' young manager, said. ``They have a great pitching staff.
They have a very competitive lineup, sometimes dominant. Then they
replace somebody every year and get somebody else. They're really
doing it right. That's what we're shooting for. They haven't won
the World Series people think they should, but every year they're
consistently good. That's what we've been talking about for two
years. We'd like to get good and stay good.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker recalled a scene from the Braves' victory over the
Astros in a 1997 playoff game that epitomized the Braves' way of
doing business. ``When they won the last game,'' Dierker said,
``they just walked out and shook hands and walked back to the
dugout. We would have been so excited we would have been in a big
pile climbing all over each other. For them it was just business.
OK, we've taken this step; now, let's take the next step. To me,
that tells you they expect to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when they play regular-season games, Dierker said, the
Braves maintain a low-key approach, eschewing overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play hard all the time and they play excellent
baseball,'' he said. ``That's where I want to get here. This is the
way you're expected to play, and you can transcend generations
where if you lose a Craig Biggio or a Shane Reynolds, the next guy
comes in and knows this is what's expected. You're expected to win;
you're expected to know what to do. It becomes a habit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who have reached the playoffs the last four years,
winning World Series in two of them, have impressed their American
League rivals in a similar way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've heard it once, I've heard it 100 times from my
players,'' Mike Hargrove, the Cleveland Indians' manager, said.
``They look at the Yankees in '98 as a tremendous model in what
intensity and work ethic does for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Parrish was the Detroit Tigers' bench coach the last two
seasons before becoming their manager last Sept. 1. He has been no
less impressed with the Yankees' approach to their jobs and their
task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really respected what the Yankees have done over the last
few years,'' he said. ``When you go into town and watch them take
infield, watch them take batting practice, they're very
professional about their job. They come to work every day. They run
the bases well. They run them hard. That's great to see out of a
good club. They play the game the way it's supposed to be played,
unlike some of the teams you see.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of those other teams, Parrish cited the 1997
Baltimore Orioles. ``They had all that talent, but it was like they
played when they wanted to play,'' he said. ``They played in
spurts. You just had a feeling watching Baltimore that year that
when they got in the playoffs they were going to get beat because
they didn't come to work. Some teams have the talent, but they
don't come to play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar Vizquel, the Indians' shortstop, saw how the Yankees
played. ``I was really impressed,'' he said, ``not only because
they won 114 games, but they kept that intensity in the playoffs.
Sometimes when you win 114 games, you think everything is going to
be easy and you take things for granted. But they came to the
playoffs with that same intensity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
