<HEADLINE>
GOALS TO PREVENT LETHARGY  
 EVOLUTION OF STRIKE ZONE  
 STRATEGY FOR BROTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Yankees, Atlanta Braves and Cleveland Indians are
considered the dominant teams in their divisions, with seemingly no
one between them and the playoffs. Of the trio, though, the Indians
appear to have the clearest path, because no one in the American
League Central is in position to challenge them.
</P>
<P>
   How do the Indians plan to stay awake all season instead of
slumbering until October? Manager Mike Hargrove has a strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come out and said our goal is to win 100 games in the
regular season and win the World Series,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His pronouncement might have caught his team's attention, but it
invited criticism from outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately,'' Hargrove related, ``I got feedback that how
arrogant that is. I wasn't being arrogant. I wasn't saying we're
going to do it. I said that's our goal. Before, we said let's get
to the postseason and we'll take our chances. All you're doing is
camouflaging your real goals. I thought, what better way to put us
all on notice that our goal is to win 100 games during the regular
season and win the World Series. It's not arrogant. There's not a
cockiness. It's just our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Evolution of Strike Zone
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the new strike zone, the one with higher but
narrower strikes, an American League umpire, Rocky Roe, offered
insight into the evolution of the mostly shrunken zone. He traced
the beginning of the change to the 1976 World Series, when, he
said, George Steinbrenner saw what he believed was a difference in
National and American League umpiring.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was the result of the chest protectors the
umpires wore. AL umpires still used the outside protector after
their NL counterparts had switched to inside protectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when they said anybody coming into the major leagues
would have to use an inside protector because they wanted to
standardize the strike zone,'' Roe said. ``Over the course of time,
because of pitching coaches and the inside protector, the strike
zone shrunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coaches, he said, stressed that pitchers should keep
the ball low in the strike zone. As the pitchers became more
successful at doing that, umpires saw more pitches low in the
strike zone, Roe recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the course of time,'' he said, ``the strike zone went
down because that's where the majority of pitches were and because
the inside protector allowed the umpires to get lower. You see the
pitch on the knees much better. When they were using the outside
protector, they saw the high pitch good. That's why the American
League at one time was known as the high-ball league.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only could the umpires get lower with the inside protector,
but they also began setting up between the batter and the catcher's
inside shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the inside protector,'' Roe said, ``you do work in the
slot and you see the inside corner better and the outside corner
sometimes you have to guess. Over the years the strike zone went
wide.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the wide strike the commissioner's office wants to take
away, although Roe argued that umpires have not given pitchers as
much off the plate as their critics claim. Television cameras, he
said, distort the view because their angle is not head-on.
</P>
<P>
   Strategy for Brothers
</P>
<P>
   During the winter, a trade separated the brothers Bret and Aaron
Boone, and a free-agent signing enabled Roberto Alomar to join his
brother Sandy Jr. Bret and Roberto are second basemen, meaning
their brothers are in a position to take them out in attempts to
break up double plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't get me,'' Atlanta's Bret, grinning impishly, said of
Aaron, Cincinnati's third baseman. ``He can try as hard as he
wants. You tell him that. I'd like him to try. I'll let him slide
by and laugh at him. Tell him that. I'm sure he's going to try to
get me, but I don't think he can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alomars, who like the Boones have followed their father into
the major leagues, are together with Cleveland, the first time they
have been teammates since they were with San Diego in 1989. Sandy
said he was never concerned he would hurt Robby in a hard slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the speed to get there in time so I don't have to
worry about it,'' Sandy said. ``I tried a couple times. It's hard
to get him because he goes in different directions all the time.
He's too unpredictable. He goes back and forth, to the sides. He
doesn't do the same thing all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
