<SLUG> BC-BKW-BIGEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN AND RUTGERS MAKE IT LOOK EASY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The women's basketball teams from Connecticut and Rutgers, both
ranked among the top 10 nationally, waltzed away with their
first-round games Friday night in the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament. Sunday night, with perhaps not too much
more difficulty, they get an opportunity to advance to the Round of
16.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the NCAA tournaments, men and women, would have the
nation's 64 strongest teams. It doesn't work out that way because
the champions of weaker conferences automatically get into the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, those less-tested teams pull off a stunning
upset, as the Harvard women did last year against top-seeded
Stanford. But for every surprise, there are two or three runaways,
like those orchestrated by Connecticut and Rutgers. UConn decimated
St. Francis of Pennsylvania, 97-46, and Rutgers put away a good but
outclassed Dartmouth team, 84-70, in a game that was hardly that
close.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut (28-4) and Rutgers (27-5) tied for the
regular-season title in the Big East. St. Francis is the Northeast
Conference champion, Dartmouth the Ivy League champion.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's games served as warm-ups for the winners. Sunday night,
again playing on their home courts, Connecticut meets Xavier of
Ohio (24-8) and Rutgers faces Arizona (18-10).
</P>
<P>
   Xavier made 64 percent of its shots in the first half in beating
Florida International, 85-71. Arizona, although falling behind by
17 points, escaped with an 87-84 overtime victory over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   UConn is seeded first in the Mideast, Rutgers third in the
Midwest. Both are expected to move on to those regional
competitions next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If the favorites keep winning, Connecticut will advance to
Cincinnati in a regional joining Clemson, Georgia and Iowa State.
Rutgers would play in Normal, Ill., with Purdue, Texas Tech and
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut and Rutgers stunned their first-round foes with
superior height and speed, unrelenting defense and quick transition
games. In the opening minutes in Storrs, Conn., UConn went on an
early 19-2 run and led at the half by 59-20. In Piscataway, N.J.,
Rutgers started with a 12-0 run and led by 33-10 and 42-14.
</P>
<P>
   Paige Sauer, UConn's 6-foot-5-inch center, is still hobbling,
but she put together 13 points and 11 rebounds in 12 minutes. The
smaller St. Francis team had no one near that height to contain
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get that in our league,'' said Jen DeFilippo of St.
Francis. ``We practiced against two defenders. It's really physical
and wears you down after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth had a related problem against Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty aggressive inside,'' said 6-1 Erin Rewalt of
Dartmouth. ``It was a lot of pushing and shoving going on, a lot
more than in our league. We were just excited to play people that
size.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Stringer, the Rutgers coach, was excited that her team
started safely in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was important,'' she said, ``was how we played, how we
won. We opened all the barrels and ran and saw each other and won
the boards. And we're capable of playing intense, focused
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Stringer, in her 27th year as a highly successful head coach,
has changed with the times. While her team concept remains unbowed,
she is more tolerant of occasional playground showboating.
</P>
<P>
   Her team has depth, and that may become a factor. Shawnetta
Stewart, a quick forward who can shoot from anywhere, played only
one minute in the second half against Dartmouth because of a jammed
right index finger. Tasha Pointer, the quick point guard, was
slowed by a contusion of the left calf.
</P>
<P>
   With the game in hand early in the second half, Stringer
substituted liberally, and she did not seem concerned with
Dartmouth's mild comeback. Dartmouth also started getting better
shots. As Chris Wielgus, the Dartmouth coach, said, ``We took good
shots that didn't fall.''
</P>
<P>
   From the first row on the sideline, Gov. Christie Whitman of New
Jersey, wearing a red Rutgers sweater, cheered on the state
university's team. After the game, she told Stringer the game was
``a nice warm-up for Rutgers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't go so far as to say nice warm-up,'' the coach said
later, ``but a nice opportunity to play a team that played spirited
and hard. I was very nervous before the game, but we appreciate the
governor's supreme confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
