<HEADLINE>
STANDING PAT, THE KNICKS LOSE GROUND 
ADVICE FOR MARBURY 
CLIPPERS MUST LEARN TO SHARE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry West, the Los Angeles Lakers' president and architect,
entered the season with a team that might already have been
championship-bound. Now, with the prompting of the Lakers' owner,
Jerry Buss, West has made several major personnel moves to improve
their chances.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, anyhow, signing Dennis Rodman and trading for Glen
Rice in the last two weeks appear to give the Lakers the inside
track for a title.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, the New York Knicks, a large-market team
with disposable income essentially stood pat at the league's
trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   And now they have lost six of their last eight games after
Friday night's debacle in Chicago in which they matched a league
low for field goals in a game with 19. They are losing ground to
Indiana and Miami and may be hard-pressed to catch Orlando in the
Atlantic Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were stunned when Stephon Marbury wound up with the
New Jersey Nets. Although the Knicks inquired about him, they were
never seriously in the running for Marbury, simply because they did
not have a grade-A point guard to tantalize anyone with.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how serious the Knicks were about Marbury, coach Jeff Van
Gundy said: ``It doesn't matter. He's in New Jersey. The bottom
line is, they did a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It can be argued that Latrell Sprewell is adjusting to his new
teammates, that Marcus Camby will justify his contract extension
and that the Knicks will regroup and be healthy enough in two
months to contend for the Eastern Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Oakley is not the only former Knick taking shots at
the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's that $50 million backcourt doing?'' a smiling Derek
Harper said late last week, referring to the combined contracts of
Chris Childs and Charlie Ward. ``I think a lot of the moves there
can be questioned. That's nothing against the players that have
signed there. If you're in line to be a free agent and you picked
up Chris, Charlie and Camby, well, more power to those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``But production is what this business is all about. And when
you produce, you win basketball games.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper, the ex-Knick whom the Lakers signed for a pittance, is
befuddled. ``After a while, you have to question Ernie,'' he said,
referring to Ernie Grunfeld, the Knicks' president and general
manager. ``You have to wonder what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Harper has a bone to pick with the Knicks after they
renounced his rights following the 1995-96 season, he says he
harbors no grudges.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Cummings is different. He has no real history with the
Knicks. He was merely a veteran power forward hoping to play for
anyone when the Knicks sent him to Golden State in the Sprewell
trade. But he, too, does not understand the method in the Garden
management's madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bring in some youth like Camby to help you in the future,
but you base your whole success around your 36-year-old franchise
center,'' Cummings said. ``Patrick has only got a couple years
left, so building for the future makes no sense for them right now.
I'm as surprised as everyone that they didn't keep Oak and everyone
together for one last run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, getting younger and more athletic doesn't always
necessarily mean you're getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they signed Camby for a contract that could total $48
million, the Knicks already had the league's highest payroll at $64
million. If they do not advance past the second round of the
playoffs, more people than former Knicks are going to wonder if
that money could have been spent more wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read Oak's quote about changing for nothing else but the
sake of change,'' Harper said. ``It's perfect. You want to tell me
they haven't missed Oak this year? How many minutes has Marcus
Camby averaged this year?''
</P>
<P>
   Camby was averaging 18.9 minutes in 18 games entering Friday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Harper it was not fair to compare West and Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry has been doing it a lot longer and he's the best there
is,'' Harper said. ``Ernie is Ernie and Jerry is Jerry. I don't
think there's a lot of comparison there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Advice for Marbury
</P>
<P>
   Another New York schoolboy legend came home to play on Thursday,
another young star who can dribble, pass, shoot and perform under
pressure. The possibilities seem limitless for Stephon Marbury,
just as they did for an earlier Nets point guard from the city's
playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my best advice is not to let his friends and family
dictate his life just because he's home,'' said Kenny Anderson, the
28-year-old floor leader of the Boston Celtics who spent four and a
half turbulent seasons in the Meadowlands. ``It's very hard to stay
focused like that. Really, I'm just learning it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Stephon has an advantage. He's more mature than I was
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury has been following in Anderson's footsteps since high
school. Anderson starred at Archbishop Molloy in Queens, while
Marbury became the nation's most coveted player at Lincoln High
School in Brooklyn. Like Anderson, Marbury enrolled at Georgia Tech
and stayed only one season before leaving for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was drafted by the Nets; Marbury spent his first two
and a half seasons at Minnesota before coming to the Nets on
Thursday in a trade that became a game of musical chairs for
veteran point guards. Terrell Brandon went to Minnesota and Sam
Cassell wound up in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury came home, which, Anderson now realizes, is not always a
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think going to the Nets will be easier than going to the
Knicks,'' Anderson said, referring to one of several other teams
that were interested in Marbury, ``because they want to win a
championship right now. The pressure is on. In New Jersey, they're
just hoping to make the playoffs. But there will be some major
distractions involved, no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson alternated between awesome and inconsistent with the
Nets, being selected to the All-Star team with Derrick Coleman in
1993 but ultimately failing to become a cornerstone for a franchise
that seemed to be on the rise in the early 1990s. That failure had
to do with both injuries and with Anderson's struggle to keep his
professional and personal lives separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell Stephon to make sure he uses aliases in hotels
and to concentrate on basketball as much as he can,'' Anderson
said. ``When I first heard about it, I was like, `Oh, man, he's
going back to Brooklyn.' I felt good for him. But then I remembered
the other side of it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to give you VIP tickets to this and that, ask
you to attend certain parties. You've really got to watch out.
Everybody's not your friend. Everybody's not in it for your best
interests.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clippers Must Learn to Share
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the facts that their owner will not invest money to keep
good players, their home court is the eyesore of the NBA and the
phone system in their main office often does not work, the Los
Angeles Clippers are terrible this season for an age-old basketball
reason: selfishness.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the players on the active roster will be free
agents. To secure better deals next season and escape the vortex of
the dreadful 1-18 franchise, some of those players have decided
that their own numbers will bring them more rewards than team
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad, but that's the situation a lot of guys are in,''
said Maurice Taylor, the starting power forward, who scored 13
points in the Clippers' 106-92 victory over Sacramento on Thursday
night. ``It's like, I can understand part of it. But I also think
teams want winners, people that play the right roles and
contribute. We haven't totally understood that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Douglas, the veteran point guard, said: ``I've never
seen anything like it. Some guys are definitely looking out for
themselves before the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMES-SQUARE-HOTEL-AR     03-13 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-HOTEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTEL TO BE BUILT ATOP NEW CINEPLEX ON 42ND STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Construction workers are building a foundation for a
455-room Doubletree Hotel in Times Square, but unlike most
foundation work, this is going on almost 200 feet in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopment of the Times Square area is producing some
unconventional structures, none more so than the building on the
south side of 42nd Street, between Seventh and Eighth Avenues, that
will have 13 levels in its base, plus the hotel on the roof. The
$290 million project will include stores, restaurants and a
25-screen movie theater capable of seating 5,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   As an opening move for the development, the 7.4-million-pound
Empire Theater was picked up last year from where it had sat since
being completed in 1912 and moved 180 feet west to serve as the
entrance to the new AMC cinemas.
</P>
<P>
   The developer of the project, Forest City Ratner Cos. of
Brooklyn, had first envisioned building just an entertainment
complex on the site, but when more money became available for the
project, the company decided to put the hotel on the roof. So the
project had to be redesigned, but the addition of the
60-million-pound structure on top of the 41st Street side of the
lower building posed substantial challenges for the architects and
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   In a conventional building, a grid of support columns runs from
the base to the top, and the weight of the structure is spread
among them.
</P>
<P>
   But movie theaters cannot have columns blocking sight lines, and
without them, all that weight on the roof would be sitting over a
lot of empty space. In addition, the 41st Street side of the
complex incorporates the historic Liberty Theater, which amounts to
another hollow box in the structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotel sits on top of a confusing array of spaces,'' said
Frederick Bland, a partner in Beyer Blinder Belle, the principal
architects. ``It's an incredible Swiss cheese with all those
holes.''
</P>
<P>
   The E-Walk development of Tishman Realty and Construction across
42nd Street faced many similar problems because a 10-story annex to
a hotel to be built on that site, the Westin New York at Times
Square, will sit on top of a 13-screen cinema. But the problem was
not as severe because the top of E-Walk is about 100 feet high,
about half that at the Ratner project.
</P>
<P>
   Forest City Ratner chief executive Bruce Ratner described the
construction of his project as ``a very complicated, hard job.''
But with hotels in Manhattan as close to full as they can get,
adding the hotel was financially attractive, despite the
engineering and construction difficulties, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to support the weight and other forces acting on
the hotel was to build a massive 1,500-ton steel truss similar to
the exposed beams at the Port Authority bus terminal across Eighth
Avenue as the foundation. The truss will support the hotel and
shift its weight to the few vertical columns available, then
directly to the sturdy bedrock that supports most buildings in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Because not many columns went all the way from the top to the
ground, larger columns were substituted, even at the cost of
intruding on theater spaces. ``It was difficult enough to arrange
columns without that behemoth on top,'' Bland said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he said, the bigger columns were fitted in. ``We
were able to do it and still accommodate the theaters,'' he said.
``We did lose some seats, but it was within the range that AMC
could live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of recent changes in the city's building code, the
designers also had to protect against the possibility of an
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   That requirement had serious implications for a building that
will be more than 425 feet high at its peak. If the ground were to
move in an earthquake, engineers said, the hotel at the top of the
structure would act like an inverted pendulum, trying to swing in
response to the shaking. Engineers say the new building code forced
them to add bulk to the foundation structure, though not to change
the basic design.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its exotic underpinning, the 25-story hotel will be
utterly conventional in design and built of reinforced concrete,
the most commonly used building material in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Guests of the hotel will have no way of knowing that the whole
building sits on only eight steel columns and a reinforced concrete
wall that runs to the ground on the west side, because everything
will be enclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will they know that 13 feet on the east side of the hotel
has been extended from the last supporting column, with no columns
directly underneath. There is no reason they should they care,
since the design and specifications have been inspected and
approved by city agencies, said Robert Sanna, Forest City Ratner's
director of construction.
</P>
<P>
   The components of the foundation are hulking. One of the two
major truss structures in the foundation weighs 750,000 pounds. It
will be fastened to the building by 8,400 pounds of bolts. In all,
the foundation weighs about 3 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   When working with components of this size, high up in the air,
engineers try to leave as little to chance as possible. The
components were cut, drilled, welded and fitted together at a
factory in Toronto before being taken apart for shipment to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the components were so heavy that they required both
cranes operating at the site to lift them, a tricky undertaking,
especially when the cranes have to turn in unison to swing the
components into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little late to find out in the field that bolt holes
are not in alignment,'' said Jeffrey Smilow, project manager for
Ysrael A. Seinuk, the structural engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Smilow said components were being bolted together rather than
welded because of the difficulty of controlling the quality of
welding in an open air setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what a bolt will do,'' he said. ``With field welding
you could end up with cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said engineers had to carefully isolate the Liberty Theater.
``There is a compatibility issue here,'' he said. ``This building
has a steel frame, while the Liberty is largely brick. If they were
connected, the Liberty would be ripped apart by the movement of the
steel.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was fabricated by Canron Construction, the same
company that built the supports for the platform over the Franklin
D. Roosevelt Drive that permitted the expansion of New York
Hospital. According to executives on the project, the company is
one of the few that can handle a project of this magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get a lot of bidders on a job like this,'' Ratner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the steel was bought from mills in North
America, some of the components called for were so thick that no
mill on this side of the Atlantic Ocean could supply them, said
Graeme Duff, Canron's manager for the project. ``We had to get them
from Luxembourg,'' he said. He said the beams weighed 750 pounds
per linear foot, compared to a few hundred pounds per foot for
typical construction columns.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the hotel and the cinema, the development will
include a Madame Tussaud's wax museum; an HMV music store; Just for
Feet, an athletic-shoe store that will have a basketball
half-court, and fast-food and cafe-style restaurants operated by
Host Marriott Services.
</P>
<P>
   The store and movie screens are scheduled to open later this
year, while the hotel is scheduled to open next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
