<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL OWNERS READY TO DISCUSS OFFICIATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It was a game against Miami back in the early '70s,'' recalled
Ralph Wilson, 80, for 39 years owner of the Buffalo Bills, spinning
a tale with dancing, colorful wit, wisdom and inflection that few
can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mercury Morris fumbled and one of our defensive ends fell on
the ball,'' Wilson recalled. ``In doing so, the officials ruled he
pushed one of their crew and slapped us with a 15-yard penalty and
gave the ball back to the Dolphins! We were getting back into the
game, and that killed us! Miami went on to score and win. I didn't
like it. I said so afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got 10 G's for that one.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Pete Rozelle, then commissioner of the National Football
League, who fined Wilson $10,000 for disparaging remarks about NFL
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, for only the second time in his nearly four decades
of pro football, Wilson was fined again, this time by Paul
Tagliabue, the current NFL commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   It was in a late-November game, Buffalo at New England, and as
the final seconds ticked away, on New England's desperation pass
into the end zone, Buffalo was called for pass interference. There
was pushing and shoving aplenty by players for both teams on the
play, and usually no penalty is called in that situation. This
time, it was. New England was awarded the ball near the goal line,
scored a touchdown and won, 25-21.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Wilson said things like, ``We got robbed!'' and
``It's awful!'' and ``That was a jump ball, and how is it our guys
were interfering!'' and ``Horrible!''
</P>
<P>
   He got fined 50 G's for that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, $50,000? Inflation, I guess,'' Wilson cracked this week.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson hopes to have the last say. NFL owners meet this week in
Phoenix in their annual spring meeting and officiating and instant
replay will command center stage. Wilson leads a group of owners
who are expected to bring replay back to the NFL for the 1999
season. There is growing discontent with officiating _ too many
rules, too many bad calls, too many game-swinging bad calls _
owners and coaches say. Enough discontent to bring back replay
after a seven-year absence. It was last used from the 1986 through
1991 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been anti-instant replay,'' said Wilson, ``but
...''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. Thinking of last season _ the New England game, and
the Jets game when Vinny Testaverde scored a game-ending,
game-winning, phantom touchdown on a run in which he actually did
not cross the goal line _ made him want to cry. Both games were
Bills losses, and both easily could have been Bills victories. Both
games cost Buffalo a chance to play its first-round playoff game at
home. Instead, the Bills played on the road, at Miami, and lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officiating last year and really the last couple of years
has helped to change my mind,'' Wilson said. ``If an offensive
lineman breathes, it's called motion. The officiating needs to be
simplified and streamlined. And it's not just calls against us. We
benefited in a game last year where they called pass interference,
and the ball was 10 feet over the head of the receiver and the
defensive back. No way it was going to be caught by us, but there
was the flag. Replay cannot correct all of these things, but it's a
start. I'm for it _ now, let's see what kind of system we're
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk is that the owners will be presented a replay system
tied to challenges. A team would receive two challenges a game and
extra challenges in the final two minutes of each half. The referee
makes the final decision on the challenge. If the call is upheld,
the team that requested the challenge loses a timeout. If the call
is overturned, the team that makes the challenge does not lose a
timeout. In the final two minutes, an official upstairs can halt
play and ask for a review of a play and the referee will again make
the final call.
</P>
<P>
   This system, or some variation of it, seems certain to pass.
Approval will require 24 of the 31 owners' votes.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, though, says beware.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into one of these meetings there is no such thing
as a lock,'' he said. ``There is no sure thing. I've gone into a
few of these where everything looked certain and everybody left
saying, `What happened?'''
</P>
<P>
   The owners this week are expected to consider approval of the
Washington Redskins sale for $800 million to real estate magnate
Howard Milstein and to award the league's 32nd franchise to either
Houston or Los Angeles. Los Angeles is the front-runner, where two
groups in the city are vying for ownership.
</P>
<P>
   A testy vote might occur on the idea of rotating the
Thanksgiving Day games to several teams around the league rather
than allowing current host cities Detroit and Dallas alone to
continue the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said: ``What I've seen happen in the last 10 years has
taken away too much tradition in the NFL. Why are we trying to
shred away the last bit we have? I strongly disapprove of this. The
fans in Detroit, in particular, go to this game and sell it out
every year despite the team's record. Families take their kids and
have been doing so for years. It's more than a game there. Moving
it is a bad idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
