<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COACHES IN THE COLLEGE RANKS FEEL EACH OTHER'S PAIN
 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GEORGE VESCEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ For the poor, beleaguered basketball coach, it's always
something.
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't a virus, it's a very visible simian perched on the
shoulder of Jim Calhoun, who coached on wobbly legs Saturday while
his Connecticut team routed New Mexico, 78-56, in the second round
of the national college basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut goes around with its own personal monkey leering at
the world, reminding people that the campus in rural Storrs is
psychologically much closer to Fenway Park in Boston than Yankee
Stadium in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun personifies Bambino terror because his Huskies have not
yet made it to the Final Four, which is apparently the only public
measure of worth in this haunted business.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can win and win, but people will say, `He's never won the
big one,''' said Nolan Richardson of Arkansas, grinding Calhoun's
ax instead of his own for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the heck is the big one?'' Richardson asked, blaming the
rising demands on ``a six-pack of beer and talk radio,'' a lethal
and common blend, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   All coaches know angst, or so it seems. Ron Jirsa was fired by
Georgia the other day after only two seasons, and his colleagues
are upset. And Clem Haskins has to go back to Minnesota to confront
a scandal after a former academic adviser told a highly credible
tale of supplying term papers and taking examinations for 20 of our
noble scholar-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   It is a quaint custom, this doing one's own work. In these
Internet days, a huge percentage of any student body undoubtedly
downloads somebody else's interpretation of Hamlet, but only the
scholarship player is accused as publicly as four Minnesota players
were before a loss to Gonzaga on Thursday. They sat out the game,
which is a context clue that the university suspects the charges
just might be true.
</P>
<P>
   Haskins says he didn't know anything. Never handled the money.
Never saw the papers. Wasn't there. Didn't see. This stance may
qualify him to replace Juan Antonio Samaranch as president of the
International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The four senior citizens in Saturday's doubleheader all seemed
to agree that theirs is a thankless occupation. Calhoun, 56, is
tired of talking about the Final Four. Dave Bliss of New Mexico,
55, was brooding that he often has to coach against the collective
wisdom of the entire community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players all have their entourages,'' Bliss said the other
day. ``They've got parents, guardians, soul mates and summer
coaches, and they're all blowing smoke. The players don't know
which coach to listen to. We call it `the self-esteem gap.' It's
not a good situation in college basketball right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches in the second game had their own gloomy outlook. Tom
Davis, 60, went into the game against Arkansas knowing that he had
exactly one more loss left in his career at Iowa. The athletic
director made a few rambling comments about why he was dumping
Davis, but the coach has taken the high road _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing what I've done for 13 years in terms of trying to
develop the program, a clean program that is respected around the
country for playing by the rules with good guys _ stuff like
that,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who would coach against Davis Saturday, took the
firing personally. Richardson always takes things personally. He
believes himself to be part of an endangered species of aging coach
that he calls ``cowboys.'' Richardson hails, after all, from out in
the west Texas town of El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Even as secure and establishment a figure as Dean Smith
qualified in Richardson's pantheon of cowboys. So does ``Doctor
Tom'' Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches like Tom, myself, John Thompson, John Chaney _ to me,
those are the cowboys,'' Richardson said on Friday. ``Our days are
numbered. But are the numbered ones as bad as the ones coming
behind them?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm the age I am at,'' said Richardson, who is 57.
``I'm glad I don't have to look over my shoulder at some little
young A.D. who's come to fire me. Some of them are hired to fire
you, and then they get fired themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Richardson was less morbid than usual because he had
won a victory earlier in the week when the NCAA's system of
admission standards was challenged by a court decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun because of Proposition 16,'' Richardson said,
perhaps envisioning a new millennium of each school setting its own
standards for entrance to higher education, which sounds like pure
anarchy rather than the ordered world that coaches profess to
respect.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson himself wishes more people would admire the high
calling of coaching. He has the fantasy of asking a surgeon buddy
of his if he can wield the scalpel in the operating room, the same
way people think they can coach better than he can. Or he envisions
himself chatting up the captain of an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, baby, let me fly this plane,'' Richardson said he
imagines himself saying. ``It's all right. I read the manual.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson added, ``The 140 people in the plane would think I'm
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   No more crazy, of course, than civilians thinking they could
make a better game plan than Richardson. It's always something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
