<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FLYTYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: THE PLEASURE OF TYING FLIES AS SPRING NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the land emerging from March's brutal embrace, this is the
ideal time for fly tying.
</P>
<P>
   Hooks, fur, feathers, tinsel, thread and floss arranged on your
desk, you can sit at your fly-tying vise, and _ as your creations
blossom under your fingers _ indulge in thoughts of the delights
that lie ahead when the soft days of the fifth month arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Because certain patterns of commercially tied fishing flies sell
for more than $5 each, economics often plays a significant role in
such endeavors. Home-tied flies cost only a fraction of the
store-bought ones if you don't count your labor, and if you have
been a serious fly fisher for a long time, you will probably have
scores, even hundreds, of flies in your possession, some for trout
or Atlantic salmon, some for fresh water black bass or pan fish and
still others for salt-water species such as striped bass, bluefish
and Atlantic bonito.
</P>
<P>
   Catching fish with self-tied flies is the major thrill awaiting
practitioners of this gentle craft, but there is solid satisfaction
in filling your fly books and fly boxes with row upon row of
handsome new creations arranged by size, type and intended quarry.
It is akin to ordering seeds and plants for your garden when frost
is still in the ground. It will also be the one time in the year
when your flies are properly organized. When you are actually
fishing, which always involves some changing or replacing of flies
and swift reactions to shifts in weather, available light or the
feeding patterns of your prey, the excitement of the endeavor will
conspire to create chaos out of order.
</P>
<P>
   You would be wise to concentrate on one or two patterns at each
tying session. Failing that, you will wind up with a bewildering
welter of materials and hooks on your desk. Each pattern requires
special technique _ whether winding on hackle, spinning deer hair
for a head or matching feathers for wings _ and it's best to tie at
least a dozen of each until the drill becomes automatic.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a beginner, you will, after fashioning a few of the
standard patterns described in step-by-step illustrations in your
just-bought fly-tying text, begin to think that you are ready to
invent something of your own. You aren't, but don't let that deter
you. It's a syndrome that every neophyte tier experiences.
</P>
<P>
   A few months or years later when the madness has departed you
will look at the melange of dreadful objects that you tucked away
on a shelf after they took few or no fish, and wonder how you could
have been so foolish. There are hundreds of recognized fly patterns
_ most of them for trout _ and it takes a certain amount of
audacity to think that you can devise yet another.
</P>
<P>
   But as the years pass, you may reach a stage wherein you are
equipped through experience to develop a fly of your own, although
its fame may not extend beyond your circle of friends or your
region. Few will come up with a fly that takes the country by storm
as did Don Gapen's Muddler Minnow.
</P>
<P>
   Some fly tiers learn that they do not possess the dexterity or
the patience to fashion truly small dry flies for trout. The hooks
for these flies, Nos. 22 or 24, are so tiny that two dozen of them
will fit on a postage stamp. If this applies to you, don't fret.
Tie the larger flies and purchase the smaller ones.
</P>
<P>
   While actually fishing, you will discover that minor changes in
recognized patterns _ perhaps a different butt or tail _ will
sometimes produce salubrious results. This is particularly true
with Atlantic salmon and trout. And there's also the matter of
sparseness. Under some circumstances, a fly pattern known to be
effective may not catch many fish if it is heavily-dressed, meaning
it's tied with an amplitude, rather than a paucity, of the
materials called for. A sparsely-tied fly will often elicit strikes
when its fuller counterpart on the same size hook is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Never, by the way, think that choosing the right fly is the only
key to successful fly fishing. Your presentation of a fly to the
fish is sometimes more important than its pattern. Fish are
opportunists, programmed to make instantaneous decisions on whether
to grab some passing morsel.
</P>
<P>
   It often happens that an artificial fly bearing little
resemblance to the critters upon which the fish has been gorging is
snatched up when it passes the quarry's field of vision in a
different and tantalizing manner. This is also a warning against
changing flies after every half-dozen nonproductive casts. No fly
will catch fish if it isn't in the water.
</P>
<P>
   As the seasons roll past, the fly tier accumulates substantial
quantities of fur, body hair, deer and squirrel tails, feathers and
hackle, which are stored, properly moth-proofed, in boxes and
bureau drawers. Some were purchased, but others might have been
gathered while hunting or taken from animals that failed to safely
negotiate highways. Gifts of such materials will also come your way
and when you put them on your fly tying desk you are reminded of
happy fishing trips with their donors.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago I began to tie some flies for striped bass. I
commonly use bucktail for this, but then I remembered that I had
been given a swatch of long and lustrous polar bear hair by Harold
``Buster'' Welch of Winnipeg, Manitoba, a few years ago after we
went fishing together for stripers off the beaches of Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   I have been hoarding it because it is unusually difficult to
obtain, but this spring I shall fashion at least a dozen polar bear
streamers and think fondly of Buster when the first striper hits
and doggedly bores offshore in the heaving, nighttime waters of
Vineyard Sound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
