<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PENGUINS-940(2TAK     03-13 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PENGUINS-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO SAVE A BANKRUPT TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once again, Mario Lemieux was the center, moving
forward with purpose and with teammates on each wing. But this was
not a comeback for the retired hockey star who left the game too
soon because of injuries and illness. Instead of wearing Pittsburgh
Penguins uniforms and carrying hockey sticks, these men wore
business suits and carried briefcases. Instead of crossing ice,
they moved over the sidewalks of midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Like many fellow pedestrians, they were on a shopping trip last
Thursday afternoon, but not for clothing, jewelry, appliances or a
better apartment. Lemieux and his men hoped to buy a hockey team,
the Penguins, a bankrupt franchise worth about $100 million but
owing more than that in debt. Inside those briefcases was the
paperwork representing the money. At age 33, a Hall of Famer who
wore No. 66 wants to run a team in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit scary,'' Lemieux said of his venture into
big business. ``But we feel we have a great chance in Pittsburgh
for a fresh start. We feel we have a great chance to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is also scary, for Lemieux and for Pittsburgh.
Because the current ownership, led by Roger Marino, has filed for
bankruptcy, Lemieux could lose much of the $31 million the Penguins
still owe him in deferred salary. He retired in 1997 after two
Stanley Cups, two back surgeries and a recovery from Hodgkin's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Marino has also requested permission from the federal bankruptcy
court to shop the franchise to other cities.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be back before the judge this week. Lemieux and
his lawyers were on their way to meet with Gary Bettman, the
commissioner of the National Hockey League. Bettman also heard
presentations from two other groups last Thursday, including
Marino's.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux wants to convert part of the money owed to him into a
share of the franchise ownership. Lemieux said he has recruited
other investors who will put up additional financing, between $40
million and $50 million. If Lemieux can convince both the NHL.and
the judge that his money and his intentions are sound, he could
become, in a few months, the controlling owner of the same
franchise he led to Stanley Cup championships in 1991 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the hockey side of it,'' Lemieux said, when asked about
his ownership qualifications. ``I've always been able to surround
myself with some smart people over the years.'' He said Craig
Patrick, the current general manager, ``is one of the best.'' And
he added: ``We have a good coaching staff, a pretty good young
team. The future looks good.''
</P>
<P>
   But who will provide the money? Lemieux said he has put together
a group of backers, including a single significant investor he
refers to only as Mr. Wonderful. The identity of the investor will
be revealed eventually, Lemieux said, but certainly not before
Lemieux and his group present their plan to the bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux emphasized that the man is a sound investor, but the NHL
has a troubled recent history with mysterious investors. A few
years ago, the Islanders were purchased by a mystery man named John
Spano. When it turned out that Spano did not have the money he said
he had, Spano lost the franchise and ended up in jail. Isn't
Lemieux a friend of Spano?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was,'' Lemieux said, stressing the past tense of the verb.
Spano is not the only embarrassment the league has had recently on
the ownership level. Bruce McNall, the former chairman of the board
of governors and the owner who brought Wayne Gretzky to Los
Angeles, also went to jail for financial fraud. The Tampa Bay
Lightning recently got its third ownership in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league has to be careful who they deal with,'' Lemieux
said. ``They got fooled a couple times.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Greenberg, one of Lemieux's lawyers, said Lemieux's group
has an advantage over the Marino group and the other prospective
ownership group because Lemieux's image in Pittsburgh will rally
fans, investors and politicians to the cause of saving the
franchise. Television deals and arena leases may need reworking and
the team wants a new arena to replace the current building, which
is more than 30 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current regime no longer has the good will necessary to
pull the different segments of the community together to turn the
situation around,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Lemieux represents the cachet, not the cash.
``This franchise is worth considerably more if Mario is the
principal owner,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux was asked about the way Marino handled the business
affairs of the Penguins in his two years of ownership. Did Lemieux
feel betrayed?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed in the way they handled the whole
situation,'' Lemieux said. ``He just decided not to pay anybody.
After 12 years of giving everything I had for the franchise, I felt
that I was cheated a little bit. That's Roger Marino. That's his
character. That's just the way he is. That's the way he does
business. He tries to bully everybody because he has a lot of
money. It just didn't work out in Pittsburgh. We stood up to him
and that's why he had to go into bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   A call to Marino for comment was not returned. Following the day
of meetings with the three groups trying to take control of the
team, the NHL issued a statement from William Daly, senior vice
president for legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are satisfied that substantial progress has been made,''
Daly's statement said. ``Although there remain certain significant
conditions that will need to be satisfied, we understand that
parties are continuing to work to resolve those remaining issues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux said Bettman ``has been very supportive'' but added,
``He has to wait and see if we're for real, if we have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   In that he is five years younger than players like Gretzky, Mark
Messier and Ray Bourque, is it possible that Lemieux would make a
comeback and become a player/owner? ``I have no plan on coming
back, even if I get no money,'' said Lemieux, who scored 613 goals
in 745 games over a 12-year career. ``I've been through a lot, with
the cancer and the back surgeries. To get back and play with these
guys would be torture.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last few seasons, Lemieux was harshly critical of the
league for allowing obstruction tactics to nullify the skills of
great players. Although goal-scoring is still low, about 5.3 goals
a game, Lemieux is among those hockey observers who think new rules
have improved the level of play for the most talented players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's showing,'' he said. ``It's very exciting for the fans and
the players.''
</P>
<P>
   With the league expanding from 27 teams to 30 teams in the next
two seasons, does Lemieux think there is enough talent to stock so
many teams?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of talent out there, especially in Europe,''
Lemieux said. ``And there are good players coming out of Canada and
colleges in the States.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the contention of some owners that high salaries are
jeopardizing the financial infrastructure of the business?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a lot of upside to it in the future,''
Lemieux said. ``We feel we have a good chance to be successful.
Franchises appreciate every year tremendously. That's the upside.
The top players should make a lot of money. They are the ones who
bring people into the buildings. They make the business what it is
today and they should be paid accordingly. I'm not so sure about
the lower-tier players who score a few goals a year and make two or
three million dollars a year. That eventually will have to change,
I would assume.''
</P>
</TEXT>
