<SLUG> BC-DODD-Y2K-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TRAVELS, DODD SPREADS WORD ABOUT COMPUTER BUG  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Conn. _ A congressional staff member calls it ``the
fine line between Paul Revere and Chicken Little.''
</P>
<P>
   Treading that line is Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, the Connecticut
Democrat, who is using his travels around the state and his network
television appearances to sound an alarm about the year 2000
computer problems, or ``the Y2K bug,'' a programming flaw that
could cause some computers to shut down or go crazy on New Year's
Day, potentially affecting everything from credit card transactions
to air travel.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd, as vice chairman of the Senate Special Committee on the
Year 2000 Technology Problem, is trying to persuade people to make
reasonable preparations (say, keeping copies of bank statements),
without building fallout shelters and stocking up on freeze-dried
food.
</P>
<P>
   That can be tricky. There he was Feb. 28 on NBC's ``Meet the
Press,'' where the senator just smiled when the moderator, Tim
Russert, transposed the nickname and asked about ``the YK2
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd replied, ``We should be OK, but it's not unwise for people
to do a little stockpiling.'' He now says he may have got a bit
carried away with that advice, and instead tells audiences they
should simply use ``good old Yankee precaution'' by squirreling
away two or three days' worth of water and canned goods, as if they
were preparing for a hurricane or ice storm.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor who is a teacher interested him in year 2000 computer
issues back in 1996, and Dodd started urging businesses to assess
their preparedness in 1997. He recalled that for the early hearings
he convened on the topic, getting news coverage was impossible.
``People thought it was funny,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own millennial plans, Dodd said he has always had
extra soup and frozen food on hand at his home in East Haddam, and
said he is likely to celebrate New Year's Eve by renting a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dodd dropped into this Connecticut River town,
according to his schedule, to ``inspect Y2K readiness'' at
Middlesex Hospital. A report released this month by the Senate's
year 2000 committee highlighted Dodd's warning that ``Y2K could put
the health-care industry in intensive care.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a friendly visit that left Dodd pleased with
the progress in health care, one of the sectors that his research
shows is the most vulnerable to disruption on Jan. 1 if computers
act as if the year is 1900.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing for Dodd, complete with slides, the hospital's
administrators said they had determined that 88 percent of their
clinical equipment was ``year 2000 compliant,'' but noted they had
found 1,168 items they could not test _ including beds, doors and
refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very impressive,'' Dodd said. He was dismayed to hear that
some suppliers were resisting the hospital's inquiries about
whether their products had been tested for year 2000 reliability,
and said he plans to work to make such companies responsible for
any failures that result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a special place I'd like to put vendors that don't
share information,'' he said, startling some of the administrators
with his intensity. ``I think a lot of it has to do with lawyers
advising them, but these companies are deluding themselves. If they
cause any kind of a problem, they'll pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the year 2000 fallout is a major issue in
Connecticut, where the capital, Hartford, is headquarters to
several of the nation's largest insurance companies. The Senate
report quoted some estimates of a ``litigation cost in excess of $1
trillion.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd said he was concerned about reports that insurers had begun
adding clauses exempting year 2000 crashes from coverage, which he
said ``could bankrupt small firms'' hit by aftershocks of computer
crashes. (A spokesman for the Insurance Information Institute, the
trade group of property and casualty insurers, said that most
losses caused directly by year 2000 problems would not be covered
by insurance, and that the clauses simply spelled that out.)
</P>
<P>
   Reassured that most businesses and agencies are waking up to the
year 2000 issues, Dodd is sprinkling his speeches and conversations
with a reminder to watch out for problems on Sept. 9, when
programmers say some computers could provide a preview of Jan. 1
glitches by balking at the 9/9/99 date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
