<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-BOYLE-2TAKES     03-13 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-BOYLE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 HOSPITAL IS HAUNTED BY HISTORY OF DEALS WITH BOARD MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORTLANDT, N.Y. _ In the early 1990s, a small nonprofit hospital
just outside Peekskill embarked on an expansion that would
transform it from a homespun but antiquated local landmark into a
regionwide medical center rated among the top 4 percent of the
nation's hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But the makeover of Peekskill Community Hospital into the Hudson
Valley Hospital Center was also striking for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The architect for a new $23 million wing was Lothrop Associates,
which has among its partners Arthur Clements, who resigned from the
hospital's board of directors to perform the work. The wing's
foundation was dug for $1.4 million by a company owned by Joseph
Lois, a board member. The $2.1 million worth of plumbing work was
handled by a board member, Bruce Lindenbaum. The land for a new
birth cottage was acquired for $783,500 from Dan and Ruth Woolfe.
Mrs. Woolfe, too, was a board member.
</P>
<P>
   These entanglements were not illegal because they were fully
disclosed to other board members and cleared by a ruling from the
state attorney general. ``There was zero secrecy,'' Lois said.
</P>
<P>
   But the expansion revealed how relaxed the hospital was about
letting board members do business with it. In recent weeks that
policy has come back to haunt the hospital and its chairman from
1986 to 1996, Robert Boyle, a longtime fund-raiser for Gov. George
Pataki and now executive director of the Port Authority of New York
and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   A federal tax-fraud indictment last month against Albert Pirro
Jr., an influential real estate lawyer married to the popular
Westchester County district attorney, Jeanine Pirro, ensnared the
hospital and Boyle. Federal authorities assert that Boyle owned a
major stake in a Pirro company that sold a medical office building
to the hospital for $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle was not charged in the indictment and was identified only
by his hospital title, not by name. He has denied ownership in the
Pirro company, but the hospital admits that it let Boyle manage
that building's renovation, and associates of Pirro's said that
Boyle was paid $292,000 in ``finder's fees.'' Boyle, however, said
those fees were for an unrelated property.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the tangle of insular deals has illuminated a
little-known facet of nonprofit institutions: members of their
governing boards, while receiving no pay, sometimes profit from
those roles. While such arrangements are not illegal if fully
disclosed and can be beneficial by, for example, offering the
institution discounts, legal experts warn that too lax a policy can
foster a mentality of ``I'll scratch your back if you scratch my
back,'' in which board members drum up work for one another.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the number of directors involved in Hudson Valley's
renovation, John Coffee, a law professor at Columbia University and
a specialist in corporate ethics, said, ``I happen to think that
that's fairly poor corporate governance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a little too much tolerance for self-dealing,'' he
said. ``Norms of reciprocity can develop such as, `If you let my
firm be the architect, I'll let your firm be the general
contractor, and I'll let his firm sell us the property that we may
or may not need.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Coffee said that large nonprofit institutions could prohibit
such self-dealing, but with smaller organizations in less populous
locales, the universe of community leaders and contractors was
smaller and self-dealing might be more common.
</P>
<P>
   In one prominent case, the State Board of Regents removed 18 of
the 19 trustees at Adelphi University in Garden City, N.Y., in 1997
after it found, among other things, that two trustees profited by
taking on the university's insurance and advertising accounts
without full disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirro indictment's references to Hudson Valley have
resonated beyond this northwestern corner of Westchester because of
the hospital's close association with Pataki. The governor served
on the board from 1988 to 1992, and many of his associates have
served there since, including Michael Finnegan, the governor's
counsel from 1995 to 1997, and two former staff members.
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of so many Pataki associates is not surprising
since Pataki grew up in Peekskill and was its mayor for many years.
A hospital traditionally looks for directors who can help it raise
money, offer it expertise and influence government. Still, Hudson
Valley's board has had a particularly Republican cast, heavily
weighted with party allies and contributors. Boyle, who also grew
up in Peekskill, served as Pataki's treasurer in his races for
state Senate in 1992 and for governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Directors now on the 26-member board besides Boyle include Rose
Marie Panio, chairwoman of Yorktown's Republican committee;
Catherine Pisani, a Republican councilwoman in Peekskill, and
Rosemary Braatz, a state Conservative Party committee member who
worked in Pataki's Senate office.
</P>
<P>
   At least once, Pataki was the beneficiary of an organized
fund-raising campaign involving doctors affiliated with the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Dr. Kenneth Schwartz, president of a large group of
radiologists who provided the hospital with X-ray services, held a
fund-raising dinner at his house in Bedford for Pataki, who was
running for his first term as governor. Pataki attended, and dozens
of doctors made donations, including the nine radiologists from the
Schwartz-led group, who gave Pataki $3,400, according to state
campaign records.
</P>
<P>
   One radiologist, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said
he was told that the renewal of the radiology group's contract with
the hospital ``may depend on'' generous donations, and another, a
Democrat, said he was ``gently coerced,'' but five other doctors
said there was no pressure at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally voluntary,'' said Dr. Marc A. Hertz, who gave
$250.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hudson Valley Hospital Center was founded on the downtown
riverbank 110 years ago as Peekskill Hospital and for generations
it served this plain-spoken city of 19,500. But by the 1980s, the
hospital, which had relocated outside Peekskill's borders, was
struggling to survive, with threats of insolvency and outdated
equipment that made it hard to attract doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Into this mess in 1986 strode Boyle, a canny businessman who
made his money in concrete, construction and real estate. By all
accounts, he was the visionary who drew up the strategies hat
rescued the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   After his selection as chairman, he determined that the hospital
needed not only to modernize, but but also to expand its patient
base by placing clinics as far north as Beacon and as far south as
Croton-on-Hudson. Doctors practicing in those outposts would refer
patients and boost hospital revenue.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure on the board, Hudson Valley Hospital, with 120
beds, has tripled its staff to 325 doctors and sharply increased
admissions and patient visits. Patients are drawn by a hospital
with a state-of-the-art emergency room (including its own
helicopter pad), a breast-care clinic and a special exercise room
for cardiac patients. In December, the Joint Commission on the
Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations, examining 500 standards
of care, awarded Hudson Valley a score of 99 percent, a rating
achieved by only 4 percent of the 5,000 accredited hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other person, Boyle, 62, is credited with this
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is his monument, that is his labor of love,'' said a
board member, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``I cannot
believe that man would do anything to harm that institution.''
</P>
<P>
   But questions are being raised within and outside the hospital
about whether Boyle may have improperly benefited from his ties to
the hospital, even though he was generous with his time and donated
large gifts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Boyle learned that a watch-assembly plant in
Croton-on-Hudson, just a few blocks from his home, was for sale.
According to the Pirro indictment, Boyle steered Pirro to the
building and in April, a Pirro-controlled company, Distinctive
Properties of Croton, bought it for $900,000. Around the same time,
the hospital agreed to lease the building as office space for
affiliated doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-count indictment against Pirro, which contends he
deducted personal expenditures like a Ferrari as business expenses,
said Boyle had acquired a 45 percent interest in Distinctive
Properties and, ``in violation of his fiduciary duties,'' never
told the hospital that he partly owned the building it was buying.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle did have the hospital's concurrence to manage the $530,000
renovation of the Croton building through his firm Rogene
Industries. Pat Morrow, a hospital spokesman, said Boyle was paid
$3,000 a month for nine months for managing the subcontractors. In
the minutes of various Croton village committees that had to
approve the renovation Boyle is sometimes referred to as the
building's owner and sometimes as the contractor. The hospital is
never mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew he was the contractor ,'' said Lois, who was on
the board at the time. ``We thought he would do a better job
because he cared for the hospital. I did not have any idea he had
an ownership interest.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1993, Distinctive Properties sold the building to the
hospital for $1.5 million. That would indicate Pirro made a
$600,000 profit in two years. But Boyle benefited amply, according
to the indictment and a Pirro associate. He was paid $292,299 from
Pirro-owned companies, which he did not disclose to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle has issued a statement asserting that he ``had no equity
interest'' in the building, and through his lawyer, Andrew
Levander, said the payments from Pirro were for an unrelated
property. But an associate of Pirro's, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the payments to Boyle were finder's fees for having
steered Pirro to the Croton building. Boyle has referred all
questions about the matter to Levander, who in recent days has not
returned repeated phone calls seeking additional comments.
</P>
<P>
   The same year that the Croton building was sold, the main
hospital campus in Cortlandt began adding a wing and redoing its
ground floor. It was one of the largest local projects in years and
drew intense interest from board members involved in construction.
Lois, who owned Elmar Contracting Co., said that if he had not been
allowed to bid on the excavation, he would have resigned from the
board. He acknowledged that being a director gave him an edge over
other bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you know a project from the inception, you're comfortable
with it and you're predisposed to bid it cheaper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lois said he made no profit from the deal. Lindenbaum said he
was the lowest bidder for the plumbing job. The Woolfes said that
the property they sold was adjacent to the hospital, and that they
donated property as well.
</P>
<P>
   Lois said the real reward for his time on the board could not be
measured in money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a stroke four years ago and a serious one,'' he said,
``and I was glad I had a first-class place to go to and to realize
that 15 years of work on my part and the board's part paid off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
