<HEADLINE>
AFTER A FIRE, SUBWAY RIDERS TAKE A DETOUR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Subway riders in the Carroll Gardens section of
Brooklyn Saturday found a patchwork of shuttle trains and buses to
help them bypass the Bergen Street station of the F and G lines,
whose control panel was ravaged by fire Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Riders on the G train, a little-used local line that makes 26
stops, faced the most disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   A back-and-forth shuttle train replaced the normal trains to the
five stops from Bedford-Nostrand to Hoyt-Schermerhorn in the Fort
Greene neighborhood. The train stopped at Hoyt-Schermerhorn rather
than making its last three stops, but riders could catch a bus
upstairs that ran in a triangle from Hoyt Street to Jay Street _
where they could catch trains into Manhattan or deeper into
Brooklyn _ then down to the closed Bergen Street station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to mean a lot of extra commuting time, and I'm not
happy about it,'' said Stella Ajulu, 36, an environmental
technician from Rego Park, Queens, who was riding the shuttle bus
as the last leg in a morning journey that was also disrupted by
construction elsewhere. ``All I can say is, there has to be a
better plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Repairs to the Bergen Street station are expected to take up to
two months. Melissa Farley, a spokeswoman for New York City
Transit, said the replacement shuttle buses and trains would
continue indefinitely. The cause of the fire remains under
investigation, and the cost of repairs unknown, Ms. Farley said.
</P>
<P>
   Service on the F line resumed at midnight Friday, with trains
bypassing the Bergen Street station. People who normally get on or
off at Bergen could walk a half-dozen blocks to the Carroll Street
station to pick up the train, or catch a special bus up to Jay
Street to meet it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just going to take them a little bit longer,'' Ms. Farley
said. ``We have as much service as we can put out there to get
people where they want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 4 million daily subway riders, Ms. Farley estimated that
the disruptions would affect only about 2,000. The G line carries
only about 10,000 people on weekends and 30,000 on weekdays,
compared to about 500,000 people who ride the system's busiest
lines, including the F and the 4, 5, and 6 trains, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those interviewed seemed unfazed by the delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to set me back about 15 minutes, but it just
means getting here earlier,'' said Robin Pishton, 26, a student at
the Fashion Institute of Technology waiting at Bergen Street for
one of the five buses making the triangle route.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
