<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DABBLING IN DIETS AND OTHER DATA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: You've heard of March Madness. Well, this is March
Mailness, when your Uncle Fearless dives into the mailbag to
retrieve tidbits of interesting reader feedback worth sharing.
Today's first offering concerns confusion over marketing tactics by
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that reputable banks and loan companies seem to be
directing their advertising at people with poor credit? Every day I
hear things like, `Even if you've had a glitch in your credit in
the past...we want to loan you money.' I'm sure there's some logic
to it all, but I just can't figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Confused:
</P>
<P>
   Depends on your definition of reputable. If my bank starts
running an aggressive ad campaign aimed at deadbeats or pitching
home equity loans amounting to 125 percent of the property's value,
my first move will be to start looking for a new bank.
</P>
<P>
   One reader took issue with a column endorsing Medicare reform
proposals designed to ease the program's financial squeeze:
</P>
<P>
   ``Re your callous remarks about Medicare. In a few years you may
not be so anxious to withhold care and be rid of the old geezers
when you have become one of them. Remember: What goes around comes
around. Here's hoping your future brings you all you deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Peeved:
</P>
<P>
   Callous? Moi? As someone within flirtation range of geezerhood
who has a mother almost 84, you misunderstood my point, which
wasn't to withhold care. However, as a parent and grandparent, the
coming health-care needs of me and my spouse are tempered by the
knowledge that whatever my generation does should be done with an
eye toward preserving the system for those who will be paying the
bills that make our benefits possible.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Internet commerce is also gaining momentum, to the
point that one alert reader thought he caught Uncle Fearless doing
a back-pedaling act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interesting piece on the challenges of collecting sales taxes
on Internet transactions. I recall you wrote a (recent) column that
dismissed the importance of Internet commerce, that it accounted
for only a paltry 1 percent of all retail transactions, and that
predictions of meteoric growth were due to hype. What gives? I
sense a contradiction in your writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Alert:
</P>
<P>
   It was inevitable the second column would come back to haunt me.
The first column was in the context of overall U.S. and world
commerce. The subsequent column was in the context of revenue
effects on state and local governments. There really wasn't a
contradiction. Even with catalog sales at $50 billion and Internet
transactions close to $10 billion, this still is a minuscule part
of overall U.S. consumption spending. Given the relatively small
size of many municipal budgets, though, the growing loss of sales
tax revenues to the fast-growing Internet market might create an
inordinate budget squeeze for some local governments throughout
America.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, a fellow muser contributed this thought with the
admonition not to dwell on it too much because it might bring on a
headache:
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in America do people buy double cheeseburgers with a
large fries and a diet soft drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Musing Guy: Amazin', ain't it?
</P>
<P>
   Keep them cards and letters comin', hear?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
