<SLUG> BC-NATO-LIBRARY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE NATIONS JOIN NATO IN CEREMONY AT HARRY S. TRUMAN LIBRARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ On an Independence stage Friday, three new
flags joined those banners belonging to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The colors of Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic were placed
with those of 16 other NATO nations in the Truman Library
auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   The historic sight occurred just after the foreign ministers of
the three nations signed documents certifying their entry into the
alliance. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright then stood with all
three diplomats, enjoying a prolonged ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we recognize in fact what has always been true in
spirit,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we confirm through our actions that the lands of King
Stephen and Cardinal Mindszenty, Charles the Fourth and Vaclav
Havel, Copernicus and Pope John Paul II, reside fully and
irrevocably within the Atlantic community for freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Brief addresses by each foreign minister preceded Albright's
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kavan of the Czech Republic described how he, more than 30
years ago as a visiting student leader advocating freedom in
Czechoslovakia, was in Kansas City, Mo., on the August 1968 day
when the Soviet Union invaded his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is for me very symbolic,'' he said, ``that it is precisely
here that we today accept the guarantee that my country will never
again become a powerless victim of a foreign invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Janos Martonyi of Hungary, meanwhile, stressed that his country
was eager to shoulder the commitments that NATO membership
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bernard Shaw said that `Liberty means responsibility.
That is why most people dread it,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not. Hungarians know that membership in NATO is a
combination of advantages to enjoy and obligations to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hungary's wish to join NATO did not reflect only a desire
for security, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO accession is also about returning Hungary to her natural
habitat,'' Martonyi said. ``It has been our manifest destiny to
rejoin those with whom we share the same values, interests and
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronislaw Geremek of Poland invoked Winston Churchill's 1946
``Iron Curtain'' declaration in Fulton, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, with joy and pride, we celebrate the end of the bipolar
world symbolized by the Iron Curtain,'' Geremek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for Poland as well as for millions of
Poles scattered all over the world. Poland forever returns where
she has always belonged, in the free world. Poland is no longer
alone in the defense of her freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that lasted almost 30 minutes, Albright welcomed the
three nations to a new era of self-determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never again will your fates be tossed around like poker chips
on a bargaining table,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of NATO expansion, Albright added, was a sign that
``we have not grown complacent about protecting the security of our
citizens. The nations entering our alliance today are the first new
members since the Cold War's end, but they will not be the last.
For NATO enlargement is not an event, it is a process.''
</P>
<P>
   In her address, Albright did not discuss specifically the
current negotiations concerning the possible use of U.S. troops as
part of a potential NATO peacekeeping operation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks after the ceremony, however, Kavan of the Czech
Republic remained hopeful that the discussions between U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic would
be fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO could contribute to peace in Kosovo, it could be a
great thing for the Balkans, Europe and the world,'' he said. ``One
obviously has to be prepared for failure, but at the moment let's
hope we shall not be confronted with a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit began at 10:25 a.m., when Albright and the three
foreign ministers arrived at Kansas City's Downtown Airport on an
Air Force One 707 jet.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver was at the runway to greet
them. Limousines, with police motorcades at their side, then
whisked the ministers to the Truman Library.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived back at Downtown Airport at 3:23 p.m. and boarded
their plane, which took off 10 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Among those at the Truman Library ceremony were U.S. Reps. Karen
McCarthy and Ike Skelton of Missouri, as well as U.S. Sen. Barbara
Mikulski of Maryland, who introduced Albright.
</P>
<P>
   For the accession ceremony, Truman Library museum staff members
reached into their collection for the small table on which Harry S.
Truman, in May 1947 at the Hotel Muehlebach in Kansas City, signed
documents authorizing $400 million in aid to Greece and Turkey,
which set the stage for the restabilization of Europe after World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unusual day for the library, which was closed to the
public. Several television trucks lined the drive in front of the
library's front door, and members of the foreign press filled the
gymnasium at the University of Missouri-Kansas City's nearby Truman
campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a renewed respect for NATO,'' Truman Library Director
Larry Hackman announced as the ceremony began. ``I understand now
what it is like to be invaded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
