<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-KAN &LR;      03-13 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL, DOCTORS GROUP AGREE TO SETTLE FRAUD ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Truman Medical Center and a related doctors
group have agreed to pay the federal government $242,500 to settle
allegations of Medicare fraud, U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr.
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said Truman and Hospital Hill Health Services Corp. agreed
to pay the money to settle a civil lawsuit over allegedly
fraudulent billings for tests performed on elderly and low-income
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Truman and Hospital Hill Health Services, which employs the
doctors who practice at Truman, also have promised to cooperate
with the government in a separate but related criminal
investigation into alleged health-care fraud activities at the
hospital, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Chris Whitley said the U.S. attorney's office could
not comment on the criminal investigation except to say that it was
related to the civil case.
</P>
<P>
   John Bluford, executive director and chief executive officer of
Truman, said in a phone interview late Friday from his current home
in Minnesota that Medicare and Medicaid billings involve 12,000
different codes for different procedures that must be correctly
matched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tedious,'' Bluford said. ``All the services billed were
provided. The question involves how they were documented. I don't
think there was any intentional fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Friday, Truman stated that it and Hospital
Hill Health Services agreed to the settlement ``to avoid the
expense and uncertainty of the legal process. We have cooperated
and will continue to cooperate fully with the government's
investigation into Medicare and Medicaid billing issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, announced Friday, is the latest example of a
nationwide crackdown on fraud in government medical insurance
programs such as Medicare, which serves 39 million elderly and
disabled beneficiaries and faces the danger of financial collapse
in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The government contended that Truman and Hospital Hill Health
Services billed and received payments from Medicare for
electro-cardiogram and echo-cardiography tests to screen or ``rule
out'' diagnoses, or as part of pre-operative procedures. Medicare
does not allow such billings, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Andrew
J. Lay, who negotiated the civil settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said: ``The conduct as we alleged was not simply a
situation involving paperwork mistakes or the hospital's inability
to understand the appropriate regulations. This was a deliberate,
methodical and sustained scheme to file fraudulent claims to
defraud Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   The government said the alleged violations occurred at Truman's
Hospital Hill campus and at Truman Medical Center East from about
January 1994 through December 1996, before the current
administration at Truman was in place.Bluford stepped in as
Truman's executive director and chief executive officer March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bluford replaced E. Ratcliffe Anderson Jr., who came to Truman
in November 1996 and left last year. Anderson's predecessor was Jim
Mongan, who headed the medical center from 1981 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Mongan could not be reached for comment Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Truman's news release said the investigation showed that medical
services provided to patients were ``necessary and appropriate. The
issues investigated relate to whether the bills in question were
prepared with the correct description and billing codes.''
</P>
<P>
   The release from Truman also stated that Truman and Hospital
Hill Health Services have instituted measures, such as employee
training sessions, ``to ensure to the fullest extent possible these
types of billing errors will not happen in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil allegations against Truman and Hospital Hill Health
Services were stated in a federal lawsuit filed under seal in
federal court in Kansas City in July 1997. The lawsuit and
settlement agreement were unsealed and made public Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The civil complaint and settlement do not specify how much
Medicare paid for the allegedly fraudulent billings, Whitley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bluford declined to give a specific figure but said the amount
of the billings and the level of alleged inaccuracies were
``minuscule and insignificant in the context of the tens of
thousands of transactions we do every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitley countered: ``Perhaps it's true that viewed in the
context of the hospital's total billings for services, this would
seem small. But it is in fact a very significant case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluford added that many services from many health care providers
were probably underbilled because of the complexities of billing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement with Truman comes at a critical time for the
medical center's facilities, which are operated by a nonprofit
corporation and function as Kansas City's and Jackson County's
``safety net'' hospitals, providing treatment for many indigent
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing financial demands and shrinking government
subsidies, Truman is trying to break even during its current fiscal
year, which ends April 30.
</P>
<P>
   During its latest fiscal year, Truman received 15 percent of its
revenue from Medicare and 63 percent from Medicaid. Truman gets $32
million a year from city and county tax levies and may ask for
more.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Kansas City health care community hope Bluford,
former head of Hennepin County Medical Center in Minneapolis, can
put Truman on stronger financial footing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
