<HEADER>
A9252 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENUHIN-OBIT-KAN &LR;      03-13 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENUHIN-OBIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEHUDI MENUHIN, VIOLINIST, CONDUCTOR, HUMANITARIAN, DIES AT AGE
82 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANTRELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Yehudi Menuhin, one of the most beloved figures in
20th-century classical music, died Friday at age 82.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin, who made his name as a great violinist before
developing an estimable career as an orchestral conductor, died of
heart failure in a Berlin hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He was in Berlin to conduct the Warsaw Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Born April 22, 1916, in New York to Russian Jewish parents,
Menuhin was all of 7 when he made his professional debut in San
Francisco. He created a stir in New York two years later and a
sensation in Paris in 1927. He then began off-and-on study with the
great Romanian violinist and composer George Enescu, who was to be
his most important mentor.
</P>
<P>
   A 1927 New York performance of the Beethoven Violin Concerto,
with conductor Fritz Busch, made Menuhin an international
celebrity. He made his first recordings the next year, and his
magnificent 1932 recording of the violin concerto by Edward Elgar,
with the composer conducting, became one of the most famous in
history. Rarely out of print since its initial release, it's now
available on a compact disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tremendously elegant playing,'' says John Adams,
principal violist of the Kansas City Symphony. ``While it was
certainly emotional, it was very elegant and very pure.''
</P>
<P>
   Although obviously gifted with great natural facility, Menuhin
in later years wasn't always the tidiest player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the great violinists,'' says Tiberius Klausner,
concertmaster of the Kansas City Symphony and emeritus professor of
violin at the University of Missouri-Kansas City Conservatory of
Music. ``There is no question about it. But later, his problems
showed. His bow arm was shaking and his intonation was not
reliable. In the last years he probably should not have played.''
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin had a lifelong concern with humanitarian issues. During
World War II he gave more than 500 concerts for American and Allied
troops. In 1947 he became the first Jewish artist to play with the
Berlin Philharmonic after the overthrow of the Nazi regime.
Criticized in some circles for doing so, he said he wanted to
further ideas of tolerance and ``the brotherhood of man.''
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin settled in London in 1959, but didn't become a British
citizen until 1985. Awarded an honorary knighthood in 1965, he
became Lord Menuhin in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, in 1938, was to Nola Nicholas, daughter of
an Australian millionaire. They had one son and a daughter before
being divorced in 1947. Later that year, Menuhin married ballerina
Diana Gould, with whom he had two more sons.
</P>
<P>
   It was during his tenure as director of the Bath Festival in
England, between 1958 and 1968, that Menuhin began to make a name
as a conductor. He and the festival orchestra toured throughout the
world and made pioneering recordings of baroque music.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin eventually gave up playing to devote his attention to
conducting, appearing with leading orchestras all over the world.
Among his notable later recordings was a second one of the Elgar
Violin Concerto. This time, five decades after his collaboration
with the conductor, Menuhin was on the podium, with the Russian
violinist Dmitry Sitkovetsky as soloist.
</P>
<P>
   Musical education was another cause close to Menuhin's heart. He
promoted the teaching of music in English schools and founded a
boarding school for musically talented children and a foundation in
Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin's enthusiasms went beyond classical music. He became
interested in Indian music and philosophy, and pioneered what now
is called crossover by performing and recording with the Indian
sitar master Ravi Shankar. He also performed with the French jazz
violinist Stephane Grappelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just such a sincere man,'' said Adams, who heard
Menuhin perform numerous times and once met him. ``There was such
sincerity in everything he did _ his teaching, his research into
Indian music. He influenced a lot of people just by being what he
was, almost as much as by what he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
