<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9254 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAIN-IMAGING-KAN &LR;      03-13 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-IMAGING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS ANNOUNCE BREAKTHROUGHS IN BRAIN IMAGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ Imagine being able to watch a human brain as it
thinks: To see on a computer screen the cascade of electrical
signals that run through the brain as it sees a person, remembers
who he is and decides whether to wave ``hello.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the University of Missouri-Columbia and at
Washington University in St. Louis said Friday they have assembled
an array of technology that may ultimately unlock many such secrets
of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference on the MU campus, they presented a new device
developed at MU that uses low-powered laser light shot through
holes in a motorcycle helmet to look into the brain. The Event
Related Optical Signal (EROS) scanner is uniquely capable of
pinpointing where and when brain activity occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the verge of actually understanding how the brain as
a whole works,'' said Ed Maclin, an MU research psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers hope to use EROS and more conventional
technology to learn not only how a normal brain works, but also to
discover the sources of the many disorders that plague the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to fight an enemy (mental illness) you can't see,''
MU psychologist Steve Hackley said. ``This will make it as easy to
see sickness in the mind as it is to see a broken bone in the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   Although practical applications for patients are still far in
the future, the research, which involves dozens of researchers
collaborating at the two universities, may eventually yield many
medical benefits. For example, the technology may one day make it
possible to:
</P>
<P>
   - Locate crucial areas of language and memory that a surgeon
should avoid in brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   - Determine the exact causes of a learning or attention deficit
disorder in children so that the most appropriate treatment is
given.
</P>
<P>
   - Diagnose whether newly noticed forgetfulness is early
Alzheimer's disease or normal aging.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at several other universities in the United States
and abroad also are working on EROS technology. The researchers in
Columbia on Friday called EROS a major advance because it allows
them to see how a stimulus, such as a sound or a picture on a
computer screen, triggers a sequence of events in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The EROS computer produces a map of the brain that flashes in
bright reds and yellows on a computer screen when a portion of the
brain is activated.
</P>
<P>
   ``By knowing how a sequence lights up you really get a glimpse
about how thinking works,'' MU psychologist Monica Fabiani said.
</P>
<P>
   Scans by magnetic resonance imaging, like those done in
hospitals, produce the clearest anatomical images of the interior
of the brain. And a special MRI technique called functional MRI, or
fMRI, can locate brain activity by revealing parts of the brain
where blood circulation increases.
</P>
<P>
   But fMRI doesn't have the speed required to follow quick shifts
in brain activity. That's because the surge in blood flow the fMRI
detects may take 10 or 12 seconds, far longer than the instant it
takes the eye to send an image to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   EROS scans measure the actual activity of nerve cells and can
make images of what occurs in a thousandth of a second.
</P>
<P>
   That permits scientists to see split-second shifts in the
location of brain activity, such as the rapid firing of neurons
during an epileptic seizure.
</P>
<P>
   EROS subjects wear a motorcycle helmet with hundreds of holes
drilled through. Depending on which parts of the brain the
researchers want to study, they insert fiber optic cables into the
helmet holes. A laser shines infrared light through the cables. The
light is at a frequency that is not readily absorbed by brain
tissue so that the brain is somewhat transparent and lets some of
the light through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bouncing light through the brain. This is `Star
Trek'-like technology,'' Washington University researcher Randy
Buckner said.
</P>
<P>
   When neurons in the brain are activated, they become more
transparent to the EROS laser light. The light then travels farther
through the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Light reflected off brain tissue is picked up by other helmet
cables attached to sensors. A computer then gauges time and
location of brain activity.
</P>
<P>
   Fabiani said she is about to begin an EROS study on the effect
of aging on memory. By next year, there may be other studies
involving children, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers also have used a computer to superimpose the EROS
images onto the clearer brain images made by MRI. This creates
revealing pictures of the brain in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of technologies is the future'' of brain
research, said Gabriele Gratton, an MU psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   While MU and Washington University have been collaborating
informally on brain imaging research, researchers at the two
schools hope to create a joint research center, Gratton said.
Washington University is a recognized leader in fMRI research,
while MU has made the greatest advances in EROS, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a collaborative research center has received
tentative approval from administrators on both campuses, Gratton
said. The next step is to attract funding from government agencies,
foundations or other sources, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
