<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRST-HOME-REAL-4TAKE     03-13 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-HOME-REAL-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE FOR FIRST-TIME HOME BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At times, the struggle to become a first-time homeowner seems
like learning to ride a bicycle: You can't help but wonder how
something that seems to have been so easy for others could be so
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But perseverance apparently pays. A survey by the Chicago Title
Corp. found that more than 46 percent of home purchases nationwide
in 1998 were made by first-time buyers. In New York City, the
survey found, 52 percent of home sales in 1998 were made to
first-time buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The combination in recent months of low interest rates and
intense competition among mortgage lenders has been making home
ownership possible for increasing numbers of first-time buyers,
real estate brokers and lenders say.
</P>
<P>
   And offerings like a new mortgage program that allows buyers to
put as little as 3 percent down for a ``handyman's special'' _ and
include the cost of anticipated repairs in the mortgage _ are
making home ownership possible for first-time buyers of more modest
means.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a first home, though, is a bit like buying a custom-made
suit: it may not have to fit perfectly forever, but it sure should
fit nicely now. What follows are some tips, strategies and cautions
offered by brokers, mortgage specialists, lawyers and others with
long experience in real estate for finding the best fit for the
first-time home-buyer's dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first piece of advice I give first-time buyers is to
figure out how much house they can honestly afford,'' said Jack
Hopkins, an associate broker at Harbor Gates Realty in Greenlawn,
N.Y. ``The second is to figure out what kind of house they want to
live in.''
</P>
<P>
   While both suggestions may seem obvious, Hopkins said, it is not
uncommon for those in search of a first home to spend a lot of time
looking at houses they cannot afford. And all that does, the Long
Island broker said, is make it more difficult to be satisfied with
houses within their range.
</P>
<P>
   Finding an affordable house, however, does not always mean
finding a less expensive one. ``I always explain to first-time
buyers that you can work property taxes against the price of the
house to end up with more house for your money,'' Hopkins said,
explaining that a relatively small savings on annual property taxes
can create a sizeable increase in the price of the house one can
afford. ``I show them that at today's interest rates, paying $1,000
a year less in property taxes will enable them to buy a house worth
$12,000 more,'' he said; the increase in buying power comes from
having more money available each month to pay the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hopkins said, someone buying a $150,000 house with
a $135,000 mortgage with a fixed rate of 7.5 percent interest for
30 years would have a monthly mortgage payment of $943.93.
</P>
<P>
   If the property taxes on the house are $5,000, he said, that
would add $416.66 to the monthly payment, resulting in a total
monthly payment of $1,360.59.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, the annual taxes on the house are $4,000 instead of
$5,000 _ a difference of $83.33 a month _ the purchaser could
borrow an additional $12,000 and have the same monthly payment of
$1,360.59.
</P>
<P>
   Some buyers, Hopkins said, particularly young married couples,
spend too much time looking at houses they might be able to afford
but that one or the other doesn't like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many times I'll sit down with couples who
come into my office and find out that neither knows what the other
wants,'' he said, adding that he encourages each to articulate
``the house of their dreams'' to the other, at times using drawings
and cartoons of various kinds of houses to get the conversation
flowing with specific examples. And even if they are far apart, he
said, knowing what the other wants makes it easier to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   A willingness to compromise is, of course, essential. ``You have
to keep an open mind,'' said Gina Guarnieri, a resident of
Bronxville, N.Y., who, with her husband, Andrew Ripps, visited more
than 50 properties before finding one they both liked in Cortlandt
Manor in Westchester County. Like many first-time home-buyers, Ms.
Guarnieri and Ripps started their search with higher expectations
than they eventually realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to try and stay in lower Westchester,'' Ms.
Guarnieri said, explaining that since both she and Ripps work in
Manhattan, they wanted their commute to be as convenient as
possible. But since home prices in Westchester generally increase
as commuting times decrease, the couple found that they would have
to head farther north in the county to get the most house for their
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to find exactly what you want,'' Ms.
Guarnieri said. ``There's always going to be something you're going
to have to sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, location is not the only thing to keep an
open mind about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, I would have preferred a Victorian or a colonial,''
Ms. Guarnieri said, adding that her husband preferred a more
contemporary home. Both were surprised, then, when they walked into
a 2,400 square-foot, three-bedroom contemporary-style home in
Cortlandt Manor priced at $324,900 and she experienced the moment
first-time home-buyers yearn for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it `The Feeling,''' Ms. Guarnieri said, that
undefinable sense that the house is just the right fit.
</P>
<P>
   And while the couple is negotiating with the owner and declined
to say what they are willing to pay, they entered negotiations with
a distinct advantage over less-savvy first-time buyers: They have
already been approved for a mortgage. ``One of the most important
things a first-time buyer can do is get pre-approved for a
mortgage,'' said Peter Bell, chief operating officer of Balch
Buyers Realty in Mamaroneck, N.Y., the company that helped Ms.
Guarnieri and Ripps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about pre-qualification, I'm talking about
getting an actual commitment from a lender for a specific amount of
money,'' Bell said, adding that obtaining pre-approval from a
lender will not only give first-time buyers an indisputable idea of
what they can afford _ it may also give them an edge over other
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in a market where it's not unusual for sellers to
get several full-price offers,'' he said. ``And when they have to
choose one buyer over another, they're probably going to pick the
one who already has a mortgage lined up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kay Gallagher, an independent real estate broker in the
Prospect Park South neighborhood of Brooklyn, said that applying
for a mortgage before starting to look for a house could result in
a pleasant surprise for some buyers. ``I'm finding that people can
usually afford more than they think they can afford,'' Ms.
Gallagher said. ``I think it's because of the combination of low
interest rates and banks being willing to lend more money with less
money down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the not-too-distant-past, she said, sellers would get
skittish about going into contract with a buyer with a low down
payment, fearing that the buyer would ultimately not be able to get
a mortgage. That fear is eliminated, however, if the buyer's
mortgage has already been approved, no matter how low the down
payment may be.
</P>
<P>
   And how low is low?
</P>
<P>
   ``First-time buyers can get into a house with as little as 3
percent down,'' said John Minicozzi, a loan specialist with Norwest
Mortgage in Wayne, N.J. ``And in some cases, you can even borrow
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a program sponsored by the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, prospective buyers who want to save money by
purchasing a handyman's special, hoping to improve the property
while they own it, can now include the anticipated cost of the
improvements in the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great deal for first-time buyers,'' Minicozzi said,
explaining that the program, known as Section 203(k), can be used
to rehabilitate significantly deteriorated property or to make
repairs or capital improvements in properties that just need
upgrading. Section 203(k) mortgages have no income or geographical
limitations, he said, and can be used for one- to four-family
dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   The down payment required under the program, Minicozzi said, is
3 percent. The total mortgage, which is based on the anticipated
improved value of the property, cannot exceed FHA loan limits for
the area where the property is situated. In New York City and
Westchester and Rockland Counties, Fairfield County in Connecticut
and Bergen County in New Jersey, the maximum 203(k) loan is
$208,800 for a one-family house and $401,375 for a four-family.
</P>
<P>
   A similar mortgage product _ offered through lenders approved by
Fannie Mae, a congressionally chartered, shareholder-owned
corporation that is the nation's largest source of residential
mortgage funds _ allows buyers to obtain mortgages up to current
Fannie Mae limits.
</P>
<P>
   Those limits range from $240,000 for a one-family house to
$461,350 for a four-family. The borrowers may apply up to 50
percent of the financing to repairs and structural alterations and
to nonessential items like sun rooms, swimming pools, saunas and
even hot tubs.
</P>
<P>
   Raschelle Burton, a spokeswoman for Fannie Mae, said that the
minimum down payment for such loans is 5 percent. Another Fannie
Mae program, Flexible 97, allows buyers to obtain mortgages with as
little as 3 percent down _ and that 3 percent can be a gift from a
family member.
</P>
<P>
   But what can a first-time buyer do if there are no potential
benefactors in the family? ``You might be able to borrow some money
from yourself,'' said Saul Simon, a certified financial planner in
Edison, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, Simon said, a person who has a 401(k)
retirement plan can borrow 50 percent of the plan balance, up to
$50,000, and use it for a down payment on a house, no matter how
the mortgage is obtained.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not paying any penalty because you're taking the money
as a loan,'' he said. ``Then you pay yourself back at 5 or 6
percent interest and amortize the repayment over five years. It's a
great technique.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't want to borrow money, even from themselves,
because it will increase their monthly expenses and so decrease the
maximum mortgage they can qualify for, there is another option.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person with an Individual Retirement Account can withdraw up
to $10,000 without paying a penalty, and then use the money as a
down payment on a house,'' Simon said. ``It's only available for
first-time home buyers,'' he said, adding that the withdrawn money
is taxable and must be reported as ordinary income.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Daly, an associate broker with Prudential Rand Real
Estate in Nanuet, N.Y., said that many first-time buyers believe
that the best mortgage for them is an adjustable-rate loan. But,
she said, such mortgages, which have a low introductory interest
rate that can increase after as little as one year, are a risky
proposition in today's market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest rates are so reasonable today that most people are
much better off with a fixed-rate loan,'' Ms. Daly said. ``At least
you know your payments are going to remain the same no matter what
happens to the interest rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith T. Gumbinger, vice president of HSH Associates, a mortgage
publishing company in Butler, N.J., agreed. ``The interest rate on
one-year adjustables is about 5.8 percent today,'' Gumbinger said,
about 1.3 percentage points lower than the current rate for 30-year
fixed-rate loans.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, under the terms of most adjustable-rate
mortgage agreements, that 5.8 percent will likely jump to 7.5
percent next year, even if interest rates on fixed-rate loans
remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adjustables are usually worthwhile only when the difference
between the 30-year fixed rate and the one-year adjustable is 2.25
percent or more,'' he said. ``That at least provides you with some
fairly substantial savings in the first year and a bit of a cushion
in the second.''
</P>
<P>
   Some new programs reduce the cost of Private Mortgage Insurance,
which is generally required when the down payment is less than 20
percent. The Mortgage Guarantee Insurance Corp. in Milwaukee allows
borrowers to reduce their monthly insurance payments by including
part of the insurance cost in the mortgage. And Fannie Mae's
``Lowest Cost M.I.'' program, available from lenders who use its
Desktop Underwriter system, allows borrowers to make down payments
of as little as 5 or 10 percent without having to buy PMI.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, innovative mortgage programs won't help a first-time
buyer with bad credit _ right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not so,'' said Gerri Detweiler, education adviser for Debt
Counselors of America, a nonprofit debt counseling agency based in
Rockville, Md. Ms. Detweiler said that even those with negative
marks on their credit _ late payments, repossessions, liens,
judgments and even bankruptcy _ can get a mortgage if they have
sufficient income.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, mortgage lenders only wrote A loans,'' Ms.
Detweiler said, explaining that such loans _ typically available
only to borrowers with excellent credit _ usually carry the best
interest rates and require the lowest down payments.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, increasing numbers of lenders have
been writing what are known as B, C and D loans for borrowers with
credit histories ranging anywhere from marred to horrible.
</P>
<P>
   And while such loans generally require significant down payments
and carry higher-than-average interest rates, she said, their
availability makes it possible for even those with terrible credit
to buy a house.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what a prospective buyer thinks his or her credit
history is, Ms. Detweiler said, it is always prudent to call one of
the three nationwide credit reporting agencies _ Equifax,
TransUnion or Experion _ and request a credit report. The typical
fee is $8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, you should do this six to eight weeks before you plan
to get pre-approved,'' Ms. Detweiler said, explaining that if
incorrect information is contained in the report, the borrower
should obtain reports from the other agencies to see if the mistake
is repeated and then advise each agency of all errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a form included with the report that can be used
to dispute any incorrect information,'' she said. ``Fill out the
form and send it in as soon as possible because mistakes don't get
fixed overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   For negative items that are not removed or credit blotches that
are accurate, she said, it is typically worthwhile for the borrower
to send the agency a statement giving the borrower's side of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're allowed by law to have a 100-word statement added to
your credit report,'' she said. ``Just be sure to make it
straightforward, honest and factual.''
</P>
<P>
   Once first-time buyers have decided what kind of house they're
looking for and where they are going to look for it, and once the
best available financing is in place, the only thing left is start
looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest mistake first-time buyers make is buying as the
result of an emotional decision,'' said Enid Hamelin, director of
advertising and public relations for Lawrence Properties, a
Manhattan brokerage company. ``They walk into a house or apartment
and the first thing they do is visualize where the nursery is going
to be and what it will look like.''
</P>
<P>
   And while getting ``the feeling'' about a particular house or
apartment is undoubtedly important, Ms. Hamelin said, it is just as
important to keep in mind that buying property is an investment.
``This is business,'' she said. ``And one has to do one's
homework.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ms. Hamelin said, a prospective purchaser looking
at a co-op or condominium apartment should try to talk to as many
people in the building as possible _ particularly the
superintendent or other building employees _ to obtain as much
first-hand information as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Those buying houses, she said, should make a trip to the
buildings department in the town where the property is situated and
ask to see whatever documentation is on file for the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might find out that your dream house is built on a
landfill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important things a buyer can do, she said _
particularly a first-time buyer who may not be familiar with how a
house works _ is hire a competent engineer to inspect the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want somebody who is going to do a hands-on inspection,''
she said. ``You want the house inspected inside and outside, from
top to bottom. You want an inspector who will be able to tell you
exactly what you're buying.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   House inspections can cost from several hundred dollars to
$1,000, Ms. Hamelin said, depending on the type and location of the
property.
</P>
<P>
   Richard L. Heimer, president of Heimer Engineering in Huntington
Station, N.Y., said that a similar price range applies to co-ops
and condominiums. While such inspections cannot cover a building's
structural details, he said, they are nevertheless important
because they emphasize items unique to the apartment. Andrew
Brodnick, a White Plains real estate lawyer, said that it is also
important for first-time buyers to accompany the engineer or
inspector while the inspection is being performed. That, he said,
will allow the buyer to ask specific questions about appliances and
systems in the house. In addition, he said, it would be very
helpful for a buyer to obtain a copy of the survey for the property
and ask the engineer to walk the property lines with the survey in
hand and the buyer in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to think you own a section of property that really
belongs to your neighbor,'' Brodnick said, adding that a buyer
should also determine, with the help of the lawyer who will handle
the closing, whether there are existing easements or rights-of-way
that give others use or access to the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen easements where the next-door neighbor has a right
to use a driveway but has no obligation to plow it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Billingsley, an owner of Frances Billingsley Realty in
Katonah, N.Y., said that first-time buyers looking in an area they
are not familiar with should drive around the neighborhood _ a lot
_ at different times of day. ``Drive into town one way and out
another,'' Billingsley said. ``Drive around at 8 o'clock on a
Monday morning to find out where the traffic is and drive around on
Friday night to find out where the teenagers hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   And once zeroed in on a particular house, he said, get out of
the car and walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knock on the neighbors' doors, talk to them, find out what
they like about the neighborhood and what they don't like about
it,'' he said. ``If you're moving into a development, talk to
people who live there and ask if there are any problems with the
houses. They'll probably be able to tell you something the broker
doesn't even know.''
</P>
<P>
   If, after all that, Mr. Billingsley said, a house still seems
right, be decisive. ``In this market you've got to move quickly,''
he said. ``I know many a person who has found a house they love,
but then gone and seen a couple of dozen more only to come back and
find the first house already in contract.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, he said, every buyer should resist the urge to be
``penny wise and pound foolish'' when negotiating in a seller's
market. ``I've seen quarter-million-dollar sales fall apart over a
$250 chandelier,'' Mr. Billingsley said. ``If the seller wants to
take the chandelier, let them have it. You can always buy
another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
