<HEADER>
A9260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      03-13 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: HAIL TO THE CHIEF  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, March 14:
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos seems to feel bad, in retrospect, that he
did not press Bill Clinton harder about what went on with Gennifer
Flowers before jumping to his candidate's defense. ``I needed
Clinton to see me as his defender, not his interrogator, which made
me, of course, an enabler,'' he writes in his new memoir, ``All Too
Human.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambivalence and regret are the two main emotional chords in the
book, but in this case Stephanopoulos seems to be beating himself
up unnecessarily. Throughout American history, when a bimbo
eruption has hit an American presidential campaign, the last thing
a candidates' aides have considered doing is asking the Big Guy for
the real story.
</P>
<P>
   When Grover Cleveland was accused of having an illegitimate
child, he ordered his advisers to ``tell the truth'' and went off
to sulk for the rest of the campaign. Nobody ran after him to ask
exactly what the truth was supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos' treatment of the Clintons seems pretty
evenhanded, even though, like almost everyone connected to the
Clintons who did not leave the administration under indictment, he
left clutching a prescription for anti-depressants. ``All Too
Human'' is not the sort of book that is going to make the younger
generation yearn for a career as White House communications
director.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of the insider's tell-all has many critics, who
believe that a president cannot be effective if he feels he is
surrounded by a roomful of future memoirists. ``It's like trying to
govern on national TV,'' says Jody Powell, the Carter
administration press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton White House would, of course, be a happier place
today if the president always had conducted himself as if there
were a film crew in the room. Besides, by the time Stephanopoulos
got around to publishing, the president and his wife had been
trashed by so many books, depositions and Congressional proceedings
that it is hard to imagine what secret he could have disclosed that
would have made any additional impact.
</P>
<P>
   White House insider memoirs are almost always less damaging than
anticipated because the people who write them are almost always
people who want to be taken seriously, and they tend to write
serious books. A Secretary of Defense pouring his heart out to a
computer generally errs on the side of telling too little. The
employee you really have to worry about is the one with no
delusions of grandeur _ if presidents are going to indulge in
self-censorship, they should probably start with the dog walker and
backstairs maids.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 15 years, White House aides have become authors
with the same regularity that defeated congressmen turn into
lobbyists. While Stephanopoulos' $2.8-million advance raised some
eyebrows, it was not as much, adjusting for inflation, as David
Stockman, Ronald Reagan's former budget director, got for ``The
Triumph of Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The tome Stockman produced turned out to be tabloid fodder only
for the Congressional Quarterly crowd. Stockman's biggest
revelation was that Reagan was not very interested in the budget
process. It differed from the memoirs that followed only in that
Stockman did not blame Nancy Reagan for the federal deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton could not be less alike, and it
is interesting that the two of them seem to have inspired a similar
eagerness on the part of their top appointees to start typing as
soon as they were out the door. The reason may simply be that these
presidents stayed in office longest, outlasting their ex-aides'
patience.
</P>
<P>
   But they also managed, in very different ways, to leave their
former associates feeling betrayed. Clinton promised one thing,
then did another. Reagan was a man whose charm was equaled by his
disassociation from the people around him. Aides who had labored on
his behalf for years sometimes came to realize that he barely knew
their names, let alone what they had done. (That emotional distance
was painfully apparent long before Reagan showed symptoms of
Alzheimer's disease, and was possibly the reason his administration
boasts a list of tell-all authors that includes the president's own
offspring.)
</P>
<P>
   The most successful insider memoirist in recent presidential
history _ unless we are counting Barbara Bush's spaniel _ may have
been the former Reagan chief of staff Donald Regan, who revealed
the seminal role Mrs. Reagan's astrologer was playing in White
House planning.
</P>
<P>
   Regan had been dumped rather unceremoniously from his job,
unlike any of the Clinton-era memoirists thus far _ unless we are
counting Monica Lewinsky. The publishers apparently did not know
about the astrologer story when they signed Regan up, but they were
banking on what they had sensed of his mood. There was, Regan's
editor noted, a ``vendetta quality'' about their new author that
seemed promising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
