<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-BOMB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13 DEAD AFTER ATTACK IN BUSY STORE IN ISTANBUL
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Thirteen people were killed and three others
were injured Saturday in a bomb attack on a shopping center in an
outlying section of Istanbul, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No one immediately claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Several attacks have been made on civilian targets here in the
weeks since the capture of Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan
but none nearly as deadly as the one on Saturday, the most serious
in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan's group has normally avoided attacks on civilian targets
in the western part of the country, though another group, known for
its Maoist orientation, has begun emerging. Militant Kurdish
factions claiming to fill the vacuum left by Ocalan's arrest have
also vowed to continue the armed struggle here.
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, Saturday's attack was carried out by
three men who hurled a firebomb into the crowded shopping center in
the Goztepe section of Istanbul and then fled on foot. Goztepe lies
on the Asian side of the Bosporus waterway, which divides the city.
Like other neighborhoods there, it is far from areas frequented by
tourists but is often crowded with Turkish shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The shopping center, a modern five-story concrete and glass
building building, was gutted in the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan is facing a trial that could lead to his execution.
Violent protests against his arrest have erupted in various
European cities. In Turkey, police have reinforced their presence
in Istanbul and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who perpetrated this attack will be caught,'' Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit vowed Saturday. ``They are trying to cause
panic during an election period.''
</P>
<P>
   Turks are scheduled to go to the polls to elect a new government
on April 18. Ecevit's position seems to have been strengthened by
the capture of Ocalan, the country's most wanted and most widely
hated fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Istanbul remained calm this week, and business and daily
life continued as usual. But the attacks carried out last week,
including one in which a taxi driver was killed, have already begun
to have an impact on the lucrative tourist trade. Hotel managers
and tour organizers reported that they have had cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors planning trips to Istanbul have asked their hosts
here when Ocalan's trial may take place. No date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   There have not yet been any attacks on Mediterranean towns where
much of the country's tourism is centered. If there are, the
country may suffer serious economic as well as political losses.
</P>
<P>
   Civilian and military leaders in Turkey have rejected
suggestions that they grant greater cultural rights to the Kurdish
minority as a way of heading off future protests and terrorist
attacks. They say that such concessions could lay the basis for a
national collapse like those that broke Yugoslavia and the Soviet
Union apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
