<HEADER>
A9264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE14-COX     03-13 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    League held hostage
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The underlying and disturbing reminder that came from the two
megatrades last week was this: The inmates not only are running the
asylum, they're running it into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In the cases of the Glen Rice trade to the Los Angeles Lakers
and Stephon Marbury to the New Jersey Nets, the key players
essentially held their old teams hostage, forcing the deals by
telling the clubs that no matter how much they offered, they would
not re-sign with them.
</P>
<P>
   So the Charlotte Hornets and Minnesota Timberwolves had no
alternative. The teams had to deal players they did not want to
trade to prevent losing them to free agency with nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue that in a free enterprise system, employees
should be able to determine where they work. But that's not how the
NBA is supposed to function. With the average salary around $1.6
million, the league hardly exists as does, say, corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   There are guidelines set up to negotiate player movement. None
of them outline players' threats as a way of exacting change. And
yet, more and more it is heard: ``I'm going to test the free-agent
market, see what my value is. I love playing here, but I have to
see what's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That was more Marbury's deal than Rice's. A former Georgia Tech
star from Brooklyn, Marbury never liked Minneapolis and its frigid
winters and always wondered aloud about playing back home in his
native New York.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nets showed interest, Marbury basically said, ``That's
close enough. I'm outta here. See ya.'' Never mind that he and
Kevin Garnett represented one of the league's top young-gun tandems
or that the Timberwolves were 12-6 at the time of the trade.
Marbury held them up to go ``home'' to a Nets club that was
second-worst in the NBA (3-15) and in such disarray that it
contemplated firing its coach on the same day it traded for
Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the deal was none other than agent David Falk.
The thought was that Falk's power would be stripped with the new
collective bargaining agreement, which slots players' salaries by
their experience. And, indeed, Falk has been limited in what he can
do on that end of it.
</P>
<P>
   But he still has most of the game's big names, and it was he who
essentially set up both trades. Falk dealt with the Lakers, telling
them that Rice would approve the trade only if he received the kind
of money he wanted in a new contract. So, Rice didn't hold
Charlotte hostage so much as he did L.A. Falk told Minnesota's
owner that Marbury would not re-sign, and then brokered that deal
by insisting the Nets sign Marbury to the max he could receive.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a crazy way for business to be handled. But then, it's
always something crazy in an asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to restructure around players who are serious and
committed,'' Milwaukee coach George Karl said. ``We let too many
players blackmail us in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   BOX TO ACCOMPANY THE STORY
</P>
<P>
   LOWDOWN ON THE DEALS
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, B.J. Armstrong, J.R. Reid from Charlotte to L.A.
Lakers for Eddie Jones, Elden Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   -- Analysis: Lakers elevated to undisputed champion of talent in
NBA. Can Rice, Shaq and Kobe share the ball? Will Reid be a
suitable O'Neal backup? There are questions, but L.A. had to do it.
Charlotte got appreciably better but may not make playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Winner: Lakers, but not by much. Rice gives them dominance
inside (O'Neal), a damaging slasher (Bryant) and a deadly perimeter
marksman (Rice) to go with a rebounding phenom (Dennis Rodman) and
a host of other talented players. They should win the title.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury to New Jersey Nets, Sam Cassell and Chris
Gatling to Milwaukee, Terrell Brandon to Minnesota (plus other
minor player movement).
</P>
<P>
   -- Analysis: Marbury wanted out of Minnesota and to be home, or
close to it. He brings a liveliness to the nearly dead Nets, a star
quality. But Minnesota will not suffer as much as people think.
Brandon's actually more solid than Marbury, an All-Star who
requires less of the ball but can score when necessary and defend.
The Bucks wanted him to stay, but he wanted out. In Cassell,
Milwaukee gets a scorer at the point _ when he's healthy. Only
played four games this season.
</P>
<P>
   -- Winner: Nets, but not by much. Marbury's a star for the next
decade who should shine brightly near New York. But Brandon's
talented and committed and will make the drop-off of Marbury's
departure minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
