<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA NOTES: Karl lets Sonics brass have it
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milwaukee coach George Karl, formerly of the Seattle
SuperSonics, has his new team on the move but his old team on his
mind. Days before beating Seattle at home last week for the Bucks'
sixth consecutive win, Karl let the Sonics hierarchy have it.
</P>
<P>
   The targets were general manager Wally Walker and vice president
Billy McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   Karl: ``I believe the basketball people have to make the
basketball decisions, and I don't think Wally's a basketball guy. I
don't think Billy McKinney's a basketball guy. They're pseudo-gym
guys. They don't feel comfortable in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``My animosity comes from the fact I want the truth to come out.
And the truth is, when you talk about the construction of the
tradition that we had in Seattle, Wally Walker's name should be
sixth or seventh on the rung of importance. Wally's not an
innovator. He's just there.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker responded: ``I think George is still mad about Virginia
beating North Carolina in 1973. That game was in a gym, I
believe.'' (Walker was a sophomore at Virginia and Karl a UNC
senior for that game.)
</P>
<P>
   Said McKinney: ``If you look at me, and you look at George, and
you look at Wally, it's evident who spends time in the gym and who
doesn't. If he spent more time in the gym working out his body
instead of being critical of people, maybe he could fit into these
Armani suits that I'm wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Proud alumnus
</P>
<P>
   Think NBA players aren't tuned in to the NCAA Tournament?
Consider this from Houston's Charles Barkley, a former Auburn star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to skip a game if (Auburn) goes to the Final Four,''
Barkley said. ``I'm going to the Final Four. I don't care if we're
playing the Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Rockets play at Golden State on the Final
Four date, and are off March 29, the night of the championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a special moment for Auburn, even more special if
someone like Charles showed up to show his support,'' said Auburn
coach Cliff Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   New route for Mailman
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone, who tried his hand as a sports talk-radio host in
the summer, said his next non-NBA gig will be hosting a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling it, `Karl Malone's Great Outdoors,''' the host
said. ``It will be 26 episodes of 30-minute programs where I will
hunt big game, do some snowmobiling, bungee-jumping, whitewater
rafting, camping and fishing all around the world. Anywhere I want
to go, I'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   Can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   He said it
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a shooter (Glen Rice) and I got another thug power
forward (Dennis Rodman). Ain't no excuses now, for me or anybody
else in this locker room. We should be on our way,'' Lakers center
Shaquille O'Neal, on his team's championship hopes after the two
key acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs Up
</P>
<P>
   To the Portland Trail Blazers. Long thought of as a group of
enigmatic underachievers, the Blazers are rolling with the league's
best record under first-year coach Mike Dunleavy. Outstanding guard
Isaiah Rider has been suspended only once, which is good for him.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs Down
</P>
<P>
   To the New Jersey Nets. A team many felt would challenge for the
Atlantic Division title is second-worst in the league behind the
Los Angeles Clippers. Last year, New Jersey tried to dismiss New
York as also-rans. Turns out, it is the Nets who are fakers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
