<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL NOTES: No. 1 pick might not be Couch
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Five weeks before the Cleveland Browns' triumvirate of
president Carmen Policy, GM Dwight Clark and coach Chris Palmer
exercises the first choice in the draft, the race for the No. 1
spot suddenly has become a three-man derby. Despite reports that
the Browns have settled on Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch as their
man, Oregon quarterback Akili Smith and Texas tailback Ricky
Williams now are neck-and-neck with him entering the home stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Couch likely could have secured the top spot at his on-campus
workout Thursday. But while his throwing session for NFL scouts was
solid, it was not spectacular. Some in attendance noted that Couch
may have tried too hard to dispel the lingering notion he lacks raw
arm strength, particularly on the deep ``out'' pattern. That
workout apparently was similar to a private audience Couch had
earlier in the week with Cincinnati coach Bruce Coslet and
offensive coordinator Ken Anderson. And it's no secret Palmer feels
Couch developed some mechanical flaws in coach Hal Mumme's
run-and-shoot offense.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Tom Condon has hired former NFL assistant Larry Kennan, a
longtime offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach, to work with
Couch.
</P>
<P>
   The recent acquisition of Ty Detmer means Cleveland won't have
to force a rookie quarterback into the lineup and can provide a
young passer a season or two of apprenticeship. Given that
scenario, Couch remains the likely first choice, but it's no
slam-dunk. Before owner Al Lerner doles out the kind of contract
Peyton Manning signed last spring, Cleveland will want to examine
its options a little further.
</P>
<P>
   It's believed Clark's private preference is for Williams, who
would be running behind a line that features center Dave
Wohlabaugh, guard Jim Pyne and tackles Orlando Brown and Lomas
Brown and already might be better than half the blocking units in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons fodder
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are in an unusual situation with their salary cap
for 2000. Even with the multiyear signings of quarterback Danny
Kanell, cornerback Ronnie Bradford, safeties Gerald McBurrows and
Marty Carter and wideout Ronnie Harris, the team still has only 21
players under contract beyond 1999. That is one of the lowest
totals in the league and those players count an aggregate $30
million against the cap. For now, it means Atlanta has more than
$30 million to spend for 2000, more even than the Browns. That
total will be diminished as GM Harold Richardson attempts to
re-sign or extend potential free agents such as tailback Jamal
Anderson, center Robbie Tobeck, wide receiver Terance Mathis,
defensive ends Chuck Smith and Lester Archambeau and fullback Bob
Christian, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore personnel director Ozzie Newsome will meet today with
Detroit general manager Chuck Schmidt to try to consummate a trade
for quarterback Scott Mitchell. The Ravens have offered a
third-round pick in 2000 and the Lions want more than that. ...
Dallas owner Jerry Jones is seeking allies in his quest to dissolve
NFL Properties, the league's lucrative marketing branch. Jones
feels each team should market itself instead of sharing revenues.
... Clemson safety Antwan Edwards didn't endear himself to the
scouts Thursday when he declined to run the 40 at the school's Pro
Day workout. ... Jacksonville offensive tackle Tony Boselli is
chafing that the team has yet to extend his contract. Eleven
players on the Jaguars' roster will earn more than Boselli in 1999,
including six on offense. ... Seattle quietly worked out
quarterback Todd Marinovich, the former Raiders first-round bust,
last week but has decided not to pursue him. He hasn't played since
1992. ... Miami assistant head coach Dave Wannstedt will attend the
NFL meetings, further fueling speculation he will replace Jimmy
Johnson in 2000. ... Look for CBS to retain the league's radio
broadcast rights, fending off a bid by ESPN. ... Unless they trade
up from the sixth spot in the first round for Williams, the Rams
will take Miami tailback Edgerrin James. ... The era of the big
cornerback will take a de-evolutionary step in this year's draft.
Of the 23 corners at the combine, only Chris McAlister (Arizona),
Anthony Parker (Weber State) and Ken Wright (Northwestern
Louisiana) are more than 6 feet tall. Thirteen corners are 5 feet
10 or shorter. ... Two Ohio State stars, wideout David Boston and
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer, helped themselves considerably with
superb workouts Friday.
</P>
<P>
   No realignment?
</P>
<P>
   League vice president Joe Browne insisted last week there are
``some reservations'' about splitting the NFL into eight divisions
of four teams each once a 32nd franchise is added in 2002. But
influential Pittsburgh owner Dan Rooney will vote against expansion
Tuesday unless it is tied to realignment. Bengals owner Mike Brown
might join him. ... The Competition Committee has recommended that
the ball be placed at the 25-yard line instead of the 20 following
touchbacks on kickoffs. Only 80.3 percent of kickoffs were returned
in 1998, compared with 88.4 percent four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions apply
</P>
<P>
   With the pool of unrestricted free agents all but dried up,
here's a list of 10 restricted free agents who might draw interest,
and the draft choice compensation each will cost a team that signs
them: Seattle DE Phillip Daniels (No. 4 pick), N.Y. Giants FS Percy
Ellsworth (none), Dallas WR Patrick Jeffers (No. 5), Kansas City DT
Tom Barndt (No. 6), Arizona OG Matt Joyce (none), Cincinnati FS
Greg Myers (No. 5), Minnesota TE Hunter Goodwin (No. 4), Tampa Bay
LB Jeff Gooch (none), Miami SS Shawn Wooden (No. 6), Detroit DE
Kerwin Waldroup (No. 5).
</P>
<P>
   Fly boys
</P>
<P>
   Once again, about one-third of the 318 prospects who attended
the combine workouts in Indianapolis declined to run the 40-yard
dash on the slow surface of the RCA Dome. Of those who did run,
here are the fastest times: CB Paul Miranda (Central Florida),
4.37; RB Cecil Collins (McNeese State), 4.41; WR Tai Streets
(Michigan), 4.42; CB Dee Moronkola (Washington State), 4.43; WR
Darran Hall (Colorado State), 4.44; CB Chris Cummings (LSU), 4.45.
</P>
</TEXT>
