<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLOWNERS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aides' benefits finally getting NFL's attention
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ With a schedule that includes the likely return of
instant replay, expansion to either Los Angeles or Houston for the
2002 season and the future of the Washington Redskins, owners will
deliberate over one of the more high-profile agendas in the last
several years when the NFL's annual meetings convene here Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Those significant issues notwithstanding, it may be a decision
by the league's Finance Committee _ one that doesn't even appear on
the official docket _ that could present the most far-reaching
ramifications for the near future. At some point in the next few
days, the committee will make a recommendation to owners on how the
league should deal with myriad work-related issues brought forward
by the NFL Coaches Association.
</P>
<P>
   League officials have promised longtime NFL assistant Larry
Kennan, the new full-time executive director of the NFLCA, a
``significant'' response to the request for enhanced benefits.
Anything less could result in the association moving toward
unionization, or even a work stoppage by assistant coaches in
training camp this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the NFL has been slow to act on these kinds of things,
but since last winter we have been told by prominent league
officials that we will get a significant response to the issues
we've raised,'' Kennan said late last week. ``We will be highly
disappointed if that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Kennan, 54, as the NFLCA's initial full-time
employee gives the association legitimacy. The NFL Players
Association has provided office space and counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Most owners recognize that their aides have grievances that
sorely need to be addressed. Among them are standardized health
insurance, life insurance, severance pay, full playoff shares and a
lower retirement age. The group is also concerned about diminished
job security and perceived age discrimination. Coaches have
suggested it would take no more than the salary of a player like
Deion Sanders to fund the upgraded benefits package.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money,'' Kennan said, ``should not be a factor in a league
with a television contract that's worth $18 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   While most owners seem more enlightened than in the past, those
in Dallas, Cincinnati and New Orleans have forbidden assistants to
join the NFLCA. The NFL appointed former New York Giants general
manager George Young to serve as liaison to the coaches and he has
apparently been a good sounding board.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in my mind, it shouldn't be a public debate,'' Bengals
owner Mike Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest issue of the week, the replay system recommended by
the Competition Committee, figures to generate plenty of debate
before a vote on Wednesday. Coming off a '98 season in which
officiating gaffes increased, replay proponents appear to have the
24 votes necessary to resurrect the tool.
</P>
<P>
   Owners are expected to vote for expansion on Tuesday, with Los
Angeles the favorite over Houston. In a move that could produce the
first $1 billion franchise fee in history, the league likely will
award a team to the city of Los Angeles rather than an owner and
then set up a bid process similar to the one used in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
