<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 16 YEARS, THE SACK EXCHANGE TO REUNITE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y., N.J.)   (jw) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They had a two-year run of great success and then it was
suddenly over. After registering 44.5 sacks in 1981 for the Jets,
the Sack Exchange came apart because of injuries and trades, and
its members began to go their separate ways 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But they are being reunited in that great sports phenomenon of
the modern era: the autograph session. As part of a Jets and Giants
Reunion Weekend, the Sack Exchange will appear next Sunday at the
Crowne Plaza in Secaucus, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   And just who were those guys?
</P>
<P>
   -- There was Abdul Salaam, who took the Arabic name meaning
Soldier of Peace after joining the Jets as Larry Faulk, and then
was traded following the 1983 season.
</P>
<P>
   -- There was Mark Gastineau, the emotional quarterback-sacker
who enjoyed exploring Indian burial grounds as much as chasing Dan
Marino. He still holds the National Football League record of 22
sacks in a season, set in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   -- The heart and soul of the group was Joe Klecko, the
self-described lunch-pail slob and the only player ever to go to
the Pro Bowl at three positions on the defensive line. He led the
league in sacks in 1981 with 21{, just ahead of Gastineau's 20, but
a torn knee ligament forced him to miss most of the 1982 season.
</P>
<P>
   -- And there was Marty Lyons, now a stockbroker, but then the
fellow who used to break windows with his fist before games to
energize his teammates. Once, he broke a table in half; another
time he hoisted a film projector and threatened to heave it against
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   In that 1981 season, when the Jets produced their first winning
season since the 1960s, they helped lead the way to a total of 66
sacks, then the second-most in NFL history and still the team
record. The assistant trainer, Pepper Burruss, used to chart the
sacks like stocks. One day a fan at Shea Stadium held up a sign
calling them the Sack Exchange, and the team's public relations
director, Frank Ramos, began officially referring to them that way
in his news releases. Soon they visited the New York Stock
Exchange, where they received a raucous ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, both Gastineau and Klecko have served time in jail _
Klecko for lying to a federal grand jury about helping a friend in
an insurance scam and Gastineau for hitting the woman who is now
his wife. Lyons went through a divorce, but rebounded with a
position at Paine Webber, and remains committed to charitable
causes. Salaam became a high school wrestling coach in Cincinnati.
In the early 1990s he also managed a singing group.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Salaam seemed to have disappeared. Lyons, Klecko
and Gastineau had made various appearances over the years, but when
the promoter of the reunion weekend tried to find Salaam, not even
the players association could help. Finally, somehow, the Secret
Service was asked to find him and they tracked him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why it was so difficult,'' Salaam said. ``I've
been here. But I'm such a quiet guy, even when I was traded away
back in 1983, no one even knew I had left New York.''
</P>
<P>
   He even had remained close to the public eye. ``I was managing
and promoting a top group, Sly Fox. We did Disneyland, Six Flags.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite going his own way, the special bond of the Sack Exchange
remained vibrant to Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make these guys believe in themselves,''
recalled Salaam, who joined the team in 1976. ``I was there first.
I wanted to build something. The Sack Exchange was the result of
that philosophy, so Mark could have that personality, a pure
performer, who was into himself. He wanted that record, which he
has. And Joe was analytical, figuring out where he could see his
opponent and make the best of it. Marty was a politician, getting
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   They loved who they were even though they didn't necessarily
love one another. Certainly, Klecko abhorred Gastineau. ``We're
from two different worlds,'' Klecko said now that the two have made
up. ``I'm a lunch-pail guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sack Exchange found love outside of football. Klecko is back
on his feet after disastrous financial setbacks. He and his wife,
Debbie, have produced a second group of three children many years
after they raised their first three.
</P>
<P>
   Gastineau is undergoing counseling and his wife, Patty, said:
``He is a changed man. He has insight into who he is and why he did
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Klecko still appreciates that, as a group, ``We were up there
with the Purple People Eaters, the Steel Curtain, the Fearsome
Foursome.''
</P>
<P>
   Salaam said: ``It's a great story. How we each have different
personalities but we each have one of the four elements that are in
creation _ what's the reason why we were able to establish
ourselves, and then to be named after the New York Stock
Exchange?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
