<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-NEWMEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
17-0 START PROPELS CONNECTICUT TO SWEET SIXTEEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ No shocks, no surprises, no problems. There was not
even a hint of them for Connecticut Saturday. The Huskies swaggered
onto the court fully focused on continuing their march toward a
national championship, and did it in an emphatic manner. A dazed
New Mexico team was finished before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the game with a 17-0 spurt and never letting the Lobos
wake up from the defensive sleeper hold they aggressively applied,
the Huskies rumbled to a 78-56 victory in the second round of the
West Regional of the NCAA tournament at McNichols Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case there were any skeptics in the arena who doubted
their supremacy after the first half, the Huskies also exploded for
the first 13 points of the second half. UConn made awesome look
ho-hum.
</P>
<P>
   In destroying the ninth-seeded Lobos (25-9), the top-seeded
Huskies (30-2) were precise, powerful and impenetrable. They shot
poorly, but they played stingy defense, they hustled as if they
were the underdogs and they suffocated Kenny Thomas, New Mexico's
finest player, holding him to one point _ 17.5 below his average.
Thomas looked lost, and looked as if he could not wait to get on an
airplane back to Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   UConn coach Jim Calhoun returned to the bench after missing
Thursday's 91-66 victory over Texas-San Antonio with an intestinal
virus, and he was his usual hyperactive self. Red-faced and
excitable, Calhoun was still barking instructions when the Huskies
led by 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? The approach has worked wondrously for Calhoun, who
especially enjoyed Saturday's triumph because it was his 300th
career victory at Connecticut. Richard Hamilton and Khalid El-Amin
helped carry Calhoun to the plateau in his 420th game with 21
points each.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies advanced to the regional semifinals Thursday in
Phoenix and will play either Arkansas or Iowa, who met in
Saturday's second game. No matter who UConn meets next, the Huskies
will definitely be favored.
</P>
<P>
   They have displayed their depth and their desire in easily
winning their first two games of the tournament by an average of
23.5 points. Other than perhaps second-seeded Stanford, there are
no serious obstacles for UConn in pursuit of a spot in the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody is going to lose each and every night,'' said
Hamilton. ``We just hope it's not us. As long as we come out and
play hard and aggressive on defense and play as one, we don't think
that we're ever going to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking a little thinner in the face, Calhoun was back
patrolling the sideline and he shouted instructions, rarely sat
down and chewed gum as if he were being paid by the bite.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old Calhoun said he felt some lingering effects of
an intestinal virus, but he was happy to be home after feeling
helpless while watching the last game on television.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun liked what he saw Saturday. Connecticut was assertive
while New Mexico was tentative, and the combination proved
delightful for the Huskies as they rolled to a 17-0 lead and held a
37-22 edge at halftime. El-Amin had 10 points while Hamilton,
despite shooting 2 of 9 from the floor, had nine points.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Thomas, New Mexico's talented center, touched the
ball, he stepped on the baseline. It was a terrible omen for the
Lobos, who struggled to handle the ball and even make shots against
UConn's feisty man-to man defense. New Mexico was a brutal 5 for 22
from the field, which disguised how abysmal UConn was at 12 for 32.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton and El-Amin drilled 3-pointers on UConn's first three
possessions to get the Huskies moving, and the avalanche continued
in a methodical manner.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies were not running by the Lobos for every basket, but
they did not have to because New Mexico's offense was absent. Kevin
Freeman had a nice tip-in and a strong dunk, El-Amin drove for a
layup and sank a 3-pointer and Edmund Saunders made two free throws
as the Huskies took their astounding 17-0 lead with 13 minutes 8
seconds left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was not astounding. At that point, the Lobos were 0 for
7 from the field with seven turnovers while UConn was a decent 6
for 14 with a lone turnover. The Lobos failed to get the ball
inside to Thomas, their meal ticket, who was being fronted by a
very physical Jake Voskuhl.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the 6-foot-8-inch Thomas touched the ball, Freeman
quickly slid across the paint to double-team him. It worked.
Thomas, who had 20 points in New Mexico's 61-59 first-round victory
over Missouri, was limited to one point in the half, missed all
four of his shots and did not play the last five and a half minutes
after getting his second foul.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With 12:48 remaining in the half, the Lobos finally ended the
shutout when Greg Davis nailed a free throw after being fouled by
Souleymane Wane. Of course, the fans at McNichols cheered the
long-awaited point in derisive fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Davis hit the second free throw to bring the Lobos within 15 at
17-2. After UConn's E.J. Harrison made a 3-pointer to lift the lead
to 18, New Mexico showed its most life. The Lobos scored nine
straight points, which included their first field goal, by Damion
Walker, 8:15 into the game, to trim the deficit to 20-11.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Lobos performed more competitively for the final
nine minutes of the half, the Huskies remained steady and never let
them get closer than nine points.
</P>
<P>
   The lead fluctuated between 10 and 17, which is what it was at
37-20 after Ricky Moore buried a 3-pointer with a few seconds left.
But John Robinson 2nd knifed between Moore and El-Amin to make an
8-foot jumper as the buzzer sounded, causing Calhoun to storm off
the bench and scream, ``How does that happen?'' to his two guards.
Yes, Calhoun was back. UConn never left. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
