u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUFFOLK-FEUD-460(2TAK     03-13 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUFFOLK-FEUD-460(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANCOR BETWEEN 2 SUFFOLK OFFICIALS GROWS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. _ The blood is bad between the Suffolk County
sheriff and the district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   So bad that in recent days the two of them, the county's top law
enforcement officers, have been making direct and oblique
references to Hitler, Hoffa and Oswald in talking about the other.
</P>
<P>
   So bad that the sheriff refers derisively to the district
attorney's son, himself a former deputy county attorney, as
``little Jimmy.''
</P>
<P>
   So bad that when Republican officials gather for publicity
photos, nobody wants the unsavory task of standing between the two
so they do not brush arms.
</P>
<P>
   The feud goes back at least as far as 1993, when District
Attorney James Catterson felt that Sheriff Patrick Mahoney had
upstaged him after Katie Beers, a 10-year-old who was kidnapped and
held for 16 days, was found alive.
</P>
<P>
   And the battle has become so well known that for years many on
the far edges of Long Island ignored the noise when the two
ambitious Republican officials clashed. But last month, even the
most hardened observers could not ignore the sheriff's cries of
``fascism,'' ``conspiracy'' and ``witch hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest eruption occurred a few weeks ago when Mahoney
announced that he was exploring the possibility of challenging
Catterson's longtime political ally, County Executive Robert
Gaffney, in the November election. Later that day Catterson
announced that a grand jury had indicted the Sheriff's Department's
chief mechanic on 51 counts, including charges of stealing cash and
surplus equipment and filing false overtime claims.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, Catterson convened a grand jury to investigate
what he called leads about corruption in the sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   There is ``a total conspiracy to ruin me by the district
attorney, and his ally, the county executive,'' Mahoney said.
``It's like living in Nazi Germany. Catterson should spend his time
trying murderers, rapists and burglars instead of his political
opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   But Catterson and Gaffney, also a Republican, rejected the
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the sheriff's continued references to
conspiracy,'' Catterson said. ``What's next? He's going to tell us
where Jimmy Hoffa is buried? Or who fired the second gun at
Kennedy? This investigation will continue until all leads are
followed up. Personally, I could care less about him one way or the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, including those of friends, they are cut from
the same cloth: two hard-driving, politically ambitious men proud
of their Irish roots.
</P>
<P>
   But Suffolk Republicans, who have long controlled this county of
1.4 million, are worried that voters, fed up with the feud and
other party problems, will decide to pull the Democratic lever in
the local elections this fall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For instance, John Powell, the former Suffolk County Republican
chairman and a close associate of Catterson's, was led from his
home in handcuffs in November, accused of taking bribes from a
carter for access to a public landfill and of conspiring to traffic
in stolen trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a total nuclear meltdown the likes of which you could
never have imagined at the Shoreham plant,'' said one top aide to a
Republican legislator who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``The problem is, it's really public. In the old days we had strong
leadership, and at least you could put them at the same table.''
</P>
<P>
   John Klein, the former Suffolk County executive and now a
prominent Republican lawyer based in Nassau County, was equally
hyperbolic. ``They're insane,'' he said. ``The theory is that there
is something in the ground water or in the overhead power lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Catterson's 10-year tenure as district attorney has been marked
by allegations that he has bullied public officials who crossed
him. But even his harshest critics concede the effectiveness of his
criminal prosecutions. Although he tends to become personally
involved in only the most public cases, his office boasts a 96
percent conviction rate, one of the highest in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In his investigation of the sheriff, Catterson said he was
looking into allegations that some of the 1,000 employees at the
county jail had been required to pay kickbacks to the sheriff in
return for promotions. Mahoney says the charges stem from a dispute
about overtime pay between the correction officers and the deputy
sheriffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tries to get my mechanic to flip on me for an offer of
immunity,'' Mahoney said. ``There's your smoking gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney called the charges absurd. And he pointed out that Judge
Gary Weber of State Supreme Court released the mechanic last month
on a very low bond, $5,000, despite the 51 counts against him.
</P>
<P>
   Catterson, 68, the son of a Suffolk County sheriff, cut his
political teeth in Nassau, where he was the county attorney and an
adviser to Joseph Margiotta, the legendary former Republican
chairman. Catterson went on to work as counsel for Perry Duryea,
the former Assembly speaker, and in private practice before he was
elected district attorney in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way Catterson became the consummate political insider,
with an extensive network of allies that stretched across the
island, north to Albany and south into the Washington office of
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his Nassau connections, Catterson eventually became a
dominating figure in Suffolk County politics. He is described by
many as a combative, no-holds-barred politician.
</P>
<P>
   County Comptroller Joseph Caputo, who is also a Republican, said
Catterson threatened him with an investigation in 1995 in
connection with health contracts he oversaw. Caputo contends that
the district attorney's threats were in retaliation for an
investigation he led involving Catterson's personal use of a BMW
forfeited by a convicted drug dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I surprised about the investigation into the sheriff?''
Caputo said. ``No. Catterson thinks he runs this island, and if you
stand up to him, you pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Catterson was investigated by the governor's office in 1995 when
he was accused of abusing his prosecutorial powers, including
alleged threats of reprisals against the former commissioner of
health services, the chief medical examiner and the presiding
officer of the county legislature. The investigation found
insufficient evidence to warrant criminal charges or proceedings to
remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   There is, perhaps, an especially cold place in Catterson's heart
for Mahoney, a former Suffolk County detective and county
legislator who was his running mate when they first sought their
current offices in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a year after they tangled over Katie Beers, Mahoney was
the first to make public a county car-leasing deal arranged by
Catterson's son, James III, who was then a deputy county attorney.
The deal was canceled when a legislative investigator determined
that it would cost the county $9 million less to buy the cars
outright.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Catterson's son had congressional aspirations, but
he ultimately became a state judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still thinks I ruined it for little Jimmy,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the sheriff sat in his Riverhead office, wondering if
he had made a big mistake in tangling again with Catterson. In
1997, in a letter to Gov. George Pataki, Mahoney accused Catterson
of intimidating a grand juror who had refused to indict a woman in
connection with the murder of her child. State investigators found
the charges baseless.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney, 56, said he would like to move beyond his current
office, which entails oversight of the county jails and serving
warrants. But he knows his chances of receiving the Republican
nomination for county executive are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke Reagan's rule: Never criticize a fellow Republican,''
Mahoney said. ``But hey, both my parents were Democrats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
