<SLUG> BC-BARUCH-BODY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY OF STUDENT IS DISCOVERED IN SHAFTWAY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The body of a 19-year-old Baruch College student who
had been missing for more than four days was discovered Friday
night inside a trash-filled shaftway separating two of the school's
buildings, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Security guards on the campus in Manhattan found the body of the
student, Yankum Huang, at 9:45 p.m., a little more than an hour
after the New York City Police Department held a news conference to
publicize her disappearance on Monday morning. Police said her
death was apparently a suicide but cautioned that a final
determination would be made by the city's medical examiner.
</P>
<P>
   A city official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said
the security guards had checked the shaftway, between 111 E. 19th
St. and 106 E. 18th St., after a student at the school told them
she had seen something fall past a window earlier in the week. The
shaftway is not reachable or visible from the street.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Huang, a sophomore in the college's liberal arts program,
had last been seen by a friend around 10 a.m. on Monday. Police
said it was believed that she was on her way to Bensonhurst, where
she lived with her family. But she never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents searched for her until Thursday morning, before
phoning one of Ms. Huang's friends and having the friend call
police. They later indicated to the officers that Ms. Huang's home
life had been pleasant and that she did not have a boyfriend,
police said. Shy and studious, she was in the college's honors
program and not one to stay out late, they told police.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Cronholm, interim president of the 25,000 student college,
met with Ms. Huang's parents on Friday night after hearing of the
discovery. ``Everyone is distraught about what has happened, and it
has come as a total shock,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Huang's disappearance had been compared to that of another
honors student, Kristine Kupka, 28, who is still missing. Five
months pregnant, she vanished from her Brooklyn home in October.
Her family suspects that she may have been killed, but
investigators have made no arrests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
