</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winston driver wins Busch race again
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NASCAR's Catch-22 in the Busch series continued
Saturday with a Winston Cup driver winning the Busch race for the
third time in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner, the Winston Cup points leader, took the lead with
20 laps to go in the No. 19 Chevrolet and held off pole-sitter Dave
Blaney to win the Yellow Freight 300 by 2.261 seconds at Atlanta
Motor Speedway. Defending Busch champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. was
third.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wreck-filled event, bringing out six cautions for 49
laps. The most spectacular accident, on lap 134, involved eight
cars and sent drivers Wayne Grubb and Dick Trickle to Atlanta
Medical Center for examination.
</P>
<P>
   But the topic of post-race conversation was once again the
presence of the more experienced Cup drivers in the Busch event,
which NASCAR has been trying to market as a league of its own.
However, seven Busch regulars finished in the top 10 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. characterized seeing one of his fellow Busch guys
failing to qualify in emotional terms: ''It's like a punch in the
gut to send a guy home who's fifth in points.''
</P>
<P>
   But he believes NASCAR ought to level the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody needs track time,'' Little E said. ''But I think the
first thing they should do is look at the teams. You don't need to
cater to an underfunded team. But maybe look at whether they're
running full schedules. Maybe limit the other teams that have Cup
drivers to five or eight races a year. Or leave five spots open for
the Cup guys to qualify for anywhere in the field and send the rest
of them home.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's two sides to the story. I don't think I'd be half the
race car driver I am today without what I learned following Mark
Martin and Jeff Burton and all those guys last year. And still,
today, I yearn to be with them and race with them. When you see
them up there dicing for the lead, you want to go up there and race
wth them and see how patient they are and learn gobs of stuff.
There's no limit to what these guys can teach you and they're very
eager to work with young drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   With two top fives in three Cup races, Skinners is off to his
best start. But Saturday's win was his first in nine career Busch
starts and his first top 10. His previous best finish was 24th.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't expect to win with this new team also sponsored by
Yellow Freight.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were really junk in yesterday morning's practice. It was
really loose and scared me half to death.'' He said he got help
from his regular Cup team, the No. 31 Chevy, to get things right.
</P>
<P>
   He also sees both sides of the Busch controversy. ''Are you
hurting people's careers with the Winston Cup drivers getting in
there and winning some of the races? I don't really think so,''
Skinner said. ''I guess that's a decision NASCAR has to make and
I'll be behind them either way they go. If they don't want any more
Cup drivers in the Busch series that'll be fine with me. I've got a
son, 21 (Jamie), that's going to drive this Monte Carlo 3 or 4
races this year anyway and we'll just slide him in there full
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
