</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once again, rain in forecast at AMS
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In what is becoming an annual rite, NASCAR will battle
the weather in completing today's Cracker Barrel Old Country Store
500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Weather forecasts were predicting showers and thunderstorms in
the area this morning, with high temperatures expected to reach
only the upper 40s to low 50s. The rain was expected to end by
midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather is what we always seem to have here _ cloudy, damp
and cold,'' driver Jeff Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Inclement weather during race week in Atlanta has become an all
too familiar sight for Bruton Smith, chairman of Speedway
Motorsports, which owns AMS.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he's lobbying NASCAR president Bill France Jr. and
chief operating officer Mike Helton to get Atlanta's spring Winston
Cup race moved to later in the season. The second date at AMS, the
NAPA 500 on Nov. 21, is the Cup season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back in history, March has always been a bad date
for Atlanta,'' Smith said. ``We need to do something. Maybe next
year we can do a little shuffling or trading. Darlington always has
good weather this time of year. Maybe it would be beneficial for
them to switch, but it would be NASCAR's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   It's apparent that NASCAR must do something. Last year's spring
race, the Primestar 500, was postponed one day after rain washed
away any hopes of racing on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In November, drivers and fans endured rain delays of 6 hours, 39
minutes. When the race finally resumed, there were still 19 laps
remaining at 11 p.m in the 221-lap, rain-shortened event.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales for today's event were slow after
less-than-favorable weather forecasts earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we get it in everybody will be happy,'' said Bobby
Labonte, who will start on the pole in his No. 18 Pontiac. ``The
worst thing is to sit around all day watching and then have to come
back the next day. With the lights, we have some options here.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who has won three of the last five races at AMS, and
Joe Gibbs Racing teammate Tony Stewart will start in the first two
rows, with Mike Skinner starting outside Labonte on Row 1. Ford
drivers Dale Jarrett and Jeremy Mayfield will start fourth and
fifth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon, who got his
record-tying 13th victory of last season at AMS, will start eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good memories from the last time we were here, that's
for sure,'' Gordon said. ``It's going real well for us, like the
last time we were here. The car feels very similar and the track
feels very similar. I'm sure some other guys have gotten better,
but as far as the weather, we can't control that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since winning the season-opening Daytona 500 on Feb. 14, Gordon
hasn't found victory lane. Jack Roush Racing teammates Mark Martin
and Jeff Burton have taken the last two wins at Rockingham and Las
Vegas. But Burton needed a provisional to make the field for
today's race and will start 37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the results of the last two races, I'd say
(there's some parity in the sport),'' Gordon said. ``I was a little
nervous about halfway through Las Vegas last weekend because I was
the first Chevy and I was running 10th. I personally think the
Pontiacs are the best cars right now. The Fords are really good,
and the Chevys seem to be pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
