</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARADE-CONTROVERSY-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONX IS JOINING FUROR OVER ST. PATRICK'S DAY PARADE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first St. Patrick's Day parade in the Bronx in 70
years has, in the last few days, become embroiled in the same
political turmoil over gay marchers that has troubled the St.
Patrick's Day parade in Manhattan since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer, and other elected
officials said Friday that they would not march in Sunday's parade
because organizers had decided to exclude a gay and lesbian Irish
organization, the Lavender and Green Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parades should be bringing people together, not tearing them
apart,'' Ferrer said. ``I was under the original impression that
this was an event intended to be open to all comers.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, organizers from the Throgs Neck Benevolent
Association invited the gay organization to march under its own
banner. Advertisements for the parade also said that all groups
were welcome.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, alliance officials said, parade organizers told
them that the group would not be welcome after Irish church and
school groups threatened to withdraw in protest over the inclusion
of gay marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy McNulty, a co-chairman of the Lavender and Green Alliance,
said the decision was ``completely disheartening after the welcome
that was extended to us.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Here it is, in 1999. We've finally seen that there
are people willing to include us. But under pressure, bigotry has
ruled once again.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ferrer said the parade was intended to be a ``great
celebration,'' instead it is now replicating an annual controversy
over the parade up Fifth Avenue and exposing strains within the
Irish community.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, gay organizations have been prohibited from marching
in the Manhattan parade under their own banners. Despite legal
battles and protests, the Ancient Order of the Hibernians, which
organizes the parade, has refused to modify its stand.
</P>
<P>
   At the St. Patrick's Day Parade in 1993, Cardinal John O'Connor
defended the decision to exclude gay groups, declaring that
political correctness is not worth ``one comma in the Apostles'
Creed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Over the years, conflict over the right to march has practically
become a mini-tradition within the larger tradition of the Irish
parade. Gay groups have also been banned from marching in the St.
Patrick's Day Parade in Brooklyn. But the Bronx parade promised to
be an exception, and to members of the Lavender and Green Alliance
that signaled a new era.
</P>
<P>
   McNulty said that he was ecstatic on March 4 when the alliance
received an invitation from a parade organizer, Patrick Devine.
``It was the first parade in the city to welcome us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, at a party to celebrate the group's fifth
anniversary, the group announced that it would march. The
celebration itself was another milestone, because a Roman Catholic
church, St. Paul the Apostle on Ninth Avenue in Manhattan, let the
group hold its party there.
</P>
<P>
   A March 7 press release from the alliance hailed its invitation
to march. As a result, two Irish newspapers ran articles about the
group being welcomed, and pressure started to build from
organizations like the Ancient Order of the Hibernians and the
Knights of Columbus, McNulty said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Devine called the alliance and withdrew the
invitation. ``He told us that he's getting pressure, that churches
would pull out and schools would pull out, and that they were going
to have to withdraw the welcome,'' McNulty said.
</P>
<P>
   Devine did not return two phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx parade is scheduled to begin Sunday at noon on the
corner of East Tremont and Lafayette avenues in the Throgs Neck
section of the Bronx. Gay organizations including the alliance, the
Gay and Lesbian Independent Democrats, and Dignity, a Catholic
group, plan to protest at the march, and are to be joined by City
Councilwoman Christine Quinn and state Senator Thomas K. Duane.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Guiliani will not attend the Bronx parade because
of scheduling conflicts, a spokeswoman said, but will attend the
Manhattan parade on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
