<HEADLINE>
SEA SCOUTS TRY FOR ANOTHER SAILING SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: R.I., Conn.)   (jw) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is with understandable optimism that a bunch of teen-age
sailors are preparing these cold, wintry days for Block Island Race
Week in June. The team of Sea Scouts slipped into the event through
the back door two years ago, and an unexpected victory made them
defending champions in the biennial rendition of the regatta.
</P>
<P>
   The teens shocked a fleet of adult crew members in 1997 by
winning the Cruising Canvas Class. The Storm Trysail Club and
Yachting Magazine stage the Block Island regatta on alternate years
and the race series is traditionally well attended and competitive.
No one expects less of the event this year, scheduled for June
20-25 on Rhode Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost on the teen-agers' minds these days is making a new
high-tech Kevlar sail, which they plan to build this month at a
loft in Norwalk, Conn., where most of them live and the Sea Scout
group, Ship 6, is based.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of diligence allows the teens to be taken seriously in
big-boat sailing. Teen-agers in yachting usually compete in small
dinghies, and they rarely move beyond the junior-race level except
as a crew member here and there. Their appearance at Block Island
was the first for a crew of teens.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Austin, the Sea Scouts' team leader and boat skipper, said
that the victory two years ago might have been a surprise to
everyone else, but not to the seven scouts racing. ``It was
basically a boatload of children on a race horse,'' Austin said.
``People said, `Oh, you're here to watch.' And we said, `No, we're
here to race.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Their 40-foot race boat, known in its former racing circles as
Celebration, was donated to the group six years ago. The sailboat
was not in the best of shape when it arrived. But Celebration had a
respected past that included victories in the Southern Ocean Racing
Conference, an annual grand prix regatta off Florida. And for the
Sea Scouts, the yacht's tender condition upon arrival became a
rallying point, an inspiration for their do-it-yourself eagerness.
</P>
<P>
   The Hathaway, Reiser &AMP; Raymond sail loft in Norwalk has already
helped the Sea Scouts build a 580-square-foot Dacron mainsail,
which will be used for many of the group's 60 or more day sails,
races and overnight trips that the Ship No. 6 Sea Scouts take each
summer. The mainsail would have cost them about $4,200 to buy, but
donations in time and materials from the Hathaway loft meant that
the only cost to them was time _ after school and on Saturdays this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the teens received free sail cloth from Dimension
Polyant Sailcloth, a marine company in Putnam, Conn., and use of a
laser-cutting machine from Banks Sails in Norwalk.
</P>
<P>
   The mainsail made of Kevlar, a material that allows a more
streamlined design, will be used for racing at Block Island.
Prospects for a faster sail have the scouts more enthused than
ever. ``We'll be doing a lot more work on that sail,'' said David
Flewellyn, a 16-year-old Sea Scout who raced at Block Island.
``It's mostly going to be glued together with industrial glue, so
we can do 80 percent of the work. With the Dacron sail, we had to
let the loft seamstresses do all the sewing.'' If they had to buy
the sail retail, it would cost about $6,500.
</P>
<P>
   Flewellyn said he was confident that his team could win again at
Block Island. But it will be hard to duplicate the excitement of
coming out of nowhere two years ago. ``I was ecstatic,'' he said
about that victory. ``I couldn't believe it. Dennis Conner was
right there as they announced our name. All week people had been
rooting for us because we were the underdog. But we knew we could
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, others also think they can do it again. ``They're
very focused and well trained, '' said Rich du Moulin, an America's
Cup crew member in the 1960s and 1970s who has donated used
headsails from his Express 37 grand prix boat to the Sea Scouts.
``My feeling is that they could win in that class again.''
</P>
<P>
   MAKING WAVES
</P>
<P>
   With five of the nine sailboats in the Around Alone
single-handed fleet safely ashore last week in Punta del Este,
Uruguay, the fourth port of call, race organizers confirmed the
overall standings in the two race classes. In first place among the
60-foot Class I sailboats is Giovanni Soldini, the Italian solo
racer who rescued Isabelle Autissier from her capsized boat last
month in the South Pacific Ocean. By heeding Autissier's distress
call, Soldini was awarded a 24-hour reduction in elapsed time for
Leg 3. ... Leading Class II, for boats up to 50 feet, is
Jean-Pierre Mouligne, a Frenchman who lives in Newport, R.I. As
skipper of the 50-foot yacht, Cray Valley, Mouligne has finished
first in all three legs so far of the 27,000-mile competition . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
