<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTENDED-STAY-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: HOME SWEET HOTEL, WITH EXTENDED RATES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Wash., Calif.)   By ALAN S. OSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home for Jonathan Worswick is San Diego. But since last July he
has been living in Manhattan, first in one hotel and now in another
_ Plaza 50.
</P>
<P>
   His employer, Advanced Information Resources, a San Diego-based
software company, sent him here with a few colleagues to tend to
the computer needs of a handful of commercial banks. He came
expecting to be on the job for three months, but the stay has been
extended twice, and now is expected to run at least until July.
</P>
<P>
   The assignment made the 35-year-old Worswick a candidate for
residence in what the lodging industry has come to label an
``extended-stay hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   He is in a building that has 74 guest rooms and operates as a
transient hotel. But it also has 132 suites with kitchens, and it
offers discounts for stays up to 30 days. A total of 22 percent of
its occupancy consists of guests staying two weeks or longer, the
management says.
</P>
<P>
   So Plaza 50 is in a sense a hybrid, a transient hotel filled
with suites appropriate for longer-term occupancy, and one among
many of the recent variants in forms of lodging operations that are
cropping up in Manhattan. The hybrid is presenting challenges for
New York City zoning law, especially in residential condominiums,
where it is illegal to rent out rooms on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Most suite hotels or pure extended-stay hotels are run by
national chains in suburban centers of corporate activity, where
they are frequently hosts to visiting business people and trainees.
More of these hotel products are en route to Manhattan, via such
chains as Doubletree Guest Suites, Embassy Suites and perhaps
Homewood Suites, Homestead Village and Candlewood. Nationally, the
length of stay in an extended-stay hotel typically ranges from two
weeks to three months; suite hotels have a shorter-term occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   There already has been a growth in Manhattan of longer-term
occupancy hotels that provide furnished suites and hotel and maid
services, but they do not necessarily consider themselves
extended-stay hotels. If the building is in a zone that bars
transient occupancy, the management may be at pains to avoid the
term hotel entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-suite Envoy Club, which occupies the first five floors of
a new rental building, is an example. It requires a minimum stay of
30 days, and it may give a lease for as long as one year. Prices
for a 30-day stay in a one-bedroom suite start at $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillips Club, with 200 suites is now being built by
Millennium Partners, and 96 suites are in operation within the
company's Grand Millennium residential condominium. The Phillips
Club describes itself as an extended-stay hotel, but nevertheless
has a one-month minimum stay, with prices for a one-bedroom suite
starting at $6,600 a month.
</P>
<P>
   But nomenclature differs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our average length of stay is five months though our minimum
is one month,'' said Claes Loven, who runs the 84-unit Sutton
Hotel, though he prefers to call it merely the Sutton. ``We are not
an extended-stay hotel.'' Monthly rates for one-bedroom suites
range from $6,000 to $9,000. Another example is the 108-suite
Marmora-Manhattan Hotel, with one-bedroom monthly rates of $4,500
to $7,200.
</P>
<P>
   Some zoning specialists believe that the city's zoning code is
poorly designed to deal with the phenomenon of temporary occupancy
in service-enhanced housing. In the zoning code a ``hotel'' is by
definition for transients only, meaning that customers cannot book
for more than 30 days. Hotels are allowed in commercial zones only.
An apartment hotel, a category allowed in residential zones, must
offer leases of 30 days or more. There is no other category.
</P>
<P>
   What happens in a time-share situation, when a unit is purchased
in a condominium and then leased out regularly for brief periods of
time?'' asked Michael Parley, the principal in Development
Consulting Services, which provides zoning consulting services to
the real estate industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the extended-stay operators come to New York and we tell
them they have to file for a building permit either as a
residential building or a transient hotel, they are amazed,''
Parley said. ``It often means they can't function in a location
where they believe their operation would be totally appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The zoning code should be updated, Parley said, to take the
extended-stay phenomenon into account. This would benefit
legitimate extended-stay operators if it allowed them to operate in
any of the residential districts where apartment hotels are already
allowed. It could also enable condominium developers to offer
apartments that may legally be used for extended stays or transient
occupancy as well as permanent occupancy. Currently, it is not
unusual for individual owners in residential condominiums to rent
out their apartments through brokers on a daily basis, although
this violates zoning law when the building has a residential
certificate of occupancy. ``In some locations the hybrid building
should be legal,'' Parley said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the city's foremost developer of a hybrid hotel is the
locally based, family-run Manhattan East Suite Hotels chain, the
owner of Plaza 50 and nine other Manhattan hotels. Its latest
project is the Benjamin, a $40 million reconstruction of the former
Beverly Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Still under construction, the Benjamin will open next month with
209 rooms, including 97 one-bedroom suites, and function as a
transient hotel with discount rates for extended stays. Nightly
rates will start at $320 for a room and $420 for a standard
one-bedroom suite, with a standard discount of 15 percent for seven
days and 20 percent for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   When Benjamin J. Denihan Sr. started developing all-suite hotels
in the early 60s, he called them apartment hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The first project was the 134-unit Lyden Gardens, where he had
long run a high-end laundry and dry-cleaning establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In its expansion through acquisitions over the years the chain
has converted many rooms into suites, with full kitchens, to meet
the demand for longer stays. For example, the company bought the
400-room Shelburne Hotel in 1967 and converted it into 263 suites
with kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 25 percent of Manhattan East Suite's overall
occupancy is for a week or longer, said Daniel J. Denihan and his
sister, Brooke Denihan Barrett, two of the owning partners, in an
interview. Eighty percent of the business is corporate.
</P>
<P>
   The company still does its own laundry. At its headquarters in a
converted loft it handles 4.5 million pounds of laundry a year on
one shift, servicing all 2,000 of its rooms or suites. ``After we
get to 5.5 million pounds we'll have to go to two shifts,'' said
Denihan, whose partners include two brothers, his sister, a nephew
and one nonfamily associate.
</P>
<P>
   While the Manhattan East Suite Hotel chain has evolved from an
apartment-hotel operation into a suite-hotel operator with
substantial transient occupancy, the national chains accustomed to
serving corporate clients in suburban office parks are developing
long-term-stay operations in the city. The operators say they find
that the average length of an extended stay in a ``destination''
city is longer than it is in a suburban office park.
</P>
<P>
   Stevan D. Porter, executive vice president for operations of
Promus Hotel Corp., the Memphis-based owner-operator and franchiser
of more than 1,300 hotels with 192,000 rooms, said that the
Doubletree hotel in Times Square and the Embassy Suites hotel under
construction in Battery Park City would be traditional transient
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But if Promus develops one of its Homewood Suites projects in
the city it will be a ``pure extended-stay hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Homewood Suites buildings have one-and two-bedroom suites
with a sizable entertainment area and a full eat-in kitchen. ``The
expectation is that 55 percent of the guests will stay 15 nights or
longer, but it's not a residential hotel,'' Porter said. ``We have
it in downtown Chicago and we're working on it in Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
</TEXT>
