<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: CO-OPS STRIKE UNOFFICIAL TRUCE WITH IRS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For nearly 20 years, lawyers and accountants for
residential co-ops across the country have been engaged in a
running battle with the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   It revolves around an IRS assertion that income received by a
co-op corporation from sources other than tenant shareholders
cannot be offset by the expenses of running the co-op _ an
interpretation of the Tax Code that can cost co-ops considerable
amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   Co-op lawyers and accountants have consistently argued that the
IRS interpretation of the law is wrong _ a contention supported by
a 1996 Federal Tax Court ruling involving a co-op at 665 Thwaites
Place in the Bronx. Notwithstanding that ruling, however, the
service continued to audit co-ops that did not report the income in
question as taxable _ apparently willing to litigate the issue
again.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by the apparent intractability of the IRS, co-op
organizations across the country and their professionals formed a
task force to initiate a federal lawsuit that would put the matter
to rest once and for all. Last April, Joel Miller, a Queens tax
lawyer hired for the job, sued the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The service answered the lawsuit, reiterated its position and
continued collecting taxes on all income derived from sources other
than shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Then the IRS blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The position of the government has changed,'' said Shelly
Bienenstock, a Manhattan-based IRS Appeals Officer, speaking to a
group of co-op lawyers and accountants at a meeting convened by the
Council of New York Cooperatives and Condominiums and the
Federation of New York Housing Cooperatives on Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who were at the meeting, which was recorded on
audiotape, say that Bienenstock's appearance was unusual, because
when the IRS has something official to say, it usually does so in
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Bienenstock explained, however, that while the position of the
government had indeed changed, it had not changed officially.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of today, Revenue Ruling 90-36 is still in effect,''
Bienenstock said, referring to the official written pronouncement
on the subject issued by the IRS in 1990. ``But I can tell you that
it's going to be applied rarely, if at all.''
</P>
<P>
   What does all this mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that the IRS is saying, `We're not going to give you
anything in writing, but we're probably going to leave you alone,'
'' said Miller, the lawyer for the task force. And, he added, that
can be very important indeed to many co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the great majority of co-ops will derive some
benefit from this,'' Miller said. ``And there are some that will
save tens of thousands of dollars.'' That benefit, he said, will
largely result from co-ops being able to reduce or eliminate taxes
on income from reserve funds by using co-op expenses and perhaps
even depreciation to offset such income.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Siegler, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, explained that the
controversy originated as the result of a determination by the IRS
that for tax purposes, residential co-ops more closely resembled a
``membership organization'' than a true cooperative, such as the
early farm cooperatives. The distinction was critical, he said,
because while residential co-ops are governed by what is known as
Subchapter T of the tax code, membership organizations are governed
by what is called Section 277.
</P>
<P>
   The original intent behind Section 277, Siegler explained, was
to prevent membership organizations and social clubs that are not
tax exempt from nevertheless escaping taxes on business or
investment income by using such income to provide services to their
members and then deducting the expense from the income.
</P>
<P>
   Under Section 277, he said, membership organizations may deduct
expenses associated with providing services to members only from
income derived from the members themselves. Income from outside
sources may not be offset by expenses incurred in providing
services to members.
</P>
<P>
   When the IRS decided that co-ops fall under Section 277, Siegler
said, that meant that income from outside sources _ including
interest income on the co-op's reserve fund _ could not be offset
by the expenses associated with running the co-op.
</P>
<P>
   ``This resulted in co-ops with otherwise deductible expenses
equal to or in excess of their gross income being liable for income
tax,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Siegler said, the IRS adopted Revenue Ruling 90-36, the
one referred to by Bienenstock, which officially declared that
residential co-ops were subject to Section 277. However, he said,
many accountants took the position that unless the co-op had been
audited in the past, the co-op was not subject to tax liability
under Section 277. That, however, resulted in hitting some co-ops
with tax bills that could add up to tens of thousands of dollars
when the IRS conducted an audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a number of co-ops that have been audited by the
IRS,'' said Dennis Greenstein, a Manhattan co-op lawyer. ``They
were absolutely shocked when they found out they owed taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenstein said that the change in the IRS position is
significant for a large number of co-ops in New York. ``This is a
major issue because until now, any building that had any kind of
investment income could be affected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since the IRS has decided that it will no longer be likely to
tax co-ops under Section 277, that means that it will be taxing
them under Subchapter T.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Kleiman, a Manhattan accountant, said that co-ops faced a
whole new set of challenges and uncertainties. Under Subchapter T,
Kleiman said, co-op income is divided into two categories _
``patronage-sourced'' and ``nonpatronage-sourced.'' ``Income is
considered patronage-sourced if it is derived from an activity that
is closely linked with the main cooperative effort,'' he said,
adding that such income must also be ``directly related to, and
inseparable from, the co-ops' principal business activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Income is considered non-patronage-sourced, Kleiman said, if it
results from an activity that merely enhances the co-op's
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Under Subchapter T, he said, nonpatronage-sourced income is
taxed in much the same way that nonmembership income is taxed under
Section 277. While that may seem to imply that co-ops are no better
off under Subchapter T, that is not necessarily the case.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, while income from the investment of the
co-op's reserve fund would be exposed to tax under Section 277, it
would likely be considered patronage-sourced income under
Subchapter T.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that while he believed there was little chance that
the IRS would revert to its former position on Section 277, the
task force stood ready to file a new lawsuit if necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
