<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VERMONT-REAL-NYT &LR;      03-13 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: VERMONT'S STRONG ECONOMY PUSHES HOUSING DEVELOPMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Wis., Mass.)   By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLISTON, Vt. _ Economic growth is stoking new residential
construction here in the northwestern part of the state, as well as
in Vermont's southeast. The activity in both regions is giving the
state a handful of large new subdivisions with long-term completion
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The homes include traditional detached houses on half-acre lots
as well as clustered smaller, but nevertheless detached, houses
that the developer calls carriage homes. In these the buyer owns
the house and the ground on which it is built, but the grounds
around them are owned and maintained by a homeowners' association.
All the houses have two-car garages.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the master plans for these large developments
generally call for house lots of a half acre or less with a
significant percentage of the land kept as natural open space.
</P>
<P>
   The profile of the buyers is also changing, builders say. The
strong economy is attracting people from other parts of the country
who are moving here to work. Changing demographics have led
developers to cater to more older clients who are attracted to
small, easy-to-care-for properties. On the other side of the market
equation, more large tracts of land are becoming available as the
owners of unprofitable farms age.
</P>
<P>
   While new home prices in these subdivisions can be 50 percent
greater than homes that the same developers built in the early
1990s, houses are selling as fast as they can be constructed, the
builders say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen a market this strong in 10 years,'' said
Robert A. Snyder, president of the Snyder Cos., which is developing
Brennan Woods, a 174-lot subdivision on 183 acres purchased from a
dairy farmer eager to retire.
</P>
<P>
   What propels home buyers is not the region's 1.9 percent
unemployment rate, added Snyder, who is putting up 22 carriage
homes and 152 larger detached houses at Brennan Woods. ``It's job
creation,'' he said. ``As more people get good jobs or advance,
they can buy starter homes so other buyers can move up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Snyder Cos. started construction on Brennan Woods four
months ago in this town once dominated by dairy farms. So far, the
developer has sold 17 homes, priced from $185,000 to $196,000 for
carriage houses with 1,500 to 1,700 square feet of space on one or
two levels, to $220,000 to $250,000 for the larger homes. These
range from 1,900 to 3,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to keep a pace of about 25 sales a year for
the next six or seven years, Snyder said. Many of his buyers are
people who are trading up or relocating. For example, in January
Suzanne and Joseph Bourgeois moved here with their two small
children from LaCrosse, Wis. Bourgeois was promoted and moved to
headquarters by his employer, the Blodgett Corp., a maker of ovens
based in Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started looking in September but nothing was available,''
said Ms. Bourgeois, 34, who with her 37-year-old husband purchased
a $254,000 house in Brennan Woods. ``We fell in love with Williston
because it's a rural setting with friendly people but close to
work, shopping and the highway. We saw some other Snyder homes we
liked. So we decided to build.''
</P>
<P>
   The Snyder company's experience here in Chittenden County is
being repeated in southeastern Vermont's Windsor County, which
extends from central Vermont east to the New Hampshire border and
south to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Windsor County town of Hartford, said Hunter F.
Rieseberg, the town manager, ``for businesses, the main restraint
on growth is the lack of housing at all price levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Both counties are close to centers of economic growth. Here in
Chittenden County, the economic engine is the metropolitan
Burlington region. In Windsor, it is just over the state line in
Hanover, N.H., the home of Dartmouth College and the Mary Hitchcock
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   For Vermont, the accelerated economic activity has generated
about 31,000 new jobs since 1992, increasing the supply of nonfarm
jobs to 280,000. As a result, unemployment has fallen to 3.4
percent statewide, from 6.7 percent in 1992, and down to 1.9
percent in Chittenden County, said Jeffrey G. Carr, vice president
of Economic &AMP; Policy Resources, a consulting firm in Williston.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s, real estate development was pushing growth,''
Carr said. ``Now, the situation is reversed. Strong economic
fundamentals are driving the demand for housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year 1,971 permits were issued for new home construction
throughout Vermont, a 19.5 percent rise from a year earlier. Even
more houses would have been built had there not been a labor
shortage, Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   The sales market has benefited from the fact that there has been
so little new residential construction. In the '90s most new
development projects have been commercial or industrial, said
Charles LaRosa, president of the Vermont Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Now, developers are seizing the moment. In Hartford, for
example, the Simpson Development Corp. recently completed a 152-lot
subdivision on 126 acres and a 72-lot project on 33 acres. The
company is now seeking permits to build an 85-lot project on 63
acres just over the state line in Lebanon, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   They are all cluster developments with single-family detached
houses of 1,400 to 2,000 square feet, with prices starting at
$170,000. The target market is retirees and people working for
Dartmouth or the Mary Hitchcock Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Simpson built town-house condominium projects
with units of about 1,100 square feet priced at $100,000, many of
which were sold to investors, said Dennis Marquis, the company's
director of development. Now, the company presells all homes at
higher prices and builds fewer units per project. ``We have fewer
construction dollars at risk,'' he explained. ``And our current
buyers are older and more affluent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Snyder Companies is also welcoming older buyers at Brennan
Woods. The project, which will cost about $30 million to build,
will leave 53 percent of the site as open space, compared to 30
percent at Southridge, the last subdivision the company built here.
At Southridge, detached home prices started at $170,000. At Brennan
Woods, they start at $220,000 and offer the carriage houses that
attracted Shirley and Leonard Mercia who are 72 and 76,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the views of the Adirondacks on one side and Lake
Champlain on the other,'' said Mrs. Mercia, a retired secretary.
``We wanted the country setting and the convenience of being within
10 miles of the club in Burlington where we dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercia, a retired professor of agriculture who has lived in
Williston for 45 years, was also drawn to the practical
conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to mow the lawn or shovel snow off the roof,'' he
said. ``Plus, we like living near families with children. It keeps
us young.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
