r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCAA-LYONSCOLUMN-TEX     03-13 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-LYONS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA NEEDS NATIONAL STANDARDS
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, U.S. District Judge Ronald Buckwalter will
hear arguments in Philadelphia on a ruling he made last week that
stops the NCAA from using minimum standardized-test scores in
freshman eligibility requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping Judge Buckwalter changes his mind about
Proposition 16.
</P>
<P>
   To keep colleges and universities from taking the ``student,''
out of student-athlete, it is critical a national standard remain
in place. Since 1986, Proposition 16 has been that standard for
student-athletes, requiring a high school senior to have at least
an 820 on the SAT and a 2.5 grade-point-average in 13 ``core
classes'' in order to be declared eligible to play sports in
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, the standardized-test scores and the core
GPA requirements have been a pretty good predictor of academic
success,'' said Pete Carlon, athletic director at the University of
Texas at Arlington. ``I'm afraid without (Prop 16), you'd have a
lot of kids who'd get exploited for one or two years.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, you'd have a lot of youths with absolutely no
chance of succeeding in college being recruited by coaches who are
more concerned about victories than about education.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many coaches, and Judge Buckwalter, disagree with the
importance of Prop 16, and specifically the weight it places on
standardized tests. They say that the ACT and SAT are culturally
biased against inner-city kids and students from poor neighborhoods
_ you know, black kids. In fact, in his 54-page ruling, Buckwalter
wrote that, ``African-American and low-income student-athletes have
been disproportionately impacted,'' by Proposition 16.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, numbers don't lie. So the tests should be tweaked to
make sure that people with brown skin like me have as much a chance
at passing the tests as those with pale skin.
</P>
<P>
   That tweaking, in fact, has been going on for the past decade or
so, said Bill Reeves, the UTA associate athletic director who is on
the NCAA's initial eligibility waiver committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of intelligent people who have worked for 10
years to remove the bias from the SAT,'' Reeves said. ``If there is
something better out there, then I don't know what it is. Before we
say, `there is a better way,' we better name it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said student-athletes have not been declared ineligible
at UTA any more with Prop 16 than before the guideline was put in
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have fewer minorities now than before,'' Reeves said.
``We have better ones. We have minorities (athletes) who are
successful now. A big reason for that, I think, is (Prop 16). Each
year, the quality of our student has improved, but the percentage
of minorities (in sports) has not gone down.''
</P>
<P>
   And isn't that what college is all about? Higher learning.
</P>
<P>
   (Quick aside. A few years ago, the SAT people changed the
scoring on its exam. The required minimum of 820 is actually the
same 700 that had to be scored in the 1980s. Seems like a fairly
attainable score to achieve. A perfect score on the SAT is 1,600,
which means you just have to get a little more than half the
questions right to qualify. Too bad life isn't always that easy.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, though, after you tweak the SAT, and after you get more
youths passing it, invariably, you'll still have many of the same
poor and inner-city kids failing the test.
</P>
<P>
   So what do we do?
</P>
<P>
   How about demand more from our public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference in the quality of inner-city schools and
suburban schools,'' Reeves said. ``A kid making A's and B's at one
school may have a hard time making C's at another school.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason that a student making A's at Inner City High
couldn't make the same kinds of grades at Suburban Hills High. Yet
unfortunately, that is exactly what has happened. This disparity of
the education is usually exposed with SAT testing, where one
student makes the passing score and the other one _ the one who
hasn't been exposed to some of the ideologies that an SAT exam may
go over _ doesn't pass.
</P>
<P>
   Should the student at Inner City High who is striving for
academic excellence be penalized because he wasn't taught the,
``SAT basics''? No. And sooner or later, we'll have to hold the
public schools accountable for that student's failure.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a problem that is too far-reaching for colleges
athletic programs to handle. Right now, to weed out who wants to
learn and who doesn't, who should be eligible to play college
sports and who shouldn't, colleges need Prop 16 to ensure that
college athletics does not become a playground for student-athletes
who have no chance as students.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping that Judge Buckwalter agrees. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
