<SLUG> BC-BKC-EASTADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    East Regional: Tulsa vows not to be intimidated by Duke
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Tulsa has heard all the terms used this week
to described the No. 1 Duke Blue Devils: Unbeatable. Unstoppable.
Team of the Century. All that scary stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But to a man, the Golden Hurricanes (23-9) said Saturday they
will not be intimidated today when they face Duke and its 28-game
winning streak in the second round of the NCAA East Regional at the
Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (33-1) was more than a little intimidating in its opener
Friday night, beating Florida A&AMP;M by 41 (99-58). It could have very
easily been 81.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa, however, has already ended the 25-game winning streak
that belonged to the College of Charleston, which it beat 62-53
late Friday night. So why not go for another?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to back down from anybody,'' said sophomore
guard Marcus Hill. ``We're not going into this game looking for any
kind of moral victories. If we take care of the basketball and get
back on the break, we have a chance to be in this thing with five
minutes remaining. Then anything could happen. I don't think
anybody on this team thinks Duke is unbeatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are just the words that coach Bill Self wants to hear. He
believes that a team will never beat Duke unless it can play
without fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said I think Duke is the most talented team I've seen
since the end of the John Wooden era (at UCLA) and I still believe
that,'' said Self. ``So why not just go out and play and let's see
what happens?''
</P>
<P>
   A major reason Tulsa feels good about today's game is the
presence of senior forward Michael Ruffin, who may be the best
player you've never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-8 Ruffin, the school's all-time leading shot blocker and
rebounder, is Tulsa's designated defensive stopper. Over the course
of the last four years he has caused a lot of problems for many of
the WAC's best offensive players. Ruffin is expected to be matched
against Elton Brand, Duke's All-America center, in what should be a
classic battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's a guy who can dominate a game without ever
scoring,'' said Self. ``He does all the little things that help you
win. If he's playing well, he can play with anybody. But he'll have
to have a special game if we're going to have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand and Ruffin went head to head last summer in Seattle during
tryouts for the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember him being very physical and you can't back
down when he starts doing that,'' said Ruffin, who has 17
double-doubles this season. ``I don't think either one of us got
the better of it when we played.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin, from Englewood, Colo., is not your everyday basketball
player. He carries a 3.77 GPA in chemical engineering and has been
twice named an academic All-American. Ruffin can translate those
smarts to the court, said Self, and having faced Brand before will
be an advantage for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is a very intelligent person. He remembers another
player's tendencies and does a good job of taking away what a
player likes to do,'' said Self.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin, who has played the most games in Tulsa history (127)
said he is very much looking forward to his matchup with Brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the reason you play,'' said Ruffin. ``To get
an opportunity to play against one of the best players in the
country is very special.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Langdon will be back
</P>
<P>
   Duke guard Trajon Langdon, who has missed three straight games
with a strained left foot, will be back in the starting lineup for
today's second-round East Regional game with Tulsa, coach Mike
Krzyzewski said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon, a first-team All-ACC performer, aggravated an old foot
injury against Virginia in the ACC Tournament on March 4. He then
sat out Duke's final two ACC Tournament games against N.C. State
and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Duke's leading scorer was fitted with a special
insert in his shoe in order to take the pressure off his injury. He
went through a light workout here on Thursday but did not play in
Friday's NCAA Tournament opener against Florida A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday Langdon finally went full speed in defensive
drills and Krzyzewski made the decision to play him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to do a few things with him to make sure he was ready
and now we think it's time to test it,'' said Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski did not say how long Langdon would play, but it was
clear he wanted to get Langdon some minutes before next week's
regional semifinals in East Rutherford, N.J., which is where Duke
goes next if it wins today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned that we were picking up some bad habits,''
said Krzyzewski. ``Players sometimes pace themselves defensively
when they know a starter is out and you're not as deep. I don't
want us to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alford to Iowa?
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State's Steve Alford is on a lot of
prospective coaching lists, including Georgia's. But the college
basketball grapevine has the former Indiana star being named the
head coach at Iowa after the Bears' run in the NCAA Tournament is
over.
</P>
<P>
   Alford, who is 155-76 in eight years as a head coach, says all
the speculation about his future is merely a compliment to his
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as this tournament is going on, we'll let other people
talk about that stuff because they are not talking to me,'' said
Alford, in his fourth year at SMS. ``Sure, it strokes your ego when
other people think you're doing a good job. But right now I'm just
focusing on keeping this season going.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for respect
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's all-time record in the NCAA Tournament is 6-12 and
the Vols have never won two games in a row in this event. So
winning today's game with Southwest Missouri State and advancing to
the Sweet 16 could be a huge shot in the arm for the Volunteer
program, said coach Jerry Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it. You don't get a lot of attention by sitting at
home,'' said Green, in his second year in Knoxville. ``You really
can't measure what this kind of exposure can do. It opens a lot of
doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgery for Coach K
</P>
<P>
   Mike Krzyzewski doesn't jump up and down off the bench as much
as he used to. It's not that he's mellowed. The Duke coach has a
bad hip that is scheduled to be replaced on April 5, about a week
after the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a set date has been really good,'' said Krzyzewski, 52.
``I'm looking forward to getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski will have about a two-month recovery period during
which he plans to start on a book about leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
