<HEADER>
A9289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLW-TOUR14-COX     03-13 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLW-TOUR14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pro fishing's splashy look
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE LANIER, Ga. _ The Wal-Mart FLW Tour is dropping the green
flag on NASCAR-style marketing in the good ol' boy sport of
professional bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   And Irwin Jacobs, the former corporate raider from Minneapolis
who has brought glitz, glamour and greenbacks to the sport in just
a few years, has the pedal to the metal.
</P>
<P>
   When Jacobs' professional tour _ called the FLW by most in the
industry _ comes to Lake Lanier this week for its third stop of the
1999 season, it will showcase a flashy new marketing ploy more in
line with something you'd see coming around the turn at Atlanta
Motor Speedway than working the shoreline up Wahoo Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The FLW is expected to showcase eight of its fleet of 10
brightly colored sponsor boats, each built by Ranger Boats to the
tune of more than $40,000, as part of the FLW's latest attempt to
wow bass-fishing enthusiasts, as well as put big smiles on the
faces of its major sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people who aren't even anglers to see the boats and
say, `My God, what is that?''' Jacobs said, applying the
advertising philosophy of increasing awareness of a product.
``They're a crowd-stopper, a crowd-pleaser. Each one of these is a
work of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Sayner, vice president of communications for Operation
Bass, said, ``They are knock-your-socks-off cool. They really give
a NASCAR flavor to bass fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   That comparison has been made more than once since Jacobs got
involved in bass tournaments in 1995. That's when he took over
Operation Bass, the Kentucky-based company that runs the
tournament, as well as two other national bass-fishing circuits.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he thought the sport _ ruled by the Bass Anglers
Sportsman Society for most of the previous 30 years _ was spinning
its wheels. Since then, his lead-foot leadership has made the
made-for-TV tournament trail the biggest name-dropper in an
industry that benefits from the interests of 50 million U.S.
anglers.
</P>
<P>
   With Jacobs behind the wheel, the FLW offers big payoffs _
$100,000 goes to the winner of the Lanier event, and the total of
$471,500 is the largest purse in Georgia history _ and attracts
nontraditional sponsors not tied to the outdoors or fishing.
</P>
<P>
   This week, five of the boats will be used in the final round
Saturday, but all 10 are expected to be ready for future
tournaments and to be used in the final two rounds, which are
broadcast on ESPN and ESPN2. Qualifying anglers can win additional
money if they wear the company's colors while fishing. Obviously,
sponsors stand to get high exposure with their boats shown on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said the cost for a company to sponsor a boat is
``confidential, but I can tell you it's a lot cheaper than
sponsoring a NASCAR car.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the boats debuted in the recent FLW tournament at Lake
Murray, S.C., and they were a hit with the fans, according to
Charlie Hoover, Operation Bass president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are probably the most exciting things that have
happened to professional bass fishing besides the fishing itself,''
Hoover said. ``They generated a lot of enthusiasm (at Lake Murray).
People wanted to know where they could get one.''
</P>
<P>
   The top-of-the-line Ranger (518 DVX model) runs $36,000 fully
rigged with a 200 horsepower Evinrude motor and various other
features, according to Hoover. Another $10,000 or so has gone into
customizing it with the sponsor's colors and inlaid carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're something else,'' said Larry Lewis of H.D. Marine in
Buford, where many of the boats are being stored until the
tournament. ``We've had a lot of people come by and look at 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The boats, which will be on display at the parking lot of the
Wal-Mart Supercenter in Gainesville, will spin off at least a
couple of more products. The boats will be featured in an updated
computer game _ in which players can win Angler of the Year and be
put on the cover of a Wheaties box like angling superstar Denny
Brauer _ and a line of models is expected to be ready by the fall.
Both products will be sold only at Wal-Marts. Also, Ranger will
provide boats for pros to use in tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making bass fishing a spectator sport is my No. 1 priority,''
Jacobs says. ``We've just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   THE WAL-MART FLW TOUR
</P>
<P>
   What: Professional bass tournament trail, with seven tournaments
and $4 million purse.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Lake Lanier, third stop on the trail; the 38,000-acre
impoundment is 30 miles northeast of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   When: Wednesday through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers: 300 _ 150 professionals, 150 amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   Prize money: $471,500, $100,000 of which goes to the winner of
the pro division.
</P>
<P>
   Format: All of the professional field competes the first two
days to determine the top 10, which starts over on third day. Top
five is then determined and starts anew in the final round.
Amateurs follow same format, but the round of top 10 is the finals.
</P>
<P>
   TV: Taped coverage, ESPN, 6 p.m., April 3.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
