<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not-so-Great Gretzky
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two months ago, he was back in his familiar position
as the NHL's famous glorious adjective: the Great One. Wayne
Gretzky scored a goal, assisted on two others, was named the Most
Valuable Player of the All-Star Game in Tampa and for one night
looked far younger than his 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the only thing great is how the New York Rangers sometimes
perform without Gretzky, and the league's all-time point producer
looks 38 going on shuffleboard.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky has not played since Feb. 22 because of a disc
protrusion in his cervical spine. He had a cortisone shot Tuesday
and will be re-evaluated by doctors this week, but chances are he
is at least a week from returning. Neck and back injuries are never
a good thing, particularly for a 38-year-old who has been playing
as a pro since he was 16. That some wonder if Gretzky will be back
at all this season is not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only part of the story in New York. Gretzky has not
scored a goal since Feb. 4, and that's his only goal since the
All-Star Game. He has only eight goals this season and carries a
shockingly ill plus-minus rating of minus-21, which not only is the
worst on the Rangers by far but ranks among the dregs in the league
(he's one of the few that low without a Tampa Bay address).
</P>
<P>
   Has New York fallen apart without him? No. In fact, the Rangers,
thought to be comatose during the playoff stretch, went 5-0-1 in
their first six games without Gretzky until a loss Wednesday to
Ottawa. New York, getting terrific efforts from veterans Petr
Nedved, Brian Leetch and Adam Graves and a handful of newcomers
like Marc Savard and Manny Malhotra, moved back into the postseason
chase that finds five teams (New York, Florida, Boston, Washington,
Montreal) still in contention for one spot in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, some in Manhattan are wondering if the Rangers will be
given a boost if and when Gretzky returns. There's little question
his teammates have elevated their play in his absence. If he should
come back and play 30 minutes a game, taking up the ice time of
others, will it help or hurt?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we need Wayne Gretzky back,'' coach John Muckler said.
``We'll be a better hockey club when Wayne comes back. When you can
add a player of his caliber, good things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky has not said for certain that he will play beyond this
season, though he has a year remaining on his contract. General
manager Neil Smith has indicated that when the Rangers allowed Mark
Messier to sign with Vancouver, the decision was made to rebuild
the organization with youth. That seemingly counters Gretzky's
belief that the Rangers would try to get him some high-priced
scoring help to make another run at the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky wanted out of Los Angeles because he didn't want to be a
part of another rebuilding process. He doesn't want out of New
York. He likes living and playing here. But a few more wins without
Gretzky and a nudge out the door wouldn't be all that surprising,
which isn't quite the way the Great One should be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
