<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL EAST NOTES: Phree Phalling
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia coach Roger Neilson is running out of excuses for
the Flyers' sudden tumble. Any thoughts the team needed more speed
or scoring punch to make a run at the Stanley Cup ended when
general manager Bob Clarke acquired former Flyer and impending free
agent Mark Recchi from Montreal. But even with Recchi scoring a
goal in his debut, the Flyers lost at home to Colorado 5-3. The
Flyers' defense has been playing giveaway in their own end, making
life difficult for goalie John Vanbiesbrouck. And with Philly
tumbling to 2-10-4 following a 16-1-7 streak, you knew this had to
happen: There are rumors of friction between Clarke and Neilson.
Clarke reportedly ordered the coach to start rookie goalie
Jean-Marc Pelletier against Ottawa, and the result was a 5-0 loss.
One rumor has Neilson being fired and replaced by former Flyers
coach Mike Keenan. We are not making this up. But Keenan might
have.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes scholar
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa goalie Damian Rhodes may be playing his way right into a
Thrashers uniform. The backup posted his second shutout in three
starts when he stopped 29 shots in a 3-0 win Wednesday against the
Rangers in New York, raising his record to 19-11-3 and dropping his
goals-against average to 2.48. The Senators likely will protect Ron
Tugnutt before the expansion draft and leave Rhodes exposed in the
expansion draft. To protect both goalies would require them to
leave more of their young defensemen or forwards unprotected.
Rhodes, who originally came up with Toronto, also was impressive
last season for the Senators, particularly in the playoffs,
allowing 21 goals in 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Front-office shuffle
</P>
<P>
   New Tampa Bay owner Bill Davidson denies he has decided to bring
in coach Steve Ludzik from the IHL's Detroit Vipers (another
Davidson property), but there's little question Jacques Demers'
business card is about to either change or be burned entirely.
Demers will lose at least one of his two job descriptions, coach
and general manager. Even if he remains GM, a lot of the power is
expected to shift to current club adviser Cliff Fletcher, the
former Flames executive who clearly is a favorite of the new owner.
Demers is not about to whine. ``If the best thing for the team is
for me to do one thing, then I'll do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Etc. ...
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Barnaby, on getting his trade request fulfilled, from
Buffalo to Pittsburgh: ``It got to the point where the only time I
felt happy was when I heard my name in trade rumors, and that's not
right.'' ... Scott Lachance wasn't upset to escape New York when
the Islanders shipped him to Montreal for a third-round draft pick,
but he feared for his old teammates: ``No matter which way you look
at it, a third-round pick won't help (the Islanders) for four or
five years, so it's got to be frustrating for the guys on the team.
I just hope this isn't an indication of what's going to happen. I
hope it isn't what it seems it is.'' Which is to say, a salary
dumping. Lance Pitlick
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
