<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL NOTES: Thrashers update
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not that it will make a significant difference in the
Thrashers' expansion draft, but the NHL has closed a loophole on
teams signing players to voidable option years. The issue arose a
few weeks ago when it was learned Edmonton general manager Glen
Sather planned to sign defenseman Marty McSorley to a one-year,
$2.3 million extension, which would amount to a $1.3 million raise
next year. The deal would be at the Oilers' option and would expire
June 30, five days after the expansion draft. All existing teams
are required to make one veteran defenseman and two forwards
available to the Thrashers in the expansion draft, with veteran
defined as someone who played at least 40 games this year or 70 in
the last two. Sather's belief was that Atlanta never would claim
McSorley because of his contract. The Oilers would then let the
option expire and re-sign McSorley for far less, which would suit
the player fine because he would rather stay in Edmonton.
Regardless, the league has slammed the door on the rule
circumvention, saying any option deals now can no longer expire in
June. It's a little late, though. Last year, there were 18 players
signed to option deals before Nashville's expansion draft. There
were already 74 players signed to option deals before the NHL's new
mandate last week, although maybe none as extreme as McSorley's.
The McSorley deal will stand because the new rule was not
implemented until after the fact. Alluding to the option deals
already signed by players, Thrashers general manager Don Waddell
said: ``It was a smart play on their part.'' Columbus and
Minnesota, which come into the league in the 2000-01 season, figure
to benefit from the league's new position more than the Thrashers.
GOING OVERTIME
</P>
<P>
   For those who have missed it, the AHL has been cooperating with
the NHL to experiment with a new format to break ties, skating four
players (plus the goalie) a side in overtime. Not surprisingly,
ties are way down. In the first 17 games tied after three periods,
10 games (59 percent) were decided in the extra period. The AHL's
normal average, with a normal five-on-five format, is 33 percent of
ties being broken in overtime. The NHL's current average is 26
percent. One reason the AHL's percentage is higher is the league
automatically gives each team one point for tying in regulation,
whereas the NHL doesn't. That point gives each team more incentive
to go for a win in overtime, knowing it will not come away empty
handed if it gambles and loses the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
