</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL WEST NOTES: Dead Wings?
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the party isn't over in Detroit after consecutive Stanley
Cups, the Red Wings are creating a pretty atypical backdrop for a
team getting ready to start another title run. Defenseman Uwe Krupp
has been out since Dec. 19 with a back injury and still has
numbness in a foot. He has been assured his career isn't over, but
the same can't be said for this season, so the pressure is on
general manager Ken Holland to make a trade. But there are other
problems. Detroit took a 1-4-2 streak into the weekend and had
scored on only three of 25 power plays. The Wings couldn't manage
even one shot during a four-minute power play against struggling
Los Angeles. Things aren't much better off the ice, where assistant
coaches Dave Lewis and Barry Smith are signed only through this
season but being left in limbo because of Scotty Bowman's uncertain
(again) future. There is reason to believe that Holland probably
would promote an assistant (likely Lewis) if the Wings have a great
playoff run and Bowman retires. But if Detroit is bounced quickly,
the team may start with a new face. Lewis has hired an agent to
explore job opportunities. Smith has been particularly outspoken,
saying, ``A few years ago you thought you had your cards in your
hand _ you thought there was something out there. I'm not going to
do that any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Desert storm
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that the only win during the Wings' skid came
against Phoenix, which lost for the 11th time in 13 games at home
to lowly Vancouver the other night. Goaltending and defense have
taken most of the blame, but those areas don't excuse getting shut
out by the Canucks. ``There is nobody _ and I mean nobody _ to
blame but the players on the ice,'' Keith Tkachuk said. ``It's
ridiculous. It's brutal. It's the total team.'' The Coyotes are in
danger of losing home ice in the first round of the playoffs to
Anaheim. ``We can't coast in,'' Tkachuk said. ``So we came out
strong early (in the season), it doesn't mean (expletive). If we're
not careful, we'll coast right out of the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc. ...
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix backup goalie Jim Waite's struggles and subsequent
demotion to the minors is being blamed on significant weight loss
(22 pounds) since the start of season. Waite acknowledges he has
hasn't felt strong in many games and has suffered from dehydration.
... Calgary coach Brian Sutter, after the Flames went 3-1 in their
first four games without Theoren Fleury: ``It's a wonder there's
not a lot of dead people in town. So many people are jumping on and
off our bandwagon.'' ... Mark Messier, who has been out for three
weeks with a sprained knee, acknowledges that he is not rushing
back from the injury because the Canucks are out of the playoff
chase. ``I'd be lying if I said it wouldn't alter the thinking,''
he said. ``I've had a tendency in the past to rush back to help
when I wasn't 100 percent, and maybe it wasn't the smartest thing
to do. I don't want to hurt myself further and jeopardize the next
five years.'' ... Steve Duchesne ($11.25 million) is an official
free agent bust. He was a healthy scratch for L.A. the other night.
``He's not willing to pay the price to make a play,'' coach Larry
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
