<SLUG> BC-BKC-AUBURN-OSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCAA SOUTH REGIONAL: Auburn's kid is the man
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ If Auburn was to finally return to the Sweet 16,
then a child shall lead them. But then, Scott Pohlman only looks
like a kid. On Saturday, the reed-thin kid was the man for Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   The little sophomore guard scored a career-high 28 points,
including both ends of a 1-and-1 with 13 seconds left that
certified Auburn's 81-74 win over Oklahoma State in the second
round of the NCAA South Region at the RCA Dome. The top-seeded
Tigers (29-3) now advance to their third Sweet 16 and the regional
finals Thursday night in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn also got 17 points from Bryant Smith and 13 from Doc
Robinson. But it was Pohlman who led the Tigers to their first
Sweet 16 since 1986. He hit 11-of-17 shots, including 2-of-3
3-pointers, and all four of his free throw attempts. Adrian
Peterson led OSU (23-11) with 27 points and Desmond Mason had 26.
</P>
<P>
   Pohlman's jumper had given Auburn a 10-point lead, 67-57, with
6:08 left before OSU rallied behind Peterson and Mason. Joe Adkins'
3-pointer with 1:20 left cut it to 74-72. But Pohlman hit a jumper
in the lane after making contact with Brian Montonati, who tried
unsuccessfully to draw a charge. When Chris Porter inadvertently
tipped in an OSU miss, Mamadou N'Diaye sank one free throw. Then
Smith and Pohlman hit 1-and-1's to clinch it.
</P>
<P>
   Pohlman is still a teenager, won't turn 20 until May 30 and
looks like he should be playing for Gene Hackman and Hickory High
in ''Hoosiers.'' Of all the players at this site, Pohlman most
resembled a Hoosier gym rat, the Indiana high school legends who've
become almost mythic in this state.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday afternoon, in the same city where the Indiana
state high school championship will be decided later this month,
Pohlman showed these Hoosiers that skinny little kids from Roswell
can play some hoops, too.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the first half, Oklahoma State had the slow-paced
game it needed against Auburn and an 18-15 lead. Unfazed by the
Tigers' press, the Cowboys played tough man-to-man defense and got
six points from Desmond Mason to take that three-point lead. Then
came Pohlman, with a face like Opie Taylor and body by Barney.
Barney Fife.
</P>
<P>
   ''What he's done is matured,'' said Auburn coach Cliff Ellis.
''He's always been a player, just knows how to play. Doesn't look
like it when he's warming up. He's one of those guys who doesn't
look like he's going to sit there and bite you, but he does.''
</P>
<P>
   He devoured Oklahoma State for the rest of the half. Pohlman
scored his first points on two free throws with 9:20 left in the
half. Then he embarked on an all-you-can-chew Cowboy buffet,
scoring the game's next 11 points to put Auburn ahead 30-21.
</P>
<P>
   Working against OSU's Glendon Alexander, Pohlman scored first on
a jumper, then another when Doc Robinson drove and dished.
</P>
<P>
   Moving nicely to his left to catch an inbounds pass, Pohlman
caught it, turned without dribbling and stuck another jumper.
Auburn's full-court pressure finally got to Oklahoma, which
committed turnovers on three straight possessions. Pohlman then
sank his first 3-pointer, then a layup on another inbounds pass for
Auburn's biggest lead of the half, 30-21.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Oklahoma State had drawn within 37-33 despite 13
points from Pohlman, 12 from Bryant Smith and 12 Cowboys' turnovers
- one less than their average.
</P>
<P>
   Once Pohlman opened the second half with a jumper, Robinson and
Adrian Peterson played some one-upmanship. Robinson scored seven
straight Auburn points, sandwiching a 3-pointer with two
short-range jumpers. Peterson sank two jumpers of his own, then
later a 3 that cut it to 52-47.
</P>
<P>
   Pohlman, having rested for a couple of minutes, returned and
promptly loosed a 3-point airball from the top of the key. That
allowed Desmond Mason to score and draw OSU within 52-51. After
three Auburn misses, Peterson's 3-ball that would've finally given
OSU the lead rattled around and out. Then, it was Pohlman's time
again.
</P>
<P>
   He scored on a fast break off Peterson's miss, then made a
pretty pump-up-and-under move to easily score inside for a 56-51
lead. The littlest guy on the was playing the biggest. He was also
playing the point with Robinson sitting with four personals. No
problem. Coming out of an Auburn timeout, Pohlman drained another 3
to give himself a career-high 22 points and the Tigers a 63-55
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
