<HEADER>
A9310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-13 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Knight's best days are behind him
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Some things change with time. Some things just
get old.
</P>
<P>
   Here were creaking legs, a heaving chest and a head hung so low
you might have thought there were lead weights holding it down as
the laboring figure climbed the steps to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Knight looked positively ancient.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, so did his Hoosiers, suddenly as out of place at the
Big Dance as a fellow with two left feet and no sense of rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   As the 21st century approaches, Knight's storied Indiana program
appears to be more suited for the horse-and-buggy days.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's not only had a better basketball team than the
Hoosiers by a wide 86-61 margin. They had quicker, faster,
stronger, better players all over the floor of the Orlando Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we played five more times, I'm not sure we'd ever beat
them,'' Knight said wearily.
</P>
<P>
   Which says, as much as anything, about the state of Indiana
basketball in the state he used to hold practically in the palm of
his hand.
</P>
<P>
   It's no longer a sure bet that Knight would be elected Indiana's
governor if he chose to run for office.
</P>
<P>
   His weekly TV show is no longer a ratings hit on par with ER.
</P>
<P>
   Home games in Bloomington and Indianapolis are no longer
automatic sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   He is no longer a fashion trendsetter when he changes to a new
style of red sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, his teams have become virtually irrelevant amid
the madness of March.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA exits getting uglier
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Storm picked up the Hoosiers in the swirling winds
of an aggressive zone defense and an attacking, unselfish offense
and tossed them around like so much patio furniture on Saturday
afternoon, it marked the sixth straight year that Indiana (22-11)
has failed to make it past the second round of the NCAA Tournament,
with five straight exits coming via double-digit losses.
</P>
<P>
   Since their last appearance in the Sweet 16 and last Big Ten
title in 1993, the Hoosiers have been bounced in the first round
four times, and their elimination losses have grown increasingly
ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago at Greensboro, N.C., in what was Dean Smith's
retirement run, the great Tar Heels coach and Knight were on track
for a legendary meeting in the second round of the Tournament. But
the meeting never occurred because the Hoosiers were flattened
80-62 by Colorado in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   This most recent wipeout was Knight's worst in the Tourney as
St. John's completely smothered Indiana's motion attack with a
basic 3-2 zone and ran an offense that moved the ball around until
finding the best possible shot.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the ball movement, the precision passing and
the unselfish style displayed by the Red Storm's Ron Artest, Erick
Barkley, Bootsy Thornton and Lavor Postell is what we used to see
from Indiana. The sharp cuts, the clean, razor's edge plays, the
skill of surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about just saying that they have a better team than us?''
said Knight.
</P>
<P>
   A better team because the talent level is now so much higher at
St. John's and most other places than at Indiana. And that likely
has much to do with Knight and his unyielding ways.
</P>
<P>
   Paying a price for rigidity
</P>
<P>
   Mike Krzyzewski learned the game at Knight's knee and will
always be a devoted disciple. But Coach K's Duke teams have
expanded upon all those principles and incorporated NBA-level
talent into the program. Mike Jarvis, the St. John's coach, spoke
fondly of learning so much about the game from Knight. Yet Jarvis
has more raw athletic talent on his bench than Knight does in his
starters, save A.J. Guyton.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Knight's rigid, abrasive manner is finally catching up
to him in the manner that hurts him most as a coach. He isn't
interested in the kids who only want to stay for a year or two and
then move on to the NBA, and the top-level talent among four-year
players doesn't want to listen to him. And after 28 years at
Indiana, it shows.
</P>
<P>
   It was country bumpkins, wide-eyed and innocent, vs. city kids
just out there to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say the Red Storm simply runs and guns. For a
team with such individual ability, St. John's plays so smart and in
unison. Open 3-pointers in the corner are passed up in favor of
more-open 3-pointers on the wing. Six-foot jump shots in the lane
are suddenly passes whipped around the back of an unsuspecting
defender to produce layups or dunks.
</P>
<P>
   Artest, a sophomore, will likely head to the NBA next season,
and he will succeed. Barkley, a freshman from Brooklyn, says his
idol is John Stockton. When have you heard that from a New York
kid?
</P>
<P>
   And when is the last time anybody feared Bob Knight in March?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I give a lot of thought to is when I'm going
fishing next,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, mostly, as the bait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 1945EST &QL; 
