<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREBOMBS KILL 13 IN WESTERN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN GORVETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ In the deadliest attacks in western Turkey in years,
assailants hurled firebombs into a mall crowded with shoppers
Saturday afternoon, killing 13 people. The attack prompted new
security measures in the nation's biggest city.
</P>
<P>
   There was no claim of responsibility for the bombing and fire,
which tore through the six-story Mavi Carsi shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was the third in recent days in Istanbul, and it was
conducted amid a campaign of violence after the Turkish arrest last
month in Kenya of Abdullah Ocalan, the Kurdish separatist leader.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit accused the assailants of trying to
spread panic ahead of general elections on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's attack was the deadliest in Istanbul since a leftist
bombing killed 12 people in 1991. It began when three assailants
rushed into the mall, threw a number of firebombs onto the ground
floor, thenescaped, witnesses said. The bombs quickly set the mall
ablaze, trapping customers who had rushed upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them were probably killed because there was no fire
escape,'' the Turkish television channel NTV reported.
</P>
<P>
   Eight others were injured, two of them seriously, after jumping
from a second-floor window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three people were on the roof and tried to jump,'' said Basak
Ozkeceli, a passerby. ``They were shouting for help, then
disappeared in the smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the ruined building, only red ``sale'' signs and a
grotesque tangle of mannequins remained inside ground-floor display
windows.
</P>
<P>
   The attack followed a car bombing Wednesday outside an upscale
shopping center that killed a taxi driver and wounded eight
pedestrians. Hours later Wednesday, another car bomb exploded
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, a bomb exploded in the car of the governor of the
central Turkish region of Cankiri, killing a 14-year-old girl and
seriously wounding the official.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous bomb attacks, often targeting commercial properties and
bars, have also occurred in Ankara, the capital, and in Izmir.
However, Saturday's attack was the first firebombing to occur in
broad daylight, said Sabri Yalim, the regional fire chief. He
inferred that the bombers had intended to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Istanbul's governor, Erol Cakir, saying he expected further
attacks, ordered identity checks on public transportation and told
the public not to accept parcels from strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying hard with the police force and gendarmerie,'' or
paramilitary police, to protect citizens throughout the city of 12
million people, Cakir told Turkish television. ``We have issued
warnings to places where crowds go that they should take measures
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The attacks have been attributed largely to the Turkish Workers'
and Peasants Liberation Army, who, according to the Turkish police
minister, Necati Bilican, claimed responsibility for the attack on
the Cankiri governor.
</P>
<P>
   However, supporters of Ocalan's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
are widely blamed for these attacks. The Turkish Workers' and
Peasants Liberation Army and other leftist groups have cooperated
with the Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these terrorists think that they can achieve anything with
their banditry, or save the person who has been encouraging them,
they are wrong,'' Prime Minister Ecevit said, referring to Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Kurdish rebel leader's arrest and return to Turkey
to face trial, Ocalan's group issued a statement through the
newspaper Ozgur Politika calling on ``all Kurds to explode in the
heart of the enemy.'' That call was literally observed in the
eastern city of Batman where, on March 4, a woman blew herself up
outside a police station, wounding three bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, the Kurdish rebels also claimed to have downed a
Turkish Army helicopter, killing 20 soldiers on board. The Turkish
military denied the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns are mounting that with Ocalan's capture, the 15-year
war between the Turkish military and his rebel force, fought mainly
in the mountainous southeast, may be moving into a new phase of
urban violence. About 30,000 people have been killed so far.
</P>
<P>
   Security concerns are high not only for next month's elections
but for the Kurdish spring celebration of Newroz on March 21. The
holiday has often been a flashpoint between Kurdish nationalists
and Turkish security forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
