<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD BETS BUOY LONE STAR PARK OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
 STAR PARK-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Buoyed by a record simulcast handle in
February and a fast start this month, Lone Star Park is flying high
as another thoroughbred racing season approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-day meeting begins April 15, a month from Monday, and
continues through July 25.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star took $16.7 million in simulcast bets in February, a
record for the month and an average of almost $700,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   That bodes well for the resumption of live racing, said track
assistant general manager Steve Sexton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shows us two things,'' he said. ``One, that people are
becoming more educated about wagering and are more confident. And
it also shows that the awareness level of racing in North Texas has
been heightened, which continues to be one of our primary goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lone Star equaled or bettered its attendance and
betting numbers from the inaugural thoroughbred meet in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was quite a feat,'' Sexton said. ``But we've set the bar
one level higher this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The major thoroughbred racing events at Lone Star are the
opening-weekend tandem of the $300,000 Lone Star Derby and $250,000
Texas Mile (the track's first graded stakes) on April 18; the first
Lone Star Million Day on May 31, featuring seven races totaling $1
million in purses; and the popular NTRA All-Star Jockey
Championship on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the big names at the track last year will return, with
the notable exception of the horses owned by John Franks and
trained by Bobby Barnett. The Franks horses will be kept at
Churchill Downs in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Walden, who trains Belmont Stakes winner Victory Gallop,
has expressed interest in dividing his Kentucky-based stable and
sending about 20 horses to Lone Star. Walden finished among the
country's top 10 trainers in purse earnings in 1998, and among his
clients are Houston owners Art, Jack and J.R. Preston.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent media release, Lone Star also is spending
$500,000 on facility improvements, including a Pavilion Patio with
seating for groups of up to 300 being built in the beer garden
between the stands and the Post Time Pavilion simulcast center.
Also, the dirt racing surface is being reformulated.
</P>
<P>
   General admission is being increased from $2 to $2.50, but a
book of 15 live-racing admission tickets will be available
beginning April 1 for $25. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
