<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES: COWBOYS WILL BE PRODUCTIVE IN FREE AGENCY
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While in Tampa, Fla., a week ago, Jerry Jones received an
invitation he couldn't refuse. The Boss wanted some company in his
private suite at a Yankees' exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   So there they sat for nine innings. The most powerful owner in
baseball and the most powerful owner in football, joined by Catfish
Hunter and Phil Rizzuto.
</P>
<P>
   This could have been the ultimate socks-and-jocks summit
meeting. George Steinbrenner and Jerry Jones _ in pro sports, it
doesn't get any more hands-on than that. Get these two together and
you've got one of those U.N. debates during the Cold War days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually not,'' Jones said. ``I spent all day just listening.
It was fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I tend to doubt Jones being totally mum in this
situation. But if so, it continues a trend.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't Jerry and the Cowboys been way too quiet in the
off-season? Here it is mid-March, and a team desperately needing to
make a free-agent impact has done exactly nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Salary-cap problems, yes. Massive overspending around the league
driving up free-agent salaries, yes. But sad songs and waltzes
still aren't selling in Fort Worth-Dallas this year, not with that
painful Arizona playoff memory so vivid.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest way, however, to start Jones talking is by calling
the Cowboys docile in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``My comment on that,'' said Jerry, getting his back up, ``is we
will accomplish more in this off-season than we've ever done with
free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. Then when?
</P>
<P>
   ``By us going slow, it shouldn't be considered a negative,''
continued Jones on Friday, as he prepared to accompany Chan Gailey
and other coaches to Ohio for a workout session for a college
player. ``There have been a lot of blockbuster signings thus far,
but I also contend the big-money free agents have mainly been busts
in our league. We had to let the first wave go by, and now we will
catch the next wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones confirmed the obvious _ that speed receiver Rocket Ismail,
center Mark Stepnoski and linebacker Quentin Coryatt are top
priorities on the Cowboys' current list of free-agent desires.
Ismail's agent has said the Rocket will announce today if he stays
with the Carolina Panthers or signs with Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we are looking at filling a need at those three
positions,'' said Jones. ``As far as the three names, it's not
wrong to link them to us. But at two of the three positions, if we
miss on those names, then we have a good fall-back option. My
opinion is that market-wise, we can be competitive, and will
improve our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones brought up last year's free-agent class as an example of
upgrading, but then backtracked on Everett McIver, Ernie Mills and
Chris Warren. ``I guess all of them did end up injured, didn't
they,'' he said. ``But when they were on the field, they make us
better.''
</P>
<P>
   One change for the Cowboys this time is that free agency will
dictate how selections are made in the April 17-18 NFL Draft. ``If
we sign the players we need, that gives us a chance to do what we
should do in the draft _ take the best player available instead of
drafting for position,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   So as quiet as it's been thus far in free agency, the priority
to do something remains very high.
</P>
<P>
   As does Jones' energy level and league-wide impact. He spent a
week in Tampa as a member of the NFL's powerful competition
committee, and will be in Phoenix today for the opening of the
owner's meetings. Jerry will hit the desert running, conducting a
campaign among fellow owners on such subjects as the return of
instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got the 23 votes to get this thing passed,'' he
said. ``What we (the competition committee) came up with on instant
replay seems to have been well-received.''
</P>
<P>
   If approved, instant replay for next season will fall under
these new guidelines:
</P>
<P>
   A coach will have two challenges on questionable calls until the
two-minute mark of a game. A timeout will be lost if the play is
not overturned. In the last two minutes, there will be a league
appointed ``eye-in-the-sky,'' working with the officiating crew to
review any questionable call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can improve the game with this,'' said Jones, who
also remains confident free agency will improve his team.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, it's iffy on both counts. If George
really did all the talking last week, it's past time for Jerry to
be heard. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
