u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-PEACE-BOS &LR;      03-13 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUS OF IRISH TALKS SHIFTS TO WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The peace process in Northern Ireland will shift
temporarily this week to Washington, where President Clinton will
use St. Patrick's Day to urge the various parties to reach
compromise in the stalled efforts to revive local government after
27 years of direct rule from London.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, politicians from Northern Ireland have descended
on the White House, looking for support, not to mention the
``craic,'' or fun, to be had at the legions of Beltway St.
Patrick's Day parties. And each year, Clinton finds himself in a
similar position, asked to mediate what seems to be an intractable
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, politicians from Northern Ireland reached the Good
Friday Agreement just three weeks after returning from a series of
parties and pep talks in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton slapped backs, promised investment, and urged Irish
nationalist and British unionist politicians to write themselves
into history by ending centuries of conflict. There were similar
promises of support on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who negotiated the agreement gave Clinton credit
for steeling their nerves and encouraging them to jettison old
shibboleths to reach a compromise. His telephone calls to Belfast
in the waning hours of the negotiating deadline last year were
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, it remains unclear what Clinton can offer
the various politicians and paramilitary groups that the British
and Irish governments have not already offered in an attempt to end
the stalemate over IRA weapons.
</P>
<P>
   That stalemate forced the British government last week to
postpone until April 2 the deadline for handing over home-rule
powers to the new Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 people are expected to attend the celebration on
Wednesday. While the party is usually held in the East Room, White
House officials say this year's crowd is so big, probably the
biggest ever, that they are going to put a tent on the South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The unionists, led by the Nobel Peace Prize co-winner David
Trimble, are refusing to form a power-sharing executive that would
include members of Sinn Fein, the Irish Republican Army's political
wing, because the IRA has refused to turn in any of its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Unionist paramilitaries are also reluctant to give up their guns
ahead of IRA disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   The Sinn Fein leader, Gerry Adams, points out that nothing in
the Good Friday Agreement links the disarming of the IRA with his
party's taking two seats on the 10-member executive that they won
in an election.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA says it has no intention of giving up any weapons,
insisting that it did not surrender when it renewed its cease-fire
in 1997, but that it merely committed itself to allowing democratic
politics to replace its militaristic campaign to establish a united
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from the White House, a senior
administration official said the president will not propose a
specific compromise to the weapons dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no negotiating sessions,'' the official said,
speaking on the condition he was not identified. ``We won't broker
deals. Those things have to happen back in Belfast.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said the president's message, in his keynote speech
Wednesday and in private meetings with each of the party leaders,
will be ``to provide perspective and context, to remind them of
their accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials are hoping the change of scene will help
the politicians from Northern Ireland to realize how far they have
come, and how much they could lose if they fail to reach a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting off the island has its advantages,'' one official
said. ``You're away from the normal constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, away from the fishbowl of Belfast, and encouraged
by impressive surroundings and powerful hosts, rivals from Northern
Ireland have been able to talk and act more openly.
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments have tried just about
everything to get the unionists and republicans to soften their
positions, believing that if one side made a gesture the other
would quickly follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   But in what is a measure of the absence of goodwill among the
parties, and of the governments' increasing desperation, both
London and Dublin consider the annual pilgrimage to the White House
more important this year than before.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Mo Mowlam, Britain's top official in Northern
Ireland, said she hoped Clinton could find ground to compromise
where she and her Irish counterparts could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that just providing an environment for people to meet
and talk in a relaxed fashion will help build up some of the
confidence we need to move forward in the weeks ahead,'' Mowlam
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
