<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9317 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-TEX     03-13 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH IS ON FOR `THE NEXT ONE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a little guy, Wayne Gretzky casts a giant shadow.
</P>
<P>
   It's five championships wide and nine Hart Trophies tall and as
ominous as the ghostly spectre of 215 points in one season.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, for many, is the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   But with The Great One having just turned 38, currently
wrestling a neck injury and, in many ways, already having been
swallowed up by the shadow himself, the question is often asked,
who will be The Next One?
</P>
<P>
   Who takes the torch from Gretzky and carries the NHL into the
new millenium? Who sells hockey when the greatest salesman on earth
finally draws a well-deserved pension?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and their fans are getting a close look. Paul Kariya
and Teemu Selanne of the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim were in town on
Friday. The Stars face Eric Lindros and the Flyers on Sunday night
in Philadelphia and then will visit Jaromir Jagr and the Penguins
on Tuesday. And to round out the week, Alexei Yashin and the Ottawa
Senators will visit Reunion Arena on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In that group are five players who are drawing MVP mention this
season, as well as the Stars' own million-dollar salesman Mike
Modano.
</P>
<P>
   So who wants the torch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne Gretzky the player is one thing, Wayne Gretzky the
person is another thing,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I
don't know that any one person can replace him. But we can all
learn from what he's done. To me what was so great about Wayne
Gretzky was he was a great salesman; you couldn't help but feel how
excited he was about the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And how excited the game felt about him.
</P>
<P>
   What Gretzky delivered was a mix of skill, excitement, winning
and records that likely will never be matched in the history of the
NHL. So maybe it's pointless to try to look for ``The Next One.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will ever match his records, nobody. The game has
changed too much,'' Stars winger Pat Verbeek said. ``So maybe
that's the problem, maybe we shouldn't be looking for the player
who can be just like him, maybe the next great player is one who
does something completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros is in many ways the antithesis of Gretzky. The Great One
is small and swift. Lindros is 6-foot-4 and 230 pounds and may be
one of the most punishing hitters in the league. Gretzky is a
magician, Lindros a tank.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he's not worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lindros is such a different player than Gretzky. You can still
sell that though,'' Verbeek said. ``He has such tremendous power
and he plays such an aggressive game. That's what people want to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros has the numbers to become a superstar. He is second in
the NHL in scoring with 87 points (37 goals, 50 assists), is one of
the league's top faceoff men and also is among the top hitters. He
leads the league at a plus-35 and should be drawing all sorts of
MVP talk.
</P>
<P>
   And yet he doesn't. What Lindros gets most is talk about
disappointment, about how he has never lived up to the hype that
made him the first overall pick in the 1991 entry draft, about the
skirmish that forced a trade from the Quebec Nordiques to the
Flyers when Lindros, then 18, refused to play for the Nordiques.
</P>
<P>
   No one talks about his 1995 Hart Trophy as league MVP, they
prefer to talk about the 1997 sweep of his Flyers against the Red
Wings in the Stanley Cup Finals. It's hard to be The Next One when
you can't win The Big One.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that probably goes for everyone,'' said Modano, who
has deftly avoided talk of being anyone's savior. ``Until you win
at least one Stanley Cup, and probably a couple or three, nobody is
going to consider you great.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, in fact, said he'd just as soon not hoist the mantle of
greatness on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always talk about some guy coming along to carry the
torch, but I don't think anyone ever will,'' Modano said. ``First
of all, I'm not sure anyone could do it if he wanted; and then, a
lot of guys don't want that responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano's boyish good looks, easy going way with the media and
maneuverability on the ice make him a candidate to be one of the
league's top salesmen. But he sees himself more as a Steve
Yzerman-type _ a sturdy, two-way player who will be quietly judged
on a long career and (he hopes) a few championships rather than any
kind of run at the Hart Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   He saves talk of salesmen for the European players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would I pay to watch? Jagr, (Pavel) Bure, the European
players,'' Modano said, before chuckling to himself at a
revelation. ``Maybe that's why we're in trouble, the guys we got
selling the game don't even speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   But players such as Jagr, Bure and Selanne speak another
language _ one of fun. The Penguins' Jagr carries his team, mixes
the skill of Gretzky with the strength of Lindros _ and has a nifty
salute when he scores goals. He's the early favorite to win the
Hart Trophy this season. Bure, with his speed, has played just two
months in Miami after a trade from the Canucks and already has
South Florida abuzz about the game of hockey. Selanne might have
more personality than any NHL player if you can get through his
thick Finnish accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important, you have to look after the fans and treat
people well,'' Selanne said of his philosophy of selling hockey.
``It's just part of our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne has gone a long way in helping Kariya become more of a
public figure. Kariya is painfully shy and likes his privacy _ not
unlike former superstar Mario Lemieux. But Kariya is making a
concerted effort to be more available to the media and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be yourself out there, no matter if your Mike
Modano or Eric Lindros or whoever else. You want to establish
yourself as a player and as a person,'' Kariya said. ``As a young
player coming in, I felt I had to establish myself on the ice
first. Now I'm a little more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kariya stresses that players ``aren't out there doing The
Gong Show.'' Instead, they're hockey players first and salesmen
second. And as for all that talk about ``The Next One,'' well
that's a group project, as far as Kariya is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of players I'd pay to watch, especially on a
team like Dallas,'' Kariya said. ``Brett Hull, Mike Modano, (Jere)
Lehtinen, (Sergei) Zubov, I think any of those guys are worth
watching. I think all of them are worth watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is a fan has to watch, and watch closely, to
appreciate what each player does.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't basketball, you're not going to have (Michael)
Jordan be incredible every second he's on the floor like in the
NBA,'' Verbeek said. ``Hockey is a different game. Just because
you're the best player who's ever played doesn't necessarily mean
you're going to be the best player on the ice in any particular
game.''
</P>
<P>
   And that means the search for The Next One could be lengthy.
Maybe, the NHL simply has to look back to a time when it was a
league of stars, instead of one star, when Maurice ``Rocket''
Richard and Gordie Howe and Ted Lindsay and Elmer Lach and Bernie
``Boom Boom'' Geoffrion all shared the job of selling the league
back in the 1940s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there might be a player as talented as Wayne Gretzky.
I think there will be,'' Hitchcock said. ``But what's missing is
someone who loves and respects the game as much as he does. He grew
up with outdoor rinks and Saturday morning hockey. The players that
come up now are so much more sophisticated. Television, media
exposure, indoor arenas, all that stuff has changed the game so
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference between Wayne Gretzky and everyone
else,'' Hitchcock said as he pondered who could be The Next One.
``That's the hardest thing to replace.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
