<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9319 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-13 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JARVIS' REBUILDING PASSES A TEST  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Suddenly, the sky is looking to be the limit for
St. John's. A team that was picked to finish fourth in its own
league, a team with a freshman point guard, a first-year coach and
a volatile sophomore star, is headed to the Round of 16 for the
first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought that St. John's was nearly 30 points
better than Indiana's fabled program and its fabled and perhaps
fading coach? Not everyone here, putting statistic against
statistic and myth against myth, thought St. John's stood a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Jarvis has been the model of diplomacy this season,
but on the eve of Saturday's game he showed signs of irritation as
he fielded questions from the national news media. Many of the
questions directed to him had to do with his team's attitude about
going up against big, bad Indiana and Hoosiers Coach Bob Knight.
The Hoosiers have appeared in so many National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournaments, have won three national championships,
have gone undefeated once. Jarvis responded with appropriate
deference. He recalled how he had picked Knight's brain to help get
his own career started.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first coaching clinic I could actually afford to go to was
in 1967 in Framingham, Mass., and it was conducted by Bobby
Knight,'' Jarvis said. ``I bought his book for $1.50 and I learned
the finer points of man-to-man defense. It's five against the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Graciously but firmly, the 52-year-old Jarvis reminded the
audience that St. John's has pretty deep roots itself; that St.
John's, founded in 1870, does not look up at the mountain of
college basketball lore but is an integral part of that mountain.
Knight put Indiana on the map; the St. John's legacy was built by
many coaches. Joe Lapchick and Lou Carnesecca are intertwined, not
merely in college basketball lore, but in the basketball history of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's is the fifth-winningest team in college basketball
history; Indiana is 10th. St. John's has the sixth-best winning
percentage in college basketball, the ninth-most NCAA tournament
appearances. Eight St. John's players are in the Naismith Memorial
Basketball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, 32 years after watching Knight's clinic, Jarvis repaid
the favor as St. John's conducted a clinic for Indiana. The Red
Storm used fundamental, textbook basketball to rout Indiana, 86-61.
The pulverizing blow came midway in the first half when Jarvis
switched from man-to-man to a variation of a zone defense _ and a
zone press _ that stopped Indiana cold. St. John's extended its
lead from 30-23 to 45-30 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a new millennium, Indiana and St. John's are at
opposite junctures. While Knight has become something of a coaching
relic whose standing in the game hinges mostly on what he has
accomplished, Jarvis' time is now.
</P>
<P>
   The great challenge Jarvis faces is how he will continue to
build on the St. John's foundation. How will he forge his special
persona on a program that has a long history but also needs a
transfusion?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, St. John's glory had begun to seem tarnished. St. John's
has never won a national basketball title. The school has not been
to a Final Four since 1985. The program's 26 victories this season
are the most since the 1984-85 season, when St. John's went 31-5.
St. John's victory over Stamford on Thursday was the school's first
NCAA tournament victory since March 1993, when St. John's defeated
Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis doesn't have the luxury of reflecting on tradition when
there is a new one to build. And he knows how difficult it is to
build in the current climate, when outstanding players are likely
to leave after two seasons. Barring a miracle, Ron Artest, St.
John's best player, may leave college after this season for the
National Basketball Association. With Artest back in the lineup
next season, St. John's is a top-five program.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his career, Jarvis is in position to
compete nationally for the best players. But rebuilding can be a
fragile process, subject not only to the whims of teen-agers but
also to the twists and tragedies of life. Jarvis has only to look
at Kentucky and Tubby Smith, who took over that fabled program last
season. He completed a fairy-tale rookie season by leading the
Wildcats to the national championship. He set about rebuilding and
this season enjoyed one of the best recruiting classes in Kentucky
history.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Kentucky received commitments from two of the
nation's top three high school scorers: guard Keith Bogans of
Hyattsville, Md., and John Stewart, a talented 7-footer from
Indianapolis North Lawrence High School.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, 30 minutes before Kentucky played New Mexico
State, Smith received terrible news: Stewart had collapsed and died
during a playoff game against Bloomington South that evening.
</P>
<P>
   With two minutes to play in the third quarter, Stewart, who had
scored 10 straight points, asked to be taken out, complaining of
shortness of breath. Moments after coming out, he crumpled on the
bench. Emergency personnel administered c.p.r. Stewart was put on a
stretcher and taken to a hospital, where he was pronounced dead.
After Kentucky's victory over New Mexico State, Smith broke down in
tears.
</P>
<P>
   For Jarvis, Stewart's death illuminates the importance of
savoring the moment, enjoying the day. After Saturday's victory, he
told his team to enjoy the moment. ``The first three letters in
fundamental is fun,'' Jarvis said. ``Nothing is guaranteed about
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But the stakes and expectations are raised, and Jarvis' team is
hungry. ``This group is never going to be satisfied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Jarvis? Is he satisfied? ``I am very satisfied,
today,'' he said. ``I have a tremendous sense of accomplishment, I
have a tremendous sense of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the Round of 16 enough? ``It's enough today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
