<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/13/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- March 13, 1999 -- NY-RUSSIAN-IMMIGRATION-3,
03-13 -- Among 27 family members who arrived in the Brighton Beach
section of Brooklyn, N.Y., in 1975 from Odessa, a Ukrainian resort
city on the Black Sea, are from left to right, Sofia Vinokurov,
owner of a food store and smoked-fish business called the
International, Lara Akkerman and Bella Rakhman. It has been about
25 years since the first immigrants from the Soviet Union came to
this small neighborhood in Brooklyn. Now, for many of them, it
seems to have become a stepping stone to somewhere else. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 13, 1999 -- NY-RUSSIAN-IMMIGRATION-2,
03-13 -- Guests at a United Jewish Appeal fund-raising party in the
Brighton Beach section of Brooklyn, N.Y., portraying stock
characters from Soviet society. It has been about 25 years since
the first immigrants from the Soviet Union came to this small
neighborhood in Brooklyn, where the rents were low and you could
walk by the sea, and turned it into a Russian-speaking hub. Now,
for many of them, it seems to have become a stepping stone to
somewhere else. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 13, 1999 --
SUB-NY-RUSSIAN-IMMIGRATION-1, 03-13 -- Sofia Garber, 51, who lives
in the Brighton Beach section of Brooklyn, N.Y. Ms. Garber
emigrated from Odessa, a Ukrainian resort city on the Black Sea,
and was part of the first wave of Russian immigrants to arrive in
this small neighborhood in Brooklyn in 1973. ``I used to work all
day in the city,'' says Ms. Garber. ``Then I would come out here to
think and cry. I didn't know what my future would be.'' Now, for
many Russian immigrants, Brighton Beach seems to have become a
stepping stone to somewhere else. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) TSURUGASHIMA, Japan -- March 13, 1999 -- JAPAN-COUPONS,
03-13 -- Shizuko Nagasawa, who works for a printing company,
displays coupons being printed under a plan to stimulate Japan's
economy. Nearly $6 billion in vouchers will be distributed to
encourage shopping. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 13, 1999 -- BBA-YANKEES-ZIMMER,
03-13 -- Don Zimmer seems to have known everyone and seen
everything in his half century in the game of baseball as a player,
coach and manager, and now, at 68, he is filling in for his close
friend Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, who has learned that he has
prostate cancer. Zimmer's mission is to maintain the culture Torre
has created. ``Friends, that's what baseball has been about,'' says
Zimmer. (Jon Adams/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HAVERSTRAW, N.Y. -- March 13, 1999 -- SUBURBIA-FENCES,
03-13 -- Denise Werlitz, a 45-year-old insurance representative,
has angered her neighbors in Haverstraw, N.Y., by building a fence
with the ``bad side'' out. The town board has adopted a law that
bars homeowners from installing stockade fences so that the
unfinished side faces the neighbors and the pretty, polished side
faces the house. Outlaws have 30 days to comply or face a $250
fine. ``I feel, if I'm buying it, I should be able to see the nicer
side of it,'' says Werlitz. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- March 13, 1999 -- BOSTON-SCHOOLS-2, 03-13 -- To
some black leaders like Leonard Alkins, president of the Boston
Chapter of the NAACP, Boston appears to be moving toward a system
in which students will be racially separated in schools that are
supposedly equal. They are not sure whether the move is intended to
improve schools or resegregate them. ``It is not in vogue to have
diversity,'' says Alkins. ``Affirmative action and diversity are
being attacked on all levels.'' (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- March 13, 1999 -- BOSTON-SCHOOLS-1, 03-13 -- In
Boston, the crosstown busing of students like those here at the
Thomas A. Edison School in the Brighton section may be drastically
reduced. In January, Mayor Thomas Menino announced a new effort to
build more schools in minority neighborhoods throughout Boston over
the next six years as part of a plan to allow more students to
attend school nearer their homes and thus reduce the need for
busing. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 13, 1999 -- IMMIGRANT-TEENS-3, 03-13 --
Jian, the son of a Chinese farmer, taking part in a Bible class in
Chinatown. At 21, his dream of a college education seems out of
reach. Jian's weekends are spent behind the plexiglass of a Chinese
takeout restaurant in New Jersey with 12-hour shifts paying $70 a
day. Even with the security of asylum, even with a diploma, he says
he will have to postpone college until he can climb his mountain of
debt: the $40,000 that his parents borrowed to have him smuggled to
America. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 13, 1999 -- IMMIGRANT-TEENS-2, 03-13 --
Abdoulaye, right, 20, came to New York from Senegal at 19, with his
parents blessings, but struggles with loneliness and yearns for his
friends back home. But Abdoulaye is luckier than many of his peers.
He lives with relatives in the Bronx and works at the family
business, selling color televisions. He just wasn't prepared for
the loneliness. ``You know, in my country, every time I walk the
street, I was with one of my friends,'' he says. ``Here nobody
talks to me and I don't talk to nobody.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 13, 1999 -- IMMIGRANT-TEENS-1, 03-13 --
For teen-agers like Monir, of Bangladesh, work and poverty are the
markings of life alone in New York. What drove him from home was
neither poverty nor war, just the sure specter of a dead-end
future. At 15, Monir took flight, in search of an American
education, another life. Now 18 and still struggling through his
sophomore year of high school, Monir works late every night,
packing takeout orders of Thai food. The fear of failure follows
him like a ghost. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
