<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9338 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLMEETINGS-HNS &LR;      03-13 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
 MEETINGS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NFL owners tackle instant replay plan
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ While Houston and Los Angeles are eager to find out which
city is going to get the 32nd expansion franchise at the NFL spring
meetings this week, the rest of the nation's fans are more
concerned about the likely return of instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion, instant replay, the Thanksgiving Day games, unsettled
ownership situations in Washington and San Francisco, and a
possible change of the kickoff rule are issues on the docket for
meetings that begin today and end Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Instant replay was used from 1986-91, and a new two-plus-two
system is probably going to be approved for two reasons:
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue wants replay, and he usually gets what
he wants. And the competition committee voted 7-1 to recommend the
new system to the owners this week.
</P>
<P>
   What the league is calling the ``two-plus-two'' system allows
coaches to challenge calls two times per game and calls for an
unlimited review of disputed plays in the last two minutes of the
first and second half and overtime _ even if the teams have used
their allotted challenges.
</P>
<P>
   All decisions will be made by the referee using a sideline
monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The coach-challenge part says that if the call isn't overturned,
the team will be charged with a timeout. If the call is overturned,
the team doesn't lose a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two minutes of each half and overtime, a replay
official in a booth on the press-box level can stop play and ask
the referee to review it. There is no limit on how many times the
replay official upstairs can ask for a review as long as it's in
the last two minutes of each half and overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Replay must get 24 of the 31 votes to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Several teams that have voted against replay because they didn't
approve of the system proposed at the time are going to change
their vote. Cincinnati owner Mike Brown was the only member of the
competition committee to vote against the current proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh coach Bill Cowher, a member of the competition
committee, likes the proposal that will be presented to the owners
this week. Having a replay official upstairs to call for reviews in
the last two minutes of each half and overtime is the element that
should convince some teams to change their vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for it,'' Cowher says. ``I think two-plus-two has a good
chance of passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about this system, it won't allow enough stoppages
to slow down the pace of the game because you're only going to be
involved with a limited amount of use based on the challenges and
just two minutes each half.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the old system caused long delays while the replay
official in the booth made all the decisions, it was voted down
17-11 in 1992. It was voted down 20-10 and 21-9 the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh, San Diego, Buffalo, Tampa Bay and the New York
Giants are former opponents who are expected to vote yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear all about this new technology and everything,'' says
Giants owner Wellington Mara, who has never voted in favor of
replay. ``If I'm convinced that they've done something to correct
the faults we had before, there's a chance I would vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have an open mind. After I see what the technology is,
then I'll decide.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL says that under the old replay system, 77 out of about
37,000 plays would have been reversed last season. Under the system
that's being proposed, 40 plays would have been reversed. The
league says that in the playoffs, only one of 1,750 plays in 11
games would have been reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, we get killed (by the media) on these plays,
when, in fact, we're right,'' says Jerry Seeman, the league's
director of officiating. ``Any plays last season with any real
controversy, you can count on with two hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a shame that these came near the ends of games, and
that's why I think you're seeing a lot of the criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Also this week, the owners are expected to review the
controversial ownership situation in San Francisco, where Eddie
DeBartolo Jr. has been declared persona non grata by the league and
his sister, Denis DeBartolo York, who is running the franchise in
his absence because of legal problems in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The owners also may vote on Howard Milstein and Daniel Snyder as
owners of the Redskins. They bid $800 million for the franchise and
Jack Kent Cooke Stadium. Milstein, in particular, is being heavily
investigated by the league.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners want Cooke's son, John Kent Cooke, to remain as the
team president. He has been in control of the franchise and will
continue to be until the owners vote on Milstein and Snyder. If
they are not approved, they will file a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   As for the possible change in the kickoff rule, the proposal
calls for the receiving team to get the ball at its 25 rather than
its 20 if the kickoff goes out of the end zone. The idea behind
this proposal is for the kicker to put the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one of the league's traditions _ the Thanksgiving Day
games at Detroit and Dallas _ is being challenged. Several owners,
led by Kansas City's Lamar Hunt and New Orleans' Tom Benson, want
to rotate the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions have hosted the game since 1934 and the Cowboys since
1966. Owners William Clay Ford and Jerry Jones are lobbying hard
against any changes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Ford used his influence to to kill the same proposal
before it came to a vote. He was backed by the Big Three automakers
that spend millions to advertise on NFL telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ambush,'' Ford says. ``Once again, it's a total
disregard of the fans. Once again, it's a total disregard of
tradition. To heck with communities. To heck with tradition. To
heck with families. It's a real slap in the face of the Detroit
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is everything that's wrong with pro sports _
greed, lack of tradition, and lack of caring for the fans. It
sounds to me like the commissioner is behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tagliabue is, indeed, behind it, don't be surprised if the
owners vote to rotate the Thanksgiving Day games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
