<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUBURN BEATS OKLAHOMA STATE, 81-74  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Auburn, the best team in the Southeastern
Conference during the regular season, is noted for its overall
athleticism, its 20 offensive rebounds per game and its trapping
defensive pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But when the top-seeded team in the South Regional was unable to
shake Oklahoma State on Saturday, it turned to the most unassuming
of Tigers, the slender sophomore guard Scott Pohlman. His
career-best 28 points proved the difference as Auburn defeated the
ninth-seeded Cowboys, 81-74.
</P>
<P>
   The victory advanced Auburn (29-3) to Thursday's regional
semifinal in Knoxville, Tenn. The nation's fourth-ranked team will
face the winner of tonight's game between fourth-seeded Ohio State
and 12th-seeded Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (23-11) twice pulled within 2 points in the final
1 minute 21 seconds, but couldn't catch the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a boxing match,'' said Auburn Coach Cliff Ellis.
``They just wouldn't wilt. They wouldn't go away. We gave them the
one-two-three punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way for Auburn was Pohlman, a 160-pound guard from
the Atlanta suburbs who has floppy, light brown hair and is
nicknamed Opie, after the character from the old Andy Griffith
television show.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn held a 37-33 lead at halftime and pushed its lead to 10
points with 6:08 remaining on a jumper by Pohlman, who was 11 of 17
shooting in the game. But behind the inside scoring of forward
Desmond Mason and the perimeter shooting of guard Adrian Peterson,
Oklahoma State pulled within four, 73-69, with 1:52 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson (27 points) made a 3-pointer and a long jumper during
the burst. Mason (26 points and 9 rebounds) added three inside
baskets and a free throw as he outplayed forward Chris Porter, the
SEC player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peterson put on a show,'' Ellis said. ``Mason was right there
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Cowboys closing in, Porter was fouled and made 1 of 2
free throws to push the lead back to 5. Joe Adkins responded with a
long 3-pointer for Oklahoma State, and with 1:21 left the Auburn
lead was down to 74-72.
</P>
<P>
   On the Tigers' next possession, Pohlman leaned into Brian
Montonati, the 220-pound Cowboys forward, sending him sprawling.
With a clear view of the basket, Pohlman sank a jumper in the lane
and Auburn led by four with 51.9 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was,'' Pohlman said of his scoring. ``I
was just getting good looks at it. I can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter's inadvertent tip-in of an errant 3-pointer by the
Cowboys cut the lead to 76-74 with 34.2 seconds left, but Auburn
made 5 of 6 free throws in the final 29 seconds to preserve its
victory.
</P>
<P>
   There were seven lead changes in the game's first seven minutes.
The Cowboys emerged from the initial flurry to build their largest
lead of the game, 18-12, on a 3-pointer by Adkins at the 11:08
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State was able to hold its own on the boards in the
first half, fighting to a 21-21 draw against a Tigers squad that
enjoyed the nation's fourth-best rebound margin. For the game,
Auburn held a 35-29 rebounding edge.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's defensive pressure took its toll on Oklahoma St. in the
first half. The Cowboys, an at-large entrant from the Big 12,
committed a dozen turnovers in the half, one fewer than its
per-game average.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, Oklahoma State could not contain Pohlman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys who doesn't look like he's going to sit
there and bite you, but he does,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Pohlman scored 11 unanswered points in a span of less than three
and a half minutes, the last on a layup off an inbounds pass, to
put Auburn into the lead for good, 30-21, with 4 minutes 43 seconds
left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn, making its first NCAA appearance since 1988, has not
been in many close games this season, giving rise to doubts about
its toughness. The Tigers _ only the ninth team to become a No.
1-seeded team a year after failing to reach the tournament _
answered those doubts, at least for now. Of the previous eight,
three reached the Final Four, most recently Minnesota in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
