<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA BEATS STANFORD, 82-74  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Tiny Gonzaga University joined the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament's tradition of giant-killers
Saturday by shocking second-seeded Stanford University, 82-74, in
the second round of the West Region at Key Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory made 10th-seeded Gonzaga, a school of 4,500 students
in Spokane, Wash., one of the 16 finalists for the college
championship, heady territory for a school that was known mainly in
basketball circles only as the school that produced the Utah Jazz
star John Stockton in the mid-1980s. Now, though, it joins such
teams as Valparaiso, Cleveland State, Ball State and
Tennessee-Chattanooga as schools that have burst into national
attention after playing on the fringes of big-time college
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford _ which made it to the Final Four last season, was the
Pac-10 champion this year and was a preseason choice for the
national title by several publications _ scored the first point of
the game on a free throw and never led again.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga had never won an NCAA tournament game until this past
week, but Coach Dan Monson insisted: ``This is not a fluke
situation. We knew we were good enough to do it. Our kids believed
they were going to win that game. Obviously it puts us in the
spotlight, but this has been a good program for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga reached this game by beating the depleted University of
Minnesota, 75-63, on Thursday, the biggest previous victory in
Gonzaga's history. But it was a victory tarnished by game-day
suspensions of four Minnesota players in an academic fraud scandal.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing to tarnish Gonzaga's upset of Stanford. The
Bulldogs, the West Coast Conference champion, who were on a mission
for respect after being bypassed for the tournament last year with
24 victories, won with athleticism and courage, not intimidated by
the bigger, stronger and highly regarded Stanford. Gonzaga went toe
to toe with Stanford inside, outrebounding the Cardinal, 47-33.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be here since last year,'' said guard Matt
Santangelo, who led the Bulldogs with 22 points, 14 in the second
half. ``If we didn't play this way, I'd be embarrassed now.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Richie Frahm added 15 points for Gonzaga and guard Quentin
Hall had 14.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Arthur Lee had a game-high 24 points to lead
Stanford. Kris Weems added 18 points. He hit four 3-point jumpers,
including three in the final two minutes to keep Stanford close.
Mark Madsen had 15 points and a game-high 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   For the game, Stanford hit only 39 percent from the field and
Gonzaga only 40 percent, but the Bulldogs drained 11 3-pointers
compared with five for the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   Monson, Gonzaga's second-year coach and the son of the longtime
University of Idaho and University of Oregon coach Dan Monson, will
lead the Bulldogs against the winner of the Florida-Weber State
game Thursday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred on by a virtual home-court advantage with a large
contingent of fans who made the 300-mile drive from Spokane, the
Bulldogs trailed only in the opening minute, 1-0. Stanford tied the
score at 49-49 with 11 minutes 18 seconds left, but Gonzaga
answered with a 20-10 run to rebuild its lead.
</P>
<P>
   At the start, Gonzaga defied expectations and went to work
inside against the Cardinal's big men, scoring no points but
clearing room for Casey Calvary to hit his first two 3-pointers.
Less than five minutes into the game, the Bulldogs' lead was 5 when
Calvary took a lob from Santangelo and slammed it home.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Gonzaga knew the big Cardinal would work inside to
use its height advantage, but the Bulldogs held their ground and
even outrebounded Stanford in the first half, 20-17. When close
Stanford shots did not fall, the smaller Bulldogs hit the boards
and won the early transition game. With five 3-point shots, they
led by 13 after nine minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford answered with a 12-3 run and cut the lead to 26-22, 6
of the points coming on free throws as Gonzaga's pesky defense
inside also resulted in foul trouble. The Cardinal was lucky to
trail by only 4 at halftime, scoring at the buzzer on a Peter Sauer
layin after a Gonzaga turnover with five seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   With Lee taking over, Stanford slowly went to work on that lead,
and finally caught Gonzaga, 49-49, on two Lee free throws. But
Gonzaga would not fold and led, 69-59, when Weems nailed a
3-pointer with 1:28 remaining. Calvary hit one of two free throws,
but Lee brought Stanford back with an uncontested dribble-drive
layin, and the lead was 70-64. Gonzaga broke a full-court press for
a breakaway layin by Frahm, but Stanford then got a pair of free
throws from Lee after a foul by Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Frahm restored the lead to 8 points with two free throws, but
Weems cut it to 5 with another 3-pointer. In the waning moments,
Stanford never got closer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
