<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY READY TO FIRE AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ His opening-day start is still a question, but
Angels pitcher Chuck Finley says he'll be ready to take his turn in
the rotation once the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who has not pitched in a Cactus League game this spring
because of a muscle strain in his upper back and neck, threw off
the mound Saturday for the first time in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All went well, and he plans to start Tuesday's game against the
Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on taking my turn from here on out,'' Finley said. ``I
don't know how my pitch count will fall as far as (being ready by)
opening day. Opening day is a special day, but I've got to
understand the fact there are 35 starts in there for me and I've
got to be able to make every one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the other Angels starter have each made two starts
and are up to a pitch-count of about 60, Finley says he isn't that
far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been inactive,'' Finley said. ``It's not like
they're just taking me out of the wrapper. I've been throwing, just
not off the hill. I'll go out and just get a feel for it, get my
work in.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's 10-minute stint on the mound Saturday convinced him
he's over the stiffness he experiences every spring.
</P>
<P>
   Other ailments: Infielder Justin Baughman is in town to see team
orthopedist Dr. Lewis Yocum. Baughman is recovering from multiple
fractures in his left leg suffered Nov. 7 in the Mexican Winter
League, but it is taking longer than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going very, very slow,'' Baughman said. ``We're going to
discuss other alternatives. They said it would be four to six
months, but it was four months last week. And I don't think it'll
be ready by six months. Yeah, it's very disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the other alternatives is a second surgery (the first was
Nov. 11), which would put Baughman out for the entire season. Yocum
said a decision should be made by this week.
</P>
<P>
   Any questions about Tim Salmon's left foot have been answered,
and never more so than Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Salmon raced to the right-field line to cut
off a ball hit by Mickey Morandini, holding him to a single. In the
sixth, Salmon flew around the bases with an RBI triple.
</P>
<P>
   No Sammy: The 7,411 fans at Tempe Diablo Stadium on Saturday
represented the largest crowd of the spring at the Angels'
ballpark, and it had a lot to do with the anticipated appearance of
the visiting Chicago Cubs and Sammy Sosa. Just one problem _ the
Cubs played a split-squad game in Peoria against the Padres on
Saturday night, and Sosa was scheduled to play there.
</P>
<P>
   The other draw was Cubs starter Kerry Wood, who made his first
spring appearance. Wood gave up three runs (all earned) and three
hits in 11/3 innings in the Angels' 6-5 win. The Angels improved to
3-6 in Cactus League play.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Ken Hill, who gave up two runs (none earned) and
four hits in 22/3 innings, says his surgically repaired elbow feels
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been two years since I've felt this good,'' Hill said.
``I'll just pray, knock on wood, that I stay healthy all year. If I
stay healthy, I can help this ballclub. I know they're counting on
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
