<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FEUDS HEAT UP IN NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There might not be an All-Star Game, but another NBA tradition
has survived in this post-lockout season.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, after a brief honeymoon, player-coach feuds are beginning
to heat up from the Pacific Northwest to the Sunshine State. And
that's just in the past seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a look at some of the current matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson vs. Larry Brown: Wait a minute, isn't Iverson
leading the league in scoring? Yes, but Brown is still troubled
with his star, claiming he is reverting to his old ways since being
named player of the month in February.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson has missed two practices in the past week, having his
bodyguard call the Sixers the first time and then not phoning at
all the second absence. It's beginning to wear thin on Brown, who
has privately called Iverson a phony, and is tired of his theatrics
and aversion to playing defense.
</P>
<P>
   This one could last awhile.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway vs. Chuck Daly: All is not well in Orlando? Oh
really? The ever-sensitive Penny, who is shooting 39.8 percent from
the field, is complaining that the coaching staff doesn't
appreciate how many double-teams he's facing so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a guy who tries to create for everyone else,'' said
Penny, after taking 28 shots against San Antonio and Atlanta, then
settling for nine against Dallas. ``I only shot nine times (against
Dallas) so it wasn't like I had a really bad night. I want to get
the ball up 20 or 22 times a game, but I'm not able to do that
right now. We're struggling. The coaches are going to have to come
up with some more creative ways to get me shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Did we mention Penny is a free agent after the season?
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker vs. Paul Westphal: A team player at odds with a
players' coach? Are the Sonics sleepless in Seattle or what?
</P>
<P>
   Baker was livid that Westphal benched him for the final eight
minutes of the Sonics' loss to the Bucks (and ex-coach George Karl)
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what Paul Westphal is thinking right now
as far as playing me. It doesn't help when you're not playing well
and not getting a lot of minutes,'' Baker said. ``The only way I'm
going to be productive is being on the floor. I'm still capable of
helping this basketball team win games, and that's the bottom line.
He might feel differently, but he hasn't expressed that to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Westphal never met a player he didn't want to please, the
pair quickly had a heart-to-heart talk, with Baker telling Westphal
an All-Star shouldn't sit so much in the fourth quarter and
Westphal telling Baker to play like an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle's next game against Chicago, Baker played 42 minutes
and scored 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Look, I'm an All-Star, I want to be in the game in
the fourth quarter,''' Westphal said, referring to their meeting.
``And he backed up his words.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade talk: Remember when a team made a trade to better itself?
</P>
<P>
   NBA trades are rarely that simple anymore, and lately, it seems
as if every deal is finalized just so a team can make sure it
doesn't lose a star player to free agency without some form of
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Minnesota breaks up close friends Kevin Garnett and
Stephon Marbury and alters the heart of the franchise by shipping
free-agent-to-be Marbury to New Jersey. Or Milwaukee ships Terrell
Brandon to Minnesota, sure that he will never re-sign with the
Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks received point guard Sam Cassell in return, who is not
the caliber of Brandon, but is locked up in a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea if it was the right move or the wrong move,''
Bucks coach Karl said. ``I think we made a basketball decision
based on people basically wanting to be in Milwaukee. I don't think
you can be successful building a team without committed athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need commitment and players who will talk about it, and
have a desire and a passion and an anger for it. The professional
NBA (expletive), that game we've got to restructure around players
who are serious and committed. That's my feeling. I think we let
too many players blackmail us in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Where's the beef? The Bulls' marketing department set up a
contest in which fans in attendance, when the Bulls score 100
points and win, get a free taco from Taco Bell. Last year, the
Bulls had to score 110 points to reach Taco Time, but times being
what they are...
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls finally reached 100 points for the first time Tuesday
against New Jersey and won the game. Brent Barry, the former
Clipper, missed a free throw that would have given the Bulls their
100th point, but Toni Kukoc got it later in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of pressure, having to feed 23,000 Chicagoans,''
Barry said. ``When I missed, I thought I heard someone say `Go to
hell' but what they were saying was `Taco Bell.' I never got booed
while we were up 17 points and I was missing a free throw,'' Barry
said. ``In L.A. if we scored 70 points, every fan got a free car.
Of course, there were only six free cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Help wanted: The Lakers didn't want B.J. Armstrong, but that
doesn't mean he's short of options. Expect the point guard to sign
with Seattle or Detroit early next week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
