u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-BOMBSCARE-NYT     03-13 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-BOMBSCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPICIOUS BAG AT AIRPORT MAY BE LINKED TO EX-TRANSIT OFFICIAL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The police at the airport in Columbus, Ohio, rushed
hundreds of passengers out of a major concourse on Friday afternoon
and ordered planes pushed back from their gates, causing extensive
delays, after workers at America West Airlines took a suspicious
bag that had been checked to a security checkpoint, and screeners
saw what they suspected was a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   It was a false alarm. But Chief Richard L. Morgan, director of
public safety at the Columbus Airport Authority, said that
preliminary evidence tied the bag to Mary Schiavo, a former
inspector general of the U.S. Department of Transportation who had
been critical of the Federal Aviation Administration on airport
security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said that his department, which called in the Federal
Bureau of Investigation, had not verified that the bag was Ms.
Schiavo's or that she had had a ticket on the flight to Washington
on which it was checked. Nor did he describe the evidence linking
her to the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schiavo lives in the Columbus area but does not have a
listed telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   Two Washington officials speaking on the condition of anonymity
said that the object found in the bag appeared to have been
intended to look like a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan and a spokesman for the FBI in Washington, Frank Scafidi,
said that it was not clear if any law had been violated but that
airport operations had been disrupted for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure caused a hell of a mess out there,'' Scafidi said. The
Franklin County bomb squad took the bag to the north runway,
closing it from 5:30 p.m. until 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At the Federal Aviation Administration, Paul Takemoto, a
spokesman, said only that ``we are aware there's been a security
incident at Port Columbus.''
</P>
<P>
   According to officials of law enforcement agencies,
transportation agencies and America West, the airline accepted a
bag at the check-in counter for its 2:58 p.m. flight from Port
Columbus International Airport to National Airport in Washington
but became suspicious when the passenger who had checked the bag
did not board the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Most checked bags are not X-rayed. They are supposed to be
scanned if the airline does not know enough about the passenger, or
if there is some other cause for suspicion, like a passenger's not
boarding.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Nowack, a spokeswoman for America West, would say only
that the bag ``was not loaded on the aircraft, in compliance with
Federal Aviation Administration rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Several planes, including a Boeing 747 belonging to Air India,
have been destroyed in flight by bombs placed in checked baggage by
people who posed as passengers but did not board.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said of Ms. Schiavo, ``Her name has been mentioned many
times'' in connection with the incident. ``The information I had
was she was going to be on TV in Washington,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David V. Whittaker, a spokesman for the airport authority, said,
``it was not an explosive device.'' But screeners ``did believe it
was'' when they saw it on X-ray, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Schiavo was inspector general she issued many reports
critical of the Federal Aviation Administration, which is part of
the Transportation Department. Her book, ``Flying Blind,'' was
published in 1996, shortly after she resigned from the department.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her most scathing criticism of the FAA was on security
issues. She said in an audit in September 1996 that FAA agents
overstated how well airports did on security tests, and made
efforts to help airports do well on the inspections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
