r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-USMEXICO-LADN     03-13 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USMEXICO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO BEATS U.S. 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO -- U.S. goalkeeper Tony Meola, his lip stitched after
an unfortunate collision with Mexico's Francisco Palencia, could
barely speak following Mexico's 2-1 victory over the United States
in Saturday's U.S. Cup championship at San Diego's Qualcomm Stadium
before 50,324.
</P>
<P>
   Those things tend to happen when these two heated rivals meet --
as does the result, which turned out to be Mexico's third straight
U.S. Cup title, stretching its unbeaten streak against the United
States to seven dating back to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always tension, just look at this history of these two
teams,'' said U.S. midfielder Chris Armas, facing Mexico for the
first time. ``We were outnumbered by the fans in the stands and we
accept that challenge. They got us, we got them, but in the end we
just came up a little short and that's not something anyone in this
room accepts.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, however, hardly tells the full story.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mexico, not the United States, chasing the Americans
around the field.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mexico who looked like Team USA, losing battles at
midfield on a possession-dominated U.S. day.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice change of pace -- all except the result.
</P>
<P>
   Arena, nor his troops, however, took any satisfaction with the
moral victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to win any of those battles we want to win on
the scoreboard, Arena answered when a reporter asked if he thought
his team outplayed Mexico. ``I never feel good after any kind of
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   After a moment of thinking, he compared the level of the U.S.
teams play to the Steve Sampson coached team last year that beat
Brazil, 1-0, in the Gold Cup semifinal at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take anything away from the U.S. result against Brazil,
but I walked away from today's game feeling better about the way
our team played,'' he said. ``And we beat arguably the best team
(Brazil) in the world that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of soccer we can build on. I don't want to get
into the debate of who's better, us or Mexico, because they won the
game. But I give our guys credit, they played a heck of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans dominated the first 20 minutes, getting good looks
for forwards Brian McBride and Cobi Jones, but a quick mix-up on
the back line resulted in an own-goal and 1-0 lead for Mexico in
the 13th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Jose Manuel Abundis took a pass down the left side and
turned on U.S. defender Eddie Pope to free himself down the flank.
Abundis, looking for Palencia streaking down the middle, dropped a
pass in front of the American goal where U.S. defender Robin Fraser
and Palencia were in a shoulder-to-shoulder race toward the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Palencia over-ran the cross as Fraser slid to slow himself down
about five yards in front of the U.S. net. An unlucky break for
Fraser occured when Palencia's cross ricocheted off his right arm
into the net while Palencia plowed into Meola, cutting the U.S.
keepers lip and forcing him out of the game with a head injury.
Chicago Fire goalkeeper Zack Thornton replaced Meola.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, Fraser returned the favor with some
nifty moves down the right side to set up the equalizer in the 51st
minute.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-year Galaxy defender chased down a free ball on an
over-lapping run down the right side. He started to turn back
toward the U.S. goal but slipped under the pressure of Mexican
midfielders Alberto Garcia Aspe and Rafael Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fraser regained control and slipped by Aspe and Garcia
and headed for the Mexican net. He fired a hard shot but Pavel
Pardo stuck his foot out, allowing the ball to roll softly in front
of Frankie Hejduk, who one-touched a perfectly placed shot to the
right corner to tie the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so happy when we scored. I felt like I gave one up and
helped get one back,'' said Fraser. ``It was one of those things
where we were pushing up and I was fortunate to turn the corner,
dump it in and Frankie was able to finish it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It only lasted for a few moments, however.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's Joel Sanchez headed a corner that was saved brilliantly
by Thornton, but Abundis was there to follow the rebound and score
easilly to give Mexico a 2-1 lead and the deciding goal in the 57th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some consolation in the fact that maybe we played
well,'' Fraser said. ``But I think this program is moving in the
direction where playing well is not going to be a discussion. It's
going to be about wins and losses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
