<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE PLAYING TIME FOR ROOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For most of the last two seasons, Sean Rooks' role
with the Lakers has consisted of a set routine: Play hard for 30
minutes or so, work up a good sweat . . . and then find a good seat
on the bench before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   Rooks didn't have to worry that his pregame workout routine
would affect his energy level during the game. It didn't take much
energy to watch and cheer. But his minutes are now better spent.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers sent Eddie Jones to Charlotte for Glen Rice,
they also unloaded backup forward-center Elden Campbell, and the 15
minutes a game that Shaquille O'Neal rests now belong mostly to
Rooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play,'' said Rooks, reassuringly. ``Ever since I've been
here, I've been put on the bench like I'm lucky to be a Laker or
something. I've just never really had the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no longer a problem. After appearing in a career-low 41
games last season, and usually in garbage time, Rooks began working
himself into the rotation this year even before Campbell's
departure. The seven-year veteran has played in 19 of 22 games and
is averaging 9.2 minutes, 3.2 points and 2.2 rebounds. Those
numbers could climb now that he's the only true center on the
roster behind O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's been playing very well,'' coach Kurt Rambis said.
``Any time he's gotten consistent minutes with us, he has performed
very well. You can't look at a player's numbers whenever he doesn't
play for five games, then plays for 10 minutes in three different
stints . . . or two minutes of garbage time. It's not fair to
critique a player that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooks, almost forgotten last season, is eager to prove himself
in his third year with the Lakers. But he's assuming nothing with
regard to playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've assumed in the past and you know the saying about
assuming,'' he said, ``so I'm not taking anything for granted.
Whenever Kurt or (assistants) Larry (Drew) or Bert (Bill Bertka)
calls my name, I just want to go out there and try to give the team
a boost.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Derek Harper, Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal all
sat out workouts, but only Harper is a concern. The 16-year veteran
suffered a moderate sprain of his left ankle Friday night and was
limping around with an ice bag Saturday. He's listed as a game-time
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling a lot better today,'' he said. ``I think I'll be
all right. I'm gonna try to (play today). If I can, I definitely
will. I hate missing games.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be needed on this trip, considering the point guards the
Lakers face: Sacramento rookie Jason Williams, Minnesota's Terrell
Brandon, Philadelphia's Allen Iverson and Orlando's Penny Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is nursing a minor sprain in his right ankle but will
play today. O'Neal sat out for precautionary reasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
