<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN TO SKIP LAKERS' ROAD TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Lakers signed Dennis Rodman, they knew
they were buying two players for the price of one. One is the
basketball genius. The other, walking chaos.
</P>
<P>
   With few exceptions, they got nine games, all wins, with Good
Dennis before Bad Dennis emerged Saturday. Rodman skipped practice
without explanation, then showed up just long enough to tell coach
Kurt Rambis he won't be around for a while. How long isn't certain.
All the Lakers know for sure is they embarked on a crucial
six-game, nine-day road trip starting tonight in Sacramento without
their prized rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has non-basketball-related personal issues that he needs to
take care of. It is indefinite how long he'll be out, but he's not
going with us on the road,'' team publicist Tom Savage said,
minutes after Rodman sped away in a white Mercedes with dark
windows.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers spokesman John Black later said the team considers
Rodman's absence ``excused'' but said any possible disciplinary
action ``will be handled internally.'' General manager Mitch
Kupchak and executive vice president Jerry West declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we'd prefer to have him playing,'' Black said,
``but we understand what his situation is and we're willing to give
him the time off to take care of what he needs to take care of.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first blot on Rodman's short record with the
Lakers, but it is the most serious. He was fined for arriving 30
minutes late to his first team practice, was excused from a
practice last week to attend to ``personal business'' and was
thrown out of Wednesday's game against the Clippers when referees
grew tired of his banter.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Rodman has garnered more attention for setting a
perfect on-court example for the Lakers. He's been all hustle and
rebounds, earning Rambis' praise as a ``genius'' for his basketball
savvy and occasional coaching tips.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Rambis spent several minutes in animated discussion
with Rodman's bodyguards, who arrived before Rodman did, behind the
gym at Southwest College, the Lakers' practice site. Rodman finally
arrived just before 1 p.m _ 90 minutes after practice began and 15
minutes after it concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman and Rambis spoke briefly before Rodman returned to his
car and sped away, but the coach had no insight into Rodman's
situation and ``no idea'' when he might rejoin the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to say,'' said Rambis. Though he spoke with
Rodman, ``nothing got resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers start their longest road trip of the season
without their most proficient rebounder, though they are well
stocked at the position with starter Travis Knight, newly acquired
J.R. Reid and veteran Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis offered a long pause when asked if he was bothered by the
situation, then repeated his standby philosophy for Rodman-related
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad always told me you do the best you can with what you've
got,'' he said. ``That's just the way I look at life. If he's
there, great; if he's not, then I just have to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's storied NBA career has been peppered with similar
incidents and impromptu trips to Las Vegas, so the Lakers were at
least mentally prepared for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm not gonna freak out about it,'' Rambis said.
``It's just something we're gonna have to deal with and we're not
gonna let it disrupt us, and we're just going to continue to move
on. We have a talented ballclub and I can make adjustments and we
will go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Players left Southwest College before the news of Rodman's
hiatus hit. All they knew was he was missing for a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work as hard as him, I don't give a damn what you do in
practice,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``That guy works hard in the
game, so I don't have a problem with it. . . . I think you guys
(reporters) want it to be a problem more than we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get a couple (championship) rings, I'm doing the same
stuff,'' O'Neal joked. ``I ain't going to training camp, I ain't
going to practice, I ain't going to games.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Harper declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not gonna say a word about it,'' he said. ``I just want a
ring, man. I want to slide one of those rings on.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Derek Fisher, unaware Rodman was missing more than a
practice: ``Nobody really seems to worry about where Dennis is or
what he's gonna do. As long as when he shows up to the game, he's
ready to rebound and play defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time in three weeks, they can't even be sure
of that much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
