<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-KARROS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS IS DODGERS' VALUED VETERAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ At some moment, Eric Karros went from being a
Dodger to being a symbol for the Dodgers. He was the first baseman,
is the first baseman, and is also much more.
</P>
<P>
   It just, sort of . . . happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the link from the past to the present,'' Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone said. ``He's the guy that's recognized as a
Dodger. I see stability, dependability and consistency when I look
at Eric Karros.''
</P>
<P>
   When pitcher Ramon Martinez signed a free-agent contract with
the Boston Red Sox, ending a 14-year association with the Dodgers
that included 10 years at the major-league level, Karros became the
player with the most seniority in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than spending seven-plus seasons with the Dodgers
and goes beyond his 11 years in the organization. Karros doesn't
just play in L.A. He lives there, trains there. He's always there.
When Kevin Brown signed his free-agent contract, people expected
Karros to be at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a sense of history. My father was a huge Dodgers fan,
my brother was a huge Dodgers fan, so I knew about the Dodgers
before I was even drafted,'' Karros said. ``It's a little more
meaningful now because I'm one of the few guys who can be linked to
the past teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Since being promoted to the Dodgers on Sept. 1, 1991, aside from
a four-game rehabilitation stint with San Bernardino last season,
Karros has been with the L.A. club. He's helped bridge the gap from
the family-owned Dodgers to corporate ownership, and he's been the
rock of stability amid the chaos. In the consistently altered
atmosphere of baseball, Karros is the quiet constant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware of (the link),'' Karros said. ``I don't know what
the significance is. I understand it and I respect it, but my focus
is the 1999 season. I'm sure I will understand it one day.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Karros or anyone can plan such a path. Some
players last forever in a city and never attain such a level.
</P>
<P>
   For Karros, the foundation was set when he triggered the
Dodgers' Rookie of the Year parade in 1992 by hitting 20 homers
with 88 RBI. He's hit at least 23 homers and driven in 80 runs in
each nonstrike season since, and during a three-year stretch
averaged 32 homers and 107 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I came up in '94 you had that feeling,'' pitcher
Darren Dreifort said. ``Everybody has respect for him because of
the time he's put in and because of the numbers he's put up.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the statistics and experience lies more.
</P>
<P>
   Karros could have cracked when the Dodgers left him unprotected
in the last expansion draft, but he said little. When he began last
season on the disabled list after arthroscopic knee surgery, and
the world was trumpeting Paul Konerko as the next Rookie of the
Year for the Dodgers, he remained silent. And he returned from the
injury _ earlier than expected, of course _ to hit .296 with 23
homers and 87 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Other players recognize that approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to play with one club all through our careers, but
most times it's not possible,'' said shortstop Mark Grudzielanek,
traded to the Dodgers from the Montreal Expos last season. ``He's
doing it. There's no question what he means to this organization.
Once you get over here you understand what he means.''
</P>
<P>
   To the players, to the organization, Karros seems to mean a lot.
He senses that, but he doesn't want to talk too much about it. Not
after 1,030 games without winning a playoff game, and with the
World Series seemingly within grasp this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest,'' Karros said. ``I'm playing for the selfish
reason that I want to get to a World Series. I want to win a World
Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 2223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
