<DOCNO> NYT19990313.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9607 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SULLIVANCOLUMN-TE     03-13 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE-MINDED GMS WATCH PITCHERS
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The search for pitching is consuming many general managers' time
during spring training. Those pitchers who are available or might
be available during the season are drawing large numbers of scouts
when they take the mound.
</P>
<P>
   The rundown on the candidates:
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Appier _ The Royals are openly shopping their one-time ace
who missed most of last year because of a shoulder injury. The
Royals want prospects in return, but clubs are reluctant to bite
until they are convinced he's healthy again.
</P>
<P>
   Appier pitched three scoreless innings against the Dodgers on
Wednesday and said afterward, ``It feels better than it has in
years. I threw the slider for the first time today, and it felt
pretty good. I was keeping the ball down and had better control.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Anderson _ The Diamondbacks have a surplus of starters and
are willing to trade Anderson. But they insist on getting a
front-line player in return and so far are only being offered
reserves. He could end up as a $1.8 million reliever; owner Jerry
Colangelo has told his baseball people Anderson doesn't have to be
traded.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Schilling _ He has offered to waive his no-trade demands,
but general manager Ed Wade insists he's staying ... for now. If
the Phillies aren't in contention come July, then Schilling will be
the big prize at the trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers _ The next big prize after Schilling, and the
Rangers want him. But the Athletics aren't inclined to trade him
just yet, although that could change in July.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Hentgen _ Right now the Blue Jays aren't dealing, but that
could change by the end of spring training if they feel rookie Roy
Halladay is ready to step into the rotation. There has been talk
about sending Hentgen to the Angels for an outfielder, either Jim
Edmonds or Garret Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Blue Jays are concerned about Hentgen's shoulder
and David Wells' back. Toronto general manager Gord Ash doesn't
want to trade a starter, only to have another one go down with an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser _ He's in the Indians camp on a minor-league
contract, but can cut his own deal with another team after March 21
if he's not put on the 40-man roster. He's unlikely to make the
Indians' rotation unless there is an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Fernandez _ He could be the Marlins' Opening Day starter
after missing all of last season with a torn rotator cuff. The
Marlins say they don't have to trade him just because he makes $7
million and may hold onto him. But more likely they'll wait until
after the season starts. The more people are convinced he's
healthy, the better deal they can make.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Myers _ He makes $6 million, which is incredibly expensive
for a setup reliever. He wants to close again, but the Padres have
Trevor Hoffman. They would also love to dump his salary, but there
are no takers so far. Considering the scarce availability of
left-handed relief, somebody might take a chance if the Padres help
out on the weekly payments.
</P>
<P>
   REJUVENATED CANSECO SEES 600 HOME RUNS IN HIS FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Jose Canseco is back, feeling better than ever, although with
his fifth team since 1992. Once given up for dead after all his
injuries, Canseco came back to life with the Blue Jays last year,
hitting 46 home runs and driving in 107 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco, 34, is with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays and still saying
his checkered career will have a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, people are talking about 500 home runs,
I'm thinking about 600,'' said Canseco, who has 397 career home
runs. ``I stay in very good shape. I don't see why I can't play
until I'm 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco was the one who started all the Roger Clemens commotion
this off-season. The Blue Jays' failure to re-sign him was a major
reason why Clemens demanded a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a very good run'' at the end of the 1998 season,
Canseco said of the Blue Jays. ``And I thought after that, geez, if
we keep the same team. Some of the younger players will be older. I
thought maybe if we got one more player we could contend with the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't think I was in their plans. I think it was
obvious last year at the All-Star break when I had 24 home runs and
24 stolen bases and they didn't re-sign me by then. Especially when
I had approached them a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays eventually offered Canseco a base contract of $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Jays GM) Gord Ash told me that over the phone, and I
said `Are you serious?' '' Canseco said. ``Guys are signing for $10
or $15 million. Guys are 15 times better than me? That means if you
multiply 46 home runs times 15 that's what they're hitting. Six
hundred home runs a year...''
HARGROVE'S CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   Indians manager Mike Hargrove has set two simple goals for this
season. He wants to win more than 100 games during the regular
season, and he wants to win the World Series. He told the team that
before their first full-squad workout, then he went public with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year we have meetings and say we're going to do this and
that,'' Hargrove said. ``Then we turn around and tell the public,
`We just want to get to the postseason and see what happens.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I said, `Let's be honest. Here it is out in the
open. I want to win the World Series.' This is my way of publicly
challenging the team.''
GRIFFEY-PINIELLA
</P>
<P>
   This exchange occurred between Ken Griffey Jr. and Lou Piniella
at the batting cage, after Junior had fouled off a bunt attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a little work on your bunting,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm bunting, we're in trouble,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have you squeeze a couple times this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why go for one run when I can swing and get you two?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to make your manager look good sometimes,'' Piniella
said. ``They see you squeezing, they'll be calling me a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They see me squeezing, they'll be sending you home, skip.''
SHEFFIELD'S WOES
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' Gary Sheffield has agreed to switch to left field,
but he's having some trouble. Monday in Fort Lauderdale, Orioles
outfielder Brady Anderson hit a fly ball to left that got caught up
in the wind and ended up hitting Sheffield in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always bragged about it, playing right field, that I never
got hit in the head,'' Sheffield said. ``And then I'm playing left,
and the first batter, I get hit in the head. They're still laughing
about it in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield was laughing, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to laugh to keep from crying,'' Sheffield said.
``It's whatever's best for Mondesi. If he can go out and have an
MVP season, it's good for the team. I don't care where I play, I
just want to be respected out there. I don't want to kill the team
out there.''
DAVIS BLASTS ORIOLES
</P>
<P>
   Former Orioles outfielder Eric Davis took some shots at his team
after being told he wasn't re-signed because of doubts about his
right elbow, which he favored for much of last year.
</P>
<P>
   That was news to Davis, who managed to play through it and run
off a 30-game hitting streak on the way to an outstanding offensive
season. He was annoyed at manager Ray Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was concerned about that, why didn't he pick up a phone
and call me and ask how my elbow was?'' Davis said. ``Ray didn't
call me, Frank (Wren) didn't call me, so it couldn't have been a
concern. Don't you think you should ask instead of assuming?
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't concerned about it when we were five games out.
They weren't concerned when I was hitting in all those games and
doing what I'm doing, so during the offseason you're concerned
about my elbow? I think it's an excuse.''
SHORT HOPS
</P>
<P>
   _ Former TCU pitcher Tim Grieve has hung up the uniform and is
working as a scout for the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   _ No wonder the Reds can't afford free agents. Their media guide
lists 22 people on their medical staff including three physical
therapists, two neurosurgical consultants, a dental consultant, a
massage therapist, a podiatric consultant and a foot and ankle
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   _ Braves general manager John Schuerholz said the club is
comfortable with Ryan Klesko at first base and _ for now _ will not
pursue a trade for a replacement for Andres Galarraga. nn
</P>
