<HEADLINE>
TWO BIG DEALS; TWO DIFFERENT REASONS
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two major trades. Two drastically different motives.
</P>
<P>
   Though both will have an impact on the NBA's balance of power
this season and beyond, the Lakers' acquisition of Glen Rice was a
desperate attempt to win a championship while the Timberwolves'
dealing of Stephon Marbury was simply desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Though Minnesota is obviously on the short end of Thursday's
nine-player, three-team swap in which they basically traded Stephon
Marbury for Terrell Brandon and the Nets' upcoming lottery pick,
the Timberwolves had no choice. Marbury, from Brooklyn, wanted to
play back home and threatened to leave Minnesota next summer as a
free agent, leaving the Timberwolves with nothing to show for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and his agent (David Falk) held our feet to the fire,''
said Timberwolves general manager Kevin McHale. ``It was either
trade him now or lose him for nothing later.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Timberwolves salvaged something for Marbury, their
grand plan has been shattered in the last three months. Once
figured to ride the trio of Marbury-Kevin Garnett-Tom Gugliotta to
title contention, Minnesota has now lost Marbury and Gugliotta, who
signed with the Phoenix Suns as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame Minnesota. McHale talked last week with Falk about a
maximum six-year, $71 million contract extension last week, but was
turned down. Now, Marbury says he plans to sign an identical deal
with the Nets, who sent Sam Cassell and Chris Gatling to the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't put into words how disappointing it is,'' said
Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders. ``You can throw the word loyalty
right out the window these days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, meanwhile, gave up two talented players in Eddie
Jones and Elden Campbell. But what they got in return could be the
missing pieces to the championship puzzle in Rice, a sharp-shooter,
and rugged power forward J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a shooter, and I got another thug power forward,'' said
Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal. ``Ain't no excuses now, for me or
anybody else in this locker room. We should be on our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Give Jerry West _ again _ all the credit. Jones can't do
anything that Kobe Bryant can't do better, and Campbell has always
been a defensive liability. Last summer, West had an immature team
swept out of the playoffs by the Utah Jazz. Since then, he has
added a young coach (Kurt Rambis) players relate to, a veteran
leader (Derek Harper), the game's best rebounder (Dennis Rodman)
and arguably the league's best pure shooter (Rice).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our front line in particular, we think we have
the best center in the league, we probably have the best rebounder
in the league in Dennis, and maybe we'll have the best shooter as a
small forward and one of the best players in the league at small
forward,'' said West. ``Our backcourt is a concern, but it was a
concern before. We do think we have an attractive team, and a team
that can compete in a playoff series against anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bucks coach George Karl, ``That trade makes me bitter. The
Lakers are a very, very powerful team that just got much better.''
RICE TRADE CONTINUES TREND OF HORNETS' STINGY WAYS
</P>
<P>
   Add Glen Rice to the name of former Hornets stars _ Alonzo
Mourning, Larry Johnson, Vlade Divac, Matt Geiger _ whom the team
traded rather than paid.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Rice was another example of Charlotte's favorite parlor
trick: swap their best and most expensive player to avoid paying
him. The deal is eerily similar to the Mourning trade to Miami.
Mourning went to the Heat and Rice, Geiger, Khalid Reeves and a
first-round pick to Charlotte. When Rice and Geiger matured into
top players, they were also let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typical Charlotte,'' Mourning said of trading Rice. ``Typical
George Shinn. As long as Eddie Jones is a free agent at the end of
next season, they'll probably lose him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' contract runs out after next season, and he's already on
record as saying he wants the maximum for his experience group ($11
million). So the Hornets start this whole silly process over again.
</P>
<P>
   Give coach Dave Cowens credit for knowing when to get out.
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE EAST
</P>
<P>
   What do the Bulls, 76ers, Hawks and Suns have in common? They
entered yesterday with better road records than home records. ...
Though ESPN expert Jack Ramsay picked them to win the East before
the season, isn't it time for them to change their name to the New
Jersey Nyets? ... Bucks coach George Karl isn't one to back down
from a grudge. ``My animosity comes from the fact I want the truth
to come out,'' Karl said last week before his team defeated the
Sonics, whose GM, Wally Walker, fired him last summer. ``And the
truth is, when you talk about the construction of the tradition
that we had in Seattle, Wally Walker's name should be sixth or
seventh on the rung of importance. Wally's not an innovator. He's
just there.''
AROUND THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   It almost got to the point where you had the feeling the
Clippers' next victory was going to coincide with the Y2K scare.
... It shouldn't come as any surprise that Mavericks coach Don
Nelson gave his players a choice to play on the slick surface at
Reunion Arena. Remember, it was Nelson who allowed Derek Harper to
veto a trade to Utah that would've brought the Mavericks Greg
Foster and Howard Eisley two years ago. ... Mild-mannered, quiet
star Shareef Abdur-Rahim could bite his tongue no longer after
watching his dismal Grizzlies' 15-point home loss to Houston last
week. ``We're supposed to be pros, but we look like damn high
schoolers out there,'' he said. Help apparently isn't on the way.
``A minor trade at this point is not going to correct our team,''
said GM Stu Jackson. ``If we get David Robinson or bring Michael
Jordan out of retirement, that would correct our ills. Anything
short of that is cosmetics.''
BEST AND WORST
</P>
<P>
   Best coaching move: Instead of being 9-0 with the Lakers, Kurt
Rambis could have been 1-17 with the Clippers. ``I went pretty far
with my consideration for that job,'' said Rambis, who turned down
LA's other team last summer. ``It would just be real tough for me
as a first-year head coach to be 0-17. People would be saying `Kurt
must be lousy as a coach'.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst coaching move: Sonics coach Paul Westphal moves Detlef
Schrempf to the bench as Seattle goes on its first five-game losing
streak since 1991. The Sonics won their first six games but are 3-7
in their past 10.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Next time you hear an NBA player complaining about three games
in three nights, tell them to consider the plight of the Chicago
Bulls and guard Jerry Sloan in 1967-68. That team played five games
in five nights three times within 30 days with two of the sets in
five different cities. The Bulls broke 100 points in all 15 games:
11-21-67 at New York 123-125 11-22-67 at Baltimore 105-100 11-23-67
at Milwaukee 106-96 11-24-67 vs. Philadelphia 104-122 11-25-67 at
Philadelphia 119-114 12-5-67 at Cincinnati 105-104 12-6-67 at
Detroit 121-135 12-7-67 vs. San Diego 108-118 12-8-67 at Seattle
115-114 12-9-67 at San Francisco 112-119 12-12-67 at San Diego
104-118 12-13-67 at San Francisco 109-104 12-14-67 at Los Angeles
106-101 12-15-67 vs. Seattle 115-122 12-16-67 vs. Philadelphia
123-143
nn
</P>
