<HEADLINE>
IOWA FINDS WAY TO EXTEND DAVIS' STAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Defying the odds and denying the temptation to pound a
how-do-you-like-me-now pulpit, Iowa coach Tom Davis' farewell tour
marches on.
</P>
<P>
   Next destination: the Hawkeyes' first Sweet 16 appearance in the
NCAA men's basketball tournament since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, the only team in the tournament with a lame-duck coach,
rallied from a 13-point deficit in the second half yesterday to
oust Arkansas, 82-72, at McNichols Sports Arena. By doing so, the
Hawkeyes prolonged Davis' stay at the school for at least another
week, which proved to be ample reason for lengthy postgame hugs and
free-flowing tears among players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the emotion involved in watching his fifth-seeded
Hawkeyes (20-9) rally to down the fourth-seeded Razorbacks (23-11)
after all seemed lost with 18 minutes remaining, Davis didn't mince
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so deep, I don't think I can do it justice,'' Davis said,
his voice cracking. ``I'm just trying to have fun and not worry
about the bigger questions until it's over. But it was almost over
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Hawkeyes thrust themselves back into the game
behind the long-range jumpers of guard Kent McCausland and a
full-court, pressure defense that hounded the Razorbacks into 12
second-half turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 47-34 with 18 minutes to play, McCausland _ who scored
15 of his 17 points after intermission _ buried three consecutive
three-pointers to trigger a 16-0 run that put the Hawkeyes on top,
50-46, at the 14:42 mark. When the Razorbacks appeared to regain
control with a spurt of their own, Iowa closed with a 23-6 stretch
in the final seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, McCausland began the pivotal stretch with
back-to-back three-pointers. That trimmed a 66-59 deficit to 66-65
with 6:17 remaining. Then, the really amazing stuff started. The
Iowa press forced four turnovers and two steals down the stretch,
helping the Hawkeyes pull away from a team that prides itself on
its ``40 minutes of hell'' approach to pressure defense.
</P>
<P>
   A stunned Arkansas coach Nolan Richardson acknowledged the irony
of the Iowa comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the game totally reversed itself,'' said Richardson,
whose team forced 18 turnovers in the first half but only six after
intermission. ``We couldn't handle their press. We couldn't even
get the ball inbounds at times. When we did, they did a great job
of making us cough it up, so they could spot up for jumpers.''
CONNECTICUT 78, NEW MEXICO 56 Among his team's many assets,
Connecticut basketball coach Jim Calhoun lists ``spurtability'' at
the top of the list when discussing his top-seeded Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   The word may not be in Webster's Dictionary, but it refers to
UConn's penchant for scoring points in huge hunks. New Mexico got
buried under two separate deluges yesterday, as the Huskies routed
the Lobos in McNichols Sports Arena to seal the team's seventh trip
to the ``Sweet 16'' round of the NCAA tournament in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut (30-2), the No. 1 seed in the West Regional, wasted
little time in removing any suspense from this contest by scoring
the first 17 points of the game. After the Lobos (25-9) regrouped,
the Huskies opened the second half with a 13-0 salvo to carve out a
50-22 advantage that turned the final 16:31 into an anticlimactic
exercise in emptying benches and accumulating statistics.
</P>
<P>
   When the final numbers were counted, New Mexico catalyst Kenny
Thomas once again proved to be little more than a blip on the radar
screen in an NCAA tournament game. Thomas, a 6-foot-8 center,
played 30 minutes without a field goal and scored a career-low one
point in his final college game. In eight NCAA appearances, Thomas
has scored 9.4 points per contest, well below his career average
(15.7).
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, meanwhile, rolled behind the transition baskets of
Khalid El-Amin and Richard Hamilton, who each scored 21 points and
triggered the Huskies' telling spurts. The duo combined for 11 of
the Huskies' first 17 points and contributed 11 points during
Connecticut's 13-0 run to start the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get on one of these streaks, we're as good as anybody
in the country,'' Calhoun said. ``That's the way we've been all
year, when we're playing good defense. And we played great defense
today. That's where the `spurtability' comes from.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
