<SLUG> BC-SKYHARBOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKY HARBOR FACES NEW MILLENNIUM WITH NOWHERE LEFT TO GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The little Cessna plane saw an opportunity where others didn't.
Ignoring air-traffic controllers' orders to circle, the plane
squeezed between two Boeing 737s on their approach to Sky Harbor
International Airport. It was enough to give the controllers heart
palpitations.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Cessna touched down, it proceeded down the wrong
taxiway. Bring out the nitroglycerine pills.
</P>
<P>
   The January 1998 episode ended without incident but provided a
teeth-gnashing glimpse of life at an airport that's flying into the
21st century by the seat of its pants. Pilot errors such as the one
involving the Cessna are being reported to the Federal Aviation
Administration much more frequently. And that's only part of the
story of the airport's rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
   Sky Harbor now ranks third worst in the nation in departure
delays caused by airport conditions. Delays more than doubled last
year, up 121 percent, a faster rate than any other U.S. airport.
</P>
<P>
   Urban air pollution delayed more flights at Sky Harbor last year
than did weather in soggy Seattle or smoggy Pittsburgh. Parking,
already tight, is expected to get worse before it gets better. The
Terminal 4 parking garage will double in size, but on an
excruciatingly slow schedule designed to minimize the disruption in
existing spots.
</P>
<P>
   Few cities in America demand more of their airports than
Phoenix. The Valley wants Sky Harbor to be all things to all
people, from student pilots and small-aircraft operators to a
rapidly growing number of commercial-airline passengers who want an
airport conveniently located in the middle of a big city.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But as Sky Harbor continues to expand, the region faces a
crucial question: Can the airport continue to please everyone
without creating a glut of delays and inconveniences for travelers?
</P>
<P>
   Sky Harbor, with only two runways and a central-city location,
averages 1,460 takeoffs and landings a day. Add in helicopters and
emergency ``lifeguard'' planes that criss-cross the airport, and
traffic was so brisk last year that it made the airport the
fifth-busiest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   It's only going to get busier. &QL; 
PUSHING THE ENVELOPE
</P>
<P>
   The afterburners are on, now that America West Airlines has
scratched merger talks. The airline plans a 40 percent increase in
traffic within the year. Airport officials are pushing cargo as Sky
Harbor's big-growth frontier. A new cargo building is under
construction, and FedEx already has leased 42 percent of the space.
</P>
<P>
   By 2015, Sky Harbor could be handling 2,050 daily flights,
according to an airport study. That's an average of 85 flights an
hour, although traffic would be heavier in the day and evening.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing in the wake of Sky Harbor's supersonic growth are
problems ranging from delays to parking woes to the dicey mix of
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Some relief will come when a third runway opens next spring.
</P>
<P>
   A controversial fourth runway could be built in the future, but
Phoenix isn't sure where to put it.
</P>
<P>
   The city grounded a plan last April after AlliedSignal Engines,
one of the city's largest employers, discovered it was in the path
of the project. The company said it didn't want to move.
</P>
<P>
   The airport's long-term master plan has been on ice ever since,
leaving Sky Harbor without a blueprint to guide growth through
2025.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many local planners say Sky Harbor should hold its own
for decades to come. They note that the airport has never had a
fatal collision, and that travel delays haven't prompted airlines
to move to roomier conditions. An airport can do a lot with a
limited number of runways.
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't so optimistic. They feel the Valley is missing the
chance to stake out valuable turf for a future regional airport.
They warn that without a new plan in hand, the entire Valley will
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull's newly formed transportation task force may take
on the thorny aviation-planning issue. But for now, the outlook is
for Sky Harbor to continue growing in its central _ but landlocked
_ location.
</P>
<P>
   Its growth is taking off faster than the Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   What will give with growth?
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope, nothing,'' said Phoenix's acting aviation director
David Krietor.
</P>
<P>
   But the growing pains are evident. Small aircraft weaving
between commercial airliners and U.S. National Guard planes make
air-traffic controllers, and many commercial pilots, increasingly
nervous. FAA officials, who filed the report on the Cessna, contend
it likely means nothing more than an inattentive pilot. But others
say it's at least partly a symptom of the airport's growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines are cramming more and more flights into our
airports every year,'' said Jon Russell, safety chairman for the
Western region of the Air Line Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in pilot errors reported by the FAA may be due to
more diligent reporting, said Stock of the air-traffic controllers'
union. FAA officials say the increase doesn't necessarily bode
poorly for Sky Harbor: A quarter of them involved airspace
violations miles away from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   To help deal with the increase in air traffic, FAA and city
officials are lobbying Congress for a new air-traffic control
tower. The current one is too small, too short, and ill-equipped to
handle the airport's growing needs, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods are another concern. Some Tempe residents, having
hammered out an agreement that limits the noise from departing
aircraft, would like to get similar restrictions on landings. &QL; 
PASSENGERS SUFFER
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated passengers are on the increase.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Glazier flies out of Sky Harbor weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Inching forward in a long line snaking back from a metal
detector, he talked about the airport's shortcomings _ and its
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Parking is an increasingly big headache, he said. So big that
he's ready to switch to the more-remote economy lot rather than
thread through Terminal 4's parking garage in search of a spot that
might not be there.
</P>
<P>
   It also takes longer to fly to his destinations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems like there are a lot of delays, but I don't know
if it's America West or the airport,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Glazier wouldn't trade the airport for a new, more
distant one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for me,'' he said of Sky Harbor's location. ``It's
central to my office and central to my home.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE RUNWAYS
</P>
<P>
   Sentiments like these only fuel plans for Sky Harbor to grow in
place, which is typical of airports nationwide. From San Francisco
to St. Louis, Los Angeles to Boston, airports are growing, not
relocating.
</P>
<P>
   Growth doesn't always translate into building more
land-consuming runways, said Dick Marchi, senior vice president for
technical and environmental affairs at the Airports Council
International.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most airports have seen growth beyond what was projected 20
years ago,'' he said. ``And few of them have added new runways.''
</P>
<P>
   Sky Harbor has operated for decades on two runways, allowing it
to claim the title of the busiest two-runway airport not only in
the nation, but in the world.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, the airport has had a clean safety record.
There have been no major crashes. In the past five years, two near
midair collisions have been reported over the airport, one in
February 1996 and the other in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Planning started 20 years ago for the third runway. Under
construction on the airport's south side, it will allow the airport
to handle 15 to 20 percent more flights, said George Sullivan,
air-traffic manager for the Phoenix air-traffic control tower and
the radar network that covers the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said it's hard to predict how long _ or how soon _ it
will be before growth eclipses the breathing room the new runway
will provide. ``We think it will improve a little bit,'' he said.
``(But) there's only so much you can do with the circumstances we
have.'' &QL; 
MINIMIZING NOISE
</P>
<P>
   Those circumstances are the limitations on flight departures
over Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   A noise-abatement agreement between the cities of Phoenix and
Tempe requires aircraft departing to the east to fly over the Salt
River.
</P>
<P>
   While this contains jet noise to a narrow area, the funneling
effect of the corridor makes it impossible for planes to depart
simultaneously from two _ or three _ runways, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the promise of a third runway, it will be 2004 before
Sky Harbor can truly claim to be a three-runway airport. That's
because as soon as the new runway opens, the northern runway will
close for a lengthening and resurfacing project. After that, the
remaining runway will be repaved.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said Sky Harbor may be able to operate with 2{ runways
during this phase by running smaller aircraft, which don't need as
much distance, on the western or eastern halves of whichever runway
is being resurfaced. &QL; 
DELAYS, DELAYS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Growth has already strained Sky Harbor's two runways.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only LaGuardia International and Newark International
turned in a worse performance when it came to delays caused by
airport conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Figures provided by the FAA show that Sky Harbor last year had
5,484 ``volume delays'' _ flights that took more than 15 minutes to
depart because of crowded runway conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the airport's makeup for this poor rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two runways, too many airplanes,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   There are several times when it seems everyone wants to push
back from the airport's 87 gates, Sullivan said. Peak times are the
early morning until 10 a.m., and again from 6 p.m. to 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Weather, surprisingly, was the source of 4,150 delays last year.
Blame that on air pollution, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you see the air out there,'' Sullivan said, referring
to the Valley's brown cloud of pollution. ``When the sun is setting
or rising, you can't do visual (flight operations.)''
</P>
<P>
   With the sun bouncing off suspended particles, pilots can't see
well enough to navigate on sight alone. That means they have to
take off and land using instrument flight rules, a more
time-consuming process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Sky Harbor posted the ninth-worst delay record when
other factors, such as equipment breakdowns, are added. &QL; 
A STEADFAST TENANT
</P>
<P>
   The current strains, coupled with projections that envision Sky
Harbor handling as many as 753,000 flights by 2015, only steel
opinions that the airport one day will add a fourth runway.
</P>
<P>
   In fall 1997, an airport panel recommended that the city build a
fourth runway on the airport's northern edge. Mayor Skip Rimsza,
who put the runway plans on hold last April, said he is nonetheless
``absolutely'' convinced that AlliedSignal will move some day.
</P>
<P>
   The turbine-engine manufacturer's lease for its airport land
expires in &UR; 2048, &UR; but Rimsza said he expects a move could happen
before then.
</P>
<P>
   ``When AlliedSignal is ready for us to move them and wants us to
move them, we will,'' Rimsza said.
</P>
<P>
   But AlliedSignal, in a written statement, reiterated that it has
no interest in moving and noted that its lease with the city
protects it from being moved for runway expansion.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth runway would ensure safer operations because the outer
two runways could be used for landings, while the inner two could
be dedicated to takeoffs, said David Stock, spokesman for the
National Air Traffic Controllers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The optimum situation is a fourth runway,'' he said. ``That's
a slick operation. You can land on two (runways) constantly,
without worrying about departures.''
</P>
<P>
   But future runways would have to stick to the same
noise-reducing rules already in place. &QL; 
WHY NOT WILLIAMS?
</P>
<P>
   Some Tempe residents already are talking about the need to
further curb noise, and they question why Williams Gateway Airport
in Mesa is not being prepped as a major reliever airport.
</P>
<P>
   North Tempe resident Tim Donnelly said noise pollution can reach
toxic levels near an airport. His neighbors would like to see noise
limits put on arriving aircraft, similar to those for departing
planes.
</P>
<P>
   And although he accepts that Sky Harbor will be a neighbor long
into the future, he says Valley planners should be prepared to
split off some air traffic to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   `Even now we see Williams being hemmed in by rogue county
development,'' Donnelly said. That could hamper Williams' growth as
a reliever airport.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Williams is a reliever airport for Sky Harbor, but
it is unclear when the former military base on the Valley's
southeastern edge will start taking some of that business. No
passenger service operates out of Williams, and the major operators
at Sky Harbor _ America West and Southwest Airlines _ have no
interest in splitting their operations to serve two Valley
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as Arizona State University Professor Larry Gesell,
question why no one is seriously pursuing the airport that will
handle Valley traffic by the middle of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   He likes the idea of a regional airport built on a fresh patch
of ground far from urban constraints, such as noise agreements, and
with plenty of room to expand.
</P>
<P>
   Williams can't fill that bill, said Gesell, a professor of
aeronautical technology. Its runways point northwest to southeast,
meaning departing planes would be on a collision course with Sky
Harbor's east-west movements. And Williams is being hemmed in by
urban development, further restricting its ability to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Browning, director of the Greater Phoenix Leadership and a
former Luke Air Force Base commander, thinks the Sky
Harbor-Williams system could handle air traffic well into the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But then what? Airports aren't built overnight, Browning said,
and an impartial body should explore aviation options well into the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   If not, the Valley risks repeating the same mistakes it made
with another facet of its transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at how long it's taken us to build the freeways, for
crying out loud,'' Browning said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
