<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUCKSHOT-NASCAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIAN LEARNING IT'S TOUGH BEING A WINSTON CUP ROOKIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, Ga. _ One of the dire preseason predictions given to
NASCAR Winston Cup rookie Roy ``Buckshot'' Jones has come to
fruition.
</P>
<P>
   Jones qualified a career-best seventh on Friday for today's
Cracker Barrel 500 at the Atlanta Motor Speedway. It will be Jones'
second consecutive Cup start after failing to qualify for the
opening two races of the 1999 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   And as 1998 Cup rookie Jerry Nadeau advised Jones late last
season, Winston Cup is where the fun starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to Jerry at Talladega,'' Jones said, ``and he
said, `You're going to have a lot of fun this season. I said, `What
do you mean?' He said, `You're going to be going straight to the
back. Nobody is going to help you. You're a rookie. You've got that
\Ryellow\S stripe.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He explained just how tough the transition is.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavier and more powerful than the Busch cars Jones campaigned
in 88 races between 1995 and 1998, Cup cars are a handful around
tracks like the 1.54-mile AMS quadoval. But the first part of the
equation for a start-up team like Buckshot Racing is qualifying
among the top 36 on speed. Devoid of provisional starts at the
season's outset, Jones failed to qualify on speed at the Daytona
International Speedway and North Carolina Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it was just as Nadeau had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it's not just getting used to the horsepower,'' said
Jones, 28, a University of Georgia graduate and resident of Tucker,
Ga. ``Everybody's got qualifying shocks, they've got qualifying
gears or transmissions, setups, motors _ that's stuff that doesn't
really happen in the Busch series.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' early 0-for-2 has helped relegate him to third place in
points among the rookies who have started Cup races this season.
Fellow BGN graduates Tony Stewart and Elliott Sadler stand 1-2
after having qualified for every event. But because the Raybestos
Rookie of the Year is based upon a driver's best 15 finishes, Jones
has plenty of season to make his move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it'd be tough coming here to Winston Cup,'' said
Jones, a two-time BGN race-winner who will start his eighth Cup
event today in the No. 00 Crown Fiber Communications Pontiac.
``It's one of the most difficult transitions we've had to make. But
the problems we encountered were problems we never expected _ a
chassis problem, where our chassis were off a little bit. I think
we got most of that corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he qualified here with a Pontiac chassis purchased
from Hendrick Motorsports a year ago. It is one of three
Hendrick-built Grand Prixs in Jones' inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Jones started 35th and finished 29th in the Las Vegas 400 last
Sunday, five laps behind winner Jeff Burton. But Jones and his
father and car-owner, Billy Jones, were buoyed by Buckshot's
career-best hot lap at 192.654 mph. Billy Jones and his son began
the season with high expectations, in part based upon the opening
of a $2 million, 30,000 square-foot facility in Spartanburg, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot's early slips certainly have not altered Billy Jones'
long-range plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest, and probably some people will take this the
wrong way,'' said Billy Jones, a self-described ``glorified
ditch-digger'' whose profitable fiber optics construction business
is sponsoring Buckshot's car. ``If Buckshot wins a race or two this
year, it won't surprise me. I mean, I don't expect us to go out
there and run in the back of the pack by no means.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Buckshot is going to win that rookie championship. And
our intention is to run for and win the \RCup\S championship in
three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau might beg to differ. But just for today, Buckshot would
be satisfied to rack up Cup laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to run every lap,'' Jones said. ``If we can do that,
we ought to have a pretty decent finish.''
Skinner wins Busch race
</P>
<P>
   Still searching for his first career NASCAR Winston Cup victory,
Mike Skinner settled for next-best at Atlanta Motor Speedway
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner notched his first career NASCAR Busch Grand National
Series victory in the Yellow Freight 300, a race whose title
sponsor also is the primary backer of his No. 19 Chevrolet Monte
Carlo. The race was Skinner's second start for car owner David
Ridling, and only the ninth in his BGN career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a brand new team. It's pretty awesome to come out in
the second race and win for 'em,'' said Skinner, who beat
pole-sitter Dave Blaney to the flag by 2.261 seconds. ``But if it
wasn't for the guys on the 31 team helping out, we probably
wouldn't have won the race today.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to the crew on the No. 31 Lowe's Chevy that
Skinner has qualified second for today's Winston Cup Cracker Barrel
500. Cup crew chief Larry McReynolds helped put a handling package
together that cured a chronic loose condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really junk in yesterday \RFriday\S morning's
practice,'' Skinner said. ``The car had me half scared to death. We
did some different things with shocks and it ended up pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner led twice for a race-high 72 laps, including the final
41. Reigning BGN champion Dale Earnhardt Jr., finished third, his
best result in four starts this season. The third Cup regular to
win a Busch race in 1999, Skinner averaged 117.178 mph.
LAST LAPS
</P>
<P>
   Three-time Cup champion Darrell Waltrip has been forced to use
the past champion's provisional to start all four races this season
for the new team assembled by Travis Carter and Carl Haas. Under
NASCAR rules, Waltrip must attempt to qualify for the next four
events before he can use another provisional. That stretch includes
the Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth on March
28.
</P>
<P>
   Reigning Cup champion Jeff Gordon (188.835 mph) topped the speed
chart during yesterday's final Happy Hour practice. He was followed
by Skinner (188.366) and rookie Tony Stewart (188.175). Pole-sitter
Bobby Labonte was 15th (187.019).
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
