<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MARATHON HAS CHARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It may not be on the same level as the New York
or Boston marathons, but the 14th running of the Los Angeles
Marathon this morning will have a gritty charm all its own.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 20,000 runners are scheduled to compete in the
26.2-mile annual endurance race, and several thousand others will
participate in a variety of related events that include a bicycle
tour and wheelchair race.
</P>
<P>
   It all begins promptly at 8:40 a.m. The elites will finish about
2 hours later, but the bulk of the contestants should have crossed
the finish line by 2:30 p.m., organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be an interesting race,'' said John Tope, the
marathon's lead athlete coordinator. ``The field is deep and better
than in the past, so we should have some fast times.''
</P>
<P>
   The course starts with a run south along Figueroa Blvd. to
Martin Luther King Blvd. After a jaunt along Exposition, the
runners will turn north on Crenshaw and go east for a bit before
crossing Wilshire Boulevard at New Hampshire Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The pack will head north to Hollywood, travel to Sunset, then
south on Virgil to Wilshire. The group will cross the finish line
at Flower, just south of 5th St.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, runners will see USC, the Crenshaw District,
Koreatown, Hollywood and the Civic Center. And, about 1.2 million
people in the various communities will line the streets to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say that today's race may be a bit more special than
in years past because it features five male runners whose personal
best times are faster than the course record.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the elite men's field are Kenyans Simon Bor (2:08:46),
John Kipkosgei (2:09:54) and Simon Kirwa (2:10:17), Taye Moges
(2:09:21) of Ethiopia and Russia's Leonid Shvestov (2:09:16). Each
is looking to break the mark of 2:10:19 set by Mexico's Martin
Mondragon in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's division, two-time champion Lornah Kiplagat of
Kenya (2:33:50) will try to win her third consecutive. She'll be
challenged by Kenyan Hellen Kimaiyo-Kipkosgei (2:29:45) and Alena
Peterkova (2:25:19) of the Czech Republic. Madina Bitktagirova of
Belarus holds the course record of 2:26:23 set in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the marathon is allowing 20,000 entries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the growing field of runners, $5,000 has been
added to the first-place finisher's prize. The male and female
winners will each get $35,000 and a new Honda Accord.
</P>
<P>
   And in the sometimes snobby world of marathons run in Boston,
New York and Chicago, Los Angeles is gaining newfound respect among
runners, Tope said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap's definitely closed,'' Tope said. ``We've been fourth,
but it was a distant fourth. Now, it's a lot closer than it has
been. It's very tough to displace Boston and New York.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Wire services contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
