<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLPLANE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL PLANES, STUDENT PILOTS COME UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're the Yugos of the skies above Sky Harbor International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Small aircraft, especially those with student pilots at the
controls, are the bane of air-traffic controllers and many
commercial pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The ``little guys,'' in return, bristle at the suggestion that
they can't claim a piece of the sky. They say they're singled out
for unnecessarily harsh treatment from controllers and often
required to circle needlessly above the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers are lobbying to get student pilots banned from Sky
Harbor. They argue that 12 U.S. airports, eight of them less busy
than Phoenix, have such restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, they say, fewer small aircraft in Sky Harbor's busy
airspace would make operations safer for all.
</P>
<P>
   But the FAA, which governs the skies over the airport, sees no
need to shoo away the little guys.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic is carefully monitored, with an envelope of space built
in around each aircraft, said William Shumann, an FAA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Any airport that receives federal grant money _ and Sky Harbor
certainly is one of them _ must accept all users, Shumann said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA allowed the student-pilot bans because of the level of
traffic and the complexity of the airspace at those 12 airports,
Shumann said. The FAA does not believe Sky Harbor meets those
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Still, smaller aircraft were at fault in 26 of 38 pilot-error
reports filed by local FAA officials in a 10-month period last
year. Only four were the fault of commercial pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining incidents were controller errors or involved
vehicles driving onto the runway.
</P>
<P>
   The tension over the small-airplane issue bubbles up in reports
on airport problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception by air-traffic controllers of `little airplane,
big airplane' continues to put the small guys in the ranks of
second-class citizens,'' an unidentified small-aircraft pilot wrote
in a report filed through the federal Aviation Safety Reporting
System.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot complained that air-traffic controllers ignored his
radio call in favor of larger, commercial aircraft, forcing the
smaller plane to climb higher as his plane neared South Mountain.
In the report, the pilot asserted this was part of a campaign to
neglect small aircrafts' needs so they wouldn't bother flying into
Sky Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers return the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   In an unrelated account also filed with the safety reporting
system, a controller complained that a Cessna piloted by a student
did not respond to tower instructions after takeoff. As a result,
controllers ordered a Boeing 737 off the runway, fearing the Cessna
might turn back.
</P>
<P>
   The student pilot claimed his radio had malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a common occurrence with student pilots operating at
this airport,'' the controller wrote. He concluded that student
pilots should be banned and listed other airports where this is
done.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, filed with the National Aeronautic Space
Administration, are scrubbed clean of identifying details, such as
the complainants' names or airlines, before being made public. NASA
cautions that its system is self-reporting, which makes the
accounts vulnerable to subjective reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot-deviation reports are a more reliable indicator of
trouble. The reports are filed by FAA tower officials to document
what they believe are pilot errors.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18 months from February 1996 to August 1997, the FAA
filed 35 such reports from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   But the pace picked up in late 1997. In 10 months, from December
1997 to October 1998, tower officials filed 38 reports. More than
two-thirds of them involved smaller aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Some documented harrowing events, such as on Feb. 7, 1998, when
a Rockwell AC-12 ignored tower instructions and entered the north
runway, forcing an arriving Southwest Airlines jet to abort a
landing and do another turn over the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the reports detail that the pilot was a student.
On Dec. 30, 1997, a Sawyer student ignored instructions to taxi
behind an America West Boeing 737. That forced the 737 to instead
follow the student.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 26 reports involving small aircraft documented
intrusions into Phoenix's airspace without clearance. None of those
cases resulted in any problems, and several of them occurred miles
away from Sky Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   George Sullivan, air-traffic manager of the Phoenix tower,
chalked up many of the reports to pilot inexperience with Sky
Harbor. But that doesn't make the case for banning them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What will move more of the ``little guys'' out, he said, is the
airport's increasingly busy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there are seven times each day that general-aviation
aircraft have to wait for takeoffs and landings. Traffic is just
too thick to let the small planes in immediately, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these things start to happen, they decide it's better to
use Deer Valley (Airport) or Falcon Field because they don't want
to hold out there for 20 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, general-aviation travel has been dropping at Sky
Harbor. Last year, 15 percent of the airport's traffic came from
general aviation. A decade ago, it was 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the decrease, controllers warn of the potential hazards
of small aircraft and student pilots. Their warnings have struck
some nerves.
</P>
<P>
   To Darrell Sawyer, owner of the only flight school left at Sky
Harbor, the controllers wield more influence on airport access than
the FAA or the airport's owners at Phoenix City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing hinges on what happens in the tower cab, which
is dictated by David Stock,'' said Sawyer, referring to the
president of the local air-traffic controllers' union.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to admit that the union has that much power hurts, but
it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer said shoddy treatment by air-traffic controllers is
driving his customers to suburban airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love the service, they love the airplanes, but it's too
difficult for them to get in and out of Sky Harbor,'' said Sawyer,
owner of Sawyer Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Stock said there's no campaign to squeeze out small planes. In
fact, since controllers now work on a system that links pay to
volume, they would be taking money out of their pockets if they
needlessly turned away traffic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   `I haven't been shy in talking about mistakes, I guess,'' he
said. ``And more mistakes are made by small planes than by big
planes. We want to keep mistakes to a minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer, at the request of city aviation officials, said he will
drop primary training when his lease renews in 2002. That will
remove beginners from Sky Harbor's airspace.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's debating whether to open a primary-training school
elsewhere. But, he said, his students will miss out on the rich
experience that busy Sky Harbor, with its mix of air operations,
offers.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that letting beginners roam the skies above Sky
Harbor is like letting a driver's ed student maneuver through the
I-17/I-10 stack interchange at rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   To Tom Browning, a former Luke Air Force Base commander, it's
daunting to face the prospect of flying near aircraft that are
piloted by ``Joe Six Pack, who has more money than brains, who goes
out and gets 40 hours of training.''
</P>
<P>
   But the best antidote, he said, is vigilance, not bans.
</P>
<P>
   Single-engine pilot Darrin Strosnider said he's never had
trouble flying into Sky Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   He chalks that up to doing his homework _ being up to the minute
on weather conditions and the frequencies used by the tower. Pilots
who aren't prepared for Sky Harbor's busy conditions don't deserve
to be there, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Strosnider said he has little desire to use an airport where
small aircraft are going to have to wait behind the big guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I avoid it for that very reason: They have a lot of heavies
going in and out of there, and they get the priority,'' he said. &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at 444-8963 or at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
