<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9632 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-HOTBED-2ndTak     03-13 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-HOTBED-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: most successful IPOs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Xylan IPO was a wakeup call to entrepreneurs, venture
capital and investment bankers that Southern California was now on
the map,'' said co-founder Douglas Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing and selling arcane equipment used to direct voice
and data flow over phone and computer network lines, Xylan has
flourished with the recent explosion of the Internet and corporate
intranets. So much so, in fact, that earlier this month France's
Alcatel SA agreed to buy Xylan for about $2 billion, by far the
biggest takeover of a local telecom firm to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xylan is really the major success story for Southern
California,'' observed Cliff Numark, a program director at the
nonprofit Los Angeles Regional Technology Alliance, which works to
attract high-tech firms to the area.
</P>
<P>
   News last week that the German industrial conglomerate Siemens
would buy a 20 percent stake in Accelerated Networks, a privately
held Moorpark firm, has further legitimized the region as a telecom
comer.
</P>
<P>
   The trick now, industry participants say, is to sustain and
build on the area's newfound favor. The cost of land and housing
should help. In recruiting employees, local firms can typically
offer less than, say, a Santa Clara company and still manage to
land top talent. With the same money, ``you can buy twice the house
here that you could in Santa Clara,'' said Xylan's Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital is also far easier to come by than just a few
years ago, said LARTA's Numark. Venture funding for information
technology _ led by telecom _ has grown by roughly 1,000 percent in
the past five years, he said, to more than $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, whether the local telecom industry can maintain and
improve its position relative to competitors will depend on how
large local players can grow. In a theme played out in industries
across Los Angeles, as local firms reach a certain level of success
they are often snatched up by deep-pocketed competitors. And for
many, that's not necessarily bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these companies are building gear that in the long
run makes more sense to plug into a larger-selling organization
like a Cisco, Lucent or Nortel,'' said Xircom's Gates. ``We're
probably not a big acquisition target at the moment, but that could
change. If the big guys decide they want (mobile computing) as part
of their strategy, we become a target.''
</P>
<P>
   Others pooh-pooh the notion, insisting they will be the hunter,
not the hunted. Vertel, a company based in the Woodland Hills
community in the San Fernando Valley that makes software to manage
telecommunications networks, recently bought the parent company
from which it spun off just three years ago, and last year it
acquired a San Diego competitor for $3million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that acquisition, we had $20 million cash,'' said
Vertel Vice President Ruth Cox. ``We're looking to build a sizable
company ... and have no intention of being bought. We're the ones
doing the sniffing.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
