<HEADLINE>
STARS, FLYERS COULD OFFER FINALS PRELUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ NHL experts have predicted since the All-Star
break that the Stars and Philadelphia Flyers are favorites to meet
in the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, be sure to fire up the VCR tonight, because
this is the only scouting tape that will be available on this
matchup all season. The NHL's move to six divisions has left
several teams with one meeting each season.
</P>
<P>
   So, does that put any extra emphasis on the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It's a
national TV game \RESPN\S, and they're a handful. They might be the
best team in the league from the red line in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers boast the most offensively successful line in the NHL
with Eric Lindros (89 points), John LeClair (81 points) and newly
acquired winger Mark Recchi. Lindros and LeClair are a combined
plus 67 and tied for the NHL lead in goal scoring with 38 goals
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair missed the Flyers game against the Penguins yesterday
with a hip-flexor injury, but said he would like to play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great line,'' Hitchcock said. ``I don't think we can
check them with just one line, it'll have to be a combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Mike Modano combined with linemates Jamie
Langenbrunner and Jere Lehtinen to shut down one of the hottest
lines in the league Friday when they held Anaheim's Teemu Selanne,
Paul Kariya and Steve Rucchin without a point. But while the Modano
line suffocated the Ducks' speed, they'll have a different
challenge against a burly line led by the 6-foot-4, 230-pound
Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers are riding a 10-game (0-7-3) winless streak, their
longest of the 1990s. They lost to the Penguins, 4-0, yesterday in
Pittsburgh and have fallen from the first playoff seed to the fifth
in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to the Stars going 13-3-3 against the East this season
and 12-2-2 in their past 16 games, and the matchup becomes even
bigger for the Flyers, who recently traded promising young prospect
Dainius Zubrus to the Montreal Canadiens for goal-scoring winger
Recchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got to quit hoping for a break and go out there
and make something happen,'' LeClair said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Stars and Flyers will get only one chance to do
that this season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
