<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' BURKETT ENDURES ROUGH STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Johnny Paul 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates, who often
guards his personal expectations for individual players with locked
lips, offered this bold prediction three weeks ago:
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect John Burkett to win at least 15 games this year.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a stretch if the 34-year-old right-hander cannot
solve his _ his stretch, that is.
</P>
<P>
   That deficiency reared its head in the Rangers' 13-7 victory
against the Detroit Tigers yesterday at Charlotte County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, who struggles when forced to pitch from the stretch
instead of from the windup, became the subject of torment once the
Tigers produced base runners.
</P>
<P>
   The result: a five-run second inning for the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really trying to work on that this spring, but I struggled
with it again,'' Burkett said. ``The only thing you can do is keep
working and keep grinding.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents punished Burkett with the big inning throughout 1998.
Opposing lineups scored three or more runs in an inning 19 times
against Burkett in his 32 starts. One base runner often ignites a
chain reaction of hitter-friendly pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Opening Day 1998?
</P>
<P>
   Burkett retired the first 12 batters the Chicago White Sox sent
to the plate, but seven runs scored before the completion of the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, a ``contact'' pitcher who cannot overpower hitters and
allows opponents to put the ball in play, surrenders hits.
Opponents hit .292 against Burkett in 1998, but batting averages
soar once runners reach.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents hit .347 with runners on base and .353 with runners in
scoring position; those two figures ranked as the fifth-and
third-worst among American League qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   Those type of batting averages tend to lead to big innings and
big trouble for a member of the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've gotten into a bad habit of rushing when pitching
from the stretch,'' Burkett said. ``Your natural tendency is rush
your delivery with men on base, but I don't have to. I've got the
best catcher in the history of baseball \RIvan Rodriguez\S behind
the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates and general manager Doug Melvin have reiterated their
belief that Burkett can regain the form that saw him go 67-42 with
a 3.82 earned-run average in five seasons with the San Francisco
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people from the outside might think they're crazy, but I
don't see any reason why I can't get it done if I make the correct
adjustments here and there,'' said Burkett, who went 9-13 with a
5.68 ERA in 1998. ``I believe I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates does, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very capable of pitching like he did in Anaheim last
year,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers completed a three-game sweep of the Angels after
Burkett's Sept. 23 start. The Angels managed only one run and two
hits against Burkett in his eight-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty big game he pitched for us,'' Oates said.
``He's capable of doing that 15 times this year.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   It might not, though, if Burkett solves his.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
