<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE DEADLINE NEAR FOR AMWEST FLIGHT ATTENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pay dispute between flight attendants and America West
Airlines, smoldering since the company's 1991 financial meltdown,
has left negotiators with just 59 hours to defuse the animosity and
work out a deal before Friday's strike deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Though there have been signs of hope for a settlement, the 2,400
flight attendants are toting some heavy baggage born of America
West's bankruptcy filing seven years ago. The Tempe-based carrier
cut their pay 10 percent and left them holding worthless stock in
its reorganization _ stock that the flight attendants were forced
to buy with salaries as little as $12,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the company posting record profits of $108.6 million
last year, the Association of Flight Attendants Council 66 is
adamant that the company can improve its offer, and as a result,
make up for lost time and pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The members want the company to put dollars on the table that
show a commitment to the future and sacrifices of the past,'' union
President Bill McGlashen said.
</P>
<P>
   Although acknowledging the financial turmoil the flight
attendants have endured, Greg Garger, America West vice president
of labor relations, said it is something that all the airline's
employee groups had to withstand and their pay cuts have been
restored.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of emotion attached to that, but the focus now
has to be on reaching a settlement, said Garger, who will be one of
the company's lead negotiators along with management labor
consultant Jerry Glass.
</P>
<P>
   The two will begin meetings with McGlashen and his AFA team
Wednesday afternoon at the National Mediation Board offices in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   If a contract settlement eludes them, the flight attendants can
strike at the end of the day Friday _ 10:01 p.m. in Arizona and
just after midnight on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   But they're not necessarily in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   America West also can exercise its option of locking out
employees and shutting down the airline, which it has warned
employees it will consider.
</P>
<P>
   Random strikes that the union calls CHAOS _ Create Havoc Around
Our System _ or a lockout could cripple spring travel at Phoenix
Sky Harbor International Airport, where America West accounts for
more than 40 percent of the takeoffs and landings. With CHAOS, the
flight attendants' union plans to target selected flights at the
last minute instead of a complete walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers would be left scrambling for limited seats on other
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes also are high in terms of how a strike would affect
morale among the flight attendants, who have the largest union
membership at America West and who are the company's front-line
employees. Some passengers already have complained that the dispute
has affected how flight attendants are treating passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants, who are prohibited by company policy to talk
to the media, say they are eager to reach agreement on their first
contract, which they've been awaiting since voting for a union in
1994. Longtime flight attendants talk about how they paid a steep
price to keep the company aloft during reorganization, and many
vent their anger toward management, especially Chairman William
Franke.
</P>
<P>
   It's a grudge that some suggest could be a huge stumbling block
to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Airline analyst Sam Buttrick of PaineWebber in New York said the
financial differences can be worked out, but the emotional gulf may
be harder to bridge, making a strike inevitable. &QL; 
Like `unwanted in-law' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants, two-thirds of whom have 10 to 16 years'
experience with America West, feel ``like the unwanted in-law who
stayed too long, said Jeff Zack, AFA communications director.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've brought this company back to being successful,'' he
said, adding that flight attendants are willing to fight for a
better deal than the company has offered.
</P>
<P>
   The union wants America West to up its ante by $16.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, it would be futile to reach a tentative
settlement because the flight attendants won't accept a deal that
doesn't include significant improvements in salary, travel expenses
and other pay issues, according to Zack.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants rejected a tentative agreement of $53.5
million in December 1997 over similar issues.
</P>
<P>
   America West, guarded in its public comments heading into this
week's eleventh-hour negotiations, remains hopeful it can negotiate
a contract the union will accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what our objective is and that is an agreement that's
fair to flight attendants, fair to the company and consistent to
our deals with other employees,'' Garger said.
</P>
<P>
   America West has negotiated first contracts with its pilots
union, dispatchers and mechanics, but there were some bitter
negotiations, especially with the Teamsters-represented mechanics,
who settled in October. &QL; 
1st strike deadline &QL; 
The difference in this case is that the company has never faced a
strike deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Garger declined to comment on whether that will change the
dynamics of the negotiations, saying it would only be speculation
on his part.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators expect long sessions from Wednesday through Friday
night to resolve the remaining differences, and both sides say
they're willing to extend the talks if progress is being made.
</P>
<P>
   America West has proposed a salary scale of $16.13 per hour to
start and $34.59 after 15 years. The union is pushing for industry
average pay of starting pay of $15.11 per hour, topping out at
$39.50 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   AFA leaders say that they have scaled back their proposal from
$129 million to $74.5 million but that the company's offer is still
$16.5 million short. &QL; 
Gap in dispute &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America West values its proposal at $68.7 million, suggesting
that the two sides are only $5.8 million apart, or just $1.16
million per year over the five years of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the average salary increase would total 44.7
percent over five years.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to flight attendants, Franke said the union is
holding out for wages and benefits matching the larger airlines,
which is something that America West cannot do and remain
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA disputes that, saying America West would still enjoy a
labor cost advantage if it met the union's demands.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendant labor costs as a percentage of operating
revenue were about about 2.6 percent last year, with the
next-closest Southwest Airlines at 4.7 percent, according to Zack.
</P>
<P>
   As a low-cast carrier, America West seems blindly focused on
keeping labor costs down, while ignoring other ways to shave costs,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For America West, the bottom line is keeping its costs low in
light of the fact that, because of its size, revenue is far below
the top six airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it would lose $250 million a year if its labor
costs equaled those of the six biggest U.S. carriers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the union, the rallying cry, painted on banners and across
car windows is: ``Pay us or CHAOS.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the sniping that has strained relations between flight
attendants and the company, the question remains whether
negotiators in the final days of talks can put aside their
differences and find points of agreement that can keep the flight
attendants and America West's planes in the air. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
