r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-HOTBED-2TAKES     03-13 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-HOTBED-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES' SAN FERNANDO VALLEY BECOMING HOTBED OF
TELECOMMUNICATIONS ACTIVITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Silicon Valley of telephones it ain't. At
least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   But news earlier this month that two European telecommunications
giants are buying into local firms has highlighted the fact that
Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley and its surrounding suburbs have
become a hotbed of telecom activity.
</P>
<P>
   But why here, and why now? Depending on who's talking, credit
goes to everything from the breakup of AT&AMP;T to the decline of
aerospace to the region's relative abundance of commercial and
residential property. In fact, all have played important roles,
helped along by a booming economy and a dollop of pure luck.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that, along with places like Boston, the
Dallas-Richardson corridor and Santa Clara County, the Ventura
Freeway corridor has become a cluster zone for small and midsize
firms supplying products and manpower to the booming fields of
corporate networking, the Internet and dial-tone phone service,
generating annual sales of more than $1.5 billion in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a unique opportunity in the San Fernando
Valley,'' said Bill Kula, a spokesman for Dallas-based GTE Corp.,
which maintains a regional headquarters in Thousand Oaks. ``The
seeds are being planted there to create a true
telecommunications-data networking corridor.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Silicon Valley, which dominates the nation's computer
software industry, no single city or region has a lock on
telecommunications. Indeed, the breakup of AT&AMP;T in 1984 created
seven Baby Bells scattered across the country and around which
distinct telecom industries developed.
</P>
<P>
   While it's possible a single region may one day take precedence
or, conversely, even more clusters will appear, ``As it stands,
it's as if imaginary fences have been drawn,'' divvying up the
country, Kula said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Pacific Telesis _ later bought by SBC
Communications _ was the post-Ma Bell mother lode around which
vendors grew. Though San Francisco-based, more than half of the
company's customers were and are in Southern California, requiring
major local infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   On the data networking front, for example, companies like Micom
Communications in Simi Valley and Fibermuxin Chatsworth developed
equipment to link the stand-alone computers of Pacific Telesis'
corporate customers to networks, and fiber-optic lines to then
allow those networked machines to rapidly exchange data with each
other. The Micoms and Fibermuxins in turn spawned more firms, as
did spending cutbacks at aerospace contractors such as Rockwell,
Hughes and TRW.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed computer-chip maker Vitesse Semiconductor in
Camarillo, for one, was founded in 1984 by two former Rockwell
employees with a good idea and gumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rockwell was doing a lot of government work with gallium
arsenide integrated circuits, and two of our founders had developed
a way to make these things more manufacturable,'' said spokeswoman
Trisha Ito. ``They presented the idea to Rockwell, which passed,
and these guys said, Let's see if we can do it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   After searching for seed money and finding it in a large
sandpaper manufacturer with too much cash on its hands, the pair
did just that. The relationship with Norton Sandpaper eventually
soured during an early sales slump, but a new round of venture
capital and, later, a successful initial public offering put
Vitesse on a track that has seen its revenues grow to more than
$175 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in the Woodland Hills community of the San Fernando
Valley _ then further up the Ventura Freeway to Calabasas, then
further up again to Newbury Park _ Xircom Corp. was striking out in
yet another direction, pursuing the burgeoning field of mobile
computing. Founded in 1988 by California State University,
Northridge, graduate Dirk Gates, Xircom was an early developer of
modems for portable PCs and now makes what are regarded as the top
products in their category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xircom is still probably unique among the (telecom) companies
out here,'' Gates said. ``We're not building the (infrastructure)
tree, but the leaves at the end of the tree.'' Today the company
sells more than $270 million worth of modems and related devices
annually.
</P>
<P>
   But even as such early players were making a go of it, by the
mid-1990s there was still no real groundswell, no spark that
indicated to local participants and the world at large that the
region was destined to be a major player in the telecommunications
field.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when two immigrants, a marketing whiz and a
tech-head, took their Calabasas-based company, Xylan, public. The
initial public offering generated $130 million, making it one of
the year's most successful IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
