<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NEWSWEEK-EVERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYA BEATS KUERTEN; WILLIAMS DEFEATS GRAF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIAN WELLS, Calif. _ It took a little bit of prayer and a lot
of topspin, but Carlos Moya, the shaggy-haired Spaniard who
announced himself as an impact player by capturing last year's
French Open, Saturday became the first man from his nation, and the
15th man ever, to attain the No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   With the desert sun serving as a natural spotlight, Moya
replaced the slumping Pete Sampras at the top of the standing when
he defeated Gustavo Kuerten, 6-3, 1-6, 6-1, to reach the final of
the Newsweek Champions Cup. It was Kuerten who preceded Moya as the
French Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be king,'' said Moya, whose history-making
semifinal victory was followed by another bravura breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, 17, currently the queen of the women's tennis
scene, stormed to her second consecutive title, and collected
$200,000, by ousting the two-time champion Steffi Graf, 6-3, 3-6,
7-5, in the final of the Evert Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can win the big ones now,'' said Williams, who is
unbeaten in her last 11 matches. ``That's enough to win a Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams had bragged of possessing the best forehand on the tour
on the eve of this final, and Saturday, despite falling behind a
service break after the first game of the third set, she used it,
along with nine aces, to deny the 29-year-old Graf a 107th career
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about this,'' said Williams, who sprinted
from the court to hug her father and coach, Richard; her auxiliary
coach, Nick Bollettieri, and the Hollywood producer Arnon Milchan,
who owns the WTA Tour's international television rights and last
week treated Williams and her older sister, Venus, to a screen
test. Back on court, Williams complimented Graf for making life
difficult for her in the midday sunshine, but Graf made it clear
that Williams, who pounded out 35 winners while Graf had just 11,
deserved the title for being the more aggressive player despite her
inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just going for her shots more than I did and that was
the difference at the end,'' said Graf, who surrendered her
third-set service break with a netted backhand in the eighth game.
Serving at 5-6, Graf plopped a forehand into the net to set up
double match point for Williams, then soared a forehand long to
give Williams her second title in as many finals. Graf had not lost
a final since the 1994 U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   After his victory, Moya proclaimed himself not just the king of
the world computer ranking, but the king of the world _ ``at least
for a week,'' said the 22-year-old Moya, a self-described lazybones
from Majorca who does his share of Walter Mitty fantasizing and has
even dreamed his way into a Wimbledon final. ``I was the king of
clay, and now I've been king of the world,'' said Moya, who
anticipated a message from King Juan Carlos of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the king of Spain, but he's talking about tennis; he's
going to be happy,'' Moya said.
</P>
<P>
   Moya was so happy with his achievement that, after embracing his
Brazilian buddy, Kuerten, at the net, he clasped hands with his two
coaches and, like Dorothy clicking her heels to send herself from
Oz to Kansas, jumped up and down together 10 times in a celebration
ritual borrowed from their impromptu soccer matches. In those
stress-free sessions, said Moya, the loser has to do the leaping as
a calisthenics penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Moya had been worn to a frazzle by Kuerten in their four
previous meetings, all of them contested on clay, but today, with
everything at stake, Moya achieved his ultimate goal on his very
first attempt. ``I had motivation to be the best Spanish player,
and the No. 1,'' he said. ``The world works like that. When I have
a goal, I get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moya made only 15 unforced errors in the match, and knew he had
the final-round berth, and the top spot, under control after taking
a 5-0 lead in the final set. Then, with his knees trembling, he
served for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous; I just tried to win as soon as possible,'' said
Moya, who will meet the unseeded Mark Philippoussis, a 6-1, 6-2
winner over Chris Woodruff, in the final. ``I'm going to be more
motivated than I was before. I would love to have more pressure all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after winning at Roland Garros last year, Moya made
it clear he had every intention of fighting his way to No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my time to be up,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
