<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT HORSES 1-2 IN SAN FELIPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ When it comes to good omens, trainer Bob Baffert seems
to have all of the bases covered as he goes for his third
consecutive Kentucky Derby victory.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Baffert's duo of Prime Timber and Exploit finished
one-two in the $250,000 San Felipe Stakes at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber's late rush handed Exploit his first defeat in six
career starts. But either way, Baffert's chances are looking good
after one of the major Derby preps.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's Real Quiet and Silver Charm finished second in the San
Felipe the last two years, only to win the Derby and the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   While Baffert has become a Derby regular, Prime Timber's owner,
Aaron Jones, never has run a horse in the race, something he would
love to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think all of the money in the world could buy me out
of that,'' he said. ``It's a goal that is the pinnacle of the
people in the racing business.''
</P>
<P>
   The 76-year-old owner saw his 5-2 second choice hang close to
the leaders _ High Wire Act and Exploit _ and pull away in
midstretch for a two-length victory in the 1 1/16-mile Grade II
race in 1:42.16. It was Jones' biggest victory since he won the
1986 Kentucky Oaks with Tiffany Lass.
</P>
<P>
   ``All and all, I'm very happy,'' said Jones, who battled cancer
for 10 years before getting a clean bill of health in 1996. ``I was
concerned the way he eyeballs other horses and the way we were
running him back so soon (after a second-place finish in the San
Rafael Stakes on Feb. 28).
</P>
<P>
   ``But it just goes to show you Baffert is a hell of a lot better
trainer than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing with blinkers on for the first time, Prime Timber, with
David Flores aboard, was content to lay back, even though Eddie
Delahoussaye and High Wire Act raced out to a seven-length lead and
forced Exploit and Chris McCarron to pursue them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I though he was done at the three-eighths pole, but David
found another gear turning for home,'' assistant trainer Eoin Harty
said. ``He never kicked it in like that before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was his best race by far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-99 2347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
