<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LBPT </SLUG>
 
HOUSTON'S McNAIR TAKES A STAND 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By BOB KEISSER &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The most interesting sight at the NFL's annual
meetings here this week may be a billionaire throwing himself in
front of a very slow-moving train.
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Robert McNair, fearing the NFL will give an
expansion franchise to Los Angeles without as much as an owner or
stadium in hand, is throwing up barricades and calling in all IOUs
in hopes of stalling a decision.
</P>
<P>
   McNair wants to return the league to his own disenfranchised
city, and he's had a fully-funded, ready-to-go proposal on the NFL
table for almost year. But a majority of NFL owners lean towards
L.A., drawn by sizeable numerical advantage -- more people, more TV
sets, and higher potential franchise fee.
</P>
<P>
   The league's expansion committee, made up of 14 owners, will
convene this morning and is expected to give a lukewarm
recommendation for a 32nd team in L.A. The entire membership will
consider the issue Tuesday, and 24 of 31 votes are needed for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to stall that, McNair has in the last week:
</P>
<P>
   Guaranteed sellouts of all Houston home games for five years, a
sweeping reply to L.A.'s size advantage. He said all unsold tickets
would be donated to charity by the 72-hour TV blackout deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're telling television that you're not going to suffer
blackouts in Houston,'' McNair told a Houston TV station this week.
``That should be a big challenge to Los Angeles. You hear a lot of
talk about the fact that Houston is the 11th-rated media market and
Los Angeles is the second-rated market. That's very superficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Played the political card by having seven Houston-area members
of the House of Representatives and both of Texas' senators
telegram or call Tagliabue with their support for McNair's
proposal. The plea included a reminder to Tagliabue that he sort of
promised Houston a franchise if it would build a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sent letters to the owners of eight NFL teams -- Arizona,
Buffalo, Chicago, Indianapolis, Minneapolis, New England, Oakland
and Philadelphia -- saying he is interested in buying their team
and moving it to Houston should he not get an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   And implored his supporters among the owners, including Bud
Adams, who created the vacancy by moving the Oilers to Nashville,
to rally their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to have worked. Two prominent owners who usually
judge everything by the color green, Denver's Pat Bowlen and
Dallas' Jerry Jones, pooh-poohed whatever momentum L.A. had a few
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles is not the no-brainer people are making it out to
be,'' said Bowlen, who sits on the league's expansion committee.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jones: ``The urgency to make a decision (on expansion)
right now is not compelling. We may need some more things to happen
as it relates to L.A. I could see where nothing could be done at
this meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is excellent at doing nothing. Five years ago, in the
same city, it did not approve the Rams' proposed move to St. Louis.
The league instead gave Georgia Frontiere a set of conditions to
meet, including tithing a chunk of the money she received from St.
Louis to move, before giving its blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the league approves planting a team in L.A., it will be
a generic decision, unspecific in regards to site and owner. Both
groups with proposals on the table, the Michael Ovitz/Carson plan
and the New Coliseum, anticipate being told to tighten up their
plans and bring more money to the table next time they meet. The
old assumption of a $500 million franchise fee has been severely
escalated to at least $650 million.
</P>
<P>
   Conceivably, the league could impose a deadline on L.A. to get
its act together -- say the end of the year -- that includes back
door language for Houston should L.A. fumble its opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   League officials have suggested that Team Ovitz and Team
Coliseum merge its forces -- and fortunes. Considering the
diversity of the groups and proposals, that's highly unlikely. But
the NFL is never too proud to ask.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
