<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOOK FOR AHL AFFILIATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ROGER PHILLIPS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ King GM Dave Taylor said Saturday the team
is seeking its own American Hockey League affiliate to develop its
players, but that any such arrangement probably won't happen until
at least the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at some things,'' Taylor said. ``We don't have
anything concrete. Down the road, it's definitely where we're going
to be. The time frame is uncertain. But we have talked to some
teams in the AHL.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Kings have placed some prospects in Springfield
of the AHL, which also receives players from the Phoenix Coyotes.
The Kings also have several players with the Long Beach Ice Dogs of
the IHL. Both arrangements expire after this season. The AHL is
considered the top developmental minor league, with the IHL home to
more veteran players than the AHL.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson said the Kings would benefit from having
their own AHL affiliate. Without it, he said, a team is somewhat at
the whim of the coach of the team it sends its prospects to. If the
Kings had their own affiliate, Robinson said, they'd be in more
control of how their prospects are developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have your own coach and your own system, you say, `Hey,
listen, this kid, we have to mature him and we have to educate him
and we've got to get him ready,'' Robinson said. ``When you are
sharing a team, they're going to have their ways and their players
and the coach that's in there is just trying to win hockey games.''
</P>
<P>
   Open-minded (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of this season, Robinson said he's prepared to
listen to the request of his team's leaders and stick with lineups
that are successful rather than adjusting them to match up with an
opponent's roster.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's up to the players to prove their idea was a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line is there,'' Robinson said following Saturday
morning's skate at the Forum before the evening's game against the
Vancouver Canucks. ``Strangle yourself or go fishing. In years
past, whatever coaches said went. Now, you've got to listen to the
players. I'm all for that. My door is always open.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Canucks, Robinson used the same lineup that defeated
Detroit, 4-2, on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have confidence in themselves and they feel the team
that they have has confidence and can play against anybody, I have
no problem with them,'' Robinson said. ``I'm as flexible as they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   One player omitted from the lineup the last two games is
defenseman Steve Duchesne, who has struggled all season after
signing a contract that pays him $3.75 million a year. When he was
announced as a scratch before Saturday's game, a large portion of
the crowd in the Forum cheered.
</P>
</TEXT>
