<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS APPEAR ON LENO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers' star turn on Friday's ``The Tonight
Show'' included magnificent seven-player cast that was accompanied
by head coach Chris Ford and assistant coach Jim Todd.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who did exercise an option to skip the trip was
forward Maurice Taylor. Taylor said Jay Leno's monologue jabs about
the Clippers don't bother him, and insisted he would have attended
if the entire team had agreed to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't like to celebrate one win,'' Taylor said. ``Now,
if we win 17 in a row, I'll go out there and dance buck naked.''
</P>
<P>
   One Clipper who decided to go with the show was point guard
Darrick Martin, who was once of three players included as ``You
Make The Call'' contestants. He also gave Leno a bit of grief about
his knack for making the Clippers a consistent punch line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to give him some of his own medicine,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   subhead Nothing to Wright about
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's deadline for teams to offer contract extensions to
their players selected in the 1996 NBA Draft came and went without
re-enlistment of center/forward Lorenzen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, the No. 8 pick in '96, and his agent asked for a
six-year, $60 million extension back in January. The Clippers
conferred, and - after about five seconds - said that price was a
bit steep. So Wright's agent asked for a trade.
</P>
<P>
   A trade almost occurred less than two weeks ago, when the
Clippers offered the 6-foot-10 Wright and backup guard Pooh
Richardson to Portland in exchange for shooting guard Isaiah Rider.
The deal was almost a go, but Rider's improved play - and a Blazer
winning streak -- sabotaged the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Wright snagged 25 points in the Clippers'
first victory.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead `Kandivision'
</P>
<P>
   Michael Olowokandi spent the last two days in the viewfinder of
TNT as the subject of an upcoming ``Day In The Life'' feature. The
cable network had followed Olowokandi around the University of
Pacific last year, and plans to use the current filming as a follow
story.
</P>
<P>
   Included will be exciting footage of Olowokandi shaving his
head, a fashion choice that played to rave reviews from his
teammates. The rookie center was fulfilling a promise to shave his
head after the Clippers scored their first victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
